<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MCKEITHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN J. MCKEITHEN, 81, FORMER LOUISIANA GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John J. McKeithen, Louisiana's first governor to serve two
consecutive terms, who practiced moderation at a time of intense
racial conflict in the Deep South and gave New Orleans the
Superdome, died Friday at a hospital in Columbia, La. He was 81 and
lived in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in declining health since undergoing heart surgery
two years ago, said his friend Dave Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   McKeithen was governor from 1964 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch Democrat and protege of Earl Long, who was a
multi-term governor, McKeithen was so popular in his first
administration that the Legislature passed a law allowing a
governor to succeed himself. A ban on serving two consecutive terms
as governor was instituted at the turn of the century but was
lifted for McKeithen, who was known for his oratory.
</P>
<P>
   But in his second term, McKeithen was drawn into controversy
over accusations of Mafia influence in his administration, although
the scandal was never linked to him personally.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Renwick, director of the Loyola University Institute of
Politics who followed McKeithen's career, credited him with four
major accomplishments: the beginning of the end of segregation in
Louisiana, the decision to build the Superdome, leadership in the
passage of a state constitutional amendment that permits state
governors to run for two four-year terms, and the emergence of
consensus politics.
</P>
<P>
   John Martzell, a New Orleans lawyer who was executive secretary
of the State Human Relations Commission from 1966 to 1972, said
Friday that McKeithen's efforts to promote racial harmony are
little known even today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing he did came in a speech he delivered
to the AFL-CIO convention in Baton Rouge in the summer of 1966,''
Martzell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pointed to some blacks in the audience and said, `I know
I'm not leaving this state, and I don't think you're leaving
either. So we've got to solve our problem.' It was giving the
imprimatur of the state governor to solving racial differences.
Previous governors had always proclaimed massive resistance to
integration. He had a huge impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He also appointed black Louisianans to state offices in a time
of racial unrest in his state.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Louisiana Superdome, which has 75,000 seats,
came from his friend Dixon, a successful plywood manufacturer who
now runs an art and antiques gallery in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited him in 1965 and suggested the stadium would have a
great economic impact on the state,'' Dixon recalled Friday. ``The
governor listened very carefully to what I had to say and then
jumped up, pounded his fist on the table and said `That could be
the greatest building in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Superdome's cost, estimated at $22 million, wound up being
$130 million and the stadium was not completed until 1975 after he
had been out of office for three years.
</P>
<P>
   John Julian McKeithen was born in rural Grayson on May 28, 1918,
the son of a farmer. His parents wanted him to become a Methodist
minister, but he went on to obtain a law degree at Louisiana State
University and set up a practice in Columbia, a small town in the
Red Hills of northern Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   He was an unknown country lawyer when Long picked him in 1948 as
a floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me not to worry _ I'd get on all right, and I guess I
did,'' McKeithen later recalled.
</P>
<P>
   McKeithen is survived by his wife, Marjorie, of Columbia; a son,
Walter Fox McKeithen, who is Louisiana's secretary of state and
lives in Baton Rouge; four daughters, Rebecca M. Hamilton, who
lives in China; Melissa M. Cummings of Columbia; Pamela M. Plummer
of Ruston, La.; and Jenny M. Borders of St. Francisville, La., and
15 grandchildren. His oldest son, Jesse Jay McKeithen, died last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
