</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTION-CONSPIRACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR, SHERIFF'S DEPUTIES ACQUITTED OF WRONGFULLY ACCUSING
MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (bl)  
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO, June 4 _ A former prosecutor and four sheriff's
deputies were acquitted Friday of conspiring to put an innocent man
on death row in the murder of a 10-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The case had drawn national attention because it is rare for
law-enforcement officials to face such charges and because the man
accused of the murder, Rolando Cruz, is one of 12 death-row inmates
in Illinois found to have been wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   A former DuPage state's attorney, Thomas Knight, now in private
practice, and three DuPage County sheriff's officers, James
Montesano, Thomas Vosburgh and Dennis Kurzawa, were acquitted by a
jury after 12 hours of deliberations, and 28 days of testimony, on
charges of obstruction of justice, perjury and conspiracy. A fourth
sheriff's officer, Robert Winkler, was acquitted by the presiding
judge in the case, William Kelly. In May, Kelly dismissed charges
against two other former prosecutors in the case, Robert Kilander,
now a Du Page County judge, and Patrick King, now an assistant U.S.
attorney in Chicago. Kelly said there was insufficient evidence
against them.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom erupted in loud cheers and applause as the
verdicts were announced. Among those in the courtroom were Tom and
Patricia Nicarico, the parents of the slain girl, who have defended
the actions of the investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a moment that should have happened a long time ago,''
Mrs. Nicarico said as she left the courtroom in tears. ``These are
good men who didn't deserve this. It's a true celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosburgh said after the verdict: ``This day speaks a lot for law
enforcement. I think it shows we were doing our job and we were
doing it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was charged with the murder and sexual assault of Jeanine
Nicarico, who was abducted by someone who kicked in the door of her
house in the affluent town of Naperville, outside Chicago, in 1983.
Her body was found two days later in woods about six miles away.
</P>
<P>
   After a highly publicized investigation, DuPage County sheriff's
deputies charged Cruz. He was convicted in two separate trials and
spent 10 years on death row, but was acquitted in a third trial in
1995 after one of the sheriff's officers recanted his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Hernandez was also convicted in the killing and
sentenced to death. His death sentence was later commuted and he,
too, was exonerated in 1995. But a judge ruled that the conspiracy
trial should focus only on accusations in the Cruz case.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the accusations involved the strategy used to convict
Cruz and Hernandez: testimony by Vosburgh and Kurzawa that Cruz
told them he had dreamed about the girl's killing and disclosed
details the deputies said only the killer could know.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz and his lawyers have repeatedly said the deputies
fabricated the dream, and there was no written investigator's
report about it. In 1995, in Cruz's third trial (his two previous
convictions had been overturned on appeal), Lieutenant Montesano
said he had testified falsely in the first two trials that the
deputies had told him about Cruz' s dream. As a result, the judge
acquitted Cruz. Hernandez was released shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the grand jurors who originally indicted Cruz testified
at the conspiracy trial that Cruz babbled to them that he had had a
dream about the killing, although there is no written record that
he gave such testimony.
</P>
<P>
   As the star witness in the trial, Cruz testified that he made no
dream statement. But he had made contradicting statements to
investigators in the past and before reading his verdict tonight,
Judge Kelly said he simply did not believe Cruz. At one point
during the trial, Cruz admitted that he is receiving counseling for
a lying problem.
</P>
<P>
   The jury would not comment on the verdict other than a short
statement they released in which they said they felt the state
failed to prove its case.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler was accused of falsely testifying that Cruz told him
about acquiring and disposing of a car used in the killing. King
and Knight were accused of presenting the testimony, knowing it was
false. Judge Kilander was accused of failing to inform defense
lawyers that a lawyer for Brian Dugan, a convicted child rapist and
murderer, had told him that Dugan admitted to killing Jeanine.
</P>
<P>
   Dugan, serving a life sentence for two rapes and murders, was
linked to the Nicarico slaying by DNA testing in 1989, but has not
been charged. He has said he will talk with the authorities only if
they promise not to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Kilander's lawyer, Ronald Menaker, has suggested that his client
fulfilled his obligation because he had told defense lawyers about
an interview he had had with Dugan shortly after he talked with
Dugan's lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
