r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECHINACEA-SYMPOSIUM-K     06-05 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECHINACEA-SYMPOSIUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECHINACEA, A MEDICINAL HERB, IS MAJOR TOPIC AT SCIENTIFIC
CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At an Eckerd drug
store here, all they have to do is put echinacea on the shelves and
the cash registers start ringing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``During cold season it blows out of here,'' store manager
George Honaker said. ``The last two winters everybody has been
swearing by it. They say it's wiping out colds in two days.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Echinacea, a medicinal herb made from a purple coneflower that
grows wild in the Great Plains, has become the fastest selling
herbal product in the nation, some experts say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 7 percent of Americans have tried echinacea in hopes that
it will protect them from colds and flu, according to one survey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But do the pills, cough drops, teas and extracts that people are
paying $300 million for each year really work? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, is the most some experts gathered this week in Kansas
City at a scientific conference on echinacea could say. The
conference, which ends Saturday at the Ritz-Carlton, Kansas City
hotel, was sponsored by the American Herbal Products Association,
an industry group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is mounting that taking echinacea ahead of time won't
keep you from getting a cold, researchers at the conference said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at least four studies suggest that popping some echinacea
capsules or sipping on echinacea tea at the first signs of a
scratchy throat or runny nose may shorten a cold by several days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether echinacea can prevent a cold is not well-determined by
the science. But there is evidence it can reduce symptoms,'' said
Mark Blumenthal, who teaches at the University of Texas School of
Pharmacy and directs the American Botanical Council. The council is
a nonprofit group that promotes research on medicinal herbs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, according to Blumenthal: ``We need more
studies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the research showing echinacea reduces cold symptoms
ranges in quality from ``pretty good'' to ``not particularly
convincing,'' said Bruce Barrett, a University of Wisconsin Medical
School researcher who is conducting his own study on whether
echinacea helps cold sufferers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a clear picture yet,'' Barrett said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health claims for echinacea and other medicinal herbs are often
based on slender evidence, Blumenthal said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Studies are done with small numbers of people, so their
conclusions lack the statistical certainty of large-scale studies.
Or the research is conducted in test tubes or on laboratory animals
in ways that don't clearly apply to people. &QL; 
Scant oversight &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of the problem with inadequate research has to do with the
way these products are regulated in the United States, Blumenthal
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Congress passed the Dietary Supplement Health and
Education Act, which gave manufacturers greater freedom to market
dietary supplements such as vitamins and herbs and to make claims
about their benefits on product labels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One brand of echinacea tea, for example, includes the claim:
``Supports the immune system.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These claims have to be backed by scientific evidence. But the
rules aren't as strict as for prescription drugs, which must
undergo rigorous testing for safety and effectiveness before the
Food and Drug Administration approves them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claims about a supplement don't have to be submitted to the Food
and Drug Administration for approval before the product goes on the
market. And although the manufacturer must be able to substantiate
its claim, it doesn't have to make the information publicly
available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any evaluation procedure in this country (for
herbal products),'' Blumenthal said. ``What we would like is a
rational, intelligent botanical expert advisory panel.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another area where regulation falls short is in standardizing
the ingredients in herbal products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consumers buying echinacea, for example, are faced with a
bewildering array of products. Three different species of the plant
are used commercially. Manufacturers use the plant's roots, the
parts above the ground, or both. And the plants are squeezed into
juice, dried to make capsules, or concentrated into alcohol
tinctures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no way of knowing that one brand of echinacea contains
all the same active ingredients as another brand. And no guarantee
that one batch of a single brand is the same as the next one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A higher priced product may be of higher quality, said botanist
and echinacea expert Steven Foster of Fayetteville, Ark. But
there's really little way to tell which products are best. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a congressional committee in March, Food and
Drug Administration Commissioner Jane Henney said that the agency
``still has a long way to go'' in implementing regulations for
herbs and other supplements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the FDA's ``A'' list for completion this year, she said, are
new manufacturing regulations to assure the consistency of
supplements and more specific rules on health claims. &QL; 
Questions remain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors remain highly skeptical about the value of
echinacea and other herbal remedies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many claims made for herbs and extracts and
supplements, and many of them are untrue,'' said Wallace Sampson, a
clinical professor of medicine at Stanford University and editor of
the Scientific Review of Alternative Medicine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herbs often may appear effective, Sampson said, because ``the
last thing you take before you get better seems to work.
Psychologically, these kinds of associations are very powerful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Blumenthal, who teaches physicians how to integrate
medicinal herbs into their practices, has seen a dramatic shift in
their attitudes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, they used to ask, `Do these really work?' Now
they ask which brands to recommend,'' Blumenthal said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Echinacea's history as a medicinal herb goes back to American
Indians, who used it for coughs, colds, sore throats and
toothaches. It was adopted by some doctors in the 19th century, but
other doctors called it a quack remedy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The herb has been popular in Germany and other western European
countries since the 1930s. Much of the research into its use is
being done there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one European study presented at the conference, 120 people in
the early stages of colds received either echinacea or a placebo.
About 40 percent of those getting echinacea progressed to
full-blown colds, compared to 60 percent of those receiving the
placebo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who received echinacea had cold symptoms for an average of
four days, compared to eight days for the placebo subjects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Ukraine, echinacea is even being used to treat radiation
exposure from the nuclear power plant disaster at Chernobyl,
researchers at the conference said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chernobyl rescue workers who were given daily doses of echinacea
for three weeks had fewer respiratory tract infections and were
less fatigued, Ukraine researcher Victoriya Pochernyayeva said
through an interpreter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Echinacea is being marketed in Ukraine in fruit juices, in a
sweet liqueur and even in a brownish-tinged vodka. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The echinacea-laced vodka increased sexual drive and minimized
hangovers, Pochernyayeva claimed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a very simple (drug) delivery system to me,''
Blumenthal quipped. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
