</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRE-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANELISTS DELIVER MESSAGE: JOURNALISTS ALSO MUST RESPECT RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Maybe it was the
time: 6:30 on a Friday night. Maybe it was the topic: Media
Self-Flagellation: When investigative journalism deserves it, and
when it doesn't. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who wants to be lambasted at their own convention? Besides, the
barbecue was calling. So it was a sparsely attended ``Showcase
Panel'' at the 1999 Investigative Reporters and Editors conference
at the Kansas City Marriott Downtown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The session combined a dose of group therapy, some Journalism
101 tips and a lecture in corporate rights from James Basile, a
lawyer who has represented Chiquita Brands International Inc. and
General Motors Co. in litigation against investigative
journalists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basile reminded the journalists that they too had limits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment is not an absolute license to do anything
to someone you're covering,'' Basile said. ``It doesn't give you
the right to violate their rights.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a pleasant message for journalists who have been stung
by some high-profile debacles in recent years: CNN and Time
retracting reports that the United States had used nerve gas on its
own defectors during the Vietnam War; The Cincinnati Enquirer
apologizing to Chiquita for stories based in part on stolen
voice-mail messages and paying the company $10 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Session moderator Rosemary Armao of The Baltimore Sun
congratulated the assembled for the investigative work they are
doing, ``because you're sure not hearing about it in the media.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Journalists still can do good work by doing their work well,
noted panelist Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project on
Excellence in Journalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't make the case as an expose, don't try to,'' he
said. ``Don't try to prove something you can't prove.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstiel added that reporters must make sure stories are
important and worth telling. The public trust in journalism has
eroded in part, he said, because reporters spend too much time
exposing the private lives of public figures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Bruce Selcraig, a freelance journalist, provided comic
catharsis for attendees when he donned a pair of Mickey Mouse ears
to rail against the evils of corporate ownership. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest threat to our democracy today is the unchecked
power of corporations, and corporate greed, and corporate influence
in our everyday lives,'' Selcraig said. ``We simply don't pursue
that enough.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Basile added a note of caution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you act in an unfair, biased way toward your subject, we're
going to have an easier time'' winning lawsuits, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
