<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELSIDE-LADN     06-05 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SAY THERE'S NO MUTINY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mo Vaughn had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   All this business about the inmates running the asylum just
doesn't add up, the Anaheim Angels first baseman said. But that's
exactly the idea that's been presented in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   A group of players sought out Angels general manager Bill Bavasi
to discuss concerns about manager Terry Collins, who is negotiating
a contract extension. More meetings ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi reportedly summoned a group of veteran players to find
out just how serious the problem is. Vaughn, believed to be one of
those called in, says there's no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't the mutiny I've been hearing,'' Vaughn said. ``How
it got to this point, I'm not going to let you know, but there is
no mutiny. We're not going to fall apart, it's not that type of
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, I don't care who likes who. It doesn't
matter to me. We, as professionals, have to do our job every day.
Everybody's got a right to their opinion. But it's not as drastic
and crazy a situation as it's been made out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn wasn't one of the players who initiated a meeting with
Bavasi. But he would not give Collins his endorsement, either, for
whatever that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is it's the general manager's decision,''
Vaughn said. ``Whatever happens is his decision, not ours. One
thing about Billy that's good is he talks to people. He knows where
we stand and we know where he stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins says he isn't bothered by the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you heard about guys with similar personalities?''
Collins asked. ``They clash. If they're laid back and the manager's
intense, they say `Oh, he's intense. Big deal.' But when they're as
intense as you are.... That's why I accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been blown way out of proportion,'' said Angels left
fielder Darin Erstad, one of the most intense players on the team.
``What happened was some reporter ran with it. But everybody's
making a bigger deal of it than it is. Whether I agree with him or
I don't agree with him, who cares? I play baseball, that's why I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' managerial style was an issue in Houston, where he
managed from 1994-96, and it has followed him to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough job,'' right fielder Tim Salmon said. ``You have
to manage 25 guys, 25 egos. You're not going to have 25 guys like
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Terry is he's aggressive and intense and he
wants to get down and dirty. Play hard. If it rubs you the wrong
way, what does it matter? Just do your job.... Does he always say
the right things? Probably not. But it's easy to throw darts at the
guy in front.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
