<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHOW METS HOW TO WIN IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As in the Super Bowl, there can be more hype than
substance in the Subway Series, more newsprint and bluster than
worthiness. But Friday night, in the first of this weekend's three
games between the Yankees and Mets, there were four lead changes
and two ties, there was Derek Jeter hitting a titanic home run,
each side maneuvering for the slightest advantage and fans of both
teams shouting each other down.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees clawed for a run in the seventh inning when Scott
Brosius doubled home Tony Tarasco, and then clung to a 4-3 victory
at Yankee Stadium, with their closer, Mariano Rivera, taking over
in the eighth and getting the last four outs for the save.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have won 5 of 7 games against the Mets in three
years of interleague play, are 31-21, and the Mets continue to
plummet. They have lost seven straight games, their longest such
streak since August 1996, when they dropped eight straight, and are
27-27.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the seventh inning, Tarasco pulled a grounder to
the right side. The Mets' infield was positioned perfectly, and
second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo was ready, moving a couple of steps
to his left and preparing to make the play.
</P>
<P>
   But Mets first baseman John Olerud cut in front of Alfonzo and
lunged for a ball that Alfonzo would have fielded easily. The ball
glanced off Olerud's glove and Tarasco was safe with an infield
hit. Brosius then mashed a line drive to left, over the head of
Rickey Henderson. When Henderson rushed toward the wall, the carom
skipped off the fence high and toward the infield, over Henderson's
head once again, giving Tarasco enough time to score the
tie-breaking run.
</P>
<P>
   In its third year, this series includes a familiar cast of
characters, around whom the maelstrom swirls: There is the mayor of
the two-team city who makes no secret of his love for the Yankees,
sitting next to their dugout. There is the principal owner of the
Yankees, George Steinbrenner, who postures as if this series is
meaningless and then sends two of his best scouts to watch the Mets
for nearly two weeks. There is the manager who is often criticized
for being too conspicuous, the Mets' Bobby Valentine, who remained
attached to his bench until the fourth inning, when his innate
curiosity finally drove him to the steps of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' losing streak places the brunt of the pressure on
their shoulders in this series. They must try to fight out of their
slump in the hostile atmosphere of Yankee Stadium, against a team
that has succeeded more than any other over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   That tension grew before the game as veterans Bobby Bonilla and
Brian McRae learned that the Mets had placed them on irrevocable
waivers in recent days, confirmation that the team is ready to dump
both. Valentine and General Manager Steve Phillips both fended off
questions about their intentions regarding Bonilla and McRae for
hours before Friday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   But once the game began and the Yankees' David Cone searched for
his control, the inherent burden of this series was shared. Cone
had trouble establishing his fastball, missing badly with it in the
first two innings, walking the leadoff hitter Henderson on four
pitches. The adrenaline of the Subway Series was probably pumping
through Cone with the alacrity of an express subway, and through
the crowd. When Cone struck out Mike Piazza with two runners on to
stunt a first-inning rally, most of the 56,178 fans roared.
</P>
<P>
   Cone constantly fell behind in the count, throwing a ball to
seven of the first 11 batters he faced, and tried to dig himself
out of trouble with his off-speed and breaking pitches _ his
split-fingered fastball, his curveball and slider. There were
moments when it seemed the Mets' hitters anticipated this.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, McRae fouled off a couple of pitches with
two strikes, and with the count 2 and 2, Cone threw a
split-fingered fastball, shin high _ not a bad pitch, all things
considered. But McRae swung, dropping the thick part of his bat on
the ball and launching it into the stands in right-center field.
When McRae returned to the dugout, he imitated Cone's motion with
the splitter and Bonilla and other teammates nodded: Yeah, I swung
at the same pitch, Bonilla appeared to say.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada slammed a high change-up from Rick Reed for a home
run that tied the score, 1-1, in the bottom of the second, but the
Mets controlled the tempo. Cone threw 46 pitches in the second
inning, and in the third inning, Henderson singled, stole second,
took third when Posada's throw bounced into center field and
eventually scored. Cone needed 22 pitches to get through that mess.
After three innings, he had thrown 68 pitches, Reed just 39.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter turned the momentum and a high fastball from Reed with one
swing in the fifth, with a runner at second and two out. Jeter's
contact was so pure that even if you didn't actually see him swing,
you knew from the sound that the ball was going to go a long, long
way. Reed turned away and grimaced as Jeter's 10th home run of the
year landed in the Yankees' bullpen, 418 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   But this game continued to swing, the Mets countering Jeter's
home run with a two-out rally in the sixth. After a walk and a hit,
the light-hitting Rey Ordonez stretched to poke a Cone slider down
the right-field line. It was a fair ball, one run scored and the
Mets' dugout looked like a playground at recess. Cone was relieved,
having thrown 115 pitches, with the Mets and Yankees tied at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The left field situation continues to be an unsolved mystery for
the Yankees. JOE TORRE indicated that the left-handed-hitting TONY
TARASCO, 28, would be given a chance to establish himself in left
field, probably as a part of a platoon. Tarasco, in the starting
lineup Friday night, is the fourth player to be given a chance to
win a spot in left field, following RICKY LEDEE, CHAD CURTIS, and
SHANE SPENCER, who is fully recovered from food poisoning and
apparently will get more playing time in the days ahead against
left-handed pitchers. The Mets will start AL LEITER Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
