<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTES-EXPORT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE TO CRACK DOWN ON `GRAY MARKET' OF CIGARETTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA _ The calls started coming a few months ago: wholesalers
offering name-brand cigarettes at deep discounts. What's the catch,
asked Matt Yorkston, whose Bellingham-based company owns six
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   The catch was this: The smokes were made for sale only in
foreign countries, but somehow found their way back into the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
   Yorkston was getting a glimpse of the ``gray market,'' a
netherworld of trade and commerce that has skirted legality.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next month, state liquor control agents will seize and
destroy ``export-only'' cigarettes as Washington joins nine other
states trying to shut down the gray market in tobacco. A new law,
signed by Gov. Gary Locke last month, makes it illegal to sell
these cigarettes for domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A similar federal law goes into effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials say they have targeted export-only
cigarettes to protect both consumers and public coffers.
</P>
<P>
   The recent settlement of lawsuits brought by several states
against tobacco makers allocates payments among cigarette
manufacturers based on their share of the domestic market. Payments
would be cut if the companies involved lose market share, and
export cigarettes are not covered by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, meanwhile, may be buying cigarettes that look like
their favorite brands, but have higher levels of tar, nicotine and
additives, state officials said. Cigarettes made for foreign
markets are not subject to the same regulations as those sold in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a major concern,'' said John Hough, a senior assistant
Washington Attorney General.``(Consumers) think they're getting a
better price, but they're getting cigarettes that are much more
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the gray market is unknown, but customs and state
officials and tobacco company representaives say it has exploded
since the national tobacco settlement dramatically increased
domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan McCormick, a spokesman for Philip Morris, the maker of
Marlboro and other leading brands, said complaints about export
cigarettes in the United States have grown from a handful to
several thousand in recent months. State liquor control officials,
who regulate tobacco products, say they have received an increasing
number of calls asking, ``Are they legal?''
</P>
<P>
   The gray market is driven by simple economics: Export cigarettes
are sold at significantly lower prices than are domestic products.
At the wholesale level, dealers can buy them for as much as $10
less per carton, according to one Washington-based gray market
wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesaler, who asked not to be named out of fear legal
action by tobacco companies, detailed how the gray market works.
Customs officials confirmed this account:
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies sell export cigarettes for about $4.60 per
carton. The cigarettes are shipped tax-free to other countries,
held in duty-free warehouses, then re-imported into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Even after state and federal duties and taxes are paid, the
``imported'' smokes wholesale for about $18 per carton, compared
with about $27.25 per carton for legitimate domestic cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The gray market wholesaler can then undercut the domestic price
by a few dollars per carton, and still make a small fortune. One
California dealer reportedly made a $4 million profit on gray
market cigarettes in December alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw the containers (of export cigarettes) coming
into the country,'' recalled the wholesaler, ``I said to myself,
`There's money to be made.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies sell export cigarettes cheaper in part to
compete in foreign markets, where standards of living are often
lower. They're also cheaper because they're not subject to U.S.
regulations or the tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   To pay the $200 billion settlement, tobacco companies raised
prices significantly. Philip Morris, for example, boosted prices
$4.50 per carton.
</P>
<P>
   Most gray market cigarettes sold in Washington come through Los
Angeles, where wholesalers buy them and truck them north, said
Robin Landis, a senior special agent with the U.S. Customs Service
in Seattle. Containers carrying hundreds of thousands of dollars
worth of export cigarettes land in Los Angeles daily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big business,'' he said. ``Real big business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers say that business has gotten too big. Philip
Morris has filed suit in federal court against several Indiana and
Kentucky businesses selling export cigarettes; has refused to sell
directly to wholesalers who deal in the gray market and have
dropped from incentive programs retailers who sell export
cigarettes in the Unites States.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said Philip Morris is most concerned with protecting
its products' quality and trademarks. Export cigarettes are often
damaged by improper storage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Washington wholesaler said the issue has little to do
with quality control or consumer protection. He maintains cigarette
companies are trying to protect domestic profits while states guard
their share of the tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, liquor control officials say the gray market has
been small, but growing. Small convenience and neighborhood stores
around the state occasionally dealt in the export brands, said Gary
Gilbert, the liquor board's enforcement director.
</P>
<P>
   Many Washington businesses say banning gray market cigarettes
will mean fairer competition. Mike Lawrence, of Harbor Wholesale
Grocery in Tumwater, Wash., said the law will probably boost
cigarette sales for companies like his, which won't sell the export
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there was a loophole in the law, it wasn't the
right thing to do,''' Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   Yorkston, the Bellingham store owner, also declines to buy
export cigarettes. As president of the Washington Association of
Neighborhood Stores, which supports the new state law, he was well
aware of issues of quality and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the gray market on one side, and Indian tribes (with
tax exemptions) on the other, and you're trying to compete,''
Yorkston said. ``This will help put most of us retailers on the
same playing field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
