<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-HOTELS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC HOTELS' OCCUPANCY RATE FALLS DESPITE TOURISM BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
 (bl)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the tourist boom, the occupancy rate for New
York City hotels has dropped for the first four months of this year
compared with the same period last year, in part because the
average cost of a night's stay has climbed above $200 and because
more hotels have opened.
</P>
<P>
   But industry experts say the hotel business in New York remains
robust, with the highest occupancy rate in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, hotel room occupancy for January through
April stood at 76.5 percent, compared with 78.8 percent for the
same period last year, according to figures compiled by PKF
Consulting, a company that monitors the hotel industry. But prices
have increased. The average daily room rate was $205.51 for the
first four months of the year, compared with $195.93 during the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Ader, a lodging analyst for Bear, Stearns, said New York's
hotel prices, which are the highest in the country, were depressing
the occupancy rate. ``As a hotel customer you say, `These prices
are exorbitant,''' he said. Whether consumers can expect to see
lower room rates will depend on whether the occupancy rate
continues to go down, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other reasons were cited for the decline in occupancy,
including the recent opening of several new hotels, including the
Benjamin on East 50th Street and and W on East 49th Street, and a
decline in visitors from countries with unfavorable currency
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   But it is too early for the industry to panic, several analysts
said. ``As long as the economy stays strong,'' said Chuck Ross, a
vice president of Smith Travel Research Inc., a Hendersonville,
Tenn., company that tracks industry trends, ``I think that people
will travel, and New York is high on the list of destinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trend has caused some consternation among hotel
executives, who have become accustomed to occupancy rates that have
risen almost every year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dunphy, the director of marketing for the Mark, a hotel on
Madison Avenue whose rates run as high as $475 a night, said:
``What everyone is complaining about is we had such a great year
last year that everyone budgeted relatively aggressively for this
year. You're disappointed when you're not bettering your numbers
every year.'' In May, the Mark had an occupancy rate of 84 percent,
compared with 88 percent for May 1998, Dunphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in occupancy rates has not been accompanied by a
decline in visitors to the city, said Fran Reiter, president of the
New York Convention and Visitors Bureau. She said that about 35
million people are expected to visit the city this year, up from an
estimated 34.1 million last year. (A visitor is defined as anyone
who comes to New York from more than 50 miles away, even just for
the day, who is not commuting to work.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Reiter said that fewer visitors were coming from some of
what she described as ``key feeder markets'' such as Germany,
Brazil, Japan and Canada. The loss of tourists from those countries
is being more than offset by the domestic market, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do not view this small drop-off as being anything
terribly serious,'' Ms. Reiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Giesbert, a vice president of New York and Connecticut
Marriott Lodging, which operates or manages 10 hotels in New York,
said the expanding supply of rooms accounted for what he described
as ``minute decline'' in business. Marriott alone added 1,000 rooms
in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   And more hotel rooms are coming. Even so, no one expects the
hotel market to become oversaturated. John Fox, a senior vice
president of PKF, the firm that tracks the hotel industry, said
that about two dozen new hotels are expected to open by 2002, but
the city might be able to support even more, depending on where
they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still under-hoteled,'' Ms. Reiter said. ``There are
times of the year when the occupancy rates go through the roof.''
In particular, the city needs more moderately priced rooms, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hotel market has softened, Dexter Wood Jr., a
senior manager at PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting firm,
predicted that the industry would do very well during the final
quarter of the year _ historically its strongest period _
especially because of the excitement over the Year 2000. In fact,
he said, the market may already be bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get a hotel room in New York last week,'' he
said, ``and I couldn't get one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
