r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-HARASSMENT-KAN &LR;      06-05 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-HARASSMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS FILE SEXUAL HARASSMENT SUITS AGAINST ACADEMY, AREA
SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Three Missouri
students filed federal lawsuits in Kansas City on Friday alleging
that fellow students sexually harassed and humiliated them and that
their school administrators did little or nothing to stop it. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lawsuits against the Wentworth Military Academy and the
Pleasant Hill and Richmond school districts were filed less than
two weeks after a U.S. Supreme Court ruling opened the door to
similar lawsuits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, courts are likely to see many more, said Elinor
Schroeder, who teaches discrimination law at the University of
Kansas School of Law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have the Supreme Court clarifying or defining an
area and holding that plaintiffs can recover money damages, there's
going to be a lot of interest at first,'' Schroeder said. ``The
mere publicity of the suits will generate more suits.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City lawyer Katherine Argent, who is representing the
students, said the high court's ruling and the lawsuits will send a
message to educators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly tells the school they can't turn their backs
anymore and talk about budget constraints,'' Argent said. ``A lot
of the juvenile violence we've seen these days is because
discipline has been low.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richmond Superintendent Lindell Harrison said he had not seen
the lawsuit and could not comment on it. However, he said teachers
and administrators in Richmond are required to intervene in
student-on-student sexual harassment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If a student feels she's being harassed, she's got to tell
someone,'' Harrison said. ``We try to resolve these issues at the
(school) building level. If it's not resolved at that level, we
move it up the chain.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Col. Mike Lierman, vice president for operations at the
Lexington, Mo., military academy, declined to comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Mitch Hanna of the Pleasant Hill School District
could not be reached for comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits, filed separately, allege that: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Wentworth officials failed to notify police or the mother of a
14-year-old girl that she had been sexually assaulted by five
classmates in a school stairwell. The school suspended all five but
eventually allowed two of the cadets to return. One of those cadets
continued to harass the girl, who eventually attempted suicide. She
remains in psychological counseling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Pleasant Hill school officials did nothing effective to stop
the harassment of a 14-year-old boy who other students believed was
gay. Over four years, the boy was called names in the school
cafeteria and corridors, beaten and nearly run over by a car driven
by two classmates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While a school official spoke with some of the students who were
harassing the boy, ``the harassment of plaintiff only
intensified,'' the lawsuit said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The boy sought psychological counseling for depression and
eventually quit public schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Richmond administrators waited a week to discipline a student
for sexually humiliating a high school girl in front of students,
teachers and administrators. A boy pulled down the girl's pants and
underwear in a gymnasium. The boy then grabbed his crotch and made
a crude suggestion to the girl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit does not specify what disciplinary measures school
officials eventually took against the boy but said it was not
expulsion. Other students began to harass the girl after the
incident and she sought psychological counseling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, her parents moved from the district. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year Argent represented a 16-year-old Ruskin Heights girl
who complained that school administrators did nothing to stop
months of sexual harassment by a classmate. That case eventually
was settled out of court for $10,000, with the Hickman Mills School
District denying any liability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits filed Friday seek between $10.3 million and $18.7
million in damages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If schools can feel it in their pocketbooks we can expect to
see these kinds of problem behaviors really clamped down on,''
Argent said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
