A4006 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-EVIDENCE-KAN &LR;      06-05 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-EVIDENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S THIRD MURDER TRIAL IN TROUBLE BECAUSE OF MISSING EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENITA Y. WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Prosecutors have
twice tried to convict Clarence Dexter of murdering his wife. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dexter's first trial ended in a mistrial. A murder verdict in
his second trial was overturned by the Missouri Supreme Court
because lawyers talked in court about how Dexter was silent when
arrested. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the third trial, set to begin Monday in Clay County, is in
trouble because prosecutors cannot find a police 911 tape, samples
of a T-shirt Dexter allegedly wore the night of his wife's murder,
bullet fragments from the autopsy and a newspaper with a bloody
footprint. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are nervous and the victim's family is angry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dexter is accused of shooting his 50-year-old wife, Carol
Dexter, four times at their Kansas City, North, home on Nov. 18,
1990. He then allegedly went to a supermarket. When he returned,
Dexter allegedly saw that his wife was not dead and then beat her
with a hammer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dexter, 57, has contended that he discovered his wife's body
after returning from the supermarket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers discovered the evidence was missing earlier this
spring when they wanted to have their own scientists compare the
bloody footprint to Dexter's shoe. When the lawyers opened an
evidence bag, they found several pieces of newspaper, but the
bloodied newspaper was gone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That prompted an inventory of the case's evidence, and it was
then that several critical items were discovered missing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special prosecutors Tim Finnical and Victoria Thomas have
searched for the evidence in the Kansas City Police Department
property room, the Clay County prosecutor's property room and the
Missouri attorney general's office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole family is upset. We want justice served,'' said the
victim's brother, Olan Thrasher. ``Evidently their filing system is
not too good.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thrasher, however, said he has confidence in the prosecutors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have a lot of evidence,'' Thrasher said. ``I just
hope these (missing) two or three pieces don't jeopardize the whole
case.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a pretrial hearing last month, Kansas City Regional Crime Lab
criminologist John Wilson said the evidence might have gotten
scrambled during one of Dexter's earlier trials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Dexter's first trial in July 1991, the jury deliberated more
than eight hours without reaching a verdict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A jury in his second trial in October 1991 convicted him. A Clay
County judge sentenced Dexter to execution after the jury could not
decide between death and life without parole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was overturned in 1997 by the Missouri Supreme
Court. The high court ruled unanimously that Dexter's 14th
Amendment right of due process was violated because lawyers talked
in court about how Dexter was silent after he was arrested and read
his rights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The missing evidence will make next week's trial much different
than Dexter's earlier trials, said Cyndy Short, a public defender
on Dexter's defense team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short said Dexter's link to the crime is weakened without the
evidence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the 911 tape contains Dexter's call to the
police after his wife's death. The shirt samples contain blood
stains that could show whether Dexter was present during the murder
or whether he bloodied his clothes when he discovered his wife's
body, prosecutors said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the pretrial hearing, defense forensic consultant Gene
Gietzen said a picture of the bloody footprint did not appear to
match Dexter's shoes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have done better analysis if the newspaper had been
preserved,'' Gietzen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How the clothing samples and the bullet fragments were handled
in the Dexter case also was discussed at the hearing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson the criminologist said in 1991 Clay County prosecutors
often had lab technicians bring lab samples to a trial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said other area prosecutors only asked for the lab reports
and the actual evidence. Lab samples, such as the clothing samples
and the bullet fragments, remain at the lab. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Remnants stay in the lab frozen so you can test them later,''
Wilson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clay County prosecutor's office spokesman Jim Roberts said that
at the time of Dexter's earlier trials, the office usually kept
evidence until the police asked for it. Murder case evidence was
returned to the police immediately after trial, Roberts said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new practice is that the agency that brings the evidence
is the one to bring it to trial and to take it back,'' Roberts
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said what might have happened is that the lab samples
might have been mixed with other evidence and mistakenly returned
to the Kansas City Police Department. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson testified that lab records showed that additional bullet
fragments collected at the Dexter crime scene were checked out from
the lab by a former assistant prosecutor, but the record did not
show that the fragments were ever returned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, those fragments recently were found mixed with other
evidence in the case in the police property room, said Tom
Jacquinot, a public defender on Dexter's defense team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
