<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE LOSES 2 KEY FUND-RAISING AIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES AND CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Two top fund-raisers have left the campaign of GOP presidential
hopeful Dan Quayle, one of several signals that he's having money
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The finance staff members resigned last week, apparently after
the former vice president became unhappy with the level of large
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Departing were Jennifer Hodges, Quayle's aide in charge of
seeking out large donors, and a deputy to Hodges, Liesl Hickey.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges and Hickey, who handled Quayle's Midwestern fund-raising
operation, confirmed that they quit but would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle aides would not discuss the departures, but did say that
Quayle has had to tinker with his money-raising strategy to survive
in a packed field.
</P>
<P>
   One consultant has estimated that a candidate will need $20
million to compete in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The ante has been upped by two Republican candidates _ Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, who has raised huge sums, and billionaire
Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how much money Quayle has raised. In the first
quarter, he garnered $2.1 million, but reported that he wound up in
the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months ago, almost all campaigns took assessment of
the fund-raising environment and made changes,'' Quayle spokesman
Jonathan Baron said. ``We made adjustments, given the realities of
the fund-raising environment.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential hopeful Lamar Alexander said this week that he
was dumping legal and press staffers wholesale and drastically
cutting his travel budget. He said he did so to allow his campaign
to make it through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Baron said Quayle has also ``deferred'' some campaign plans and
made other staff alterations in an effort to accommodate the new
realities of fund-raising _ that candidates need to spend more
money and spend it earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's difficulties are all the more striking because he spent
nearly four years building up what appeared to be a formidable
fundraising network, according to one campaign finance expert.
</P>
<P>
   As director of Campaign America from 1995 to 1998, Quayle
traveled the country nurturing potential donors, said Paul Hendrie,
communications director of the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason that Quayle and Alexander are hurt is that
their whole approach was built on being successful fund-raisers,``
Hendrie said. ``They had really worked for years creating the
infrastructure to raise money and the fact that Bush has been able
to come in and suck away the money has really hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle was to meet Friday with his media consultant, Fred Davis,
to map out new strategies for mining contributions.
</P>
<P>
   According to Davis, the candidate must find an entirely new set
of donors in order to overcome the Bush handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush tied the early large donors up long before anyone knew he
was going to do anything, and that was very clever,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis declined to say just how Quayle would outfox his
opponents, but promised that he would be good at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to work harder, think harder and think
out of the box,'' he said. ``And the good thing about Quayle is
that he's a good out-of-the-box thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also has been trying to tap large donors who have already
given to Bush, said Quayle's pollster, Kellyanne Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Quayle campaign is doing is going back to some of the
major donors and saying, `You gave to George W. Bush and that's
great. But you know what, you are restricted to the dollar amount
but not in the number of candidates you can give to,' ''
Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, who live in Paradise Valley, have
also been working the phones to gain donors, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Quayle acknowledged the difficulty of
raising money against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely the big sucking machine down there,'' Quayle
said. ``But we will have enough money to get our message out.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Quayle hasn't sparked much excitement in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   In national polls, he has single-digit support. He also lagged
in a recent Rocky Mountain Poll of Maricopa County Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That poll showed Bush leading with 30 percent, followed by Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., with 26 percent, and former Red Cross head
Elizabeth Dole with 12 percent, just ahead of Quayle, with 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover in Quayle's finance department comes despite his
second-place showing in the fund-raising race during the first
quarter of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle raised $2.1 million, second only to Bush's $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, Quayle had greater debts than cash, according to
Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   The big outlay is mostly due to Quayle's decision to focus on
potential donors using direct mail. That strategy calls for hefty
early spending to build a mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   The Quayle consultant in charge of direct mail said the
candidate's list of 35,000 names will begin paying off in the
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct mail is very costly upfront with a big payoff in the
end,'' said Richard Norman, a Virginia-based consultant. ``The file
is growing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the whole fund-raising phenomenon,
everyone thinks of New Hampshire as the first primary,'' Hendrie
said. ``But really, the first primary is this fund-raising
sweepstakes. That determines whether you even get to the
primaries.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
