r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-05 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS TRADE WITH CHINA GOOD U.S. POLICY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   The most controversial economic
issue of the Clinton administration's final chapter isn't likely to
be tax reform or Social Security, but the future of America's
commercial relationship with China. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all goes as expected, President Clinton is expected to push
both for an extension of China's most favored nation trade status
and its membership in the World Trade Organization. WTO entry would
lead to a congressional vote on permanent most favored nation
status for Beijing to comply with WTO rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most favored status is an anachronistic misnomer, because all it
means is that normal trade relations will be maintained with the
nation granted such recognition. It confers no particularly special
privileges. Nevertheless, the debate over whether to continue
normal economic relations with China will be acrimonious, because
many conservatives will advocate withdrawal from Clinton's policy
of constructive engagement with Beijing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent editorial in The Weekly Standard, for instance, called
it a failed policy of appeasement, under a headline exhorting the
administration to ``Call Off the Engagement.'' The arguments
offered are convincing. Since the last vote to maintain normal
relations, China has been caught stealing U.S. nuclear secrets, has
encouraged its citizens to burn American flags and stone the U.S.
Embassy, has imprisoned more of its political enemies, and has
continued its saber-rattling against Taiwan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The editorial took note of how Ronald Reagan challenged the
premises of U.S.-Soviet relations in a way that eventually led, in
the interim, to better relations and, ultimately, to the demise of
what Reagan called ``the evil empire.'' While conservatives of like
minds no doubt see a similar opportunity, the situation isn't quite
the same. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While China is no doubt committed to an adversarial relationship
with America when it suits its aims, its leadership hasn't
formalized a policy designed to ``bury'' the United States.
Meanwhile, it has shown serious signs of recognizing the benefits
of market economics, which the Soviets never seriously
acknowledged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the political reality is that even relatively
conservative Republicans aren't likely to muster the gumption to
abandon the status quo. They may slam Clinton for playing footsie
with Beijing, but when push comes to shove, most Capitol Hill
GOPsters will go along with the bid to keep China in the commercial
fold. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, this isn't an entirely negative
outcome, no matter the odiousness of China's regime. Sure, it's a
nasty, brutish bunch with no particular love for America, but
what's the alternative? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My favorite quote concerning trade is that as long as goods are
allowed to cross borders, armies won't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some abhor continued efforts to build a business relationship
with China as the work of running dogs of American capitalism.
Pushing comity with China is the work of Big Business in its
unprincipled quest for profit, some might argue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   True or not, though, it's also irrelevant. The world is in many
ways a more dangerous place today than it was at the height of the
Cold War. Any policy moves fashioned to promote geopolitical
tranquillity will prove the best moves. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIP-MERCY-SPI &LR;      06-05 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIP-MERCY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL SHIP HEADED FOR NORTH KOREA KNOWS NO BORDERS OR POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Capt. John Fadely and his 160-member crew weigh
anchor at Seattle's Bell Street Pier on Sunday, their course to
North Korea will be charted with the aid of two compasses: One
guided by magnetism, the other by mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Fadely, a veteran merchant mariner, is skipper of the Caribbean
Mercy, a former Norwegian ferry that is now one of the ``Mercy
Ships,'' floating hospitals operated by a Christian humanitarian
organization.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, the Caribbean Mercy has been on the Seattle
waterfront, its volunteer crew hoisting aboard more than 100 tons
of donated medical supplies and pharmaceuticals, 50 tons of rice,
and things such as underwear, infant formula and toys for a North
Korean orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away in the pile are bears hand-made by a Victoria, B.C.,
senior citizens' group.
</P>
<P>
   The visit, the first in decades for a Western hospital ship,
happens to coincide with the highest level U.S. diplomatic
delegation to visit North Korea in a half-century. The mission is
led by former U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and South Korean officials say as many as 3 million North
Koreans have died in four years of famine. Officials in both Koreas
say international humanitarian aid, which is not forbidden by trade
embargoes, contributes to peace and stability on the Korean
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean Mercy flies a Panamanian flag and its largely
evangelical Christian crew has 20 different passports, but borders
and politics mean little to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We serve the poorest of the poor,'' said the ship's executive
officer, Brett Curtis, a New Zealander who, with a wife and four
children, left a job exporting kiwi fruit 15 years ago to join the
Mercy Ship missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation with us is to give away compassion because it's
the right thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said Mercy Ships was asked by the North Korean government
to drop off relief supplies while en route to South Korea. The
visit will be short _ two weeks _ but the ship's doctors expect to
perform 50 eye surgeries and 20 orthopedic surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   For crewman Ilchul Cho, a South Korean, the stop has special
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a miracle to a South Korean to be able to go
there to North Korea,'' said Cho, 24, who joined the crew in
February. North Korea and its people have existed only in his
imagination, across a war-scarred, no-man's land border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we are just delivering rice and medicine and doing
eye surgeries, it's still exciting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercy Ships ministry was founded in 1978 by Don and Deyon
Stephens, of Ft. Worth, Texas, as a way to spread messages of peace
and hope. In the past 17 years, doctors from the three-ship fleet
have provided medical care for nearly 100,000 people and performed
thousands of operations on impoverished people who never dreamed
they would have access to modern medicine. Surgeries range from
correcting cleft palates, crossed eyes or cataracts to full facial
reconstructions.
</P>
<P>
   The ships have delivered more than 14 million pounds of goods
ranging from medical supplies and seeds to a fire engine. Crew
members have helped build hospitals, homes, schools, churches,
community centers and other projects, while teaching health classes
and training local doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask `Why are you doing this for free?' I always
answer `Because the Lord loves you,''' said Second Officer Kathy
Shankle, a California Maritime Academy graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was born again, the 47-year-old, 262-foot Caribbean
Mercy was the Norwegian ferry Polar Lys (Lights).
</P>
<P>
   From captain to ordinary seamen, all crew members are
volunteers, many supported by individual churches. The ship
operates on about $1.3 million a year, largely offset by donations
and goodwill. The Port of Seattle, for example, donated moorage for
the ship's stay here. International Longshore and Warehouse Union
Local 19 members donated labor, while Shurgard Storage discounted
storage space, said port spokesman Imbert Matthee.
</P>
<P>
   For Marco Estrada, 24, a Costa Rican, the volunteer work is an
opportunity to give back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about doing this, and for going to North Korea,
particularly because I lived through poverty, starvation, in my
life and I know how the people we help are feeling,'' said Estrada,
a two-year veteran deckhand and translator. ``I enjoy helping and
sharing what God has given me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
