<SLUG> BC-FORT-RILEY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVISION FLAG IS BACK AT ARMY'S FORT RILEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   After losing the 1st Infantry
Division four years ago, Fort Riley near Junction City, Kan., will
become the official headquarters today of the Army's mechanized
24th Infantry Division. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ceremony activating the division, which is made up of 12,000
active duty and National Guard soldiers, is at 10 a.m. at the
post's Cavalry Parade Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attending the event will be Army dignitaries and politicians,
including Gen. Thomas Schwartz, the U.S. Army Forces Command
commanding general; retired Gen. Barry McCaffrey, former division
commander during Desert Storm and currently director of the Office
of National Drug Control Policy; U.S. Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas;
and U.S. Rep. Jim Ryun of Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, along with other members of the Kansas delegation, had
been working to bring a new division to the post and better
integrate the active Army and National Guard and reserve units. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go over to Bosnia or Kosovo or the Mideast, you'll see
a lot of deployed National Guard and active reserves,'' Roberts
said. ``In 90 days, this unit can go anywhere in the world. It's
more mobile. This is a pretty exciting time for Fort Riley, because
it's on the crest of the wave on this (integration).'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deb Skidmore, an Army spokeswoman, said Junction City would
become home for the division's headquarters staff of more than 100.
They will command National Guard infantry brigades in North
Carolina, South Carolina and Georgia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The division is one of two that integrate Army National Guard
units. The other unit, the 7th Infantry Division, is based at Fort
Carson in Colorado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1st Infantry Division, known as the Big Red One, left
Fort Riley, the post has seen its manpower shrink from 15,000 to
10,500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the 24th Infantry Division will add only 140 command staff
personnel at most, Skidmore said, its National Guard units will add
to those numbers when they send soldiers to the fort for training
stints. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 24th Division, nicknamed the Victory Division, was formed in
1941 in Hawaii just before Pearl Harbor was bombed. It saw action
in World War II, Korea and the Persian Gulf. It's motto is ``First
to Fight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unit was deactivated in 1996 as part of the Army's effort to
reduce the number of divisions to 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will be led by Maj. Gen. Freddy McFarren, who is also Fort
Riley's commander. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
