<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT WITNESS OFFERS TESTIMONY IN SLEEPWALKING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle of the sleep experts began Friday in Scott Falater's
murder trial as a specialist in sleep disorders said the former
Motorola engineer was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Janet Tatman said that after evaluating four nights
of sleep studies performed on Falater, ``My opinion became that the
best explanation for what happened was that Mr. Falater was
sleepwalking at the time that his wife was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatman's testimony, sprinkled with references to REM sleep,
slow-wave sleep, polysomnograms and parasomnia, wrapped up the
trial's second week of testimony. It provided the jury with the
first of what will be several seminars on the mechanics of human
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Tatman testified that sleep researchers have documented many
cases of violent attacks by sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   She described several such cases, including one involving a man
who rammed his car into two women who had sought his assistance as
he slept in his car by the side of a road.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsing the defense theory that Falater was probably fixing a
backyard pool pump in his sleep when his wife came upon him, Tatman
said sleepwalkers often lash out when they are interrupted in the
middle of a task.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible to trigger a violent reaction by interfering
with them,'' Tatman said.
</P>
<P>
   Persons injured by sleepwalkers, she said, often ``just happen
to have been at the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatman said that at the time Falater admittedly killed his wife,
he was struggling with severe job-related stress and sleep
deprivation _ characteristics she said are common among
sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   She said that her study of Falater's background showed a
personal history of sleepwalking and that her evaluation of sleep
tests administered to Falater at St. Luke's Behavioral Health
Services showed his sleep patterns were consistent with
sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Tatman's testimony will resume Monday, when she faces
cross-examination from prosecutor Juan Martinez. Then the defense
will present more experts before the prosecution counters with its
own scientific team.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony about sleep, though, appeared to make some jurors
sleepy. One panelist told another during the afternoon break that
she was having a hard time staying awake.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the trial took a unusual turn as normally
circumspect Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Ronald Reinstein
ridiculed a witness who last week testified for the defense but
later offered new information to the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Randy Keadle in the absence of the jury,
Reinstein said Keadle was offering insubstantial hearsay about
alleged flaws in the defense case, which is presenting Falater as
an unflappable engineer and devout Mormon who had no reason to kill
his high school sweetheart and wife of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Keadle's courtroom appearance Friday came eight days after he
had testified as a character witness for Falater, a former
colleague at Motorola. After being flown from his current home in
France at the defense's expense, Keadle vouched for Falater as ``a
very peaceful man'' whose attack on his wife contradicted
everything his friends knew about him.
</P>
<P>
   With the jury out of the courtroom so that Reinstein could
evaluate the significance of the new information, Keadle said he
had heard that Falater had once dragged his daughter by the hair
and _ shortly before killing his wife _ had talked with co-workers
about a Canadian man whose sleepwalking defense won him acquittal
after he stabbed his mother-in-law to death.
</P>
<P>
   Under aggressive questioning from defense attorney Mike Kimerer,
Keadle acknowledged that he had no personal knowledge of either
event. He said he heard of the alleged abuse from his wife, who had
apparently heard of it from the mother of a friend of 17-year-old
Megan Falater.
</P>
<P>
   The third- or fourth-hand testimony exasperated Reinstein, who
said it was nothing more than ``hearsay on hearsay on hearsay _ and
maybe on hearsay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this before,'' Reinstein said.
``I almost feel like I'm in the ``National Inquirer'' or the
``Star'' or the ``Globe'' or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Martinez, who said Keadle ``wanted to do the right
thing,'' is expected to call other witnesses with direct knowledge
of the events Keadle discussed. Those witnesses would likely
testify in two weeks as Martinez presents his rebuttal witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The trial likely will wrap up before the end of June. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
