<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-KICKBACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT FINDS IN FAVOR OF THREE LAWYERS IN MEDICARE KICKBACK CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   A federal judge said in a ruling
released Friday that he found no evidence that three lawyers named
as unindicted co-conspirators in a Medicare kickback case tried in
Kansas City, Kan., had been involved in criminal activity. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the ruling, U.S. District Judge John W. Lungstrum also
repeated statements he made during the trial that the evidence
indicated that the lawyers had appropriately advised their clients
to engage in legal transactions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, the judge declined to take the further legal step of
making factual findings related to the innocence of Gina Kaiser, a
Health Midwest lawyer, and David Queen and Craig Holden, Baltimore
lawyers specializing in health-care matters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their names first became public as unindicted co-conspirators in
a pretrial motion filed by the government in a Medicare kickback
case against two Johnson County, Kan., physicians, three former
Baptist Medical Center executives and two other Kansas City, Mo.,
health-care lawyers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The physicians and two of the three hospital executives were
found guilty by a jury in April. The other hospital executive was
acquitted. The two other lawyers were acquitted by Lungstrum after
the close of the government's case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Kaiser, Queen and Holden were named as unindicted
co-conspirators came out again during the nine-week trial. Kaiser
testified in the trial, and documents involving Queen and Holden
were introduced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a sealed motion, the three asked that their names be cleared
and expunged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an order sealed since it was filed May 7, Lungstrum said the
government violated the due process rights of the three lawyers by
revealing their names in its pretrial motion. The motion should
have been filed under seal, the judge said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the government had a right and ``a substantial interest'' in
identifying the three lawyers as unindicted co-conspirators at
trial, he ruled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lungstrum ordered the three lawyers' names stricken from the
government's pretrial motion, but he denied a request that they be
expunged from the trial record. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
