<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REDSOXBRAVES-BOS &LR;      06-05 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOXBRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American League, National League, interleague, it doesn't make
any difference to Pedro Martinez, who elevated the bar on his own
magnificence last night by striking out a career-best 16 in a
three-hit, 5-1 win over the Atlanta Braves in a Fenway Park
teetering on pandemonium.
</P>
<P>
   How about a league of his own?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Nintendo tonight,'' said Red Sox second baseman Jeff
Frye after Martinez raised his record to 11-1 with his ninth
straight victory. He is the majors' only pitcher with double-digit
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing he can throw that hard and have that good a
control. He made a lot of good hitters look bad tonight. You know a
guy has very good stuff when that happens, because they've got a
good lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the best-pitched games I've ever been involved
in.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as it was, remarkably, it wasn't the most whiffs by a
Braves team against a member of the Martinez family. It was,
however, their most strikeouts since Ramon Martinez of the Dodgers
struck out 18 Braves June 4, 1990, exactly nine years ago Friday,
in a 6-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   Billerica's Tom Glavine, who took the loss Friday night in his
second start in his backyard, was the loser against Ramon, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first time I saw Pedro,'' said Atlanta manager
Bobby Cox. ``He was pitching for the Dodgers in relief, and I said,
`My God, he looks like he's throwing 130 miles an hour and weighs
about 140 pounds.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his arm was going to fly off. But he's gotten bigger
and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smooth. He doesn't stress his delivery. (Pitching coach
Joe) Kerrigan has done a super job. He's had him forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who lowered his earned run average to 1.91, best in
the majors, gave up a leadoff single to Javy Lopez in the second, a
leadoff double to Andruw Jones in the fifth, and lost his shutout
when Ryan Klesko curled his seventh home run around the Pesky Pole
with one out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out at least one batter in every inning, and ended
seven of his nine innings with a K, which guaranteed him a frenzied
reaction from the sellout crowd of 33,411 each time he slowly made
his way back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which included Cardinal Bernard Law, was never
happier than in the ninth, when Martinez, who had thrown 104
pitches through eight, headed back to the mound to put the
finishing touches on his second complete game. He struck out
Chipper Jones for his 15th whiff, matching the career best he'd
achieved twice this season. Brian Jordan was caught looking for No.
16. Javy Lopez then had two strikes on him before grounding out to
third baseman John Valentin to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a professional hitter,'' said Chipper Jones, the All-Star
third baseman who played for the Florida state championship in
Little League against Sox catcher Jason Varitek and lost that one,
too. ``I feel like no matter who is out there, how good they are,
I'm going to get them every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I realize there are some days that no matter how good you
are, somebody out there will be better than you. And tonight, I
think Pedro was better than anybody in our dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who retired the last eight Braves, struck out every
batter in the Atlanta lineup at least once. He struck out cleanup
hitter Jordan four times. He struck out Gerald Williams, the No. 9
hitter, three times. When he had a runner on third and no outs in
the fifth after Jones's double and a wild pitch, he struck out
Randall Simon and Williams and put away Walt Weiss on a pop to
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best pitcher in the game, man,'' said Jordan, shaking
his head. ``It's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm wasn't confined to the seats. Up in the Sox
broadcast booth, Hall of Famer-to-be Dennis Eckersley, filling in
for Jerry Remy, was doing enough fist-pumping for both pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the most dominating games I've ever seen,'' said
Eckersley, who was in Oakland in 1990 when Bob Welch won 27 games,
the high-water mark for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was styling for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who were swept in three games when the Braves first
returned to the city of their roots two years ago, gave Martinez
all the cushion he would need in the first, the inning in which
Glavine historically is most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin walked on four pitches and Nomar Garciaparra
followed with a Wall double. When Glavine fell behind Mike Stanley,
2-and-0, he elected to walk the Sox cleanup hitter intentionally,
but Troy O'Leary crossed up that strategy by reaching out and
slapping an 0-and-2 pitch through the left side, scoring Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Buford followed with another single, the first of three
hits for the center fielder. He later doubled and scored on Frye's
two-out single in the third, and homered off reliever Justin Speier
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we could have won that game is 1-0,'' said
Glavine, who has won more games than any lefty this decade, claimed
his second Cy Young Award last season when he led the National
League with 20 wins, but already this season has lost more games
(7) than he did in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most nights you hold a team to four runs or less, you win,''
said Glavine, who departed after seven innings with a yield of
eight hits, two walks, and four runs. ``But not tonight. Not
against Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, now 33-20, went 13 games over .500 for the first time
this season by winning for the 21st time in the last 27 games.
Martinez, of course, is 10 over the break-even point all by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams was talking about Martinez's changeup when
he said it, but he could have been talking about the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like magic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Yawkey Way, on the loveliest of June nights, only a fool _ or
a Brave _ would call it anything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
