r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-05 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE PANIC PLANNED IN DOUGLAS COUNTY AS Y2K GETS CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   It's New Year's. News broadcasts
stream in from across the globe as the Y2K bug marches through time
zones toward Lawrence, Kan. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computerized train switches have stalled an Amtrak train at the
depot for two hours. More than 150 fidgety passengers are growing
restless as security officers fear for the safety of a high-profile
dignitary on board. Across town, a nursing home has been without
power for six hours and the water has dried up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gas is selling for $12 a gallon. Chlorine smells are being
reported in a nearby community, and six bodies have been found at a
campsite, victims of a Y2K suicide pact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a bomb threat at the water plant, and a woman is about
to give birth in a second-floor tavern surrounded by 10,000 New
Year's revelers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Millennium Madness,'' a June 22 Y2K disaster
exercise being planned by the Lawrence-Douglas County Y2K Community
Information Task Force. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is a test. This is only a test. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with seven months to go before Jan. 1, it's one of the more
creative Y2K disaster drills being planned across the country.
Police officers, firefighters and utility workers will get a chance
to test their ability to react to a cascade of hypothetical,
worst-case Y2K problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the drill, ``A lot of people will be excited, a lot of
people will be panicking and a lot of people will be trying to do
whatever they can to take advantage of a lot of vulnerable
people,'' said Paula Phillips, director of the Douglas County
emergency management office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to prepare for what kind of mischief we think the
public will be up to that night and how might they make life
difficult for emergency responders.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The June 22 drill, which simulates the time frame from 11 p.m.
Dec. 31 to 2 a.m. Jan. 1, begins with fictitious East Coast
newscasts streaming into a unified command center. There, 45
service-sector representatives from the Lawrence area will react to
whatever surprises Phillips throws at them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fictitious weather reports call for an unseasonably warm 55
degrees in January ``that's going to bring people out of the
woodwork,'' she said. And because Kansas has allowed the sale of
fireworks from Dec. 28 to Jan. 1, the drill calls for the rocket's
red glare of year 2000 pyrotechnics bursting in air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drill will end with a live media briefing to interject a
sense of realism from on-deadline reporters clamoring for the
story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Douglas County task force, which has caught the attention of
the White House and is featured in a federal guide to Y2K community
preparation, will follow the drill with a countywide summit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similar drills are being planned in Johnson County, Kan., on
Oct. 13 and Shawnee County, Kan., on July 22. Both drills will be
based on the assumption that Y2K will cause a three-day disruption
in key services. &QL; 
Money in the bank &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``your money is safe with us'' report is coming from
Robert Parry, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of San
Francisco. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For months now, banks and federal regulators have been trying to
calm fears that bank computer failures and automated teller machine
shutdowns will keep Americans from their money on Jan. 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not going to happen, Parry said Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 98 percent of the Federal Reserve's ``critical'' computer
systems are Y2K-ready, Parry said. And 97 percent of U.S. banks are
``making satisfactory progress'' toward meeting Y2K deadlines, he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the probabilities are very high that on Jan. 1, 2000,
nothing very unusual is going to happen,'' Parry said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. this week said only 200 of
the nation's 10,379 federally insured banks and thrifts were behind
in Y2K preparation. Only 19 banks are rated as making
``unsatisfactory'' progress, the FDIC said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The number of banks rated as ``needing to improve'' has dropped
by about 50 percent since late March, when the FDIC issued its last
report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, during a speech in San Francisco, Parry said Y2K could
cause some economic problems in 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parry said spending by U.S. companies getting ready for the year
2000 problem might increase in the last six months of 1999 but drop
during the year 2000 as a result. He said the nation's gross
domestic product might go up by less than a percentage point this
year but drop by the same amount next year. &QL; 
Green light for Yellow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Freight System is the first major local company to report
that it is Y2K-ready. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased to report that our computer systems are ready
for the new millennium well ahead of time,'' said Yellow Freight
President Bill Zollars. ``Our focus has been both on our own
systems and equipment as well as those of key suppliers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zollars said Y2K work had been completed on the company's
critical mainframe and its client/server computer systems. Computer
code fixes and testing were completed March 31, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the year, Yellow Freight will complete
contingency plans, retest systems for Y2K compliance and do further
Y2K reviews of key suppliers, Zollars said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Freight began its Y2K program in 1995. &QL; 
Cramming for Y2K &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, a group of Kansas City, Mo., and national
agencies is sponsoring Y2K ``how to'' workshops for businesses in
Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on the idea that the year 2000 problem could affect
everything from company phone systems to farm machinery, the
workshops will tell business owners how to assess their risk,
develop contingency plans and troubleshoot computer systems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area workshops are scheduled for June 15, 24,
and 29. Titled ``How to Meet the Y2K Challenge,'' the workshops are
being sponsored by the U.S. Small Business Administration,
Mid-America Manufacturing Technology Center, University Outreach
and Extension, and other agencies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuition is $59. The workshops run from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at (888) 679-4333. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
