u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ KING OF HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the few times all night anyone caught up to him.
Pedro Martinez was walking through the Red Sox clubhouse Friday
night when Dennis Eckersley stopped him. The former pitcher hugged
the current one, let him go, then hugged him again. And that was
the restrained Eck.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he stood a few feet away from Martinez, pointing and
mentioning the great Sandy Koufax. No one flinched at the
reference. Martinez is that good. And since he is only 27, he may
not be as good as we think _ he's probably better.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out 16 Braves and held them to three hits in a
5-1 win at Fenway Park. The strikeouts are a career high, one more
than he had in consecutive starts last month against the Mariners
and Angels. Please, take a pause here for perspective. The Mariners
have Ken Griffey Jr. and Edgar Martinez. The Angels have Mo Vaughn
and Tim Salmon. The Braves have Chipper and Andruw Jones, Brian
Jordan, and Javy Lopez. You don't strike those guys out like they
are a group of Double A kids learning the art of hitting. Not
unless you are Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no (expletive) idea where he was throwing,'' said the
giddy Eck. ``No idea. It was one of the most dominant performances
I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   If you had recited the following numbers before the season and
said Martinez would have them on June 5, someone would have told
you to go in a corner and deal with yourself until you stopped
talking silly: 11-1, 1.91 earned run average, eight
10-or-more-strikeout games (his total from all of last season), and
18 walks.
</P>
<P>
   I do not claim to have an eighth of Joe Torre's baseball
knowledge. But I would hope there is at least a Post-It on the
Yankee manager's refrigerator, a reminder to pencil in Martinez to
start the All-Star Game here next month. I obviously do not work in
the American League office, but I hope the person in charge of the
engraving for the Cy Young Award is keeping up with all of
Martinez's information. Friday night's win was his ninth in a row.
He has done this while bothered by a sore hip and sore knee. He was
jokingly asked if the hip bothered him Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe it,'' he said, ``but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does a completely healthy Martinez do, throw and catch
his own pitches? You want to know what his only mistake was Friday
night? Giving up a 310-foot home run to Ryan Klesko. If you hit a
home run like that in a game, you wouldn't tell anybody. It was a
tiny pop down the right-field line. Afterward, Klesko disputed the
official distance, arguing that it had to be longer than 310. It
wasn't. Even more frightening is that Martinez knew what he was
doing with the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only place he could have hit it,'' he said. ``I
jammed him and he hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the few times the crowd of 33,411 fell silent.
For most of the night, fans were chanting ``Pedro'' and pinning up
the ``K'' signs for strikeouts. One group in the bleachers put up
their Ks in a small area. After the 10th strikeout, the Ks started
to look like they were part of a Tic-Tac-Toe game; there wasn't
much room for all of them, so they had to be boxed.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have speculated that all this Martinez winning is
boring. Please. The beauty of Martinez is that you never know
what's coming. Of course you know about the strikeouts, the
dominance, and the praise (and frustration) from the other team.
But then there is the mystical element to the man.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's date was June 4. Nine years ago, on the same
date, Ramon Martinez struck out 18 Braves when he played for the
Dodgers. And while Martinez was striking out 16 Friday night in
Boston, Sox farmhand Michael Coleman was going 7 for 7 in
Pawtucket, R.I. After the game, Sox manager Jimy Williams sounded
like a mystic, talking about the power ``the little white ball''
creates when it is not hit. Then he said of Martinez, ``It's like
magic.'' Williams was asked when he knew Martinez was going to have
a special season like this. ``Oh,'' he said with a dramatic pause,
``about February.''
</P>
<P>
   On the mound for the Braves Friday night was Tom Glavine. He got
off to a rough start, giving up two runs in the first and another
in the third. He lost his seventh game of the season, but didn't
pitch poorly. Afterward, Martinez acknowledged that he studied
Glavine at the 1996 All-Star Game in Cleveland. He said he was
inspired by Glavine's focus and ``how nothing mattered to him but
the game.'' Martinez said he tries to learn something from everyone
he faces. ``I was just a young kid at the time,'' he said of '96.
</P>
<P>
   Now the young kid has grown into a professor of pitching. If he
wins 30 games this year, I won't be surprised. If he strikes out
300 and walks 45, I won't be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is on pace to strike out over 300 and walk something like
40,'' Eckersley said. ``That is unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he is done, he will be the subject of sonnets and
symphonies. You won't read about him only in English and Spanish;
they'll have holograms of him in newspapers soon. In some areas,
you'll be able to tap a page and hear his adoring crowds in
surround sound.
</P>
<P>
   What can he do next?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said catcher Jason Varitek, ``you'll have to come out
when he pitches again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
