<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS FEVER BECOMES A REAL AREA EPIDEMIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Hockey madness engulfed Reunion Arena on Friday night
as the Stars' quest for Lord Stanley's hardware went speeding past
yet another mile marker.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, coming up next, that fabled road paved with silver. Four
more wins _ the toughest four wins in professional sports _ and the
desired piece of silver will be relocated to the chicken-fried
kingdom. How's that for Canada's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But while saving their finest performance for last in these
Western Conference finals, the Stars didn't simply win a showdown
Game 7. This went beyond one team moving on, and one team moving
out for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   This was the next best thing to winning the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   This was a Cup clinic. Hello, Buffalo. Were you guys taking
notes?
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche had one period _ the first _ to get
something going. They did, but while dominating the 20 minutes, the
only puck that reached the net came off the smokin' stick of Jamie
Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   And except for the ticking clock, and the clicking Stars, this
Game 7 was over by midway in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a textbook Dallas Stars hockey team,'' coach Ken
Hitchcock said after the 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``textbook,'' but the class was for advanced students only.
This hockey clinic was all about slicing, dicing, frustrating and
flustering a very strong and game opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Only the best could make such Game 7 patsies of a high-octane
Avalanche outfit. And a gracious Colorado coach Bob Hartley
admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the best hockey club in the NHL, on top of being the
toughest team to play against when they have the lead,'' Hartley
said in his postgame concession speech.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the hockey world, the Stars' style is called
``ugly.'' Friday night it was a thing of beauty to the 17,001
voices who howled constant approval in a show of vocal force
matching the Mavericks' old Reunion Rowdies of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   You want ``ugly,'' see Claude Lemieux. You want to win the
Stanley Cup, take lessons from Friday night's clinic. And then tune
in to Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Show on Tuesday night at Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Never in North Texas history has a local Big Four club other
than the Cowboys reached a league finals. Now the Stars have, and
the Reunion joy was immense, plus that joy spread quickly to all
local precincts.
</P>
<P>
   While remembering that the last time the Stars were on home ice
_ five days ago _ they were tattooed for seven goals, please
consider the second period Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado kept trying, but Colorado kept failing to get off a
shot. Yes, a shot. Eddie Belfour, very instrumental in halting the
Avalanche's first-period surge, watched from a rocking chair as the
Stars defense cut the rink in half. Most of the second period was
played on Patrick Roy's end of the ice, or in the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   The curtain was about to fall on the Avalanche, and with so much
of Game 7 still to play, how could they have known?
</P>
<P>
   But with just over 11 minutes gone in the period, Pat Verbeek
charged Roy from the right side and took a shot that never reached
the crease. The puck appeared to deflect off Guy Carbonneau's stick
and then took a perfect and lucky bounce out to Mike Keane in the
slot. Bingo ... Keane banged it past Roy, and with a 2-0 lead, the
game changed dramatically for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What surprised me was how well we played when we went up
2-0,'' said Hitchcock. ``From then on, it was like we were
executing out of the textbook. That goal turned our nervousness
into energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane would strike again as the desperate Avalanche became
loosey-goosey on defense. On an odd man rush with Verbeek, Keane
kept the puck as Roy got no help from defenseman Adam Foote.
Suddenly, Keane was parked on Roy's doorstep, and when Patrick
over-committed, the puck went sliding by him.
</P>
<P>
   At 3-0, the smell of Colorado blood was in the Reunion air. And
the packed house cut loose with a roar that was heard in upstate
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Avalanche got its first shot after 14 minutes of
the second period. And it only had three for the entire 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For those who came Friday night expecting three periods, at
least, of extreme sweat, the Game 7 celebration got a very early
start. The only suspense left involved Lemieux. Would he
sucker-punch Belfour in the hand-shake line?
</P>
<P>
   And just to keep the record straight, apologies will be accepted
beginning today by general manager Bob Gainey. All of us who barked
14 months ago when Gainey traded the popular Todd Harvey for
old-timers Keane and Brian Skrudland, well ...
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are all in place. The silver-paved road awaits.
Hello, Buffalo. Hello, Lord Stanley.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
