<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4031 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-NCAA-USC-LADN     06-05 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-NCAA-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS COME UP EMPTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Zito almost meant zero _ as in hits allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, nothing is what the USC baseball team got from one of
its best pitching performances of the season. Nothing is what the
Trojans got out of what for a moment looked like a game-tying home
run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing means more to the Trojans than a win today in their
best two-of-three NCAA playoff super regional series against
Stanford. If they lose, their season is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, which didn't get a hit against Barry Zito, USC's
All-American left-hander and first-round draft choice, until the
sixth inning, went on to beat the Trojans 1-0 Friday night in front
of 3,708 at Sunken Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   USC was shut out for the first time since last year, and that
was also to Stanford by the same score, only after Brad Ticehurst
hit a long fly ball down the right-field line with two outs in the
top of the ninth that was called foul by first-base umpire Randy
Bruns.
</P>
<P>
   USC head coach Mike Gillespie didn't argue. Stanford
right-hander Jason Young, who threw a complete game and struck out
10, said for split-second he thought the game would be tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's breaks like that which make for a championship season,''
Young said. ``It was an amazing moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito, pitching while the Oakland A's, the team that drafted him
No. 9 overall in this week's major-league draft, were playing about
20 minutes up the road against the Giants, was outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Zito didn't allow a baserunner until the fifth, when he walked
two. He didn't allow a hit until the sixth, when Ticehurst lost
Eric Bruntlett's fly ball in the lights in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Bruntlett had a gift double, and suddenly, Stanford (47-13) had
a runner in scoring position. The Cardinal seized the opportunity _
Jeff Rizzo's one-out double brought home Bruntlett with the game's
only run.
</P>
<P>
   Zito (12-3) gave up two hits, matching his season low, and
struck out eight in eight innings. He lost for the first time since
Feb. 19 and had an 11-game winning streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't think about a no-hitter,'' Zito said after the game,
``you just think about holding (the other team) down.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending national champion USC (36-25) put itself on the brink
of elimination with poor hitting in clutch situations against
Young, who set the school record for strikeouts in a season midway
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Young (11-3) continually pitched out of jams in the middle
innings _ including the fourth, when he struck out Ticehurst with
the bases loaded with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   USC also didn't execute in two hit-and-run situations with Eric
Munson on first (Munson was thrown out both times) and Jason Lane
was thrown out trying to steal third in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Lane sent a buzz through the crowd in the eighth when he sent a
fly ball to the warning track in right field. It was caught by Joe
Borchard (Camarillo High) a few feet from the fence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
