<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4032 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PLAYOFFS-SPI &LR;      06-05 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFFS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS CRUSH COLD-SHOOTING BLAZERS, CLOSE IN ON SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ It appeared as though Rasheed Wallace conjured up
what would be an auspicious day for the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   On the game's first play, Wallace found himself with the ball, a
dying shot clock and a prayer of a shot. Somehow, though, his
off-balanced, 20-foot heave from the top of the key swished through
the net to a thunderous roar.
</P>
<P>
   However, by the time the San Antonio Spurs finished off the
Blazers 85-63 Friday night at the Rose Garden, Wallace's opening
basket boiled down to this: Two points. Bad omen.
</P>
<P>
   Portland's offense remained stagnant for the rest of Friday's
Game 3 loss in the Western Conference finals. Whenever the Blazers
attempted anything with the basketball, it was ugly, off-balanced
and mostly off.
</P>
<P>
   Their final point total tied an NBA playoff-low this season.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of the Blazers' ineptitude came in the third quarter,
when they missed nine straight shots and turned the ball over three
times during the final 6:44 off the period. That allowed Spurs to
score 16 straight points en route to an 18-point lead and a 3-0
advantage in this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the much deeper and younger Blazers are fading fast,
needing a minor miracle to move on to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not kid ourselves,'' Blazer guard Greg Anthony said.
``We've got a lot of wounds to lick, a lot of pride to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Blazers do not find a way to climb into this series, they
face being swept in Game 5 Sunday at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who have never advanced to the NBA Finals, swept the
Los Angeles Lakers in their conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a good job of finishing teams off,'' Spurs guard
Mario Elie said, well aware that San Antonio is 5-0 on the road in
the playoffs. ``We know we're ahead and in good position, so we
might as well go for the knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   For all practical matters, the collective face of the Blazers
might already be five inches from the mat. At least their psyche
has taken a hard hit. Portland bargained for a much stronger
showing at home after dropping two close games in San Antonio, but
responded with a horrendous 24-percent shooting performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing shots wears on you,'' Blazers guard Jim Jackson said
in a somber tone. ``This was just a disappointing game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing their fans boo as the Blazers floundered through an
eight-point quarter must have hurt, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had every right to boo,'' Portland's Damon Stoudamire
said. ``I would too if I was a fan and paid good money. The Spurs
beat out butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland trailed 48-46 midway through the third, but fell behind
64-46 heading into the fourth. The Blazers' third-quarter output
was nearly as bad as their five-point fourth quarter in Game 1 of
the conference semifinals against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done that before,'' San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich
said. ``Every team has a night like that. You just hope it doesn't
come in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Wallace had more than three field goals for the Blazers. He
finished with 22 points but was in constant foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire went 1-for-12. Isaiah Rider missed 8 of his 11 shots
and Brian Grant misfired on all five of his shot attempts. The more
the Blazers missed, the more anxious they became.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about some of the shots we got,'' Jackson
said. ``But there were times when our time management wasn't there
and we just needed to get easy baskets. But San Antonio is a great
defensive team. They talk, they rotate. You have to be able to
space the floor, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland's desperation fed San Antonio's already aggressive
defense. The Spurs made getting to the basket difficult largely due
to David Robinson's seven blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good rotation,'' Robinson said. ``We really took them
out of their offense. They were isolating more than we've seen, and
I think it was because they were frustrated about not being able to
get into their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson dominated the third quarter. He seemed to grow larger
after Tim Duncan picked up his fourth foul only 40 seconds into the
period.
</P>
<P>
   All of the damage had been done by the time Duncan returned. If
the Blazers did anything right, it was taking away the Spurs' best
low-post threat. Portland crowded the post to the point where
Duncan tied a career-low with five points.
</P>
<P>
   However, San Antonio's shooters made the Blazers pay with every
double team. Starting point guard Avery Johnson and reserves Jaren
Jackson and Steve Kerr each made their open shots count.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made six 3-pointers, which erased the Blazers' early
23-15 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has been about stepping up,'' said Duncan, who
averaged 22 points and 11.5 rebounds in the first two games. ``You
can go through every playoff series and find a guy who stepped up
at some point for us. It's a nice feeling because we have a team.''
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night, Portland did not look like much of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a matter of quitting,'' Anthony said. ``I
think the spirit was killed at times. ... You live to fight another
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers have at least one more game to give it their best
shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
