<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4057 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-05 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO'S SHARP START WASTED AGAINST PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Jeff Fassero and Jose Paniagua reversed roles Friday
night. Fassero, who has struggled most of the season, was sharp.
Paniagua, normally the sharp one, struggled.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 3-2 Mariners loss to the San Diego Padres on
the opening day of interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero came into the game with a 7.34 earned run average, but
had one of his best outings this year, working seven innings,
allowing two runs on six hits and three walks, striking out six.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff pitched as well as he has at any time this year,''
pitching coach Stan Williams said. ``He was relaxed out on the hill
and threw the ball extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero left the game after seven innings, and Paniagua entered
with the score tied 2-2. The right-hander had walked only one in
his last eight appearances, but he loaded the bases in the eighth
on two walks and a hit batter.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, pinch-hitter John Vander Wal tapped a slow
grounder to second, and the Mariners nearly escaped trouble. But
Alex Rodriguez's relay throw bounced in front of first baseman
Butch Huskey, and by the time Huskey had scooped it, Vander Wal was
safe, rookie David Newhan had scored, and the Padres had their
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close enough to where I thought he could've been called
out or he could have been called safe,'' Huskey said. ``It was one
of those toss-up plays, and (umpire Jerry Layne) made the decision
to call him safe. We've got to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was not concerned about Paniagua's wildness, citing a
good at-bat by Jim Leyritz to draw the leadoff walk and the fact
that Paniagua was around the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be giving the hitters too much credit,'' Williams said.
``He's got too good stuff to try to be fine like that. You get
ahead, and then try to be fine afterwards. I'll talk to him about
it tomorrow. He's got the kind of stuff that gets the hitter in
trouble as soon as he gets out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had opportunities, especially in the fifth inning.
Brian Hunter singled and stole second with one out. Trying to
advance on a ball in the dirt, Hunter was thrown out at third.
David Bell and Ken Griffey Jr. walked, bringing up Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock again threw in the dirt, and as the ball got
away from catcher Phil Nevin, Bell broke for third. But Nevin
recovered, threw out Bell, too, and the inning was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard somebody say `Go!' so I went,'' Bell said. ``From the
angle I had, I couldn't tell how far away from the catcher it was.
That's why I didn't break right away. If I had, I would have made
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he didn't. Rodriguez opened the next inning with a
437-foot bomb into the second deck at Qualcomm Stadium, the first
this year and just the 23rd ball hit there in 31 years. It was
Rodriguez's ninth homer of the year, and sent fans from neighboring
sections scrambling over, hunting for the ball for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero kept the score tied, getting a 1-2-3 sixth. That was in
the midst of a stretch of 10 consecutive outs, the longest such run
for Fassero this year. He was touched only for a solo home run by
Ruben Rivera leading off the second and a steal of home in the
fourth by Gary Matthews Jr., who like Newwhan was making his major
league debut.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at first and third and one out, Ed Giavanola broke
for second, drawing a throw from catcher Dan Wilson that bounced in
front of Rodriguez. As Rodriguez ran back Giavanola to first,
finally tossing to Huskey, Matthews broke for home, scoring in
front of Huskey's throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wilson's) throw was in the dirt, and it threw off the timing
of the play,'' M's manager Lou Piniella said. ``Alex bobbled it,
and the ball short-hopped him. He started running him back to
first, and the runner got too far off third.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last run Fassero allowed, and the left-hander was
pleased with his performance. He pitched well enough to win,
changing speeds more often than he has in past starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of my last four starts have been good, and I'm happy
with them,'' said Fassero, whose record remains 3-6. ``You do what
you can. It's always nice to get the win, but at the same time it'd
be nice for the team to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory would have been doubly nice Friday because the Texas
Rangers lost to snap their nine-game winning streak. The Rangers
still lead the third-place Mariners by five games in the American
League West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
