<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-05 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND PAINTS PERFECT PICTURE OF SELF-DESTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ An error has been reported in the results of the
Western Conference semifinal playoff series between the Portland
Trail Blazers and Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, both teams lost.
</P>
<P>
   It was known earlier that the Jazz were defeated, 4-2. But after
Friday night's game in the Rose Garden against the San Antonio
Spurs, it appears the Blazers were wiped out, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the Fail Blazers have nothing to bring to the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the series 0-2, the Blazers were supposed to be revived
by the series' return to Portland. Instead, they blew right past
the Doze City and went straight to the edge of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Where
</P>
<P>
   they
</P>
<P>
   went
</P>
<P>
   this
</P>
<P>
   way.
</P>
<P>
   All of Paul Allen's horses and all of his billions won't be able
to put this mess together again. Hey, the Blazer owner doesn't have
enough money to get the stink out of the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, 85-63? On 25 percent shooting? When Spurs star Tim Duncan
was nearly worthless? And the Spurs overall were ordinary?
</P>
<P>
   This one went beyond bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst displays I've ever seen from a basketball
team,'' said Blazer guard Greg Anthony, the ex-Sonic. ``We were so
indecisive, in such disarray, that we never gave ourselves a chance
to get in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not quite true. Disarrayed and indecisive, yes, but
they were actually in the game for awhile. The Spurs early on were
near collapse themselves, giving 17 free throws to the Blazers in
the first quarter while Duncan and David Robinson fell into foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But they ``righted'' themselves with a 24-8 third quarter that
was breathtaking only compared to Portland's ineptitude. They did
not score a point in the quarter's final seven minutes. Even the
loyal Blazer partisans were moved to heckle their heroes, some
catcallers intimating the Blazers quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a matter of quitting,'' said Anthony, one
of the few Blazers with the professionalism to talk afterwards.
``Maybe it was more like the spirit was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, it was another example of how rotten the NBA
has been this season, and it came without the standard excuse of
fatigue. These teams had three days between games. One more day of
rest, and mass graves would have been ordered by the health
department.
</P>
<P>
   In the little picture, the Blazers not only displayed all the
flaws long associated with this team, they screamed them to the
world. Even though Rasheed Wallace led the Blazers with 22 points,
he offered a good example of the Blazers' pointless petulance and
knotheadedness they have worked hard to repress.
</P>
<P>
   During a dead-ball moment in the second quarter, Spurs reserve
forward Jerome Kersey slammed the ball off the front of the
scorer's table, dismayed that he was being pulled from the game.
Referee Ronnie Nunn knew Kersey's gesture was directed at no one,
but Wallace immediately castigated the official for not calling a
technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   After play began, Wallace stupidly kept up his tirade, finally
drawing a technical himself. Blazer coach Mike Dunleavy came onto
the floor and lit into Wallace himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazer who really did himself poorly was Damon Stoudamire.
He couldn't have picked a worse moment to miss 11 of 12 shots and
produce only three assists from his point guard position, and not
just because this was desperation time for the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the off-days preceding the game was Stoudamire's
pout that he wasn't getting enough playing time in the fourth
quarter. Playing time has always been an issue for the talent-rich
Blazers, and Dunleavy was named coach of the year mainly for his
deft handling of the potential trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Stoudamire threw a rock through Dunleavy's trophy case with
his ill-timed whine, because it re-focused attention on the
Blazers' tender psyches. It also put pressure on him to produce big
time in order to deflect further consequences of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stoudamire, who had two tepid games in San Antonio, was
horrid, scoring only a lay-in as the first half closed and getting
thoroughly outplayed by his oft-maligned Spurs counterpart, Avery
Johnson (14 points, 8 assists).
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of what I said ... I probably would take it back,''
said Stoudamire. ``That made it look as if it was one of the
reasons why the team was not as focused tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But overall, the Spurs just came out and beat our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   As this team has been assembled over the past two or three
seasons, the Blazers have wished for more than a few take-backs,
for misdeeds off the court as well as on the court. Stoudamire's
gaffe was more of a misdemeanor than the usual Blazer felony, but
it took on heft with Friday's magnum decay.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sports world is well-versed in the notion that no NBA
team has recovered from an 0-3 deficit, and Friday represented the
Spurs' sixth straight win over Portland, the Blazers are fresh out
of room for more take-backs.
</P>
<P>
   They get to live with this odor for months.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
