</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VETERAN STAR, IT'S STILL TOO EARLY TO PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When he faked the goaltender, his bon ami, to his knees
and then whisked the puck past Patrick Roy for his second goal, the
building erupted in a mighty roar.
</P>
<P>
   History sang last night. Mike Keane already knew the words.
</P>
<P>
   On the biggest night in franchise history, the 5-foot-10 Keane
rose to snatch the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   When a team trades for a 31-year-old veteran just before the
deadline, as the Stars did last season, there must be a higher
motive. In Keane's case, the clue was only ankle high.
</P>
<P>
   Tattooed on his left ankle are images of the 1993 and 1996
Stanley Cups that Keane helped win while he played in Montreal and
Colorado, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Keane has been there, in other words, and done that. On the
grand recipe to bring a Stanley Cup finalist to Texas, he was
deemed an essential ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a seventh game,'' Keane said after his two goals
helped bury the Avalanche, 4-1. ``You can't be nervous. It's a fun
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have the experience. They have the depth. They have
the tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were nervous in the first period,'' Keane
corrected. ``I just think we spent a lot of time in our end. In
between periods, I think we just took a couple of deep breaths and
realized what we had to do to get back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not a goal scorer, Keane will tell you. In his 11 NHL
seasons, his high is 16. Keane found it amusing that before the
Western Conference final series, the media grilled him on the best
way to outfox his former two-time teammate and bon ami, Patrick
Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Keane scored only six goals during the regular season, and Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock had publicly wondered when the veteran was
going to air it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there were some times that we were very frustrated with
him during the regular season,'' Hitchcock admitted last night.
``But he's a lot smarter than any coach we've got on our team _
I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane, Hitchcock said, ``just lives for this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   If Keane's first goal, prompted by Pat Verbeek's hustle in the
corner, ignited the 17,001 at Reunion Arena, his second goal _ a
deft display of black magic on his old friend Roy _ sent the crowd
over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a goal scorer,'' Keane repeated. ``I just hope to be
in the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of big goals in these playoffs _ from people like
Jamie Langenbrunner and Dave Reid. I've always said that you need
three or four lines to produce, and we've had that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It had seemed a low-watt deal at the time. On March 24, 1998,
the Stars sent Todd Harvey, Bob Errey and a fourth-round draft pick
to the New York Rangers for battled-scarred veterans Keane and
Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   Keane promptly scored four goals and had eight points in last
year's playoffs. His encore came last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew the challenges and how difficult it was, so he was
able to pace himself during the regular season, knowing how much he
would have to blow it out,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   They are not the youngest team in the league, Keane explained
later. They are not the fastest or the sleekest. But the Stars brim
with depth and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Their time is nigh, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like comparing teams or wins,'' Keane said. ``We have
our own identity. But I think everyone realizes how important a
year this is for the Dallas Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night when nobody at Reunion seemed to want to go home,
Keane said solemnly that the party will have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there are a lot of happy faces,'' Keane said, ``but we
didn't reach our goal tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made great strides. We beat a great hockey club. But the
party only comes after we reach our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo party, he means. There's still room on Mike Keane's
for one more Stanley Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
