<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT JOURNEY'S END, WORDS WEREN'T NEEDED FOR HULL, MODANO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ With a minute left in the game that would make this the
most glorious season in the Stars' brief six years in Texas, Brett
Hull and Mike Modano skated to the bench in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   They were far too excited to sit.
</P>
<P>
   As they stood there at the bench side by side, watching the
final seconds tick away in a 4-1 Game 7 victory over the Colorado
Avalanche in the Western Conference finals, Hull draped an arm
around Modano's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Their smiles, visible even from the press box in the rafters far
across the ice, captured the moment perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't say anything,'' Modano would say later, the smile
still pasted across his face in the Stars' locker room. ``We didn't
have to. We knew we had it at that point. We just kind of smiled.
We were glad it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I have been through a lot together. We played against
each other for a long time. Our paths have crossed many times, we
had a super year together this year, and it was great to be
together for this.''
</P>
<P>
   To put it in historical, perspective, ``this'' was the Cowboys
vs. the 49ers, any year you name.
</P>
<P>
   Times seven.
</P>
<P>
   With their overwhelming victory last night _ they stunned even
themselves with their dominance of an excellent team _ the Stars
climbed to heights previously only reached by the ``other'' team at
Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   We've reached the big time, sports fans. We're four Stanley Cup
Finals victories away from being home to two world championship
teams.
</P>
<P>
   If you were there, among the 17,001 screaming, delirious fans at
Reunion Arena, you'll never forget that moment last night when you
absolutely knew the Stars were going to win.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling began to build when Mike Keane, breaking down the
middle, drilled home a shot after a centering pass from Pat Verbeek
deflected off an Avs' defenseman. That gave the Stars a 2-0 lead
with 8:47 left in the second period, and the Stars' incredible
defense threw a sleeper-hold on the Avalanche offense.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you felt it when Keane danced in on Patrick Roy for his
second goal, the dynamic conclusion to a 2-on-1 Stars' rush. And
you knew it, without a doubt, when Jere Lehtinen caught Roy out of
position trying to defend against a Modano breakaway and slapped in
an empty-netter for a 4-0 Stars lead.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody cue the band and light up the cigars, this one's over,
baby.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night of unbridled emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, what was great was to see the emotion of people who
have never been here before,'' said coach Ken Hitchcock, who just
happens to be one of those people. ``Hull, particularly, was just
raw. His emotions were incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're usually so guarded, but he really let it rip. He just
put it all out there, he was so excited.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the 34-year-old Hull wanted to spend those final 60
seconds, standing alongside Modano, the man he has skated with and
learned to admire this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pressure that a guy like Mike is under and I know
how hard Jere works and you just want to give 'em a hug,'' Hull
said. ``They feel like family to me, those two guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an incredible moment and an unbelievable feeling.
You begin to wonder if maybe it's never meant to be or something.''
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts, Hull said, were about Modano and Lehtinen and what
they've meant to him since he came to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing together all year, and Mike and Jere helped
me adapt to the system here and made me look, at times, a lot
better than I've been,'' he said. ``To come in, change my game and
fit in here, I couldn't have done it without them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Modano, it has been a 10-year journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into this decade in the Finals \Ras the Minnesota
North Stars\S and we're going out in the Finals,'' he said. ``It's
been a long time coming, a roller-coaster ride, and when you get it
to this point, you just ride it as long as you can take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty young and dumb at 19. I didn't really know what
it took to get there, but as you get older and wiser you realize
that this is the hardest championship to win in all of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the score, they said. It never felt easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of responsibility put on our line to play
against Forsberg and those guys,'' Modano said. ``We knew we had to
keep them off the board to give ourselves a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   With a minute to play, the two stood shoulder to shoulder,
watching the seconds tick away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't wind down fast enough,'' Hull said. ``It's Game 7,
you're playing such a fantastic hockey team. I read the papers and
listen to the people on ESPN and what not, and no one even thought
we could win 6 or 7. So it was a great feeling to kind of shove it
up there a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clarence Campbell Bowl, a huge piece of hardware that goes
to the Western Conference champions, sat by itself in the middle of
the room, largely ignored, as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have taken us to the brink of another, far more sacred
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Stanley's Cup is now theirs for the taking.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
