<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories on Kosovo for
Sunday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ACCORD (Blace, Macedonia) _ In a stunning admission of
defeat, five senior Yugoslav military officers came here Saturday
to review and sign the terms for their capitulation to NATO armed
forces, going over the details for their full withdrawal from
Kosovo with top NATO officers. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT (Undated) _ Special Report: If the peace deal
holds up, the curious war comes out this way: The richest,
best-armed military alliance in history won, but at a savage cost
to the people who were supposed to be protected. A wily Balkan
dictator lost, but he stays on in his shrinking Yugoslavia. And
just possibly a new lesson in war has been learned: Thanks to the
wonders of high-tech weaponry, an overwhelmingly powerful alliance
can crush a small nation's aggressive will without having to risk
its own soldiers, if it is willing to spend enough money and if it
can tolerate mistakes that kill innocent civilians. By Blaine
Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Two conflicting senses _ relief that
the war appears near its end mingled with remorse over the U.S.'
supposed desire to impose its will on the weak _ were threads than
ran through a conversation about Kosovo on Saturday with several
well-educated Muscovites. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Undated) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army, the Albanian
separatist movement that remains heavily armed and deeply divided,
is likely to become the new power broker in the southern Serbian
province under any deal worked out between NATO and Belgrade. By
Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ With the sudden and
apparent end of NATO's bombing war against Yugoslavia, Serbs are
relieved, angry, proud, disgusted and resigned, probably in that
order, suggested Slobodanka Bogic, as she stood in her still
windowless house, helping workers repair the damage. But soon
enough, she said, ``everyone will start to become more afraid,
because the winter is coming and there will not be enough heat,
power or food.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CANDIDATES (Washington) _ If a possible peace settlement
in Kosovo has any effect on presidential politics in 2000, it
highlights an advantage of being the sitting vice president and the
disadvantage of a fractious mass of opposition candidates vying for
attention. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
