<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT (Undated) _ Special Report: If the peace deal
holds up, the curious war comes out this way: The richest,
best-armed military alliance in history won, but at a savage cost
to the people who were supposed to be protected. A wily Balkan
dictator lost, but he stays on in his shrinking Yugoslavia. And
just possibly a new lesson in war has been learned: Thanks to the
wonders of high-tech weaponry, an overwhelmingly powerful alliance
can crush a small nation's aggressive will without having to risk
its own soldiers, if it is willing to spend enough money and if it
can tolerate mistakes that kill innocent civilians. By Blaine
Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ACCORD (Blace, Macedonia) _ In what could mark the end of
a decade of wars that destroyed Yugoslavia, five senior Yugoslav
military officers came here Saturday to meet with NATO officials
and to review and sign the terms for their withdrawal from Kosovo
after 10 weeks of bombardment by the alliance. By Elizabeth Becker
and David Rohde..
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Two conflicting senses _ relief that
the war appears near its end mingled with remorse over the U.S.'
supposed desire to impose its will on the weak _ were threads than
ran through a conversation about Kosovo on Saturday with several
well-educated Muscovites. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Undated) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army, the Albanian
separatist movement that remains heavily armed and deeply divided,
is likely to become the new power broker in the southern Serbian
province under any deal worked out between NATO and Belgrade. By
Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ With the sudden and
apparent end of NATO's bombing war against Yugoslavia, Serbs are
relieved, angry, proud, disgusted and resigned, probably in that
order, suggested Slobodanka Bogic, as she stood in her still
windowless house, helping workers repair the damage. But soon
enough, she said, ``everyone will start to become more afraid,
because the winter is coming and there will not be enough heat,
power or food.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CANDIDATES (Washington) _ If a possible peace settlement
in Kosovo has any effect on presidential politics in 2000, it
highlights an advantage of being the sitting vice president and the
disadvantage of a fractious mass of opposition candidates vying for
attention. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-CORNELL-AIDS _ Special Report: Nearly 20 years after
Cornell Medical College opened a clinic in Port-au-Prince, Haiti,
it provides the best AIDS treatment available in a country on the
front lines of the epidemic. But that is a lower standard of care
than patients receive routinely at American institutions, including
Cornell's own hospital in New York City. And patients who
participate in AIDS research do not receive the drugs or the
counseling that would be standard in the United States. By Nina
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL-ELECTION (Katmandu) _ In a two-stage election last month,
voters had the opportunity to create some order out of this social
entropy, and if local analysts are correct they demonstrated
admirable wisdom. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-POLAND (Gdansk, Poland) _ Pope John Paul II arrived
Saturday in the birthplace of the Solidarity movement that he
sparked with his first papal visit 20 years ago, offering Poles
``the greeting of a fellow Pole who comes among you to fulfill the
needs of his own heart.'' By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Since last year, Bao Tong, a former
senior Communist Party official, has been prodding and exhorting
China's leaders to rethink their verdict on June 4, 1989, when
soldiers used guns to quash a massive pro-democracy protest,
killing hundreds in and around Tiananmen Square. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Indonesia steps into the unknown
on Monday with a highly complex parliamentary election in which,
even if everything goes smoothly, the outcome is sure to cause
confusion and protests. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Johannesburg) _ A close look at last week's
election reveals that parties with long histories virtually died
and one new one got a foothold that will keep two potent
personalities in the headlines. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARABS (Beirut) _ The election of a new Israeli government
has rekindled Arab hopes for renewed Middle East peace talks, but
an enduring rift between Syria and the Palestinians has blocked an
effort to forge a common Arab stand. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SCHOOL-AID (Washington) _ Raising the stakes in the
debate over public aid to parochial schools, the Clinton
administration is urging the Supreme Court to allow local school
districts to provide computers for parochial school classrooms
under a program declared unconstitutional by a federal appeals
court. The case has received little notice so far, but that will
change if the justices agree later this month to hear it; the
court's precedents on parochial aid will be in play, with
implications for school vouchers. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY-CASE (Washington) _ New evidence in the case of a
nuclear scientist suspected as a spy for Beijing suggests that a
rigid bureaucracy at the Justice Department thwarted an aggressive
investigation by the FBI. The result: We may never know the truth
about Wen Ho Lee, the suspected scientist at the center of a furor
over what is potentially the costliest counterespionage blunder of
the post-Cold War era. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CITIES (Washington) _ Welfare rolls are shrinking more
slowly in big cities than in the surrounding states, and as a
result welfare recipients are increasingly concentrated in urban
areas. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKLEY-PROSECUTION (Washington) _ Ronald H. Blackley, once a
top aide to former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, faces two years
in prison for not reporting outside income. Blackley's real
offense, his lawyer says, was to run afoul of an independent
counsel pursuing Espy and hoping to use Blackley's testimony.
Blackley had nothing useful to say, Espy was acquitted and
Blackley's life is in ruins. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT-A-PAINTING (New York) _ Getting your name on something at
an art museum usually requires a fat bank account. But not at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, where having your name on a label next to a
painting now costs just $500 a year. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   BIKING-DECLINE (Hannibal, Mo.) _ These are exquisite days to
ride a bike in this all-American, middle-American boyhood home of
Mark Twain. Kids can ride to school, to the Tom Sawyer Cave three
miles south, to fish on the banks of the Mississippi, to play pitch
and catch in a park. They can and they did, but they don't anymore.
Hannibal's parks, river banks and schools are all but barren of
bikes. And as Hannibal goes, so goes the nation. In the shadow of a
long, slow decline in cycling generally, the bicycle as a
century-old symbol of childhood freedom and transportation is
nearly extinct. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-FAITH (Littleton, Colo.) _ For all the talk of the
jocks, preps and trench coat mafia, it was faith that bound Cassie
Bernall and many of her peers at Colombine High School. By Sarah
Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-POWER-CONFERENCE (Mackinac Island, Mich.) _ Every state has
its insiders, its striding embodiments of wealth or power, and
Michigan is no different. But in no other state do so many of them
_ 1,400 this year _ gather at a single schmoozefest like the one
held here each summer. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   ORE-UNLOADERS (Cleveland) _ A fight over whether or not to
preserve huge iron ore unloaders, relics of Cleveland's industrial
past.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ ``Liberties'' by Maureen Dowd: Even at this
distance, you can almost hear Rudy raving, the shrill sound of one
mayor carping: So she's going to do it. Bring her on. I can take
her.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ ``In America'' by Bob Herbert: She's gotten
through the health-care debacle, Whitewater, the Lewinsky scandal
and the impeachment of her husband. Now Hillary Rodham Clinton is
packing her carpetbag and preparing to run for the U.S. Senate in
New York. Welcome to the post-traumatic stress campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
