<HEADER>
A1375 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-HEALTHCARE-REV     06-05 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-HEALTHCARE-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: psychiatric intervention.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police departments across the country refer officers with
troubling memories to therapists who specialize in treating
post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Robert Volpe, the father of Justin Volpe, the New
York City police officer who pleaded guilty to savagely assaulting
a suspect in a precinct bathroom, employed the sort of therapeutic
language found on Internet sites devoted to police post-traumatic
stress disorder to defend his son. He likened police work to combat
and suggested that his son suffered memories of traumatic
experiences on the job.
</P>
<P>
   As a diagnosis, post-traumatic stress disorder ``just started
taking off in 1985 and it keeps growing,'' said Allan Young,
chairman of the department of Social Studies of Medicine,
Anthropology and Psychiatry at McGill University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   If the pool of patients grows and parity laws require insurers
to pay for all demands for treatment, something will have to give,
experts say. A 1997 study by the Employee Benefit Research
Institute warned that as mental-health parity causes employer costs
to rise, workers can expect to see erosion in other benefits, and
that some employers could react by dropping health-insurance
coverage altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The correct approach, said Ms. Rappaport of the National
Alliance for the Mentally Ill, is ``redirecting money already in
the system for those who have the most severe disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   The priority is simple, she said: ``You save the neediest
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
