<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES-R     06-05 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES-REVIEW-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING GOOD WHILE EVERYBODY SWEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ohio, Mich.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he struts along the basketball sidelines, screaming out plays
while wearing a Giorgio Armani suit, P.J. Carlesimo feels blessed.
But sometimes he also feels foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of nights when you're sweating through a $2,000
suit that you kind of wonder why you're wearing a shirt and tie,''
said Carlesimo, coach of the Golden State Warriors. ``I think the
baseball managers and football coaches are smarter than basketball
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans watching the National Basketball Association playoffs this
weekend will no doubt note the visual disconnect between the baggy
jerseys of perspiring players engaged in grueling competition and
the sleek suits of coaches equally focused on the game. Carlesimo,
whose team failed to make the playoffs and whose wardrobe is
strictly Saks Fifth Avenue, makes it look good.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NBA coaches are widely considered to be the best
dressed in the world, as these things go. While their counterparts
in the National Football League and major-league baseball wear
warm-up jackets, baseball caps and, in the case of baseball
managers, team uniforms, the coaches in the media-savvy NBA wear
suits by some of the most trend-setting designers on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley of the Miami Heat has his Armani suits and sports
coats shipped directly from Italy. Chuck Daly, who recently retired
from the Orlando Magic, sat on the bench in the finely finished
fabrics of Hugo Boss and Ermenegildo Zegna, and the relatively
diminutive Mike Fratello, a veteran of 13 NBA seasons, is one of
the league's most exciting sideline personalities, mostly because
of his antics and his fashion flair. Fratello, who was dismissed
last week by the Cleveland Cavaliers, favored Boss.
</P>
<P>
   When Carlesimo left Seton Hall and entered the league five years
ago, he had no choice but to trade up in his clothing. Upon signing
to coach the Portland Trail Blazers, he was notified that one of
the team's sponsors, a local clothing store, wanted to outfit him
in Donna Karan (whose line President Clinton has been known to
wear).
</P>
<P>
   Now at Golden State, he has an agreement with Saks Fifth Avenue
that calls for him to dress in Armani or Zegna throughout the
season. While Carlesimo appreciates his good fortune, he says that
dressing to the nines is not necessarily practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to coach in what we wear at practice, which would
be closer to what NFL coaches wear in good weather _ a coaching
shirt and slacks,'' Carlesimo said. ``But I think that it has
become an image thing in the NBA and that it's going to be
difficult to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Because their game is played indoors, NBA coaches have always
worn suits. But it was not until the mid-1980s that many of them
started paying attention to the label inside their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey, an NBA assistant coach for 18 years, said the shift
began when David Stern became the league's commissioner and
embarked on what has become the greatest mass-marketing campaign in
the history of professional sports. As the league gained fame and
an international following, the top players and coaches became
celebrities. The media began to take note of what the coaches were
wearing as they glowered or exploded or sat catatonic on the
sidelines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They didn't dress like that in the '60s and '70s,'' said
Casey, who during his brief stint as the head coach of the Los
Angeles Clippers was viewed as one of the league's worst-dressed
coaches in his lackluster suits and ties. ``The coaches were just
people coaching the game, but when national TV came in, the coaches
started becoming entities and looking professional and like _
you're on Wall Street _ came the look.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, who wore Armani while leading the Los Angeles Lakers to
four championships during the 1980s, and Daly, who became a dapper
dresser while coaching in Detroit, are considered to be the
pioneers of the current trend. While other coaches were wearing
cotton-blend shirts and polyester ties, Riley and Daly were walking
the court in shoes handmade by Bally and suits worth thousands of
dollars. Now, many of the league's coaches, armed with lucrative
clothing deals of their own, can match the Riley look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that now there's that pressure to keep up with the
Joneses,'' Casey said. ``Still, sometimes I don't feel like wearing
a tie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
