<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-R     06-05 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-REVIEW-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY RENOIR BEATS YOUR VERMEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Summer is blockbuster season, from the multiplex to
the august halls of culture. That's one way to explain a big van
Gogh show at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Or ``Impressionists in
Winter,'' the first exhibition to assemble the snowscapes of Monet,
Renoir, Gauguin and others, served up by the Brooklyn Museum of Art
in the city's hottest months.
</P>
<P>
   Museums may shun comparisons with Hollywood but they, too,
strive for that explosion of interest (named for a super-powerful
World War II bomb) that spells ``blockbuster,'' filling the
coffers, swelling the membership rolls and exciting envy at fellow
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums have discovered advertising,'' said David Ross,
director of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and former
director of the Whitney Museum of American Art. ``You can advertise
garbage and make millions. Imagine if you advertise something with
real value.''
</P>
<P>
   With Americans flocking to art museums in record numbers, such
hits _ shows that seize you by the lapels and bellow, ``What! You
haven't lined up for `The Treasury of Saint Francis of Assisi'
yet?'' _ lend a gloss and urgency to art, science and history,
while posing questions about commercialism and exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows in the museum world arched last December when Ben
Hartley, director of communications and sponsorship for the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum in New York, said, ``We are in the
entertainment business and competing against other forms of
entertainment out there.'' The Guggenheim reached blockbuster
nirvana with its show on motorcycles, which drew half a million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But blockbusters have their defenders. ``These great moments of
acute interest create exceptional teaching opportunities,'' said
Ellen Futter, director of the Museum of Natural History, whose show
``Epidemic!'' on infectious diseases, has drawn more than 150,000
visitors since Feb. 27. ``They create a gateway to learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum calendars are replete with big exhibitions of plainly
blockbuster ambitions _ shows on Ingres' portraiture, the age of
the Pyramids, new archaeological finds from China and the
ever-popular impressionists, truly the museum world's most reliable
moneymakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Met weighed in last month with ``Cezanne to van Gogh,''
featuring the renowned collection of van Gogh's physician, Dr.
Paul-Ferdinand Gachet. ``I don't sit around thinking what will
bring in crowds,'' said Philippe de Montebello, who after two
decades as director was recently elevated to chief executive
officer as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum of Art days later opened its
``Impressionists in Winter,'' lauded by the museum's director,
Arnold Lehman, as ``literally the coolest show.''
</P>
<P>
   A show last year at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, ``Monet
in the 20th Century,'' became the most popular in the country in
1998, drawing nearly 566,000 visitors. The recent Jackson Pollock
show at the Museum of Modern Art in New York also proved a bonanza,
drawing nearly 330,000 visitors, a striking number, if still short
of the 940,000 _ more than 8,000 a day _ who swamped the museum's
Matisse show of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The John Singer Sargent show, which closed last week at the
National Gallery in Washington, drew about 425,000 visitors, or
nearly 4,500 a day, catapulting it into the realm of the smash 1995
Vermeer show, said Dodge Thompson, the chief of exhibitions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The modern age of blockbusters arrived with a sensational show
in 1948. With the museums of war-shattered Germany in ruins and
many of their treasures recovered by the Allies from salt mines and
other caches, the U.S. authorities shipped 202 masterpieces to the
National Gallery for exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Called simply ``Paintings From the Berlin Museums,'' the show,
with its Rembrandts, Vermeers, Titians, Duerers, van Eycks,
Botticellis, Breughels and a Bosch, drew near-riotous crowds. The
intense interest and short run of just 40 days, made for the
unprecedented arithmetic of an average 24,124 visitors a day.
</P>
<P>
   When the Louvre's Mona Lisa went on view at the National Gallery
in 1963, it drew an average daily attendance of more than 19,200,
for a total of 518,525.
</P>
<P>
   In overall numbers, the Met may hold the modern record, with
more than 1.2 million visitors to its ``Treasures of Tutankhamun''
of 1978 to '79.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bigger blockbusters on the horizon may not really be
blockbusters at all, but permanent installations. The new Gottesman
Hall of Planet Earth opens at the Museum of Natural History on June
12, the first stage of the spherical Rose Center for Earth and
Space to be unveiled early next year, replacing the old
planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Met opened its new Greek Galleries in a soaring
barrel-vaulted space hemmed in since World War II, drawing throngs
of visitors tabulated at more than 10,000 a day, until guards gave
up counting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-R     06-05 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-REVIEW-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY RENOIR BEATS YOUR VERMEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
