</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-SAFRICA-REVIEW-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NIGERIA'S TURN TO KEEP THE PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ As Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo waited to be
inaugurated as Nigeria's new president a week ago, a man he used to
visit in prison sat a few seats to his right: President Nelson
Mandela of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Africa's two most powerful nations, possibly the
two most respected politicians on the continent, embraced warmly.
Maybe it occurred to them that the pupil seemed to have overtaken
the teacher. It is a thought that has occurred to many in recent
days as Nigeria installed its first elected president in a
generation and South Africa successfully held its second democratic
election.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, after all, once stood as the uncontested leader in
Africa. It was the staunchest backer of liberation movements in
South Africa and other white-ruled countries, and Obasanjo stood as
one of the most vocal critics of apartheid. And yet South Africa
preceded Nigeria into democratic government, holding its first
all-race elections in 1994 even as Nigeria slipped into a ruthless
military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Now here was Mandela traveling to Nigeria just four days before
South Africa's elections on Wednesday, evidently confident of the
stability he leaves behind in his retirement. Contrast that to the
situation of Obasanjo, who recently came out of retirement to lead
his disoriented nation into the shakiest of democracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that although Nigeria assisted South Africa
to get rid of apartheid, South Africa breathed the air of democracy
before we did,'' said Larry Agboh, an official in Obasanjo's
People's Democratic Party. ``We were expecting Nigeria, as the most
populous nation in Africa, to lead Africa toward full democracy.
That would have guaranteed Nigeria's position as the true leader on
the continent.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 election in South Africa was a bittersweet moment,
Agboh added, ``sweet in the sense that I was happy that apartheid
was over, and bitter in the sense that here was the junior brother
leading Nigeria, the senior brother, into democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Agboh was inspecting the new National Assembly building here as
Nigeria's newly elected senators and representatives met for the
first time on Thursday. With fixtures still unattached and the
smell of fresh paint in the air, the building suggested a democracy
in the making. The point did not escape visitors who wandered into
a third-floor gallery, pressing their noses against windows that
looked down on the assembly hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were still a military administration, I will not be
allowed beyond the gate,'' said Mohammed Gawuna, 35. ``From this
window, I can peep and see my representatives at work.'' Another
onlooker, Morgan West, 31, added, ``This building is a symbol of
the beginning of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, creating an enduring democracy here will be an
enormous task. The constitution is a month old, handed down by
decree by the outgoing military government. There is no
institutional check on corruption, though Obasanjo took a first
step last week by setting up a panel to investigate contracts
awarded since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing close to a middle class, as the gulf has
widened between an extremely rich minority and an impoverished
majority. A generation of corrupt military rule has eroded popular
trust, as the government of the world's seventh-largest
oil-producer has failed to deliver basics like electricity and
potable water to its 110 million people.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, since Mandela's African National Congress was
elected in 1994, South Africa has adopted one of the most liberal
constitutions in the world, and its legal system has been entirely
reformed. Millions more have clean water now, and even residents of
squatter camps have access to electricity and telephones. And if
last week's election of Thabo Mbeki, the ANC's only candidate to
replace Mandela, is any indication, Mandela's legacy includes a
self-sustaining democracy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the 1970s, it looked as though Nigeria would be the giant
leading postcolonial Africa into democracy. Its coffers flush with
oil money, Nigeria became the leading African opponent of
white-ruled governments in South Africa, Namibia and the former
Rhodesia, now Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria opened its checkbook, leaders of several African
liberation movements operated out of Lagos. Nigeria even had a
civilian government in 1979 until a coup ended it in 1983.
Obasanjo, the military ruler in the late 1970s, pursued efforts to
end apartheid after his retirement. As a member of a Commonwealth
mediation effort, he visited Mandela three times in Pollsmoor
prison outside Cape Town, South Africa, in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Often the only African nation with embassies in Western
capitals, Nigeria came to regard itself as the world's black
superpower. ``Some of us dream of Nigeria being to blacks in the
diaspora what Jerusalem is to Jews in the diaspora,'' Nigeria's
foreign minister, Bolaji Akinyemi, said in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But the country's northern military rulers tightened their grip
in the 1990s. They annulled the results of the presidential
elections on June 12, 1993, which would have given victory to a
southern Yoruba businessman, Moshood K.O. Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   ``June 12 has done us a lot of damage,'' said Anthony Adefuye, a
senator from 1991 to 1993, when the military government briefly
permitted civilians at the state and local levels. ``If June 12 had
been real, we would have democratized before South Africa. In
politics, one slip will take you a hundred steps to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after South Africa's post-apartheid era began, Nigeria fell
under the repressive regime of Gen. Sani Abacha. As investors left
Nigeria, they gravitated to South Africa. In 1995, after the writer
Ken Saro-Wiwa was hanged for protesting the use of oil resources,
Nigeria became an international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, leading the nation that many regarded as Africa's new
leader, repeatedly called for an oil boycott of Nigeria. Abacha
retaliated by withdrawing Nigeria's soccer team from the African
Nations Cup, which was held in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But Abacha died suddenly a year ago, and Obasanjo has returned
as Nigeria's leader. ``It is our firm resolve to restore Nigeria
fully to her previous prestigious position in the comity of
nations,'' he said during his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   So Nigeria finds itself under enormous pressure to fulfill the
moment's promise. It is Nigeria's last chance, many here say. But
in the same breath, Nigerians, famous for their fighting spirit,
declare they will soon catch up to and surpass their southern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk of African-ness,'' Agboh said, ``Nigeria is 100
percent African, much more than South Africa, which is mixed. The
greatness of Nigeria will be a pride to the whole black race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
