<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Lead:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ACCORD (Blace, Macedonia) _ Enemy Generals Meet Over
Withdrawal: Five senior Yugoslav military officers came here
Saturday to meet with NATO officials and to review and sign the
terms for their withdrawal from Kosovo after 10 weeks of
bombardment by the alliance. By Elizabeth Becker and David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Center right:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT (Undated) _ Special Report: Waging War on the
Serbs: Old Problem, New Lesson: If the peace deal holds up, the
curious war comes out this way: The richest, best-armed military
alliance in history won, but at a savage cost to the people who
were supposed to be protected. A wily Balkan dictator lost, but he
stays on in his shrinking Yugoslavia. And just possibly a new
lesson in war has been learned: Thanks to the wonders of high-tech
weaponry, an overwhelmingly powerful alliance can crush a small
nation's aggressive will without having to risk its own soldiers,
if it is willing to spend enough money and if it can tolerate
mistakes that kill innocent civilians. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead:
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-CORNELL-AIDS _ Special Report: For Subjects in Haiti
Study, Frees AIDS Care Has a Price: Nearly 20 years after Cornell
Medical College opened a clinic in Port-au-Prince, Haiti, it
provides the best AIDS treatment available in a country on the
front lines of the epidemic. But that is a lower standard of care
than patients receive routinely at American institutions, and
patients who participate in AIDS research do not receive the drugs
or the counseling that would be standard in the United States. By
Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' and ``a'' news
files.
</P>
<P>
   Above fold reefer:
</P>
<P>
   MUNICIPALITIES-ACCOUNTING (Undated) _ Financial Revolution for
Cities and States: The group that sets the standards for how the
nation's 84,000 state and local governments keep their books is
expected to approve a plan this week that would require them to
operate more like businesses. Hundreds of cities, towns and other
local governments complain the change will be difficult and costly
to comply with, but citizens groups say it will provide taxpayers
with a more complete picture of what their dollars buy. By Melody
Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Center, above fold:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Weary Belgrade Starts
to Rebuild as Despair and Pessimism Linger: With the sudden and
apparent end of NATO's bombing war against Yugoslavia, Serbs are
relieved, angry, proud, disgusted and resigned, probably in that
order, suggested Slobodanka Bogic, as she stood in her still
windowless house, helping workers repair the damage. But soon
enough, she said, ``everyone will start to become more afraid,
because the winter is coming and there will not be enough heat,
power or food.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Below fold:
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT-A-PAINTING (New York) _ `Adopting' Masterpieces: Touch of
Class or Crass?: Getting your name on something at an art museum
usually requires a fat bank account. But not at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, where having your name on a label next to a painting now
costs $500 a year. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CITIES (Washington) _ Welfare rolls are shrinking more
slowly in big cities than in the surrounding states, and as a
result welfare recipients are increasingly concentrated in urban
areas. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY-REPORT (New York) _ Saying that the City University of New
York is ``an institution adrift'' and is ``caught in a spiral of
decline,'' a mayoral task force is calling for a total revamping of
the university. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
</TEXT>
