<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DDAY06-COX     06-05 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDAY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remembering the horrors, heroism of D-Day
 &HT;    By Joanne Huist Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Steak and eggs for breakfast were not a good sign
to Franklin Twp. resident Virgil Akers, a member of the 276-member
crew of the USS Gherardi on June 6, 1944, D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   Anchored in the English Channel with World War II booming around
them, the crew of the Navy destroyer recognized the meal as
standard fare issued by their skipper, Commander Neal R. Curtin,
before a call to battle stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think I was smart enough to realize the danger
to the fullest,'' Akers, now 74, said, recalling what he was doing
55 years ago today.
</P>
<P>
   Torpedoman Akers, then just 19, rolled out of his cot below
decks to an unseasonably cold morning. The seaman dressed quickly
in Navy dungarees, a blue denim shirt and pants.
</P>
<P>
   At 5'8'' and 130 pounds, Akers' slight frame shivered in the
pre-dawn chill. From a locker the size of a stereo speaker he
pulled out foul-weather gear, a one-piece jumpsuit that zipped up
the front.
</P>
<P>
   The young sailor knew he'd need the heavy suit on deck for
warmth. He also knew the weighted material would soak up the
freezing waters of the Atlantic if his ship took a hit and he
landed in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   To Allied servicemen who faced German artillery and aircraft at
that early summer morning, it was the long-anticipated H-Hour, a
first step toward the liberation of France and overthrowing
Hitler's Germany.
</P>
<P>
   American casualties during the 15-day period that began with
D-Day tallied more than 24,000 with at least 3,082 killed, 13,121
wounded, and 7,959 missing, according to The D-Day Encyclopedia,
edited by David G. Chandler, of the Royal Military Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States, about 6.3 million World War II
veterans like Akers still live to share their memories of the
horror and heroism of D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another 10 years, many of the veterans who fought on D-Day
will be gone, dead,'' Akers said. ``Then people will have to learn
about the war from history books.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers survived the invasion to fight other battles, but the
drone of the airplanes and the pounding of the D-Day guns at
Normandy still echo through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of the impending invasion of France started to circulate
around the fleet in April 1944, Akers said, while the USS Gherardi
was anchored at Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned early on, even from boot camp, that Americans were
fighting for one reason. That reason was to end the war,'' Akers
said. ``Hitler, to me, was like a bug that needed to be stepped on.
Our troops ran him out of Africa, out of Sicily. I'm thinking, `Why
doesn't this guy just give up.'''
</P>
<P>
   That spring, the USS Gherardi sailed for Great Britain to mass
with an armada that grew to nearly 5,000 vessels in two months.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of June 6, all soldiers, sailors and airmen in
the Allied Expeditionary Force received word from the Allied
Supreme Commander, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, that there would be
no more waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your task will not be an easy one,'' Eisenhower said in a
letter to the troops. ``Your enemy is well trained, well equipped
and battle-hardened. He will fight savagely.''
</P>
<P>
   The USS Gherardi, with a gun range of about nine miles, took up
station that day about a 1,000 yards off the beachhead at a site
known by the code name ``Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was bad, the sea was rough. I feared for the
people on the beach. I thought to myself, `I'm sitting high and dry
here, but a lot of those solders are going to die,''' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   Akers was given a pair of binoculars and sent to a landing above
the main deck to act as a lookout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw soldiers with heavy packs jump into deep water and never
come up. They never made it to land. I saw bodies float by in the
water,'' Akers said. ``Men would run side by side up the beach,
then suddenly one would just drop, fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Each shot from the four-gun destroyer, ``rattled your teeth,''
Akers said. With each shot, a 50-foot plume of smoke and fire
jumped from the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first heard the sound of guns around 6:30 a.m. We fired
every shell we had by 2 p.m.,'' Akers said. ``We had nothing left
to fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The USS Gherardi returned back to England for more munitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked all night restocking and headed right back,'' Akers
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the return trip, a dogfight between a German Focke Wulf F190,
a single-seater fighter, and a British Spitfire erupted over the
English Channel. The outcome of the fight didn't bode well for the
Allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 30 miles ahead of us the two planes were duking it
out,'' Akers said. ``The Spitfire burst into flames and the pilot
baled out. We were able to pick him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting was heavy for three days along the 50-mile stretch of
Normandy. During that period, the USS Gherardi protected a
half-mile of beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the German guns got close and we had shell bursts in the
water near us, our skipper would go forward, then reverse to throw
their gunners off,'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   Every six hours came a warm respite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every six hours the ship's cook would bring around a pot of
vegetable soup, then coffee,'' Akers said. ``Before the call to
battle stations, the skipper had opened up the ship's stores and
had all the candy bars and gum distributed to the crew. I guess he
figured if we got dumped in the ocean, at least we'd have our candy
bars.''
</P>
<P>
   After 72 hours, the crew of the USS Gherardi stood down from
battle stations without a causality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined the Navy at 17 because I figured I'd have a better
chance to survive if I got on a ship,'' Akers said. ``After D-Day,
I knew I had made the right decision. If not for that decision to
enter the service young, I might have had to claw my way up that
beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Akers said steak and eggs will always remind him of his
times on the destroyer, the retired seaman still enjoys the
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Let's have at 'em and not wonder about what lies
ahead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
