<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-EDUCATION-GAGRULE0     06-05 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-EDUCATION-GAGRULE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia school chief bans informal contact with newspaper
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Department of Education may be doing great
things to help schools, but the experts there are no longer allowed
to talk about it with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution under a new
policy.
</P>
<P>
   State School Superintendent Linda Schrenko, angered by an
editorial, has banned all but formal, written contact between her
department and the newspaper, according to her executive assistant,
Ed Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   That's unfortunate for taxpayers, especially now that a state
commission is beginning to look at Georgia education from top to
bottom, said Tim Callahan, a spokesman for the teacher group
Professional Association of Georgia Educators and a former
spokesman for Florida's commissioner of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me that it's a real bad time for the Department of
Education to unilaterally single out one specific newspaper, the
largest newspaper in the state, and decide they're not going to do
business,'' said Callahan. ``It isn't the way a public agency does
business in the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Joselyn Butler, spokeswoman for Gov. Roy Barnes, said Friday,
``In this office, we go out of our way to cooperate and not require
reporters to jump through unnecessary hoops to get information. We
feel that other agencies and elected officials should make it
easier and not harder.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Floyd, department employees are to have no further
contact with any person representing the Journal-Constitution or
any function sponsored by the newspaper. ``Any contact with the
department initiated by the AJC must be submitted to the state
superintendent of school's office by means of a written Open
Records Request,'' he said in a telephone message.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Floyd said that a May 5 Atlanta Constitution
editorial, calling some of Schrenko's proposals for school safety
``goofy,'' was the last straw, but that her mistrust of the
newspaper goes back many years, involves several reporters and
includes more than one failed effort to work out an understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Floyd's repeated insistence that the new policy came
from Schrenko, the superintendent has twice denied she had such a
policy, first in a May 24 letter to the newspaper's managing
editor, John Walter, and then in a conversation with Atlanta
Journal editorial page editor Jim Wooten.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a letter if she could explain the discrepancy between
the no-contact policy that Floyd announced four weeks ago and her
own denials of having such a policy, Schrenko wrote: ``My (May 24)
letter still stands. Therefore, no, I can't (explain the
discrepancy).''
</P>
<P>
   The department, in response to two Open Records requests, showed
no written documentation of the policy or of discussion leading up
to it. Since Floyd announced the policy, at least three AJC
reporters, seeking routine information, were not allowed to talk to
the department employee they sought, but told to submit Open
Records requests. Another reporter asking how many schools in the
state use the state's reading program, Reading First, had no
trouble getting a quick answer and was able to get a comment from
the spokesman about the department's position on an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has been further complicated by the fact that
three press officers have been fired, quit or transferred this
year. The position is now empty. Floyd, who was Schrenko's pastor
at Kiokee Baptist Church in Columbia County, and since January has
worked for Schrenko at $80,189, said all contact with the newspaper
should go through him, until a spokesperson is found by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the unwritten policy spread unevenly, but legal counsel
Melanie Stockwell said she had told some employees about it.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd reiterated several times that Schrenko initiated the
policy of ending all but formal, written contacts between the
department and the Journal-Constitution, although exceptions have
been made for Atlanta Journal editorial writers the DOE considers
sympathetic to Schrenko.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Shumake, Schrenko's deputy during her first six months
in office in 1995, said gagging the department's voice is the
opposite of the advice that he gives to local superintendents and
school leaders. ``We know that we will get across a better message,
a clearer message and a more accurate message if we convey
information to the public and the press,'' said Shumake, who has
worked for the department off and on since 1965 and says he
continues to work well with Schrenko.
</P>
<P>
   Shumake recently wrote in his newsletter on state education,
``Comments On Education,'' that Schrenko is better than her image
in the press; that she understands education, teaching and
learning. ``She is either getting very poor advice, or she is
ignoring very good advice from her staff and P.R. advisors.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the new policy terrible public relations, it also
raises serious constitutional questions, said David Hudson, lawyer
for the Georgia Press Association. First, he said, it would be
illegal for Schrenko to discipline anyone in her department for
violating such a policy, because to do so would violate their free
speech rights. Second, Hudson said, if the department allows its
employees to talk to other media outlets, then it is violating the
equal-protection rights of the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're spending taxpayers' dollars, you have a threshold
obligation to talk to the press,'' said Callahan, of PAGE. ``You
are seeking public support for your policies. How better to reach
the public than through the state's largest newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
