u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAHAM-CRUSADE06-COX     06-05 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-CRUSADE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thousands answer Graham's call to accept Christ
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ ``Jesus is knocking at your heart's door. This is
God's moment. Let's don't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Graham made a 45-minute argument for salvation, and on the
first night of his crusade here, more than 2,700 people took him up
on the offer.
</P>
<P>
   It's an invitation the 81-year-old evangelist will offer for a
final time here tonight, in a well-orchestrated worship service
that has drawn crowds of up to 50,000 people each night.
</P>
<P>
   The climax of each evening has been the ``altar call,'' when the
faithful are invited to accept Christ or rededicate themselves to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, as a 4,000-voice choir softly sings ``Just As I
Am,'' they move toward the light that shines on the field level of
the RCA Dome. Some people cry softly. Others clutch hands and close
their eyes in prayer. It's a filled-to-capacity football stadium,
but as calm and quiet as a cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Graham speaks to them as if they are in the intimacy of a
confessional. Together, they pray ``The Sinner's Prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   He asks them to do four things: read the Bible every day; pray
``all the time;'' witness for Christ, and ``bring people here
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham leaves the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Then with an efficiency that is a hallmark of a Graham crusade,
the salvation process begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inquirers'' are matched up with one of 6,000 trained
counselors who lead them through a step-by-step process. Men are
matched with men, women with women; child counselors work with
their peers. Counselor-interpreters in languages from Spanish to
Mandarin hold up signs so that non-English-speaking people can be
accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   Introductions are made, there are hugs and handshakes, and the
counselors read over ``decision cards'' with their inquirers.
``Have you come forward to personally accept Jesus Christ as your
Lord and Savior?'' they ask.
</P>
<P>
   All over the floor of the Dome, people are chanting these words,
huddled head-to-head, sitting cross-legged on the floor, or in
wheechairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray with me,'' they say. ``Proclaim Christ as your savior.''
</P>
<P>
   Inquirers fill out information cards, listing name, address,
phone number and church affiliation, if any. Then, they date the
cards. ``You know what date this is?'' Scott Davis, a counselor
from Dayton, asks a white-haired man, shaking his hand. ``This is
your birthday!''
</P>
<P>
   Inquirers also receive a book: ``Living in Christ: Beginning
Your Walk,'' and a cassette tape that is the beginning of a Bible
study course.
</P>
<P>
   Davis will work as a counselor three out of four nights of this
crusade. With each inquirer, the process ``takes as long as it
takes,'' he says _ but usually about a half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, the information cards are sent to another corps of
volunteers, who, before the night is over, will have matched up
inquirers who have no church affiliation with a church in their
hometown. If they request a Baptist church, that's what they get.
But the volunteers have assembled a list of more than 600 churches,
of all denominations, in central Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a denominational thing. It's a God thing,'' Davis
says.
</P>
<P>
   In the days to follow, counselors will check in by phone with
their inquirers.
</P>
<P>
   How many will keep their newfound commitment to Christ? ``A lot
of people don't make it,''Graham admits. ``If 25 percent remain
active for Christ five years from now, I would be very happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real follow-up agent is the Holy Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the crusade, as the crowd files out into the balmy night,
heat lightning lights up the sky. A bearded young man passes out a
paper that urges readers to ``Ban the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, the bells of St. John's Catholic Church chime
sweetly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
