<HEADER>
A4160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SARAJEVO-OVERVIEW06-C     06-05 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAJEVO-OVERVIEW06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton delegation heads to Bosnia to reaffirm peace talks
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As NATO bombs started falling over Yugoslavia in
March, a group of Dayton-area politicians, artists and business
officials took a second look at a goodwill trip planned for
neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worthwhile to visit a country still rebuilding after its
own war and facing an uncertain summer as its heavily militarized
neighbor, Yugoslavia, is pounded in an escalating war with NATO
forces?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, from Sarajevans and from state department officials,
was yes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bosnians of several ethnic stripes, their country
is trying to get on with the business of peace, even amid the
instability.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after a brutal ethnic war divided the nation and
killed thousands, Bosnia-Herzegovina and its formerly besieged
capital, Sarajevo, are where people are seeking refuge from the
fighting in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   And since Dayton's name is attached to the 1995 peace accord
that ended the warfare in Bosnia, some of the Dayton delegation
still saw symbolic value in a peace mission.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Mayor Mike Turner said Bosnian peace negotiator Richard
Holbrooke called him to urge the group to go when the Dayton group
was considering canceling the trip.
</P>
<P>
   So on Friday, a 13-member Dayton group left for an 11-day trip
to Augsburg, Germany, Bosnia and Croatia. They will sign a Sister
City pact between Dayton and Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention is to formalize the relationship between Dayton,
Bosnia and Sarajevo,'' said Turner, who is representing the Dayton
in the delegation. ``We wanted to make certain Dayton was not just
a geographical spot where the talks occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Cementing a natural connection
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the trip began last November, when the ethnic conflict
in Kosovo was still mainly an internal Yugoslavian affair.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the Dayton delegation included several city
commissioners, spouses and a wide range of area leaders. The group
pared down over concerns about the NATO offensive, which has bombed
sites in Yugoslavia 60 miles from Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia also is not without tension. The U.S. State Department
has a standing travel advisory for Bosnia that warns of ``risks
from occasional localized political violence, land mines,
unexploded ordnance and carjacking.''
</P>
<P>
   David Neer, an assistant to the president of the Dayton
Foundation and a delegation member, said the group does not want to
look like ``a bunch of Americans walking around with USA on their
foreheads.''
</P>
<P>
   But the risk of actual day-to-day danger is considered slight.
United Nations troops are still stationed in Bosnia and many
foreign countries operate relief efforts throughout the country
without problems.
</P>
<P>
   Given the history between the two cities, local officials said
there is no more natural link than between Dayton and Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here are two cities brought together by war and a search for
international peace,'' said Bruce Hitchner, director of the
University of Dayton's center for international programs. ``I can't
imagine two other cities that are better suited for a sister city
relationship. These two cities probably are the most symbolic two
cities associated with the entire Bosnian conflict. This draws
attention to how two cities brought together by the conflict can
work toward peace, hopefully not on a local level but on
international level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton-Sarajevo link began when U.S. negotiators talked all
the sides of the Bosnian conflict into coming to Wright-Patterson
Air Force Base in November 1995 to work out an end to three years
of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The location's primary contribution to the talks was that it
offered few distractions, with the base nestled away in the midst
of flat, brown Midwestern prairie, removed from the intense media
scrutiny of the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The European delegations, including Yugoslavian President
Slobodan Milosevic, toured and ate in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely peace they brokered at Wright-Patterson, however,
ended some of the most vicious fighting Europe had seen since the
Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1990s, conflicts arose between ethnic Muslims,
Croats and Serbs who lived within Bosnia-Herzegovina, a former part
of Yugoslavia that became an independent nation in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial start to the war began later that year when
gunmen opened fire from the upper floors of the Sarajevo Holiday
Inn into a peace rally on the streets below. The Dayton delegation
this week will be staying in that rebuilt hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a Bosnian-Serb military offensive began, backed by the
Serb-dominated army from neighboring Yugoslavia. Troops besieged
Sarajevo and purged non-Serbs from parts of Bosnia-Herzegovina
where Serbs held a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Sarajevo siege lasted three years, with almost-daily sniper
and mortar attacks that nearly leveled the city.
</P>
<P>
   While hostility still simmers among Bosnia's ethnic groups, the
large-scale fighting has not returned. U.N. peacekeeping forces
patrol the nation, and the country's three major ethnic groups
largely live separately. Serbs have set up their own mini-state,
called the Republika Srpska, on the east and northern parts of
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Sarajevo, once an ethnically diverse city that
hosted the 1984 Winter Olympic Games, is now almost entirely
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Trip targets educational, cultural, business links
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton delegation will find the rebuilding in Sarajevo has
gone slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The city's mayor, Hasan Gachanovic, told former Bosnian
journalist Azra Kourin that promised international aid often did
not materialize. The city is nevertheless ready to seek its past
glory and bid to host the 2010 Winter Olympic Games, Gachanovic
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton delegation is scheduled to meet with Gachanovic and
other national and city officials in Sarajevo. The delegation will
host a reception at the U.S. Embassy, and next Friday, will travel
to Tuzla, north of Sarajevo, to meet with U.S. troops working with
the United Nations peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials are trying to establish more relationships
between the two cities than just signed parchment.
</P>
<P>
   While in Sarajevo, Hitchner will finalize an agreement between
the University of Dayton and the University of Sarajevo that will
make it easier for students, faculty and research to be exchanged.
Officials will also cement an agreement to bring the Sarajevo
Symphony to Dayton later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton contingent includes local musicians Michael Bashaw
and Sandy Kreitzer, Dayton City Manager Valerie Lemmie, and Harold
Kaplan of the Dayton Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Bashaw and Kreitzer, Dayton musicians from the band Puzzle of
Light, collaborated with a Sarajevan music company in 1996 in a
performance in Bashaw's studio to recognize the one-year
anniversary of the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Bashaw and Kreitzer hope to play guitar, flute and harmonica
while in Sarajevo, possibly during a performance at a U.S. Embassy
reception Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the obvious cliche of music being the universal
language, but it is true,'' Bashaw said. ``It pulls people
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Early next week, Turner, Kaplan, Lemmie and city Public Affairs
Director Tom Biedenharn will go on to Zagreb, Croatia, where they
will continue efforts to build business contacts between Dayton and
the former Yugoslavia. Croatia was damaged far less by its war with
Serbs in Yugoslavia and has a larger economy than
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   But five years of effort have yielded little so far.
</P>
<P>
   Transwave, a Dayton firm, secured one contract to help in the
rebuilding of Sarajevo's sewer system. But there has been little
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask a Dayton business to go to Sarajevo if there is
no money to pay for those services,'' said Neer of the Dayton
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's job with the Chamber of Commerce is to foster
international trade. Despite two close calls, he said, he has yet
to get work in the Balkans for a local company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not for lack of trying,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   French Oil Machine in Piqua was close to selling vegetable oil
processing equipment to Croatia. A Dayton accounting firm narrowly
missed the cut to monitor the finances of a U.N. program in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to look to find good matches,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, business contacts the region makes could have the
greatest impact in promoting peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people have jobs, homes to go to, food to eat, they are
less likely to be belligerent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
