<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBS06-COX     06-05 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ABC's of Austin's herbal gurus
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If this garden paradise hidden away from the
traffic on east Manor Road was a cup of herb tea, it would be
calming chamomile.
</P>
<P>
   The front porch rockers, chiming bells of a nearby Catholic
church and greenery surrounding the Case Mill Homestead, a grist
mill and home built in the 1850s, all evoke a soothing sense of
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the restored Austin landmark _ the home of the
American Botanical Council _ more than tea is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, an internationally known authority on herbs that has become
a leading source of information for everyone from national media to
doctors and pharmacists, is at the center of an explosion of
interest in all things herbal: Sixty million Americans bought $4
billion in supplements last year.
</P>
<P>
   As herbs have moved from the fringe and into the mainstream, the
10-year-old ABC has been evolving as well. Since moving into its
new headquarters last year, the nonprofit council has been making
plans to increase its local visibility: Today it's included in a
tour of rainwater-collection facilities around the city. There'll
be a grand opening celebration on the grounds in October and
scheduled, guided tours in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know more? Here are the ABCs on the ABC and some of the
herbs and medicinal plants it champions.
</P>
<P>
   A is for astragalus, a plant used in traditional Chinese and
East Indian medicine for its immune-system-enhancing qualities and
recently discovered by people with AIDS and cancer patients
undergoing chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   B is for books. In the next year or two, ABC will open its
library to the general public. (It's now available only to
researchers). Some of the many books now available through ABC's
extensive sales catalogue include biographies of famous herbalists
and primers on traditional medicines in Asia, India, Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   C is for classes. The council offers everything from continuing
education for doctors, pharmacists and nurses who want to know more
about how specific herbs interact with prescription medicines to
courses in aromatherapy.
</P>
<P>
   D is for depression, the condition that's driving sales of St.
John's wort.
</P>
<P>
   E is for echinacea. The top-selling herb in the United States
for the past few years, echinacea is featured on ABC's letterhead.
Also called purple coneflower, it's best known for strengthening
the body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   F is for feverfew, used as a folk medicine for menstrual cramps
since Greco-Roman times. It's usually found in capsule form.
</P>
<P>
   G is for ginseng evaluation project. An ABC study, to be
published this year, will analyze hundreds of commercial ginseng
products to verify manufacturer claims of ginseng levels.
</P>
<P>
   H is for hawthorn and horse chestnut, two medicinal plants
poised to be the next best-sellers. Hawthorn is being used by
people with hypertension, angina pectoris and other heart ailments,
and is frequently an ingredient in ``heart healthy'' teas. Horse
chestnut is thought to reduce inflammation and discomfort from
varicose veins, phlebitis and other circulation problems. It can be
taken internally, or applied topically in lotions and ointments.
</P>
<P>
   I is for ipecac, used to induce vomiting or, in much smaller
doses, as an expectorant, particularly in treating bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   J is for jojoba oil, used by Native Americans and Mexicans as a
hair conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   K is for kudos. ABC founder Mark Blumenthal is senior editor of
the first alternative medicine publication chosen by Doody
Publishing, a leading reviewer of medical titles, as one of the top
three medical books released in 1998. ``The Complete German
Commission E Monographs'' is an exhaustive reference book for
health professionals seeking information about the benefits and
risks of herbal medicines.
</P>
<P>
   L is for lilies. Austinite Leah Neal designed a medicinal lily
garden that features sansevieria, day lilies, garlic, chives,
crinum lilies and many others plants from the family Liliaceae,
used in treating everything from sunburn to coughs to high
cholesterol. Neal won an honorable mention in a garden design
contest sponsored by HerbalGram, the council's publication. Another
prize-winning reader-suggested garden features a winding ribbon of
antioxidant plants and herbs helpful in preventing breast cancer
and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   M is for mission. ABC's is to investigate and promote the safe
and effective use of medicinal plants.
</P>
<P>
   N is for nettle. A tea made from the leaves of the plant has
been used since ancient times to reduce congestion, control coughs
and relieve asthma symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   O is for oak bark. Chopped, powdered and diluted with water,
it's an astringent wash for everything from oozing wounds to sweaty
feet. P is for purification and protection gardens. These flank the
gated entrance, filled with plants thought to provide positive
energy in various cultures: ginger, in Thailand; chili, in Central
America; holy basil, in India; lemon verbena, in Peru and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   Q is for questions. ABC fields inquiries about its research,
programs and tours, but is not a source of information on how to
use herbs medicinally, nor is it a source of herb products.
</P>
<P>
   R is for research. Researchers from around the world will use
ABC's Herbal Education and Research Center, which eventually will
include laboratories. Recent visitor Julie Bonifacio, a botanist
from the Philippines and traditional medicine expert, helped put
together a continuing-education course for health practitioners
who'll be learning about the top 25 herbs. Bonifacio was on a
fellowship from the World Health Organization and her work was
conducted in partnership with the Texas Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   S is for saw palmetto extract, a popular remedy for enlarged
prostate, common in men 50 and older, available in capsules or in
combination with other herbs in formulas designed to support the
male endocrine system.
</P>
<P>
   T is for tours. Blumenthal and others lead trips into the Amazon
rain forest, South Africa and other exotic locales, calling on
local healers to share traditional medicine secrets. The
expeditions have drawn pharmacists and others interested in herbs.
</P>
<P>
   U is for uva ursi, an herb best used in small amounts or in
remedies to treat infections of the urinary tract and bladder.
</P>
<P>
   V is for valerian root, a sleep aid also thought to reduce
nervous irritability, that's usually sold in capsules.
</P>
<P>
   W is for ``What was that again?'' Memory loss among aging baby
boomers has made Ginkgo biloba a top-selling herb capsule.
</P>
<P>
   X is for xanthium, a Chinese herb used to treat sinusitis and
arthritis, and headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Y is for yarrow, recommended for yeast infections and night
sweats. Taken as a tea, or in combination herbal formulas.
</P>
<P>
   Z is for Zingiber officinale, the botanical name for ginger,
used to treat nausea and other digestive difficulties, often in a
tea. Sources: American Botanical Council; American Pharmaceutical
Association's Practical Guide to Natural Medicines; Herbs &AMP; things.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty gardens reflect uses
</P>
<P>
   Looking for ideas about how to use herbs?
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Howearth, a Baha'i and a Mexico-based landscape
designer, is creating a patchwork quilt of theme gardens on the ABC
grounds. When it's all through, you'll be able to stroll through an
anatomy garden featuring herbs and medicinal plants considered
beneficial for specific parts of the body. In a section for skin
and hair, you'll find lavender, basil, sage, thyme, aloe,
calendula, St. John's wort, chamomile and comfrey. The digestive
system plot will have horehound, angelica, catnip, lemon verbena,
licorice and caraway. Then there are the brain herbs: ginkgo,
scullcap, wood betony, lavender, feverfew.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just one garden.
</P>
<P>
   A children's health patch will be planted with chamomile,
lavender, catnip, rosemary, sunflowers, comfrey and others.
</P>
<P>
   An array of Chinese medicinal herbs will include agastache,
angelica, astragalus and camphor.
</P>
<P>
   And an Ayurvedic garden will be filled with cardamom, ginger,
turmeric, aloe, pineapple, celery and capsicum annum.
</P>
<P>
   Other theme plots planned will feature culinary, Appalachian,
Andean, aromatherapy and medieval plants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
