<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-CAMP-1STLD-$     06-05 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-CAMP-1STLD-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DAY IN THE LIFE OF A REFUGEE CAMP: Sunny days; Not so sunny
conditions
 &HT;    EDS: Corrects dateline to SEMAN, sted of SEMA.
 &HT;    With Photo of Naim; photo mug of Roughton.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV06.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEMAN, Albania _ The sun rises fierce and hot at Camp Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The women are the first out of the olive green tents. They want
water from the new spigots set in fresh concrete squares. The water
trickles, so they wait their turns, hands on hips, talking. Most
are tanned, but a few of the fair-skinned women are burned red. It
is not so sunny in Kosovo, which must seem a sweet, cool dream.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians love conversation. It is perhaps their defining
cultural quality.
</P>
<P>
   For those in Camp Hope, that's a good thing because there are
precious few other ways to pass the time. Each day seems much like
the other, except for the evolving conversation topics.
</P>
<P>
   In the tents, the women make breakfasts of jam and bread and
powerful Turkish coffee. It seems that each family has brought a
set of fine small coffee cups and saucers and can entertain guests
at a moment's notice. You would have to be cold-blooded to be
untouched by this small civility in the most barbaric of
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, there were 3,412 refugees in the U.S. built camp
that eventually will shelter 20,000 and have the distinction of
being Albania's largest shelter. Even if the peace plan holds, camp
planners believe most of these people will spend the winter away
from their homes, either at Camp Hope or someplace like it to be
erected in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Life here revolves around the sun. The kind of sun you find in
south Georgia or central Texas or anywhere in Florida in August. So
blinding in its brightness that you can almost hear it. There is no
wind.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't enough, the cracked earth is covered with rocks
and gravel, which are light gray and powdery like the surface of
the moon. The heat is reflected up, creating the effect of an oven.
</P>
<P>
   The only shade comes from a concrete water tower, which is used
as a watch tower by U.S. Marines, who provide security.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m. it is already uncomfortably warm. The young children
squint when they emerge from their tents to head to school in a
military tent.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Naim Crchugju. He's 11 and speaks some English, as do his
five brothers who live with him in tent A2-10. There is something
unmistakably American in a refugee camp in which all the residents
have short and simple addresses and wear nametags.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Naim,'' he says with a smile. ``Get it? It sounds
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines call Naim ``Flounder,'' because he reminds them of
the character from the movie ``Animal House.'' It is hard to
overstate the importance of the 150 Marines to the refugees. After
Kosovo, it must be comforting to see such polite, well-trained and
heavily armed men who are duty-bound to protect you. They are
leaving next week, leaving a void that cannot be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Naim is fair-skinned and sunburned. With little inducement, he
will give you a tour of the camp, and try to hold your hand.
``You're my No. 1 friend,'' he says, asking a visitor for access to
a computer. ``The Americans gave my school in Kosovo a computer.
No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   He hates the food, an agonizingly common complaint. In Kosovo,
they ate fresh food from the farm and plenty of milk and cheese.
Here they get beans and bread and whatever else the aid workers can
scrape together. These days they get a lot of what the refugees
call ``Fish in a Prison'' (canned fish).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the teenagers say the sun saps their appetites anyway.
They spend their time smoking and walking up and down the long wide
gravel promenade that runs between the rows of dark green tents.
Every 100 feet or so, they walk past the wooden latrines, which
emit an unspeakable stink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so sorry, so sorry,'' says Naim, truly ashamed for the
smell.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the heat, the camp seems nearly empty _ except
for poor Marines in bulletproof vests and full battle gear. The
women have taken their small children inside, where the men sit on
their haunches and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The heat begins to break as the sun sets behind a horizon, which
is so flat that the sun lingers as a dull yellow disk before
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   As the evening cools, the camp again comes to life. The
promenade is filled with people chattering. The children say
``Hello'' to every adult who isn't obviously Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   It is social hour. People gather in small masses, squatting,
sitting, leaning, full of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about the day, the politics, things like this,''
Naim volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   There are camp lights, which provide the effect of street
lights. It is pitch black outside the camp boundaries, which is
surrounded by miles of plain. Not too far away, you can see lights
coming from the Marines' camp. From time to time, they ride through
on patrols in their jeeps and Humvees.
</P>
<P>
   After sunset, the camp is a pleasant place with a clear starry
sky and the strangely familiar feel that you find in camp grounds,
the warm sounds of people taking the night air before readying
their chidden for bed. For a brief period, it is easy to imagine
that the horrors they have seen and the miseries they endure here
are lifted from them.
</P>
<P>
   After about 10 p.m., the small children have disappeared again.
Families have lit candles inside their tents, casting warm yellow
glows. Still they talk, but now the conversation is among the 12 or
15 people inside each tent. The talk is muffled and more intimate.
</P>
<P>
   Naim must go in. He's greeted by some Marines who have shed
their armament to stroll the promenade. They kid with the boys who
huddle around them.
</P>
<P>
   As it gets later, even the number of teens on the promenade
shrinks to the few smoking cigarettes. The camp begins to be quiet,
except for the roar of the power generator and endless sound of the
heavy trucks and machinery working through the night to ready the
camp.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, the tents fall silent, except for a few baby cries
and the distinct voices of men sharing their last thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The moon is full, shining on a lone heavily armed Marine making
his late rounds down the promenade.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, the tents are silent. Most, for at least a time,
are in Kosovo once more.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
