</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HUMMER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love match at Belmont? Filly vs. colt
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Of all the strategies and mock-ups offered for
today's 131st Belmont, leave it to trainer Bob Baffert to throw out
the most warped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope as they turn for home, Charismatic is next to
(Silverbulletday) and falls in love,'' Baffert said. ``It would be
like me trying to run after Cindy Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   Love at the eighth pole probably is not an option for the
1,200-pound great-grandson of Secretariat as he bears down on the
elusive Triple Crown. They'll be a little too busy to start picking
out silver patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The last two Belmonts, Baffert was the one attempting to
complete the Triple Crown _ with Real Quiet last year and Silver
Charm in 1997. He clearly is enjoying the role of pursuer now with
the comely filly and run-on word, Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   He is hyping today's race as an eight-legged Billie Jean
King-Bobby Riggs type of extravaganza. The champion colt against
the undisputed best filly in the land. A he-neighed, she-neighed
debate of global proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Making like a racing Don King, Baffert says we are missing the
story with all this talk of Charismatic's bid for the first Triple
Crown in 21 years. The filly is ready to rumble, he crows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a heavyweight title match,'' he said.
``There's a lot on the line, some serious bragging rights. Every
fan is dying to see this matchup. I tell you, this should be on
pay-per-view. I'd like to have a piece of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The man could talk the whitewash off a stable. As the dominant
trainer in 1997 and '98, he has the credentials to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She makes me look so smart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The filly does intrigue. Silverbulletday is the most elegant
animal in the field, a smooth, sleek runner, compared with
Charismatic's muscled-up style. Identified as the top 2-year-old
filly, she has won all five of her races as a 3-year-old, and her
last eight races overall.
</P>
<P>
   But winning the mile-and-a-half Belmont would fly in the face of
history _ no filly has thrived over this distance since Tanya in
1905. Since 1954, only three have tried.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's only concession to the distance was another one-liner:
``I hope she doesn't pull a Robbie Gordon (of Indy 500 misfortune)
and run out of gas near the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten other horses in the field could have some say today, most
notably Menifee, which finished second to Charismatic in both the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness. ``He's had his chance,'' Baffert
said dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first opportunity Charismatic and
Silverbulletday have had to eye each other. The filly was chased
off by the 19-horse stampede that was the Kentucky Derby field and
discouraged by a poor post draw _ far outside 14th _ at the
Preakness. ``She's had a cupcake schedule all spring,'' Charismatic
trainer D. Wayne Lukas warns.
</P>
<P>
   A nice, simple two-horse match race would make a great story.
And how convenient that Charismatic and Silverbulletday will start
next to each other this afternoon _ post positions three and four.
If a distracted Charismatic tries to get the filly's phone number
while waiting in the gate, that would suit Baffert just fine, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
