<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRE-DREAMS06-C     06-05 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRE-DREAMS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing by the rules
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Fans go to Turner Field to see Chipper Jones
hit or Greg Maddux pitch. Not Jonathan Merry.
</P>
<P>
   When the 18-year-old North Hall High School senior watches a
baseball game, his eyes never leave the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Merry's goal is not to be the next Tom Glavine or Brian Jordan.
Instead, he wants to be the next Harry Wendelstedt or Ed Montague.
</P>
<P>
   For most, umpires are nothing more than easy targets for boos
and ridicule. To Merry, the men in blue are heroes to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, that's going to be me out there,'' Merry said.
``That's my dream, and I'm determined to make it come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds of reaching the majors as an umpire are even greater
than of making it as a player. But Merry, who has a reading
disorder, knows about overcoming obstacles. He has done it all his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Born prematurely, Merry had health problems as a youngster. Then
he was diagnosed with a severe form of dyslexia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said I would never graduate from high school,'' said
Merry, who takes tests verbally and does his papers through a
dictation software program on his computer. ``I've been proving
people wrong for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry will graduate from North Hall High School with honors
Tuesday, despite his disability. In May, the Eagle Scout was
honored as Sportsman of the Year at the Gainesville-Hall County
Sports Banquet, and won the Challenged Athlete Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that if Jonathan could graduate from high
school it would be the happiest day of my life,'' his mother,
Rebecca, said. ``But the way he keeps surprising us, who knows?
Seeing him realize his dream to become a major-league umpire would
be very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry hopes to be working in the minors by 2000. He graduated
from the Harry Wendel-
</P>
<P>
   stedt Umpire School this past winter _ ranking 35th out of 155
students, most of them in their 20s. Merry, the youngest student in
1999, will go back to the five-week school in Ormond Beach, Fla.,
next year to try to land a Rookie League job.
</P>
<P>
   Wendelstedt thinks Merry will make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed,'' said Wendelstedt, who retired after 33
years as a National League umpire. ``He has the desire, and that's
always the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wendelstedt admits that he had reservations at first when he
learned about Merry's reading disorder. An instructor dictated the
professional rulebook into a tape recorder for Merry and he was
given the final exam orally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tremendous retention,'' Wendel-
</P>
<P>
   stedt said. ``Tell him something once, and he's got it. The only
thing that I still wonder about is the lineup card.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry said, ``I know that's something I will continue to have to
work at. I write down names phonetically so I can keep track of the
changes when teams make substitutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry, who played football and wrestled at North Hall, got his
start as an umpire by working youth-league games in Hall County as
a sophomore. He had been cut from the high school team the year
before, and umpiring allowed him to stay a part of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved umpiring from the start and knew that is where I
belonged,'' Merry said.
</P>
<P>
   But umpiring youth baseball isn't easy, and he was challenged
right away. A manager complained about a call and angrily asked
Merry to show him the rule in the rulebook.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Merry was watching the game and her heart sank. She had
read the rulebook to Jonathan so he could memorize it and was
confident he had the call right. But she also knew he couldn't read
the rulebook. Luckily, Merry could remember the number for the rule
and even the page it was on. The manager found it in the rulebook
and apologized to the young ump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started crying,'' Rebecca Merry said. ``I couldn't help
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry started thinking about umpiring as a career after he saw a
magazine advertisement for Wendelstedt's umpiring school, where
tuition and room is $2,300. He signed up and adjusted his school
schedule to head to Florida for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I was nervous,'' Merry said. ``Who wouldn't be with
all those major-league umpires watching your every move?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 of Merry's classmates were hired as professional
umpires, starting at the Rookie League level. The salary is $1,800
a month for three months, with $15-a-day meal money and
25-cents-per-mile travel money.
</P>
<P>
   It takes umpires about six years to reach Class AAA if they are
good enough, with at least four more years at that level before
they get a chance at the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nauert of Lawrenceville, one of Merry's instructors, was
hired this year as one of two new full-time umpires in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's not easy to make the majors,'' Merry said. ``You
really have to love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry called high school and colleges games this spring, and now
works five or six days a week umpiring amateur games. He hopes the
added experience will help him reach the minor leagues next.
</P>
<P>
   ``No mother wants her son to be booed or heckled,'' Rebecca
Merry said. ``But I know he can handle it. I can't believe the fans
in the minors are any worse than youth league parents. They can be
pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   JONATHAN MERRY FILE
</P>
<P>
   Goal: To become a major-league umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 18.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Father Jeffery, mother Rebecca and brothers Jeffery Jr.,
23, and Joshua, 17.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Will graduate with honors from North Hall on
Tuesday despite being severely dyslexic. Played football and
wrestled.
</P>
<P>
   Achievement: Eagle Scout.
</P>
<P>
   Honors: Honored as Sportsman of the Year and Challenged Athlete
of Year at the Gainesville-Hall County Awards Banquet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
