<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas has never recorded a colder June day than it did on
Friday, when the mercury failed to climb above 67 degrees. The
chilly weather in the Southwest will yield to more seasonable
temperatures Sunday under bright sunshine. However, a new surge of
cold, moist air from the North Pacific will progress southward
through Washington and Oregon accompanied by gusty winds inland and
some showers near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an interlude of tranquil conditions in the central
and southern Rockies. Skies will remain rather cloudy in Wyoming
and southern Montana as a nearby front causes scattered showers.
Another front in the western plains may produce several severe
storms.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening low pressure system near Fargo will still trigger a
cluster of thunderstorms over the eastern Dakotas, Minnesota and
northern Wisconsin. Jet stream winds will whisk the tops of these
storms rapidly east across the Great Lakes. The leading edge of
hot, humid air should be marked by thundershowers in the St.
Lawrence Valley. A few showers will reach northwestern portions of
New England and clouds and very gusty winds will spread across
central sections.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure centered east of New England will become the
dominant weather factor in the East for the coming week. Its broad
clockwise circulation will draw sultry air from the southern Plains
across the Mississippi Valley and lower Great Lakes. A prolonged
spell of hot, humid weather is likely from the middle of the nation
to the Atlantic Seaboard this week.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: LA Chill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winter made a late appearance in Southern California this week.
On Thursday, Mt. Wilson, 18 miles northeast of Los Angeles, had a
maximum of 38 degrees and a minimum of 30, making it the coldest
June day on record. The chill then progressed farther south and
combined with unseasonal showers early Friday. When the sun rose on
the mountains of San Diego county Friday, 3 inches of wet snow
covered Mount Laguna. This marks the latest snowfall ever, an
entire week later then the previous record. Sunday, the sun will
return and the chill will modify in the Southwest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - end it- Knight &QL;
</P>
