<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY BELGRADE STARTS TO REBUILD AS DESPAIR AND PESSIMISM LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ With the sudden and apparent end of
NATO's bombing war against Yugoslavia, Serbs are relieved, angry,
proud, disgusted and resigned, probably in that order, suggested
Slobodanka Bogic, as she stood Saturday morning in her still
windowless house, helping workers repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough, she said, ``everyone will start to become more
afraid, because the winter is coming and there will not be enough
heat, power or food.''
</P>
<P>
   On a bright, hot, sunny day, with NATO's planes no longer
popping the sound barrier over Belgrade, it is easy to imagine Mrs.
Bogic indulging in Slavic pessimism, the other side of the mordant
humor and endurance that ordinary Serbs have displayed in this
bizarre and unequal war.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Zvezdara, which everyone hopes is the last area of
Belgrade to suffer collateral damage from NATO's bombs, only six
days ago now, it is hard to know what anyone's future holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope our house is the last one smashed in Belgrade,''
Mrs. Bogic said. ``But as for me, I'm not sure this is really over.
My daughter keeps telling me, `Come on, mother, don't be afraid,'
but I'm a pessimist.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her daughter, Olivera, 34, who was asleep in the house
when the bombs hit, she is still shaken, jumping nervously when
even the telephone rings. Her cuts from the flying glass are
healing nicely, but not the damage to her spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Olivera sleeps now in her office, in a real estate agency that
has had little work since the prospects of war began to seem real
in January. Her mother continues to sleep in the basement,
believing that more bombs may yet be coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our psyches are smashed,'' her mother said. ``But the worst
thing is the people who died and the invalids. Who knows how many?
And who will need them?''
</P>
<P>
   The houses here still gape emptily, doors and windows blown out,
though many now are covered with plastic. The Bogics and their
neighbors have fixed their roofs, helping one another as if in a
village. Rubble has been neatly swept up and carted away by the
city. The police barracks across the street are destroyed, like so
many other military and civilian buildings, bridges, factories and
power plants across the whole of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, holed and charred government buildings seem to mock
the peace and remind Serbs of the cost of their resistance, which
at least some believe was entirely in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Parliament building, where Serbian legislators bowed to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and confirmed Serbia's
acceptance of the NATO-Russian terms for peace, a sign remains
displayed in a shop window.
</P>
<P>
   It shows a map of Serbia with a target on it, and over Kosovo, a
large, red heart. The legend reads: ``Clinton, do you know what
this red thing is?'' The paper is yellowing, the plastic over it
cracked. How long will it stay?
</P>
<P>
   While many Serbs fume that the peace deal, or what they
understand of it, means the effective loss of Kosovo, a significant
number of people say their resistance to the might of the world is
a historic achievement. They feel that nothing damaged cannot be
rebuilt, and that Serbian defiance these last 74 days will
represent a new, proud chapter in their history.
</P>
<P>
   On Knez Mihajlova, a pedestrian walkway that is Belgrade's main
shopping street, stalls still sell bitter and amusing postcards and
pins chronicling Serbian defiance and mocking Western leaders. One
postcard shows a burning world wrapped in barbed wire with the
slogan: ``Don't worry. NATO is only here to give you a big warm
hug.'' The first six letters in ``big warm'' are in red.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs still promenade in their best casual clothes, drinking
espresso and smoking imported cigarettes as if they hadn't a care
in the world. ``It's a show, of course, just like our television,''
said Dragisa Bogdanov, a mustachioed 40-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He describes himself as opposed to Milosevic, but feels the deal
Milosevic got ``was the best we could get.'' Bogdanov shrugged.
``How could we win against the world? But at least the West
admitted it had to deal with us instead of just bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``I'm very afraid of the people who will have no
future. Factories, shops, bridges and other things are completely
destroyed. The problem here is that people don't think with their
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others feel that many more Serbs with skills will now
seek to leave a broken country that faces further Western sanctions
and the continued rule of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly speaking, I and my friends are still afraid,'' said
Ilija, a businessman whose business is nearing collapse. ``We
always feared that there would be all this destruction and death
and NATO would leave him still sitting there on top. We fear he
will be the winner, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be domestic unrest as winter nears, Ilija said, and
the soldiers come home with their stories and no barracks in which
to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people are also afraid of more blood,'' he said. ``I
marched for six months for the democrats, but they've become like
all the others. They sell themselves for a cheap price. People are
fed up with our politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An elegant woman in black called the pact ``Cherno-Bill,'' a
reference to a common joke here about a deal between President Bill
Clinton and Russian envoy Victor Chernomyrdin. ``Russia's become
the 51st state,'' she said in disgust. ``We are not all in
agreement with this agreement,'' she said bitterly. ``They say
there is peace, but I'm in black.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clothes were of mourning, she said, for relatives killed by
NATO bombings in Nis, where one of NATO's accidents of war put a
cluster bomb near a market and a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   There is significant bitterness toward Milosevic, but there is
much directed at what many Serbs consider American arrogance and
hypocrisy, where the language of human rights has clothed the naked
exercise of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I'm grateful to the Americans,'' said a prominent
Serbian journalist who asked anonymity. ``They make it clear that
the world is ruled by force. I'm almost sorry I don't live in North
Korea, with a nuclear bomb. Because then they wouldn't dare to have
done this to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksa Djilas, a historian and analyst of Milosevic's career,
said he would predict a new race by every little nation in the
world for nuclear, biological and chemical weapons in order to
prevent this kind of war from the air. ``Even if we had some
S-300's,'' the Russian version of the Patriot antiaircraft missile,
he said, ``the outcome might have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the loss of Kosovo now would fester, becoming
what Sudetenland _ German-populated territory in pre-World War II
Czechoslovakia _ was for the Germans, a potential cause for the
next war. And he is not alone in believing that this new, Western
protectorate over Kosovo, no matter how long it lasts, will be seen
by both the Serbs and the armed Kosovo Albanian rebels of the
Kosovo Liberation Army as a historic interlude before the next
chapter of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some in the West see Serb nationalists as Nazis,''
Djilas said. But the Serbs, he added, ``see themselves as
Israelis,'' alone against the world if necessary but true to their
land and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Others simply want their sense of isolation to end, for the
borders and airports to reopen, so they and the world can once
again come and go.
</P>
<P>
   But others see a period of continued isolation and further
hardship, with the future only worse than the recent, terrible
past.
</P>
<P>
   In Zvezdara, the Bogics have applied for state and city aid for
war damage, and an official has come and taken photographs of their
house. But Mileta Bogic, 62, thinks they will not see any money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like World War II,'' he said bitterly. ``Those who
were in the camps got nothing and the money all went to Broz,'' the
postwar leader of Yugoslavia known as Tito.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who care about Kosovo and its loss will learn to live
without it, he said. ``Soon, this war will only be real to the dead
and their families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
