<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-POLAND-ART-2TAKE     06-05 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-POLAND-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART ON SLEEVE, THE POPE GOES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GDANSK, Poland _ Pope John Paul II arrived Saturday in the
birthplace of the Solidarity movement that he sparked with his
first papal visit 20 years ago, offering Poles ``the greeting of a
fellow Pole who comes among you to fulfill the needs of his own
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth return to Poland by John Paul II, and like
all the previous trips it is an emotional homecoming by a Pole, now
79, who has never masked his deep nostalgia for his native land.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's 13-day visit, the longest of his tenure to Poland, is
grueling, crammed with Masses and meetings that will take him _
sometimes by helicopter _ to 21 different towns. It is a thematic
kaleidoscope of his papacy, allowing him to relive historic
moments, revisit religious landmarks, greet old friends and also
weave his own personal story with that of his nation and the entire
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one thing is different: The visit may well be the
first time that the pope has returned to Poland without a dramatic
emergency awaiting him. ``You are coming to Poland at a time when
sovereignty, security, and fast economic progress are seen as a
normal thing,'' Poland's president, Aleksander Kwasniewski, a
former Communist, told the pope at the arrival ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   From his first, electrifying papal visit in 1979 to Gdansk,
where a workers' revolt against Communism eventually took fire
across all of Eastern Europe and spread, in the end, even to the
Soviet Union, to the last visit, in 1997, when former Communists
seemed poised to win parliamentary elections and the country was
divided over a new Constitution, fellow Poles have always met the
pope with a frenzied outpouring of affection _ and an urgent
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The affection, lavished on the aging and frail pontiff by tens
of thousands of Poles who lined his parade route to town Saturday,
holding up signs and shouting his name, has not slackened. But the
tension, urgency, and feverish excitement has ebbed.
</P>
<P>
   Poland still has troubles, yet 10 years after Communism
collapsed the pope is returning to a country where the president,
once a minister in a Communist government, has proved his
commitment to democracy and capitalism. Poland became a member of
NATO this spring. Since 1997, its Parliament has been dominated by
political parties that support democracy _ and heed the Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his pontificate, in Warsaw, John Paul II
will address a national Parliament. He chose Poland, because it is
Poland, and also because this month is the 10th anniversary of the
overthrow of Communism at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Poland was the first Eastern European country where democracy
was voted in by elections, a ballot box triumph that paved the way
later in 1989 for the collapse of the Berlin wall and the crumbling
of Communist rule in East Germany, Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and
Romania.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary address is also the pope's way of paying
homage to one European democracy that still appears willing to heed
his moral teachings. All three branches of government will be
represented at the meeting, as will the diplomatic corps. Religious
leaders, Catholic and non-Catholic, are also invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their presence is a way of showing that democracy should in
some way be bound by ethical values,'' said Joaquin Navarro-Valls,
the pope's spokesman. ``Not just those of the Catholic Church, but
all religions in Poland.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, however, it was the Catholic Church that lobbied
Parliament to pass a law that bans abortion in all cases except
when the mother is a rape victim or her life is at stake. A few
weeks before his visit, with the support of the Catholic Church,
the government finally removed the crosses at the Auschwitz camp at
Oswiecim that had been erected by Catholic extremists in defiance
of the Polish bishops, and arrested the ringleader _ swiftly
smoothing over a religious controversy that has helped poison
relations between Jews and Catholics for years.
</P>
<P>
   Poland is perhaps the only capitalist democracy where the
government has banned alcohol sales and removed billboards
featuring scantily clad models in every city and town the pope
visits. The pontiff is not a teetotaler, but the Polish authorities
worry that excess drinking could lead already excitable crowds to
unseemly public behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Poles are worried about that. Adam Michnik, a former
dissident who now edits the newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza, assured
fellow journalists that some bars would remain open. ``We are a
very Catholic country, but we are secular when it comes to
alcohol,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of Poles are Catholic, and 75 percent
describe themselves as practicing believers, making Poland one of
the most devout countries in Europe. The pope, who is to meet on
several occasions with religious leaders of different faiths _
Eastern Orthodox, Jewish, Lutheran and Muslim _ will preach an
ecumenical message to a country that has not yet had much practical
experience in reaching out.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the conservative leader of
Poland's Catholic Church, seemed eager to embrace the pope's agenda
on this trip, conceding that ``there is also a need to work on
development of ecumenism, social justice and solidarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many intellectuals and liberals are hoping that the pope's
presence _ scarcely viewed as a liberalizing force among West
European Catholics _ will prod his conservative home church to be
more accepting. ``The Polish church is changing, and is more
accepting of democracy, but there is still a ways to go,'' said
Artur Domoslawski, a journalist who recently published a book about
John Paul II and his theological critics within the church that
caused a stir in a country that has yet to look critically at its
national hero. ``This visit is a chance for the pope to direct his
message of reconciliation also to the Polish church.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Poland is not exactly free of political tension or social
turmoil. The economy is relatively healthy, and even though its
growth rate has slowed, it is still expected to be 4 percent this
year _ twice that of many, more developed, European countries. Yet
economic reforms are painful, particularly in such traditional
fields as heavy industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, farmers have been using blockades and mass
protests to force the government to increase food prices and
forgive debts. The government last month granted concessions, such
as subsidies to grain producers, partly in hopes of staving off a
conflict during the pope's visit _ although such subsidies may
complicate Poland's hoped-for entry into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Kwasniewski told the pope that there was ``a large margin of
bitterness'' among those left behind in the economic and political
transformation of Poland, and conceded that ``the positive changes
of the last years have not spread evenly across the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of farmers' and other protesting unions who had asked
for an audience with the pope were rebuffed by Polish bishops,
mostly because their political representatives belong to parties
that are deeply opposed to the current government and unfriendly to
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say that the pope nevertheless insisted on adding two
stops to his schedule to towns where economic changes have cost
people jobs and security. The pope is also expected to meet with
miners and steelworkers in the industrial center of Silesia.
Restructuring plans for the aging and inefficient industries there
call for 140,000 layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has long warned against the economic injustices of
capitalism. In 1991, he scolded newly liberated Poles so sternly,
and perhaps prematurely, about morality and the dangers of Western
materialism that the visit was considered his least successful.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday he seemed mostly impressed by the economic and
social changes that have transformed a country he lived in during
the World War II occupation and Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   The pope paid his respects to the ``cry of conscience'' that
rang out first in Gdansk, and led to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I notice with joy that our country has made great progress on
the path of economic development,'' John Paul II told the cheering
crowd. ``I pray unceasingly that Poland's material development will
increase at an equal rate with its spiritual development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      06-05 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A MATURING ELECTORATE REALIGNS SOUTH AFRICA'S
OPPOSITION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ When South Africa's 15,000 polling places have
been cleaned up, the white and blue election commission flags taken
down and the final votes counted, it may look as if nothing much
happened in last week's elections.
</P>
<P>
   President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress will have
the vast majority of the seats in Parliament, as it did before. The
man who was running the day-to-day affairs of the country, Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki, will officially become president _ and go on
running the country.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition? Well, it won't be any bigger than before.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look reveals a sea change. Parties that have long
histories in this country virtually died in this election. One new
one got a foothold that will keep two potent personalities in the
headlines. Though the opposition numbers are still tiny, the
African National Congress may end up facing a far livelier
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Change may come from Mbeki, too. In the last few months, he has
sent strong signals that a major housecleaning is just around the
corner. A few weeks before the election, he fired three of the
country's nine provincial premiers in one bold stroke. Even before
that, several of the party's oldest and least effective Cabinet
ministers quietly announced that they would be retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki said recently that he would not appoint ``politically
popular'' ministers who were not very hard-working. ``This is not a
status thing,'' he said of membership in the Cabinet. ``This is a
working thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's Cabinet was a complex quilt, constructed not so much
for competence as to create a huge unifying umbrella at a time when
the country's peace was fragile. It reached out to as many
constituencies as possible and included almost every kind of South
African, from white Afrikaners to former guerrilla fighters, labor
leaders, Communists, a Zulu chief and a Pondo princess.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Mbeki is signaling a different organizing
principle _ the ability to administer. He is heeding the voters'
call, and the ANC may get even more than the 62.6 percent it got
last time. But it had to work for that support. Early on, the party
was down in the polls, huge numbers of voters were undecided and,
with crime high and jobs scarce, complaining was the national
pastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Thabo Mbeki heard all that,'' said Chris Landsberg,
the deputy director of the nonprofit Center for Policy Studies
here.
</P>
<P>
   South African racial barriers were not broken in this election.
The majority of blacks stuck to the African National Congress.
Nonblacks went elsewhere. But there was a great deal of movement
among the opposition parties. The big loser was the New National
Party, which gave South Africa apartheid and ruled for more than 40
years. In 1994, it finished with 20 percent of the vote and the
title of official opposition. This time the count suggests that it
will not get more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Its core supporters _ white Afrikaners _ jumped ship for the
liberal Democratic Party, a party that was founded on the principle
of opposition to apartheid and is now led by a feisty lawyer, Tony
Leon.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller Freedom Front, an Afrikaner party dedicated to
establishing a ``volkstaat'' where Afrikaners can rule themselves,
also lost most of its support, dropping from 2 percent of the vote
in the last election to less than 1 percent in this one.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of the Afrikaner vote, say many analysts, shows
that while Afrikaners are not yet ready to vote for a black-led
party, they have at least abandoned their ethnic fraternities and
begun voting on the issues. Many Afrikaners see the Democratic
Party, with its emphasis on individual rights, federalism and a
willingness to duke it out with the African National Congress, as
their best protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``However you look at it, it's a big deal for them,'' said Tom
Lodge, a political analyst with the University of the
Witwatersrand. ``They moved to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon's party had only seven members in Parliament last time and
yet managed to dominate the opposition, leading battles against
affirmative action, corruption and trade legislation that was
likely to anger the United States and Britain. Now, with at least
five times as many seats, the party will surely keep the fire under
the ANC's toes.
</P>
<P>
   One of South Africa's most interesting political phenomena has
been the emergence of the United Democratic Movement, founded by
Bantu Holomisa, a black former African National Congress official
thrown out of the party for insubordination, and Roelf Meyer, an
Afrikaner who left the National Party when the old guard was
unwilling to make the changes he thought necessary.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, the party was often involved in violent
confrontations with ANC supporters, which may have blackened its
image for potential white backers. As the votes were counted, it
was clear that Holomisa and Meyer were disappointed in their 3
percent share.
</P>
<P>
   But it is enough to give the United Democratic Movement a sure
toehold in Parliament and government funds to continue. It was not
eligible for a dime as it tried to begin its campaign, yet it
clearly worried the African National Congress, which spent the last
few weeks trashing Holomisa as an apartheid-era puppet.
</P>
<P>
   The elections also seemed to sound the death knell for the
Pan-Africanist Congress, which in the 1960s was the ANC's chief
rival. Many young blacks sympathize with its ``Africans first''
rhetoric, but its leadership crippled itself with infighting and it
was incompetent both in Parliament and in campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   As early election results came in showing it getting less than 1
percent of the vote, its leader, the Rev. Stanley Mogoba, offered
to resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
