<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4210 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUNICIPALITIES-ACCOUN     06-05 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUNICIPALITIES-ACCOUNTING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL GOVERNMENTS MAY HAVE TO OPERATE MORE LIKE BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City will have to dust off decades-old files to
determine the value of the 116-year-old Brooklyn Bridge. California
will have to value hundreds of miles of eight-lane freeways. And,
hundreds of cities will struggle to tally up the cost of schools,
jails and sewers built many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The group that sets the standards for how the nation's 84,000
state and local governments keep their books is expected to approve
a plan this week that would require them to operate more like
businesses, providing taxpayers with a more complete picture of
what their dollars buy.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which has attracted little publicity, has
nonetheless prompted hundreds of cities, towns and other local
governments to deluge the rule makers with letters predicting how
difficult and costly it will be to comply. Municipalities say they
are already overburdened by work associated with the Year 2000
computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But citizens groups laud the plan, saying it will eventually arm
taxpayers with new information that will help them understand when
their politicians are spending too little, as well as when their
ambitions have grown too large.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would fundamentally change the way that government
officials look at almost all financial decisions, from spending on
infrastructure to borrowing money to selling properties. But most
significantly, it would make many costs that are now hidden and
shifted to future administrations far more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a major step in the right direction,'' said
Roland Calia of the governmental Research Association, which
represents dozens of taxpayer groups across the nation. ``This will
help people raise questions about what their government is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   For many government officials, who until now have been allowed
to live in the moment _ recognizing cash only when it comes in and
costs only when the checks have been sent _ the changes are nothing
short of momentous. Even officials who applaud the new rules say
that the costs of compliance are frightening. Under the most
significant and controversial change, governments will for the
first time have to calculate the value of nearly every major asset
they own, from roads to bridges to prisons to hospitals, even if
those assets were acquired or built decades ago. Until now, the
value of those projects vanished from view on financial statements
almost the moment the money was spent.
</P>
<P>
   To comply, governments say they will have to hire armies of
accountants, engineers, consultants and appraisers to come up with
the numbers, money that could be spent on worthier causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to think, `I'm just not sure what I'm
going to do,''' said Jake Lorentz, assistant director at the
Government Finance Officers Association, a Chicago-based group of
more than 14,000 state and local officials. That group has opposed
the new rules because of the costs it would impose, especially on
the smallest cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   The Governmental Accounting Standards Board, which is at the
heart of the firestorm, has not been the object of such heated
debate since it began setting rules in 1984. Based in Norwalk,
Conn., the group's seven voting members are scheduled to approve
Statement No. 34 on Thursday. Its 200 pages of particulars are
expected to impact nearly every government in America, except the
federal government, which writes its own rules. Board chairman Tom
Allen, the former auditor of Utah, said he expected unanimous
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the board retreats, the largest governments would start
using the rules for fiscal years beginning after June 15, 2001.
Smaller governments would have one or two more years to comply.
</P>
<P>
   The rule makers have already made concessions in a few crucial
areas to appease critics.
</P>
<P>
   Governments with fewer than $10 million in annual revenues will
not be required to go back and put a value on their existing
infrastructure. But in future years, they would be bound to the
same rules as everyone else. And all governments would be exempt
from having to establish values for assets that were acquired more
than 25 years ago, unless significant renovations have taken place.
Thus, the Brooklyn Bridge might have escaped the process, but it
was renovated around the time of its centennial in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another concession, the board is also prepared to allow
the governments to estimate the cost of historic projects if that
is easier than going back through old records and determining the
actual expense. And governments will have another four years from
the effective date of the rules to include the cost of projects
built before the new rules were adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, much work will be required. In New York state, for
instance, officials must value 37,000 miles of state-owned roads
and 7,800 bridges as well as assign values to hundreds of
university classrooms, state hospitals and prisons.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Sam McCall, the state's deputy auditor general, said
accountants would have to determine the cost of the giant Sunshine
Skyway Bridge that spans Tampa Bay and was built in 1987. ``In the
past, we've taken the position that bridges were not going to be
sold, so we haven't recorded it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By forcing states and cities to include the cost of bridges and
roads on their annual financial statements, McCall said that it
would not be so easy to put off necessary repair and maintenance
when money is tight. ``If you don't fix a pothole, it only gets
bigger,'' he said. ``This is progress.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The board can not legally enforce its rules. But most state and
local governments are now required to abide by the board's
standards as a condition of the municipal bonds they issue. And, in
some states, lawmakers have passed legislation requiring cities and
towns to follow the accounting board's rules. And unless they
comply fully, governments could not expect their outside auditors
to endorse their financial statements, a red flag that would invite
taxpayer scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The board has been debating the wisdom of these new rules almost
since its inception, especially since there is no easy answer just
how to arrive at the values government officials are now expected
to produce. Should a bridge be reported at original cost,
replacement value or at some combination? Should those numbers be
adjusted for inflation? If it is architecturally significant, does
that matter?
</P>
<P>
   For now, the board has settled on relying largely on what
governments actually spent in building or acquisition costs. Those
numbers would decrease for each year of wear and tear, or increase
if the government was spending on meaningful improvements. As
vexing as all that is, governments also have to hazard a guess on
how many years those highways, bridges, prisons, schools,
firetrucks and other assets might last.
</P>
<P>
   With that information, governments' willingness to undertake
certain projects _ and what taxpayers understand about those
projects _ will almost certainly change.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a state that builds a prison for $100 million and
expects the building to last for 50 years would show $2 million in
building costs each year under the proposal. Currently, however,
the state would just report a one-time expense of $100 million in
the year the prison was built. In later years, voters who look at
the financial statements would see salaries for correctional
officers but nothing for the prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't known in the past what it cost to operate a
prison,'' McCall said. ``This will help people understand what it
costs to operate the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed system, voters would see the total cost of
operating the correctional system, allowing them to weigh the
trade-offs between building prisons and, for instance, paying for
projects that keep people out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another significant break with the past, governments
would no longer be able to shift a cost to the next year simply by
delaying payment. Until now, governments have been allowed to wait
to record an expense until a bill was paid, a financial maneuver
that is like allowing consumers to pretend they did not owe money
on purchases charged to their credit cards. But the new rules will
require governments to accrue costs in the same way businesses do.
For example, a cost will be recorded when office supplies are
delivered, not when the bill is eventually paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system has been like a little family checkbook,'' said
Wilbur Ross, executive managing director of Rothschild Inc., who
has advised New York City on some financial matters in the past.
``That is no way to run a thing as big and complicated as a city
like New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Far less controversial is a proposal to require governments to
prepare one comprehensive financial statement to account for all
the money coming in and going out. Now, governments account for
their services in many different funds, which has confused both
citizens and financial experts.
</P>
<P>
   But governments would also be encouraged to provide more
detailed breakdowns on specific services so that taxpayers can more
easily spot how much it costs to provide police protection, run the
schools, pick up garbage, or operate amenities like public golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting board is also poised to require government
managers to answer for themselves, much the way executives of
public companies do. Each fiscal year, elected officials would have
to give taxpayers ``an objective and easily readable analysis'' of
the government's financial performance. Government officials will
have to explain such things as why they sold a large piece of land
or issued millions of dollars in bonds. And for the first time,
officials must explain why they spent more than was approved in the
budget at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens will be able to see government as a whole so that
there can no longer be any games played simply by moving things
around,'' said Andrew S. Rein, who has spent years trying to track
how the governments of New York City and New York state spend
taxpayer money as a research analyst for the Citizens Budget
Office, a nonprofit group. ``They will have a much better view of
what is going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
