<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-NYT &LR;      06-05 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER INSIDER STILL HOPES LEADERS WILL RETHINK TIANANMEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Since last year, Bao Tong, a former senior Communist
Party official, has been prodding and exhorting China's leaders to
rethink their verdict on June 4, 1989, when soldiers used guns to
quash a massive pro-democracy protest, killing hundreds in and
around Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Bao, the highest government official jailed after the crackdown,
spent seven years in prison, followed by two years of house arrest,
for sympathizing with the protesters. He was released in May 1998
and quickly started talking publicly from time to time about the
incident that still haunts him.
</P>
<P>
   The killings are never openly discussed or written about in
China, except for government statements that the decision to call
in soldiers was necessary to quell ``a counterrevolutionary
rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   No one of Bao's stature has been willing to condemn the
Tiananmen killings publicly. In the tense week leading up to the
10th anniversary of the event, he intensified his efforts, writing
commentaries for liberal Hong Kong newspapers about the need to
reassess Tiananmen and discussing this strictly taboo subject on
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Tiananmen killing is not condemned, China is unlikely
to fundamentally achieve long-term political stability,'' he said
in a recent interview, adding, ``The issue will not die away.''
</P>
<P>
   As the top aide in 1989 to Zhao Ziyang, who was then president,
Bao was witness to many of the decisions that sent tanks rolling
into Beijing on June 3 that year. When Bao looks at a dais holding
the Central Committee members, he knows who supported negotiating
with the students and who supported firing on them.
</P>
<P>
   Many high officials, prominent academics and company leaders who
supported the students and recoiled at the thought of sending in
troops later lost their jobs in 1989, and now live in quiet
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Bao, a young-looking 66, has chosen a different route, and says
plainly that he considers the killings both a national tragedy and
a political error.
</P>
<P>
   Under constant surveillance, he treads on China's most forbidden
territory, seemingly oblivious to the minefields, most notably the
possibility that he will be rearrested.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese police have repeatedly warned him not to give
interviews and have prevented him from meeting visitors, but have
gone no further, perhaps because they fear the outcry that more
aggressive action would prompt here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that the police are ``generally rather polite and
well mannered,'' preventing face-to-face interviews, but not
usually interfering with phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his precarious position, Bao is a direct and
relentlessly upbeat man. Interviewed for a book that will be
published outside of China later this month, he calls his life
``very relaxed,'' centered around reading, calligraphy, shopping,
taking his granddaughter to school and tutoring her in math.
</P>
<P>
   Bao told the interviewer, an exiled Chinese journalist named
Zhang Weiguo, that his relations with the government were
``normal,'' adding, tongue in cheek, ``The government is probably
extremely concerned with my safety, and there are probably many
people who spend every moment of every day worrying about me.''
</P>
<P>
   They may have good reason: There remains much discomfort within
senior government circles about the Tiananmen killings, and Bao is,
to many, a respected old comrade.
</P>
<P>
   When Bao was hospitalized several years ago, his medical chart
indicated that he should pay his own bills, as a former convict and
disgraced party member. But on seeing his name, the doctors and
nurses decided not to charge him.
</P>
<P>
   As a former insider, Bao has produced writings that have
provided some insight into the decision-making process that called
in the troops, though he has been circumspect about pointing
fingers at those still in power.
</P>
<P>
   China's leadership was deeply divided on how to respond to the
protests, Bao said in an interview, with Supreme Leader Deng
Xiaoping supporting a ``crackdown on rebellion'' and Zhao wanting
to negotiate with them ``based on democratic principles and rule of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the public didn't know was that Zhao's policy had
obtained support of a majority at both the Politburo meetings of
May 8 and May 10,'' Bao said. ``But Deng Xiaoping tragically
overruled Zhao and I continue to believe that most of the senior
leaders did not want to see a crackdown and a halt to political
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao was toppled just after June 4 and has been under house
arrest ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Zhang, Bao said that in 1989 ``what might
have been a tremendous opportunity for kick-starting political
reform was destroyed, and we took a road backward.'' He noted that
while students may have been too uncompromising, the government
bears responsibility for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``My own thinking at the time was that I expected
reform would suffer a setback, but I never imagined they would
actually open fire on ordinary Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the troops came in to Beijing, Bao was brought to
Qincheng Prison, where he was imprisoned for the next seven years;
he never saw another inmate. He was originally charged in part with
passing news of the crackdown to the students.
</P>
<P>
   Bao was questioned extensively in an effort to understand which
of his former colleagues shared his pro-student views. ``But sadly
I'm indolent by nature, and not much of a socializer,'' he told
Zhang. ``So apart from regular work I didn't have much to confess
or impart.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his experiences, Bao is an inveterate optimist,
believing that current leaders may at some point reverse their
verdict on Tiananmen _ even though they have said they will ``never
reappraise it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he takes issue with the common wisdom that the current
leaders will not rethink June 4 because it would undermine their
authority; Li Peng, the Communist Party's second in command, was
premier in 1989 and declared martial law.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Communist party clearly believes that reassessing the
killings on June 4 will open a Pandora's box, signaling to people
that may once again aggressively speak out in their demands for
political change. In the days leading up to the 10th anniversary,
the center of Beijing was a picture of precaution, filled with
uniformed and plain-clothed police.
</P>
<P>
   But Bao argues that the leadership would actually score points
by opening discussion of a bloody event that still weighs heavily
on the minds of ordinary Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The current approach ``is a policy of mobilizing fear,'' he
said. ``But in my view, if the change could be initiated by the
highest authorities, the gain for China would be maximized and the
risk to them minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders have not listened to his advice, of course,
and speaking out has had a cost. Bao applied a year ago for a
passport to visit his son in the United States. He has made a dozen
visits to various government offices, who all say they cannot
accept his application.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``It seems the whole public security apparatus doesn't
know where I can send my application.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
