<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NY     06-05 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS VOTE NEARS, INDONESIA BRACES FOR RESULT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia steps into the unknown on Monday
with a highly complex parliamentary election in which, even if
everything goes smoothly, the outcome is sure to cause confusion
and protests.
</P>
<P>
   All across this huge archipelago, with its population of more
than 200 million, supporters of 48 parties have been celebrating
the country's first free election in a generation with a campaign
that has all the euphoria of a victory rally. Helicopters shower
crowds with leaflets, daring young men climb tall monuments to hang
strings of flags and convoys of buses wind through the streets with
sure-footed youngsters dancing on their roofs.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest Islamic nation, repressed for three decades
by former President Suharto, is pouring all its hopes for change
into this vote. Many are going to lose, a prospect they may not be
prepared to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of hope,'' said Annette Clear, an American
election monitor. ``The danger of violence comes later, when
people's hopes are dashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's tortuous and obscure electoral process, unfolding
one year after Suharto's forced resignation, seems almost intended
to cause consternation.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ballot, a tally of 30 percent or 35 percent by any
one party will be considered a victory in the overcrowded field,
but that will be only the first step in the competition for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition-building will come next, and even that will be just
the beginning of a process _ filled with pitfalls _ that could last
into November.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, among many, is that the 462 representatives to
be elected on Monday will constitute only two-thirds of an assembly
that will choose Indonesia's next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plurality of the leading party will probably be no more
than one-third,'' said Eric Bjornlund of the National Democratic
Institute, an American organization that is helping monitor the
election. ``That adds up to one-third of two-thirds. That's it.''
No one political party, therefore, will be able to stake out a
clear future for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of the 700 presidential electors will include 38
members of the military; 35 appointed representatives of sectoral
groups like religious leaders and civil servants and 165 regional
representatives to be chosen by the country's 27 provincial
assemblies, whose members will also be elected on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, on the eve of the election, the details of the
procedures for choosing the sectoral and regional representatives
still have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   As this untested process plays out, members of what seems to be
the winning party, who may dance in the streets next week, could
bit by bit see their victory taken from them. Vote manipulation,
money-politics and back-room dealing, as well as the legitimate
workings of the electoral system, may dull their joy.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, many will be dissatisfied. There are Islamic
parties who see this as their chance to win greater influence.
There are human rights groups hoping for unprecedented freedoms.
There are populists for whom the election is the chance for a
wholesale redistribution of the nation's wealth. There are the
perennially affronted student groups, who it seems will be
satisfied with nothing short of utopia.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those groups share a common opponent, Golkar, the party
of Suharto, which won every election during his 32 years in power
and is still the incumbent party, with the current president, B.J.
Habibie, as its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Golkar has looked comparatively weak during the campaign, not
daring to fly its yellow flags in some areas dominated by the
opposition. But it could still wrench its way back into power
through its political savvy, money and control of the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   It also appears to be politically strong in the outlying islands
of Indonesia, far from the showy parades of the political center on
the main island of Java, where a victory by opposition parties
sometimes gives the appearance of being inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   If Golkar is not crushed in Monday's vote, it may be able to
count in the presidential election assembly on the support of the
military bloc, which was a pillar of Suharto's old regime, as well
as on a disproportionate share of the provincial delegates, many of
whom are likely to be career Golkar functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, elected representatives have no legal obligation to
stick with their parties, and the potential price of a
parliamentary seat is rumored to run into the hundreds of thousands
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   With the raucous campaigns amounting to a show of force and
electoral momentum, particularly by the opposition party of
Megawati Sukarnoputri, the danger is that the losers may not accept
the results, said Donald K. Emmerson, an expert on Indonesia at the
University of Wisconsin who is now in Jakarta to observe the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kind of over-optimism on the part of many parties,
and if Golkar, for example, gets a plurality, a number of
Indonesians won't need to know anything more about the elections,''
he said. ``They'll conclude that somebody must have cheated on a
massive scale _ even though, to be fair, that may not be the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the picture recently at a voter education center in
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a free and fair election?'' came the question.
</P>
<P>
   The answer: If Golkar wins, the election was not free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is what some analysts, in a sort of hangover of
cloak-and-dagger caution, like to call the ``Cendana factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Cendana is the home of Suharto, the ever-smiling, ever-enigmatic
former leader who many people still believe is the most potent
political force in the country _ a billionaire with good friends in
the military and the country's best network of powerful contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have the possibility of Cendana obstruction,'' said
Kenneth D. Wollack, president of the National Democratic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   For all their expertise on Indonesia's election system, said his
colleague, Bjornlund, ``We've never figured out the Cendana
factor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
