u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ARABS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ARABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB DISUNITY STANDS IN WAY OF NEGOTIATING WITH ISRAELIS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ The election of a new Israeli government has
rekindled Arab hopes for renewed Middle East peace talks, but an
enduring rift between Syria and the Palestinians has blocked an
effort to forge a common Arab stand.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff has been intensely frustrating to many Arab
commentators, who see Ehud Barak's election as Israel's prime
minister as an opportunity for progress toward a broader Middle
East peace but believe the Arabs will be strongest if they can
speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who was elected three weeks ago, has signaled a
willingness to resume peace talks with the Palestinians, Syria and
Lebanon, possibly as early as mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   After Barak's election, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak had
tried to bring those parties together with Egypt and Jordan to
coordinate their stands. But on Friday, he was quoted as saying
that he had abandoned that effort for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot press for the convening of the meeting because there
is a Palestinian-Syrian rift,'' Mubarak told the state-owned
Egyptian newspaper Al Ahram.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting is regarded as a problem by Arab experts because
of the nature of the issues that might soon be on the negotiating
table, including the fate of Jerusalem, and of the Palestinian
refugees scattered across the Arab world. The concern is that these
issues might become submerged by the bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that the five would-be participants open the
lines of communication and hash out the issues,'' The Daily Star, a
Beirut newspaper, wrote in an editorial on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many differences to be sorted out,'' it continued,
``and probably a few apologies to be made if, as Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad said not too long ago, the Arabs are to make peace
with each other before heading into any serious attempt to do so
with the Israelis.''
</P>
<P>
   While Egypt and Jordan made their own peace with Israel, and the
Palestinians have started down that road, Syria and Lebanon have
not. What still separates the Palestinians and the Syrians is the
decision made in 1993 by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to agree
to the step-by-step peace with Israel spelled out in the accords
worked out secretly in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has never forgiven Arafat for taking that step, which left
Syria and Lebanon isolated as the only front-line Arab states still
technically at war with Israel, and that resentment still runs
deep.
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, Syria's bitter criticism still rankles,
as does the fact that Syria and Lebanon still play host to Arafat's
enemies, in the form of Palestinian factions like the militant
Islamic groups Hamas, Islamic Jihad and the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Farouq al-Sharaa, the Syrian foreign minister, said on a visit
to Lebanon last week that the differences between the Arabs would
not have been reconciled by a day or two of pomp and pageantry _ a
scathing reference to the summit meeting that Egypt had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the election of Barak, an apparent dove compared with his
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, has been seen as tantalizing by
many Arab politicians, although most take pains to disguise their
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the withdrawal of an Israeli-backed militia from
an enclave in southern Lebanon, although not related to Barak's
election, is being seen as a possible prelude to the full-scale
Israeli withdrawal from its occupation zone along the Lebanese
border that Barak has said would take place within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this much: Barak cannot be worse than Netanyahu,''
Lebanon's prime minister, Selim al-Hoss, said in an interview here
this week. Nevertheless, Hoss said: ``We are reluctant to wager on
Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lebanon, and for Syria, the very prospect of further Israeli
withdrawals poses difficulties. Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon, has been a crucial backer of the Hezbollah guerrillas,
whose 17-year campaign against the Israeli occupation force has
been instrumental in forcing Israel to consider a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah campaign in Lebanon, the last active front in the
Arab-Israeli conflict, has in effect been Syria's main pressure
point on Israel _ and a tool for efforts to force Israel to
renounce its annexation of Syria's Golan Heights, a front that the
Syrian government has preferred remain quiet.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel were to withdraw from Lebanon, Syria would be left
without that pressure point, so both Lebanon and Syria have refused
to discuss the issue except as part of peace talks involving all
three parties.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak and the Egyptians clearly believe that such a stance
will be more effective if it is echoed by all of Israel's immediate
neighbors. ``A five-way meeting of these states must be held,'' he
was quoted as saying in Al Ahram on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
