<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-5T     06-05 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-5TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGING WAR ON THE SERBS: OLD PROBLEM, NEW LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a curious mismatch of a war.
</P>
<P>
   In the near corner stood the richest, best-armed military
alliance in history: The American-led North Atlantic Treaty
Organization had been around for 50 years without having to fight a
war. It was big, but bulky. All 19 of its members had to agree
before it could throw a punch.
</P>
<P>
   In the far corner stood a wily Balkan dictator who answered to
no one but himself: Slobodan Milosevic specialized in using thugs
and his antiquated army to fight hugely destructive wars that he
ultimately lost, but which whipped up nationalist fervor inside
Serbia. They had kept him in power in a new Europe that has no
stomach for dictators.
</P>
<P>
   Equally odd were the rules. As President Clinton laid them down
on day one: ``I do not intend to put our troops in Kosovo to fight
a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of White House skittishness about U.S. combat deaths,
NATO was obliged to do what had never been done: Win a war without
risking its own soldiers on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   If the peace deal holds up, the curious war comes out this way:
The bulky alliance won, but at a savage cost to the people who were
supposed to be protected. Much of Kosovo has been razed, more than
1 million of its ethnic Albanian residents have been uprooted and
thousands of innocents have been killed. The West will have to
spend many billions of dollars to rebuild what it and the Serbs
have destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The dictator lost, but he stays on in his shrinking Yugoslavia.
If his bad habits hold and if the Serbs do not depose him, he may
well cause trouble another day.
</P>
<P>
   And just possibly a new lesson in war has been learned. Thanks
to the wonders of high-tech weaponry, an overwhelmingly powerful
alliance can crush a small nation's aggressive will without having
to risk its own soldiers, if it is willing to spend enough money
and if it can stomach mistakes that kill innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In the end it was a 72-day campaign of violent accretion.
</P>
<P>
   As bombs did their work, diplomats from the United States,
Western Europe and Russia ignored the West's oratory about
Milosevic being a latter-day Hitler and went about the delicate
business of offering him an exit.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombs did their work, Milosevic's forces did what damage
they could in Kosovo; then he prepared his people for another lost
war. As soon as he was offered a way to stay in power while losing,
he jumped on it.
</P>
<P>
   Generals and politicians often learn the wrong lessons from the
last war. The wrong lesson that U.S. officials took from dropping
bombs to end the war in Bosnia in 1995 was that Milosevic would
fold after a few days of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-chance attempt to head off war in Kosovo on March 23,
Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. special envoy to Yugoslavia, failed to
scare Milosevic with the threat of imminent bombing.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the country, Holbrooke was asked if he feared
that NATO's air attacks would ignite a humanitarian catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is our greatest fear by far, by far,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what NATO, operating only from the air, could do to
prevent a catastrophe, Holbrooke went silent and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   The Bombing Begins
</P>
<P>
   `Lessons' of Bosnia Did Not Apply
</P>
<P>
   The bombing began on March 24 and on Monday, March 29, in the
Oval Office, the grim faces of Clinton's top foreign policy
advisers, captured in official photographs and in the memories of
participants, told the story: War in the Balkans was going to be
brutish _ and not short. Hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians
were being terrorized and bullied out of Kosovo by Milosevic's
forces and NATO seemed helpless to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The president and other officials insisted in public that they
had anticipated Milosevic's defiance and had expected his brutal
ethnic assault on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But in private they acknowledged their shock, disappointment and
miscalculation. ``It's one thing to say we expected this,'' a
senior adviser said. ``But living it is not the same as thinking
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only had Milosevic refused to give in but Yugoslav
anti-aircraft gunners had downed an American F-117 stealth fighter
the night before. The loss of the aircraft, one of the jewels of
the U.S. military arsenal, was a propaganda coup for Serbia and an
embarrassing display of the vulnerability of high-technology
weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton concluded that his top aides _ including the secretaries
of state and defense and the director of central intelligence _
needed an injection of fighting spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys, let's not lose sight of why we did this,'' the president
told the group, according to one participant. ``Let's not forget
what prompted us to do this and who is responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The responsible party, Milosevic, had been the principle
provocateur in the collapse of Yugoslavia. He had orchestrated the
bloodiest explosion of violence Europe has endured since World War
II. During the 10-week war in Kosovo, he presided over a grisly
forced exodus that outraged the world and was indicted by an
international court on charges of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not a fool, and he had compelling reasons for
fighting, many of which made popular sense inside Serbia. Kosovo
has genuine religious and historical meaning to 10 million Serbs.
Peacefully surrendering control to the ethnic Albanians would have
been a national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   As important, as least to Milosevic, Kosovo was where he found
his feet as a strongman. In 1989, when he was president of Serbia,
he stripped the Albanian majority of its power by revoking the
autonomy that the province had enjoyed and tapped a deep vein of
rage among Serbs who for decades had resented the clout of other
ethnic groups in Tito's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rambouillet conference outside Paris in February, after
12 months during which the rise of an armed rebel movement in
Kosovo had led to Serbian attacks against civilians, the West
presented Milosevic with what he and many Serbs regarded as a
``capitulate or be bombed'' agreement. ``If there had been any
`cake,' Milosevic might have cut a deal,'' said Vuk Draskovic, then
a minister in the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   There was no cake to offer, as Holbrooke, looking defeated and
deeply worried, acknowledged on his way out of Belgrade. The next
day, March 24, the bombs began to fall. To Washington's
astonishment, Milosevic was more than ready for war.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stage 2
</P>
<P>
   The Only Alternative: More Fire Power
</P>
<P>
   The day the bombing began, one top Air Force general in
Washington fretted privately about a ``new Vietnam.'' On June 2,
the day before the peace deal was announced, another very senior
Pentagon official expressed doubt that the air war could ever be
won and predicted that the bombing could go on for years.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``hope to win'' strategy, said Colin Powell, the
retired general and architect of the Persian Gulf war in 1991,
which was won with a combined air-land-sea strategy of overwhelming
force.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was that just a few bombs would push Milosevic back to
the bargaining table. But the Serbian leader had launched a
blitzkrieg of ethnic purges, burning and looting Albanians' homes
and killing and mutilating enough Albanians to send hundreds of
thousands of others fleeing at the first sound of rifle butts
against their doors.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House did not have a Plan B.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to realize that his ruling out of ground troops was
a mistake, according to a White House official, and the president
last month made a point of saying he was keeping all options open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has never been prepared to lose,'' this official
said. ``From the first day, he said we have to win this. It was
absolutely clear. Because of the consequences for the U.S., for
NATO, for his responsibilities as commander in chief, we had to win
this.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's only alternative, then, was to bomb _ a lot.
</P>
<P>
   More than 33,000 missions were flown and during 12,500 of them,
bombs were dropped or missiles were fired. Hampered by bad weather
and political fears in the alliance, the air campaign started
slowly and ineffectively.
</P>
<P>
   But over time more precise weapons allowed NATO to destroy
virtually any major target it wanted at minimal risk to its pilots.
Only two aircraft were lost, and both pilots were quickly rescued.
While three Americans were captured on the ground _ abducted,
Americans believed, by Macedonians sympathetic to Yugoslavia _ they
were eventually released.
</P>
<P>
   In the last weeks of the war, a rebel Albanian offensive flushed
Serbian forces out of hiding places along the Kosovo borders and
NATO aircraft were able to cut many of them down.
</P>
<P>
   `Collateral Damage'
</P>
<P>
   Making Mistakes, Mending the Rifts
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes in the air campaign _ the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade and attacks on passenger trains, buses,
hospitals, bridges and apartment buildings that killed 1,500
civilians, by Yugoslav estimates _ brought apologies from NATO, but
no change in tactics. As weeks passed, NATO commanders were given
increasing license to go after targets like electricity grids and
water supplies. For the first time in a decade of war in
Yugoslavia, the suffering was brought home to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy on May 7 threatened
to splinter the alliance; some members, notably Greece, Italy and
Germany, faced mounting domestic protests over the civilian toll.
</P>
<P>
   As orchestrated violence erupted in China, with mobs trapping
the U.S. ambassador in his embassy, the allies realized there was
no turning back on the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Chinese Embassy debacle marked a turning point, one
at which formerly reluctant NATO members agreed to widen the range
of targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the bombing to come to an end quickly but realized
we needed to intensify to make that happen,'' one official said.
``The flip side of intensification was there would be more
collateral damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the bombing campaign began to bear fruit, the
Clinton administration had to orchestrate the 50th anniversary of
NATO in Washington so that the alliance would not be torn apart in
its search for an endgame.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of that late April meeting, the Greeks and Italians
were already making noises about a halt in the air campaign. Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain was making even louder noises,
giving speech after speech about how NATO ought to capitalize on
the bombing. He wanted to send in ground troops after the Serbian
forces were demoralized and crippled, but before there was an
agreement to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary, though, held together. Clinton pushed the issue
of ground troops off the table by convincing NATO's
secretary-general, Javier Solana, to announce a formal assessment
of ground-troop options in the weeks after the summit ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leaders presented a united front, cobbling together a
set of core demands that the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart,
summarized in four words, ``Serbs out, refugees back.'' These
demands, plus the non-negotiable insistence that Kosovo be occupied
by an international force with NATO at its core, formed the basis
of the peace plan that Milosevic signed six weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   But the crucial difference between what he accepted and the
Rambouillet plan, from Milosevic's point of view, is that the
international force is not composed solely of NATO soldiers and is
to operate under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Sidestep Slavic Allegiances
</P>
<P>
   There remained, though, a towering brick wall between NATO and
any peace settlement with Milosevic: the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The night the bombing began, Russia denounced it as an act of
brazen aggression and suspended cooperation with NATO. Yevgeny
Primakov, then the prime minister, made a dramatic U-turn in the
sky, turning his plane back from a trip to Washington at which
Russia had hoped to win loans from the International Monetary Fund
for its crumbling economy.
</P>
<P>
   (As it happens, the U-turn was staged to appease an angry
Russian public who sympathized with the Serbs, according to an
adviser to Russian President Boris Yeltsin. He said Primakov had
been informed before his plane took off that the bombing would
start.)
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, desperate for a partner in his war against the West,
seized on Russia's support and demanded that its traditional Slavic
ally become a player in any deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian government's enthusiasm for Milosevic,
notwithstanding its bravura show of solidarity as the bombing
began, has always been tepid. Milosevic, after all, had supported
the Communist generals who had tried to overthrow Yeltsin in 1991.
As Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy to the Balkans,
later told German officials, ``Russia cannot identify with this
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moscow was squeezed between a domestic political need to appear
to be defending the interest of the Serbs, and a compelling
economic need to secure more financial help from the West.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing began, many Western European leaders tried to
entice Yeltsin back into cooperation with NATO. Since the peace
agreement, officials in Bonn, Germany, and Washington have both
claimed that they had played the pivotal role.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, it seems, had greased the diplomatic track before
serious contacts were made between Washington and Moscow. Michael
Steiner, chief diplomatic adviser to Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
was driven at first by the conviction that the Russians had to be
brought on board for a political solution to be reached. Otherwise,
Milosevic would always have wriggle room.
</P>
<P>
   A political solution was the only viable way out for Germany
because if NATO moved toward a ground invasion, Schroeder's
coalition government would almost certainly fall. The Green Party,
a key part of the coalition, adamantly opposed a ground war.
Because Germany, then, would not back a ground invasion, a
political solution was needed to avoid a hugely damaging rift in
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a central difficulty in winning over the Russians.
It was Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally, we never said `the Russians,''' Steiner said. ``We
said `Yeltsin and Primakov,' because we knew there were different
positions and different possibilities there. And we always had the
sense that Primakov might go before the end of the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's first visit to Bonn on March 30 was a disaster. He
had been in Belgrade on March 29 and came straight from Milosevic
to meet with Schroeder. His position shocked the Germans. He was
supportive of Milosevic and denounced the ``illegality'' of the
NATO bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spoke in this turgid bureaucratic language of the old
Communist past,'' Steiner said, ``and what he had to say was
essentially that Russia defended Milosevic's position.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the outset, however, German contacts with Yeltsin
suggested that he saw little sense in putting Russia's standing in
the West on the line for Milosevic. Yeltsin's appointment of
Chernomyrdin on April 14 as special envoy to the Balkans was the
first concrete sign that the Russian position was shifting. He
fired Primakov a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was quickly invited to Bonn, where the meeting with
Schroeder went much better. Chernomyrdin was no pushover, but he
made clear from the start that he had no special sympathy for
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Mediation
</P>
<P>
   Team of a Russian and a Finn Arrives
</P>
<P>
   On April 25, 11 days after Chernomyrdin's appointment, Yeltsin
called Clinton. The NATO anniversary summit meeting was still going
on and Clinton was in a secure holding room at the Mellon
Auditorium in Washington preparing to address the closing session.
</P>
<P>
   According to administration officials, Yeltsin had decided he
had to reassert Moscow's position as a major world power or risk
being marginalized in the most important conflict in Europe since
the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders spoke for 90 minutes, with Yeltsin presenting a
variety of ideas for ending the Balkan war on terms acceptable to
Moscow and Belgrade, according to a U.S. official who spoke to
Clinton immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rejected most of Yeltsin's suggestions as incompatible
with the simple NATO principles: Serbian forces out, ethnic
Albanians back under the protection of a force with NATO at its
core. This rejection of Russia's ideas for ending the war while
embracing Russia's desire to once again be a big-league diplomatic
player became a defining and productive pattern of the talks that
produced the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Yeltsin's ideas did take root _ the reopening of the
dormant channel of communication between Vice President Al Gore and
Chernomyrdin. They had met several times when Chernomyrdin was
still prime minister in what became a prime channel of U.S.-Russian
communication.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke twice by telephone during the following week, with
Gore repeating the NATO position and Chernomyrdin replying that
Milosevic was unbending in his resistance to the occupation of
Kosovo by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   With matters at a standstill, Yeltsin called Clinton again on
Sunday, May 2, telling the president that he wanted to send his
envoy to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would be happy to receive him, and did so the
next day. Chernomyrdin met for 90 minutes in the Oval Office with
the president and his foreign policy team, and then traveled the
three miles to Gore's official residence on Embassy Row.
</P>
<P>
   That evening Chernomyrdin and his small delegation spent three
hours with Gore; Sandy Berger, the national security adviser;
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott; and Leon Fuerth, Gore's
top foreign policy aide. Little progress was made, but the door was
left open for new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 the next morning, the Russians called Gore's staff.
Chernomyrdin wanted to meet for breakfast. He had a new idea.
</P>
<P>
   Over muffins at Gore's house, Chernomyrdin proposed a team of
himself and someone who would both be acceptable to Milosevic and
trusted implicitly by NATO. The idea excited the White House team,
which that morning had been joined by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. ``I thought it was good to come at Milosevic from two
angles,'' Albright recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, but
Albright quickly vetoed that idea. She had another name: Martti
Ahtisaari, the president of Finland, a patient negotiator who had
worked 13 years for a peace in Namibia and who for years had urged
Europe to be patient with Russia. As the leader of a neutral
nation, he could meet with Milosevic and, according to a senior
administration official, Albright trusted him not to weaken or
compromise on NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voht!'' Chernomyrdin replied in Russian. ``That's it!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, after Ahtisaari was persuaded to come on
board, the State Department devised what it called a
``double-magnet strategy'' with the Russian and the Finn.
</P>
<P>
   As an administration official put it, ``They bring the Russians
closer to us and in turn bring the Serbs closer to a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement suited the Russians, who had warned that they
would never serve as a mere ``postman'' for NATO's demands.
Chernomyrdin could play good cop in negotiating with Milosevic,
setting down general principles of peace, while Ahtisaari, the bad
cop, could insist on the unpalatable details of surrendering Kosovo
to a NATO-controlled force.
</P>
<P>
   Albright busied herself stamping out what she called ``envoy
envy.'' To that end, she made scores of phone calls _ to the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, to members of Congress, to Czech and Greek leaders _
demanding that they stay out of Belgrade. Her aides say she was
determined not to let Milosevic play envoys off against one
another.
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly adamant that the United Nations be kept
backstage and out of Belgrade. Her aides say she pressured Annan to
delay naming an envoy. After he selected Carl Bildt, a former
senior official in the Bosnia peace deal, and Eduard Kukan, the
foreign minister of Slovakia, Albright convinced the
secretary-general to limit their role to implementing peace after a
deal was completed.
</P>
<P>
   She distrusted the United Nations because she felt that in the
past its negotiators had been played for fools by Milosevic. She
feared that such envoys would complicate and possibly derail the
work of Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   Also in early May, Germany's cultivation of the Russians paid
off. At a Bonn meeting of the Group of Seven industrial nations,
plus Russia, the first joint statement about ending the conflict in
Kosovo was issued.
</P>
<P>
   It was extremely vague on all the most contentious issues,
particularly NATO command of a peacekeeping force, but its
political message was clear: The Americans, the Europeans and the
Russians were trying to work together. In this sense, it amounted
to a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The Agreement
</P>
<P>
   Marathon Sessions Across the Continent
</P>
<P>
   To hammer out the wording of the peace agreement, Talbott, the
State Department's senior expert on Russia, met with Chernomyrdin
and Ahtisaari four times in marathon negotiating sessions. In these
and other meetings, whenever Chernomyrdin persuaded Talbott to
change the wording of the peace deal, he would ask, in Russian:
``What about Mother Boss? Will she be OK with this?''
</P>
<P>
   (He was referring to Albright, who said Chernomyrdin never
called her ``Mother Boss'' to her face, but only in reference to
her when he was negotiating with Talbott.)
</P>
<P>
   The first marathon session was at the official residence of the
Finnish president in Helsinki. Two sessions were held on the
grounds of Stalin's dacha outside Moscow, and the final one took
place over the first two days of June near Bonn, at the Petersberg,
a palatial former government guest house.
</P>
<P>
   This meeting was the longest and most fraught. Working out a
two-page, take-it-or-leave-it peace plan took until 4 a.m. on
Tuesday and much of Wednesday, until the hour when the negotiating
duo was scheduled to leave for Belgrade. The trickiest part was
persuading Chernomyrdin to accept the NATO conditions _ referred to
by Talbott as the ``family jewels'' _ in front of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Chernomyrdin was heading off for his fifth trip
to see Milosevic and he did not want to leave Belgrade with only
``jaw jaw'' as the result, one U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   After a dinner with Chernomyrdin, Ahtisaari and their host, the
German chancellor, Talbott slipped away to talk to Berger and
Albright. He then proposed a footnote to the document that was
being prepared for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote spelled out demands that the Russians had been
resisting for weeks: NATO command and control of the peacekeeping
force with control of the operation in the hands of the North
Atlantic Council, the chief decision-making body of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote allowed NATO to make its demands without Russia
having to formally endorse them, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin pledged not to argue when the document was
presented.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the Russian envoy promised to remain silent
when the Finnish president told Milosevic that if he did not accept
the conditions, the demands would only get more stringent as the
war wound on, an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade
</P>
<P>
   An Edgy Final Round With Milosevic
</P>
<P>
   When the negotiators met with Milosevic in Belgrade on Wednesday
night and Thursday morning, they found him ``serious and calm,''
according to a U.S. official. ``He did not seem under excessive
stress, as Chernomyrdin had reported from his previous visit,'' the
official added.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was respectful, correcting one of his colleagues when
he failed to address Ahtisaari as President Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   The two visitors immediately set the ground rules. They were
mediators, not negotiators. They explained the document. As they
had expected, Milosevic asked if there could be revisions.
</P>
<P>
   He was told, flatly, no.
</P>
<P>
   In the first sign of acquiescence, Milosevic told them he would
send the document to his Parliament for approval. In an odd effort
to create more cover for himself, Milosevic invited Ahtisaari to
address the Parliament; Ahtisaari declined.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first evening session, Milosevic offered a
meal, but the visitors said no thanks and went off to consult their
delegations.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Milosevic appeared to be more agitated and his
military chiefs looked fairly distraught, Ahtisaari later reported.
Milosevic opened the meeting with a rendition of the importance of
Kosovo to the Serbs, and as he was nearing the end, Ahtisaari
interrupted and asked Milosevic what he was going to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb replied, according to an American, ``We accept your
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   To seal the deal, the Yugoslavs were given the telephone number
of Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, along with several other
numbers at NATO. They were told that they should call one of the
numbers to begin the military negotiations. No mention was made at
the meetings of Milosevic's indictment on charges of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators then flew to Cologne, Germany, on Thursday to
brief Talbott and the heads of the European Union who were meeting
there. Later that day, Talbott went to the North Atlantic Council
in Brussels, Belgium, to brief the 19 NATO ambassadors. The meeting
started at 8:30 p.m., and when Clark walked into the room about 30
minutes later, he announced that he had just received a call from
the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs, according to Clark, suggested that they have
their first meeting on Sunday to work out precise details of the
Serbian withdrawal. Clark reminded them that the bombing would
continue until there was a verifiable withdrawal of their troops.
``How's Saturday morning?'' the Yugoslavs replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a plan, a strategy, a concept with regard to the
Russians,'' Talbott said on Friday. ``What happened this week has
played out impeccably.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs
</P>
<P>
   A Leader Patches Up His Political Fences
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in Belgrade, Milosevic was eager to cut a deal. Weeks
before, he had started to prepare the public for a political
solution as early as the first week of May. That it took another
month may have been a result less of his unwillingness to make a
deal than of the West's slowness to grasp that he was serious.
</P>
<P>
   The signs were everywhere. The visit of Jackson, during which
Belgrade handed over the three U.S. soldiers, was shown endlessly
on Belgrade television, complete with praise for Jackson's calls
for peace and for an end to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   All of Chernomyrdin's visits were given broad coverage, as the
state-controlled press abruptly shifted from obsessive coverage of
NATO bomb damage to an emphasis on diplomatic progress. The two top
generals in charge of the operation in Kosovo went to Belgrade to
report to Milosevic that their work was done. The Kosovo Liberation
Army, they said, had been routed, and the sovereignty of Kosovo was
assured.
</P>
<P>
   The propaganda machine that had aroused public opinion for war
in Kosovo began heralding the end of the military campaign and
preparing Serbs for a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic reportedly prepared a major announcement of a troop
withdrawal on May 9, a day when Chernomyrdin was due to visit
Belgrade. But the Russian envoy did not come and the announcement
the next day was downplayed, while being dismissed in the West.
When Chernomyrdin delayed his trip for a whole week, he was
criticized sharply in the official newspaper, Politika, a sign of
Milosevic's displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there were signals in May that the Serb
people, who had rallied around Milosevic in March, were fed up with
the war and growing angry. Demonstrations in the southern towns of
Krusevac, Aleksandrovac and Raska began after the delivery on May
14 of 10 bodies of soldiers killed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds gathered at the funerals, and there were protests at the
bus stations as more reservists were due to leave for Kosovo. Only
women protested at first, defying the ban on demonstrations during
the state of war declared shortly after the NATO bombing began.
They were careful in their demands. Not wanting to appear
unpatriotic, they asked for their sons and husbands to be allowed
leave, or at least be allowed to serve in shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government had announced a withdrawal from Kosovo,
they asked that their men be allowed home first. Some said they did
not want their men to die in a war they no longer supported. The
authorities tried to order the women home. When that did not work,
the top general, Col. Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic, traveled to meet with
the women personally. He also allowed many of their men to go home.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later as the demonstrations continued and even
spread, Pavkovic went to Raska to meet with soldiers and their
families again. After still more demonstrations, the authorities
moved in and made arrests. The regime, though, seemed shaken by the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the cities, the loss of water and electricity
brought home how miserable life was going to be if the war
continued. Ordinary Serbs began to think that civilian deaths did
not mean very much to NATO. They said, too, that NATO did not make
mistakes and that it hit hospitals in Belgrade and Nis on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it doesn't matter how they end it,'' said Momir
Karadarevic, 72, who was busy retrieving wooden beams and window
support from the rubble of his home in Valjevo. ``If you ask me,
this shouldn't have started in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Milosevic appears to have decided that months of
bombing were more likely than ground troops and that there was
little to be gained from enduring it. Belgrade analysts and
diplomats believe that Milosevic calculated that peace was better
suited to his personal survival than war.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombing had even started, there were whispers in
Belgrade that Kosovo would be lost after a war that cost the Serbs
dearly. It had happened twice before, in the former Yugoslav
republics of Croatia and Bosnia, when Milosevic abandoned the Serbs
there.
</P>
<P>
   In an uncanny bit of prophecy before NATO's bombing campaign
began, a Belgrade journalist, Bratislav Grubasic of the VIP news
agency, described Milosevic as a realist who knew it would be
better for the people of Serbia to cut a deal in Kosovo before
bombs fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is not his way,'' Grubasic said. ``Milosevic's way is
to stretch it out, make it as messy and nasty as possible, and then
still lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
