<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ACCORD-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S COMMANDER PRESENTS PACT TO THE SERBS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Five senior Yugoslav military officers came
here Saturday to meet with NATO officials and to review and sign
the terms for their withdrawal from Kosovo after 10 weeks of
bombardment by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In what could mark the end of a decade of wars that destroyed
Yugoslavia, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, commander of NATO forces
here, presented the technical military agreement to Gen. Obrad
Stevanovic, assistant secretary of the interior, and Gen. Blagoje
Kovacevic, representing the Yugoslav general staff.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO officials had made clear in advance that there were to
be no negotiations, only acceptance of the document to end the
weeks of killings and forced expulsions by Serbian troops that led
more than half a million Kosovo Albanians to flee the province.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and the Parliament in
Belgrade had already accepted NATO's terms to end the airstrikes on
Thursday, after meetings with a special Russian envoy and the
president of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no negotiations, only discussions,'' said the
NATO spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin Clifford. ``They are going over
every page. It is extremely important that this is gotten right.
Both sides need to understand what is meant by the words.''
</P>
<P>
   After five hours of discussions, members of the Yugoslav
delegation left in cars at about 5:30 p.m. and returned across the
border to use secure telephone lines to consult with officials in
Belgrade about a ``few points of detail,'' NATO officials said,
without giving more information.
</P>
<P>
   Without revealing specifics contained in the document presented
Saturday, NATO officials said it spells out, among other things,
how and when Serbian troops are to leave Kosovo, the routes NATO
troops are to use to enter the province, and the NATO troops and
equipment to be used in maintaining peace there.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires the Yugoslav army to remove the land mines with
which they have seeded the province, according to a NATO official.
And unlike the military annex to the peace accord that ended the
war in Bosnia in 1995, this document is a separate military
agreement that goes into effect as soon as it is signed.
</P>
<P>
   If the document is signed Saturday, NATO troops could enter
Kosovo as early as Monday. First, though, Serbian troops must
demonstrate in at least 24 hours that they are indeed withdrawing.
Only then, said a NATO spokesman, Maj. Trey Cate, would the
alliance call a bombing pause. The first of the 16,000 NATO troops
would immediately enter into Kosovo on the heels of the withdrawing
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature abhors a vacuum,'' Cate said, ``so we'll be following
pretty closely behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO would reserve the right to resume bombing if the Serbian
forces fail in any way to abide by the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Two sedans carrying the Yugoslav officials arrived here two
hours late for their 9:00 a.m. appointment with the NATO
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The delay came when the Yugoslav delegation, waiting across the
border less than one-half mile away, raised questions with a NATO
official about several details of the meeting, including their
insistence that the modest roadside cafe NATO had leased for the
meeting was not in a sufficiently neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that this was an attempt to postpone Saturday's signing,
NATO officials immediately solved the problems ``at the highest
levels,'' Clifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the hundreds of reporters waiting outside, the Yugoslav
officials then entered the restaurant, near the site where railway
cars had only recently disgorged some 60,000 dispirited Albanians
who had been evicted from Kosovo by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, the Yugoslav delegation sat on one side of a
U-shaped table across from Jackson, who is British, and two top
NATO officials, including one American officer.
</P>
<P>
   The four brigade commanders from Italy, France, Germany and
Great Britain sat behind the men and were joined by at least 20
other NATO officials. The meeting was put together so hastily that
the place cards were blank for the Yugoslav delegation because
Belgrade was unable to confirm who would represent the Yugoslav
military.
</P>
<P>
   As they read the document line by line on the green-covered
tables, representatives of the two sides regularly excused
themselves to walk out of the restaurant and use secure
walkie-talkies to call headquarters. First a Serbian general, then
Jackson himself, strode out of the hilltop cafe to speak in private
about matters of interpretation and translations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the atmosphere in the somber dining room was ``very
professional,'' according to Clifford, the NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As the discussions continued into late afternoon, Clifford said
they may be continued on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion marked the most humiliating defeat for Yugoslavia
under Milosevic's leadership. It was 12 years ago in Kosovo that
Milosevic gave the speech that propelled him to power, asserting
that no one would again harm the Serbs who had become a minority in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a military agreement, Milosevic is not required to
sign the document, allowing NATO to avoid further negotiations with
the Yugoslav leader, who was indicted for war crimes last month by
an international tribunal. Nor were any other members of
Milosevic's government who have been indicted sent here from
Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MORE)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO officials completed writing the military
agreement, which is a revision of the military annex to the accord
negotiated in February in France, according to a NATO spokesman.
NATO officials then sent the document to the Yugoslav government
and settled on Saturday's meeting. For extra insurance, NATO
commanders confirmed the appointment late Friday night with the
Yugoslavs after the North Atlantic Council had approved the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels Saturday, the NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said
Jackson had full authority to lay down detailed withdrawal terms to
the Yugoslav commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firstly, they have to commit themselves, and Yugoslavia, to a
phased and rapid withdrawal of the Yugoslav ground forces,'' Shea
said. ``This means that all personnel, all organizations with a
military capability, must start to withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``This would involve, of course, units from the
regular army, but also armed civilian groups, national guards,
border police, army reserves, military police, the intelligence
services, police of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, local special
riot and anti-terrorist police, and any other groups or individuals
that will be designated by General Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also means that as these military and police forces leave,
they will have to stick to a firm schedule, using designated
assembly areas and designated routes, and designated areas that
will have to be vacated,'' he added. ``The withdrawal of the
Yugoslav armed forces must be completed within seven days from the
entry into force of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav forces would also have to agree to withdraw all
their aircraft, air defense radars and communications systems,
surface-to-air missiles, and anti-aircraft artillery ``very
quickly,'' Shea said, so that allied planes could safely carry out
reconnaissance missions during the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers would also be expected to see to it that the
Kosovo Liberation Army is disbanded and disarmed, though Maj. Gen.
Walter Jertz, a spokesman for the allied military command said
Saturday that this was ``a difficult issue.''
</P>
<P>
   British forces will be the first to enter Kosovo, according to a
NATO spokesman, an acknowledgment of their leading role in the
peacekeeping force, which will be led by Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The British, French, German, Italian and American forces will
each establish a zone of command in Kosovo, NATO officials said.
Those sectors will divide the province like slices of a pie. All of
these forces will enter with armor, including tanks and armored
personnel carriers. One NATO official said the United States will
use Apache helicopters during the first phase of the entry. ``It
will send a strong message that we are serious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rough outline of the military agreement, NATO
forces will have the right to prevent any disruptions to the peace,
whether by Serbian forces or troops of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
They will also have to contend with the problems of booby traps
left by the Serbs, especially in the houses and shops of the
Kosovar Albanians who have fled over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The five sectors will also include soldiers from other NATO and
non-NATO countries to police the peace agreement for years to come,
according to NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops hope to establish a ``safe and secure environment''
in advance of any return of the more than 500,000 Kosovar refugees
waiting in camps here and in Albania. At the same time, they will
be searching for the tens of thousands of Kosovar Albanians who
have hidden in the hills and abandoned villages after being thrown
out of their own homes and are believed to be in desperate need of
food, water and medical attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
