<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      06-05 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN PUTS NO TIME LIMIT ON U.S. AND OTHER NATO FORCES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen said Saturday that
there was no time limit on the deployment of NATO forces, including
U.S. troops, in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the controversy over the deployment of U.S.
peacekeepers in Bosnia in 1995, who officials vowed would leave
within a year, the Clinton administration has not said how long it
expects the NATO force to stay. Cohen, who as a Republican senator
opposed an open-ended commitment of troops in the Balkans, said he
would not put ``time limits'' on the U.S. involvement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you a timetable,'' Cohen said in an interview
with reporters in his office. ``And I'm not going to say, `Is it
six months? Is it a year? How long is it going to take?' We will do
our best to facilitate the transformation of Kosovo into a
self-governing province under the aegis of NATO and the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also signaled that NATO saw its expanding mission in the
Balkans as extending beyond keeping peace in Kosovo and allowing
refugees to return. He said NATO had drafted military plans to
prevent President Slobodan Milosevic from overthrowing the
government of Montenegro, Yugoslavia's junior republic, and would
still be prepared to use the plans after a settlement of the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the air war against Yugoslavia, NATO said it has
tried to minimize its attacks against Montenegro, whose government,
led by Milo Djukanovic, is considered more democratic and
pro-Western than that of Milosevic's Serbia. And the alliance also
warned that it would intervene if there was an outright coup by
forces supporting Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have plans in the event there is an attempt to
destabilize Montenegro and then to pose a threat to NATO,'' Cohen
said, indicating that in his view a move against Montenegro would
undermine the settlement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's concern over Montenegro underscores the lingering
questions and potential threats swirling around Milosevic and his
country.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment of 7,000 U.S. troops _ on top of more than 6,000
still in Bosnia _ is certain to be controversial in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Before NATO's bombing began, many Republicans in Congress
opposed the administration's pledge to send only 4,000 troops to
Kosovo as part of a much smaller force of 28,000. Cohen noted that
opposition but said it was vital that the United States take part
now that Milosevic had backed down. ``It will be up to me to go
back up to the hill and try to persuade my former colleagues they
should support this effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described a daunting list of tasks facing the peacekeepers.
These include the destruction of weapons left behind, the clearing
of mine fields and booby traps and the rebuilding of homes,
bridges, roads and other infrastructure destroyed by Serbian forces
and by NATO's air strikes _ all before the bulk of the ethnic
Albanian refugees are allowed to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hard part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Cohen said he did not expect fighting to erupt in
Yugoslavia, either over Montenegro or among Serbs, Yugoslavia is
clearly moving into a period of uncertainty after two and a half
months of bombing and with the coming occupation of the southern
Serbian province of Kosovo by NATO-led troops.
</P>
<P>
   If Yugoslavia begins to withdraw its army and police units, as
called for under the proposed peace agreement, NATO troops could
begin moving into Kosovo as soon as Monday or Tuesday. The first of
7,000 U.S. troops _ marines from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit
aboard ships heading to the Aegean Sea _ could move in days after
that.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said NATO's strategy had succeeded despite strains in the
alliance and criticism from many quarters that the allies had not
prepared adequately for the possibility of using ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Despite errors in the bombing that killed dozens of civilians,
Cohen said NATO's campaign had been remarkably precise and
successful. Even as the administration and some NATO allies began
openly discussing the possibility of ground troops, he said the
intelligence reports and satellite photographs proved that the air
strikes were eroding Serbian resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw evidence mounting that the air campaign was starting to
take a toll,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After 74 days of bombing, the Pentagon now estimates that
Yugoslavia's army and police forces have lost a quarter of the
armored vehicles in Kosovo and 40 percent of artillery and mortars.
NATO, according to the Pentagon, has destroyed 80 percent of the
Yugoslav Air Force and its surface-to-air missile batteries and
severely degraded its military airfields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
