<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKLEY-PROSECUTION-     06-05 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKLEY-PROSECUTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TOP AIDE TO ESPY IS IN RUINS AFTER CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ark., Fla., Calif., Mass.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first glance, Ronald H. Blackley, a high school
graduate who says he never earned more than $30,000 a year back
home in Mississippi, does not seem like the kind of target Congress
had in mind when it created special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago in his home state, he worked for a congressman
named Mike Espy on farm issues. When Espy was named secretary of
agriculture in 1993, Blackley was hired as his chief of staff for
$115,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to Washington as an idealist,'' Blackley's lawyer,
Sheldon Krantz, said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley left Washington a convicted criminal, owing more than
$300,000 in legal fees and loans, his suburban Virginia house lost
to foreclosure. Soon, unless his appeals are successful, he will go
to prison for 27 months.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sharon, sat beside him and cried as Blackley told of
being swept up in an investigation aimed at Espy, who was accused
but ultimately cleared of taking favors from companies that did
business with the Agriculture Department. The special prosecutor in
the case, Donald Smaltz, had hoped Blackley would help him convict
his former boss. ``I could have,'' Blackley drawled, ``if I'd
lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Blackley himself became a target of Smaltz and, his
lawyer says, another victim of a statute that has spawned boundless
multimillion-dollar investigations that have often gone on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Now many in Congress are considering letting the
independent-counsel law lapse when it comes up for renewal in
Congress this month.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley, who is 48, was convicted in late 1997 of three counts
of making false statements about $22,000 in outside income he
received while serving as the agriculture secretary's chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz convinced a jury that Blackley took the money from
longtime Mississippi friends in return for helping them get
Agriculture Department subsidies, and then lied about it, first on
financial-disclosure forms and later to investigators for the
department and for the U.S. Agency for International Development,
where he worked after leaving the department in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley was guilty of nothing more than ``being in the wrong
place at the wrong time,'' Krantz said, adding that what happened
to his client ``is an example of what is wrong with the
independent-counsel statute,'' and why it should be allowed to die.
</P>
<P>
   To compare the prosecutor's version of the case with the defense
lawyer's is to wonder whether they are talking about the same man
and the same events.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz said $10,000 of the $22,000 was a loan from an old friend
who wanted to help Blackley get settled in the Washington area.
About $10,000 more came in installments for the sale of a rice
brokerage Blackley owned before coming to Washington, and another
$1,000 was a high school graduation gift to Blackley's son, the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley simply tried to cut through red tape and get subsidies
for people entitled to them, Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, Krantz elicited testimony that many people have
trouble with the financial-disclosure forms. He tried to show that
Blackley's violations, if any, were technical and attributable to
the documents' baffling language, including ambiguous wording on
how to list money earned in a certain year, compared with money
actually received in a given year.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors characterized those explanations as ludicrous
and said there was overwhelming evidence that Blackley had cashed
in on his position.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which version is true, or whether the ``truth'' lies
in some undiscoverable terrain in between, this much is clear: If
there were no independent-counsel law, Blackley would not have been
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Passed in 1978 when memories of Watergate were fresh, the Ethics
in Government Act provides for court-appointed independent counsels
to go after wrongdoing at the highest levels of government. The
statute has been endlessly debated. Its critics complain that some
special prosecutors stray far from their original missions,
spending millions to pursue people on the periphery of scandal, as
well as the truly guilty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Smaltz was appointed to investigate Espy, who resigned
amid suspicions that he had accepted tickets to sporting events,
luggage and other gifts worth thousands of dollars from people and
companies he was supposed to be regulating, like Tyson Foods, the
giant poultry producer based in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz went after Blackley mainly to get information to use
against his former boss. ``Blackley was a link in the chain to
Secretary Espy,'' the prosecutor said in a television interview
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley said: ``They wanted me to do for them what they
couldn't do, which was convict Mike Espy. I didn't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackley said he made that clear in several interviews with
investigators. He said they told him, at first, that he was not a
target. But the questioning became less friendly, and Blackley said
he began to hear from friends in Mississippi that investigators
were checking on him.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley's financial-disclosure forms came under scrutiny only
because Espy was under investigation, Krantz said. Attorney General
Janet Reno unsuccessfully opposed Smaltz's request for
authorization to pursue Blackley, reminding the federal judicial
panel overseeing the counsel's office that Blackley was not covered
in its original mandate. Reno expressed alarm at a special
prosecutor's potentially ``unbridled power.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Department of Justice and the Agriculture
Department's inspector general's office had earlier examined
Blackley's forms and found nothing to prosecute. That decision was
in keeping with the Justice Department's policy of not prosecuting
financial-disclosure violations, Krantz said, but rather allowing
filers to correct the forms, or settle cases civilly.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley was indicted on April 22, 1997, and was tried in U.S.
District Court in Washington. Blackley did not testify on his own
behalf; his lawyer thought that there was no need and that the
prosecution had not proved its case.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley was convicted on Dec. 1, 1997. On March 13, 1998, Judge
Royce Lamberth sentenced him to 27 months in prison, departing from
sentencing guidelines that indicated probation for a defendant like
Blackley, whose offense was his first of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant was a high-level government official,'' Lamberth
said, calling his conduct ``despicable'' and saying he wanted to
send a message to other officials who might be tempted to be greedy
and lie.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz lost an appeal before the District of Columbia U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals. He has asked the Supreme Court to review
the case, on the grounds that the independent counsel should never
have pursued Blackley, and that the sentence was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Blackley was never called as a witness against Espy, who was
acquitted on Dec. 2, 1998, a year and a day after Blackley was
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After the acquittal, Smaltz defended his four-year, $17 million
investigation. He noted that his office had gained more than a
dozen convictions and garnered some $12 million in fines, including
$6 million from Tyson Foods, which pleaded guilty to making illegal
gifts to Espy, who was acquitted of taking them.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, the Supreme Court overturned one of the convictions
obtained by Smaltz, setting aside a verdict against a California
agricultural cooperative that had given the secretary gifts. Simply
giving presents without a demonstrated link between the gifts and
an official's actions did not violate the law against illegal
gratuities, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz has prosecuted organized crime in Miami, taught law at
Boston University and was dean of the University of San Diego Law
School before settling in Washington to defend white-collar
defendants. ``I have never seen an injustice like this,'' he said
of Blackley's case. ``It shakes my confidence in the administration
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackley and his wife are living in her mother's house in
Mississippi, for now. His friends hold occasional fund-raising
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Is he afraid of prison? ``No. I'll just go do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he said, he will probably go back to Mississippi and
return to farming. ``I can't make too many long-term commitments,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
