A4235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CANDIDATES-NYT     06-05 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CANDIDATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO DEAL HELPS GORE CAMPAIGN AND SHOWS SPLIT AMONG REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If a possible peace settlement in Kosovo has any
effect on presidential politics in 2000, it highlights an advantage
of being the sitting vice president and the disadvantage of a
fractious mass of opposition candidates vying for attention.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been able to play a presidential-level role in
helping to resolve what is arguably one of the biggest foreign
policy crises of recent years. For two months he steadfastly
supported a war-fighting policy that, for now, seems to have
worked, without a single American combat casualty, but that still
carries great risks as long as Americans stay in the Balkans. And
at a crucial juncture, he called on ties with Russia to help
facilitate a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest advantage for Gore, assuming the settlement
holds, is what it heads off: the likelihood that Gore would have to
defend American deaths in a ground war in a far-away land just as
the presidential campaign heats up. Thus it could help Gore
campaign on the most reliable of political platforms, peace and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the political effects of any Kosovo settlement
are murkier. The conflict pointed up the divisions between the
party's isolationist and internationalist wings. The lack of a
single clear voice criticizing President Clinton's policies has
undercut the Republicans' traditional claim on foreign policy as
their area of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is well positioned to take credit while his lone Democratic
opponent for the nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, does not
overtly challenge the administration's actions, and while the
Republicans debate whether it is wise to send U.S. forces into
Kosovo to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley praised the negotiators and added: ``Our priority must
be the welfare of the refugees. We should support those who wish to
return and provide them targeted assistance. We should also support
those refugees who do not wish to return but want to resettle
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a presidential contender and a
constant critic of the White House's approach, said, ``If it works
out, the administration will deserve credit for bringing it to an
end,'' but he said that he, for one, did not know what role Gore
played. ``I've read different versions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said of his own views, ``I still believe I was right that by
ruling out the option of ground troops, the White House made
Milosevic more efficiently able to ethnically cleanse and commit
atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the American Red Cross, said,
``The Clinton-Gore administration has been very vague about the
terms of this proposal, and I'm worried that we're on the verge of
a sellout'' to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, at the moment the presumptive
Republican front-runner, put out a statement shortly after the
tentative settlement was announced. He said that any peacekeeping
force involving Americans should be under U.S. or NATO command,
which is indeed a feature of the plan. ``I think it's also
important for the president to lay out a timetable as to how long
they will be involved and when they will be withdrawn,'' Bush said,
adding it was important for Europe to ``carry the majority of the
load.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the publisher and Republican candidate, said the
administration should not send U.S. troops into Kosovo regardless
of whether the peace plan holds. ``The Clinton-Gore administration
should have learned a lesson from Bosnia,'' he said. ``American
peacekeeping troops have been in that region for years, with no end
in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle suggested that the agreement
reflected the president's falling support in public opinion
surveys. ``Faced with both declining poll numbers and the prospect
of a protracted conflict, President Clinton was forced to recognize
that negotiation, not escalation, represented the only appropriate
strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle added that the United States should send no troops. ``The
Clinton administration squandered substantial resources and, far
more importantly, our nation's credibility in the pursuit of
matters wholly unrelated to America's vital national security
interests,'' he said. ``It was a terrible mistake that has
established a troubling precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   In their struggle to depict the administration in a way that
would favor one of them over Gore, the Republicans have revealed a
new schism in their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has created another ideological division within our
party,'' said Tom Rath, a senior adviser to the presidential
campaign of former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and a long-time
Republican strategist in Concord, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Rath and others said that with Milosevic still in power, it was
too early to make any predictions about political fallout. But,
they said, unless the settlement failed and the Kosovo refugees
could not go home, the war would probably have little effect on the
presidential election beyond bringing the focus back squarely to
domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Kenneth Duberstein, who was chief of staff under
former President Ronald Reagan, said that Kosovo was never a true
litmus test for Republicans _ unlike, say, policy toward China, a
more complex and persistent issue.
</P>
<P>
   But several advisers within the Republican campaigns said there
were probably some short-term effects on the candidates. The war
prompted Bush to learn to react more promptly to unfolding events
once he was criticized for being slow in responding to the bombing
campaign. It gave Mrs. Dole a chance to spark publicity for her
campaign with a trip to a refugee camp. And it let McCain, who has
been deeply involved in international issues, emerge as a chief
foreign policy voice on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's role will no doubt become part of his campaign, even
though as recently as the week before last his advisers were
suggesting that Gore would have approached Kosovo differently from
the way Clinton did. They were not specific, but Gore has more
strongly advocated the Colin Powell doctrine _ if a nation is going
to apply force, it should seek rapid and total victory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore has had a long-time relationship with Victor
Chernomyrdin, now Russia's special envoy to the Balkans, and kept
open the lines of communication with him as official relations
frayed between the United States and Russia. It was during a
meeting with Chernomyrdin at Gore's home in Washington last month
that the two agreed on asking Finnish President Martii Ahtisaari to
help find a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign made no claims to good fortune. ``If the peace
is real, it's good for America and good for the nations around the
world to have stood up against genocide,'' said Marla Romash, the
deputy campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertainties over how the peace agreement will
actually work out, Gore's backers are being careful not to seize
this moment for boasting. But some of them say privately that they
hope the outcome can help build an image of the vice president as a
man who may not be flashy but can work with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the inverse of Gore as boring, stiff and
noncharismatic _ in his steady, methodical way, he is a guy going
toward a larger goal,'' said one backer. ``He can talk about these
issues in ways that very few others can,'' this supporter said.
``He can pick up the phone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
