<SLUG> BC-MICH-POWER-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MICHIGAN, A POWERHOUSE GATHERING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Okla., N.H., Iowa)   By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACKINAC ISLAND, Mich. _ Every state has its insiders, its
striding embodiments of wealth or power, and Michigan is no
different. But in no other state do so many of them _ 1,400 this
year _ gather at a single schmoozefest like the one held here each
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit region's chamber of commerce is host to this
sprawling conference, where the business executives rub shoulders
with politicians for three days. Each year it draws ``about
everybody who is anybody in the state,'' from local government to
Congress, said Rep. John Dingell, Democratic dean of Michigan's
congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders and their lobbyists _ including those from the
giant American automakers and a number of other Fortune 500
companies _ are drawn by the chance to hobnob with the state's
politicians in a one-stop-shopping atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   They have been gathering here 19 years, for the Detroit Regional
Chamber Leadership Policy Conference. The event has become so
popular that more 200 people were turned away this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't get away unless they can swim real well,'' said
Randolph Agley, of Talon Group, a Detroit venture-capital company.
The island, 260 miles north of Detroit, can be reached only by
ferry or private plane.
</P>
<P>
   Though checks may not be exchanged here, the future support of
business leaders is expressed in handshakes. ``They make or break
politicians through financing their campaigns or through economic
development in their districts,'' said Mario Morrow, a Detroit
political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where all the deals are made,'' Morrow said. ``This is
where all the power brokers and political activists who have any
political power at all convene to set the agenda for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing his way through a crowd of Michigan's movers and
shakers, Patrick McCollough, a longtime statehouse lobbyist,
grinned exuberantly. ``It's like Christmas shopping,'' he said,
walking out onto the porch of the Grand Hotel, as lilacs of every
hue bloomed on the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   There were Michigan's political stars, Gov. John Engler, a
Republican, and Detroit Mayor Dennis Archer, a Democrat. National
political figures attending included Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New
York; Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., R-Okla.; Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.; and
Kweisi Mfume, president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume called on the hundreds of business leaders to hire
minority workers, not just sell products to them. Mfume said he
came here from Washington because ``this audience has the ability
to affect the quality of life of hundreds of thousands of people
around the state.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Schwarz, R-Battle Creek, who is the Senate's
president pro tempore, said one of the benefits of the conference
was peculiar to the state's polarized racial politics. ``It helps
for the white business community in Oakland and McComb County to
get to know and to relate to the black business community in
Detroit and the black political leadership as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's politics extends into many other areas, though.
State legislators put the finishing touches on a bill that would
move Michigan's presidential primary to the third Tuesday of
February, after primaries in New Hampshire and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Why here? ``This is where so many of the key players are,'' said
State Sen. Ken Sikkema, who represents the Grand Rapids area.
``We're going to get it done this weekend and we'll move it next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders are involved in the politicking, as well.
William Clay Ford Jr., chairman of Ford Motor Co., encouraged
others to support Detroit. ``We look at social responsibility and
community involvement as a competitive advantage,'' Ford told the
group.
</P>
<P>
   More than 125 companies took his advice and volunteered to help
refurbish 263 run-down Detroit schools.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who got a sunburn while golfing Friday afternoon with
his son, and several business executives and lawyers, said he had
made good use of the past two days. ``Since I've been up here,'' he
said, ``I've closed a number of business deals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
