<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-MEN-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI COMPLETES TRIP TO FRENCH OPEN FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When the skies parted at noon Saturday as if on cue,
Andre Agassi, the balding optimist from Las Vegas who began growing
a French Open victory beard as soon as he negotiated his
opening-round hurdle here, quickly completed his rain-delayed
semifinal against Slovakia's Dominik Hrbaty.
</P>
<P>
   After a night spent berating himself for not sweeping the
30th-ranked Slovak in straight sets, Agassi hustled back onto
center court with his Grand Slam blinders securely in place and, 23
minutes later, had wrapped up a 6-4,7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's victory over Hrbaty, who had upset top-ranked Yevgeny
Kafelnikov and ninth-seeded Marcelo Rios, sent him into the final
against another resurgent and balding Andre, 100th-ranked Andrei
Medvedev of the Ukraine. Agassi thus earned his third trip to the
French final, whereas Medvedev's best finish here was the 1993
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I can make him worry about how to handle me,'' said
Agassi, who pronounced himself ``happy, blessed and committed'' to
making this Roland Garros final a ``no regrets'' experience for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi succumbed to Andres Gomez and Jim Courier in the 1990 and
1991 finals, but he didn't foresee that happening against Medvedev,
who sneaked into this final despite making 85 unforced errors in
his semifinal against Fernando Meligeni.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wonderful two weeks,'' Agassi said. ``I think it's
teaching me exactly what I can accomplish if I put my mind to it.
The nerves will exist before and the relief will exist after.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1990 and 1991 French Open finals, Agassi said , he didn't
have the same direction or maturity that now informs his game, and
his life. Agassi called this 1999 edition of himself a far cry even
from the player he was in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had to build over from 140th in the world; this
year I have a different goal for myself,'' said Agassi. ``I'm more
interested in coming into the slams feeling fresh, feeling strong,
and feeling ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi came into this major with an inflamed tendon in his right
shoulder but hasn't let it interfere with his mission to reassert
himself on the Grand Slam stage. ``You don't let any opportunities
to go by,'' said Agassi, who is currently three for seven in Grand
Slam finals.
</P>
<P>
   The American has not reached a Grand Slam final since the 1995
U. S. Open and won the last of his three Grand Slams at the 1995
Australian Open. If he wins this title, he would become the first
man to own titles at all four Grand Slams since Rod Laver collected
four in the space of a single season 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only Laver, Don Budge, Fred Perry and Roy Emerson have won
titles at all four Grand Slams, but their feats were accomplished
on just two surfaces, clay and grass. Agassi, who won his first
major at Wimbledon in 1992 and added two more on hard courts at the
1994 U.S. Open and 1995 Australian Open, would join Jimmy Connors
as the only men in the game's history to conquer Grand Slams on
three surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   But first Agassi has to conquer Medvedev, a man who rose to
fourth in the world after attaining the 1993 semifinals here but
soon tumbled off the radar. Injuries and a broken heart conspired
against Medvedev, but he claims to have been reborn this spring
after resuming his love affair with Anke Huber of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev's dismissals of second-seeded Pete Sampras and
eighth-seeded Gustavo Kuerten, the 1997 champion here, were
evidence of the 6-foot-4 player's rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, whose divorce from actress Brooke Shields was official
two months ago, said he didn't expect his single-minded
rededication to tennis to have any more impact on Sunday's final
than Medvedev's newfound bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like him being in love makes any difference to me
outside of the fact that he's a good guy and I'm happy to hear
that,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added with a smile, ``I'd prefer if he let his
girlfriend play for him instead, with all due respect to her
game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Agassi knows what the tall Ukrainian is capable of on court; he
was beaten by Medvedev at New Haven in 1993 in their only previous
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Against Hrbaty on Friday, Agassi, who used midweek attendance at
a Bruce Springsteen concert to help defuse the tension of this
Grand Slam campaign, quickly assumed the upper hand. After being
broken in the sixth game, he ignored a 40-0 deficit as Hrbaty
served in the seventh game and commenced a 16-point winning spree
that switched the score from 4-2 for Hrbaty to 5-4 for the Las
Vegan. In the second set's tie breaker, Agassi used an ace to take
a 5-3 lead and got his second set point with a cross-court forehand
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, however, Agassi got off to wrong-footed start in the third
by dropping serve. By the time Hrbaty held for 5-3 it was raining,
and the American, annoyed that the weather was undermining his kick
serve and topspin and assisting Hrbaty's flat ground strokes, was
broken for the set by a backhand return.
</P>
<P>
   Though Agassi wanted play suspended there and then, the duo
ventured three games into the fourth set before play was suspended
with 2:03 on the match clock.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the elements were in Agassi's favor, and after a
nervous service game where he saved two breaks to level the set at
2-2, he settled down and made life miserable for Hrbaty, a
first-time Grand Slam semifinalist. Agassi broke for a 4-3 edge
with a backhand return, held with an ace for 5-3 and served out the
match at 5-4. A service winner gained him his first match point,
and a discouraged backhand into the net by Hrabty sent Agassi into
his eighth career Grand Slam final.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the former No. 1 in the world,'' Hrbaty said. ``I mean,
he knows something about the tennis. He has the game he can play on
all surfaces. I wanted to win, but he was better. There was like no
chance for me today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
