<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNY-REPORT-2TAKES-NY     06-05 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNY-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYORAL PANEL SAYS CUNY IS `ADRIFT' AND URGES OVERHAUL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying that the City University of New York is ``an
institution adrift'' and is ``caught in a spiral of decline,'' a
mayoral task force is calling for a total revamping of the
university.
</P>
<P>
   The task force report, which will be formally released Monday by
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, reaffirms the university's historic mission
of providing access to a higher education for the city's diverse
population.
</P>
<P>
   But it says that if it is to educate New Yorkers effectively, it
must be transformed from a loosely managed confederation of
scattered institutions with no direction and few standards into a
tightly managed operation that measures what its students know when
they enter, what they have learned by the time they leave and which
approaches are most effective in teaching them.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 200,000 students and a budget of nearly $2 billion,
CUNY is the United States' third-largest public university system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `chaotic' doesn't even begin to describe it; it's
moribund,'' said Benno Schmidt, the task force chairman. ``That
suggests a huge opportunity, but first CUNY needs to invent
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   While the report is highly critical of CUNY, as expected, it
assigns some blame for the university's problems to the city and
the state, and particularly New York City's weak public schools. It
also says the state's system of financial aid forces many students
who are not prepared for college work to enroll at CUNY, because it
is the only way they can receive financial support for their
remedial work.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many reports that end up sitting on the shelf after they
are issued, the Schmidt report has an unusually good chance to
become a blueprint for change. It comes as both the mayor and the
governor are pressing to revamp the university, and a majority of
the trustees support that goal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Herman Badillo, a member of the task force who was
promoted to the university's chairmanship last weekend, will be in
a unique position to press for the commission's recommendations. He
said the report would serve as CUNY's ``goal posts'' and that he
would present it to his fellow trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The commission offered a multitude of recommendations, including
the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ The state and the city should provide separate, additional
funding for students needing remedial instruction so they do not
use up their college aid while they learn reading, writing and
mathematics skills they should have learned before college.
</P>
<P>
   _ City University should continue to offer remedial courses, but
at its community colleges, and it must test students more carefully
before and after the courses to try to learn which approaches work
best.
</P>
<P>
   _ The university should designate at least two of its senior
colleges as flagship institutions that can attract students of high
academic promise.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must work with New York City's public high schools to try
to raise their quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``CUNY's downward spiral can be and must be reversed,'' the
report says. ``At the eve of a new century, the United States
urgently needs a model of the urban public university, and CUNY
should be that model of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   The study comes at a time when many universities, and
particularly urban universities, are struggling to cope with a
flood of poorly educated high school graduates and with immigrants
who speak little or no English but are desperate for a college
education to help them prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said in an interview that in an era when a college
degree has become ``virtually the only source of opportunity,'' he
hoped the report would offer strategic help not only for CUNY but
for all urban universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``CUNY's historic mission is more important now than it has ever
been,'' he said. ``CUNY has the chance to be the model for great
public urban universities for the next century, the way land-grant
institutions were in the last century, and it's absolutely vital to
make it right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This report is not an attack on open admissions,'' he added,
referring to CUNY's decision in the late 1960s to allow all high
school graduates to enter. ``This affirms the principle that CUNY
is for anyone with a high school diploma and for immigrants and for
returning adults; it is the way CUNY goes about it that is very
very flawed,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the mayor and the governor, whom Schmidt personally briefed
about the report, were said to be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets such a positive tone for change,'' Michael McKeon,
Gov. George Pataki's press secretary, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he could not comment on how the governor would
respond to the report's recommendation for additional financial aid
for remedial students since the governor's staff was still going
through the details of the report.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office said that the 109-page report will be posted
on the the city's Web site (www.ci.nyc.ny.us). The task force made
copies of the report and its 10 volumes of supporting studies
available to newspapers on Friday on the condition that no articles
be published until Monday. The Daily News printed an article on
Saturday that it said was based on an earlier draft of the report.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the mayor created the task force in May 1998, there was
widespread skepticism that the panel would do anything more than
recommend shrinking the university and turning its work over to
private universities and corporations, since some of the panel's
seven members are advocates for privatization of government
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt is chairman of the Edison Project, a private company
that manages public schools for profit. Richard Schwartz, another
member, is a former senior adviser to Giuliani who helped design
New York City's welfare-to-work initiatives and privatization
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the report argues forcefully that City University
is critical for New York, and, if anything, should be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``CUNY's historic missions _ to provide broad access to a range
of higher education opportunities of quality, suited to New York
City's diverse population and to the city's needs _ will be more
important in the 21st century than ever before,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the task force was measured in its response to the
mayor's request to tell him how to privatize the university's
remedial functions. Rather than urging that such instruction be
shifted to private companies and private colleges, as the mayor has
advocated, the report called for experiments to stimulate
competition. It also says that City University should continue to
offer remedial courses, so long as the need exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``CUNY should provide remediation, and we applaud them for doing
it,'' Schmidt said. But, he added, ``It's very important for CUNY
to approach remediation in an organized, serious and effective way
because so many of its students fall into that category.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, Schmidt said, was that the tests the university
uses to evaluate entering students ``are not good; they do not
generate diagnostically helpful information.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, a constitutional scholar who was formerly Dean of
Columbia University's Law School and president of Yale University,
approached the panel's investigation like an academic research
project, making it into virtually a second full-time job. He wrote
the final report himself, with help from other task force members.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a year, he met twice a month and sometimes
more frequently with the other members. He and staff members
visited all of the university's 17 undergraduate campuses and
interviewed hundreds of students, professors, administrators and
others. They held public hearings (some marked by protests by
students and professors). They commissioned reports from Rand Corp.
and Pricewaterhouse Coopers, the accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that the task force raised $300,000, in sums of
$75,000 or less from various foundations, to help pay for the work,
and is still trying to raise more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
