A4243 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IT COULD HAPPEN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's gotten through the health-care debacle, Whitewater, the
Lewinsky scandal and the impeachment of her husband. Now Hillary
Rodham Clinton is packing her carpetbag and preparing to run for
the U.S. Senate in New York. Welcome to the post-traumatic stress
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense. A seat in the Senate is more satisfying than
therapy, more fun than divorce. It's the perfect way for the
Clintons to hang on to the power, glamour and excitement they both
crave. Mrs. Clinton's historic quest is already overshadowing Al
Gore's lackluster run for the presidency. If the first lady makes
it to the Senate, it will be impossible to quiet the calls that she
run for president herself.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate threat to this grand scenario is one Rudolph
Giuliani, who has grand ambitions of his own. The compulsively
combative mayor is laying the land mines and marshaling the forces
he plans to use to demolish the first lady's dream. The pollsters,
the political consultants and the press are beside themselves with
glee. They expect the coming clash to be colossal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make the gunfight at the OK Corral look like a
gourmet meal,'' said Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist
Institute for Public Opinion.
</P>
<P>
   t's a difficult fight to handicap. Both camps will be
incredibly well financed. Mrs. Clinton's carpetbagger status is an
advantage for Giuliani. But the mayor may face a primary threat
from Rep. Rick Lazio, an attractive candidate from Long Island who,
at least for now, has the support of Gov. George Pataki and former
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who are both angry (that's an understatement)
at Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he gets the nomination, Giuliani would appear to be
especially strong in the suburbs, where he is widely admired as the
man who made New York a safer place. Suburban voters who now feel
more comfortable coming into the city for work and for pleasure,
and who worry less about their kids coming into the city, are
grateful to him.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton will need to roll up an enormous majority in
traditionally Democratic New York City to offset Giuliani's
strength in the suburbs and the normal Republican advantage
upstate. Charles Schumer took nearly 75 percent of the city vote
when he defeated Al D'Amato in the Senate race last year. But
Giuliani will not be as vulnerable in the city as most Republicans
have been.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor may also be helped by the so-called Clinton fatigue
factor. A lot of voters have had their fill of Bill and Hillary and
would like to move on. For those voters, almost any other candidate
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, on the other hand, may be helped by Giuliani's
tendency to go overboard in his attacks on his opponents. He seems
to enjoy demonizing and humiliating them. Said one Democrat:
``Ohmigod, he's going to try to kick the daylights out of her. And
if he does that, it would be a mistake. He could generate sympathy
for her and unite women for her.''
</P>
<P>
   If New York Democrats were smart (and there is no evidence that
this is the case), they would be registering everything that moves
in the city and the suburbs. The publicity generated by a
Clinton-Giuliani race, the widespread hostility toward Giuliani
among blacks and some other ethnic minorities, and the fact that
the race will occur in a presidential election year will tend to
boost turnout. For Mrs. Clinton to have a good shot at winning,
that increased turnout will have to be stocked with loads of new
voters committed to her.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is scanning the real-estate listings and is
expected to set up light housekeeping in the suburbs. Her celebrity
will generate excitement and keep the money flowing. But that won't
be enough. She'll have to find a way to get New Yorkers to embrace
her. She'll need a compelling message, a rationale for her
candidacy that resonates not just with Democrats, but with
independent-minded voters, especially those in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   It could happen. If she can erode some of Giuliani's suburban
strength, and if Democrats around the state do a good job getting
their voters to the polls, and if women rally to her cause, Mrs.
Clinton could land not just in the Senate but in the history books
in her own right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
