u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-CITIES-NYT &LR;      06-05 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-CITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS WELFARE ROLES SHRINK, CITIES SHOULDER BIGGER LOAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Ohio, Tenn., Ill., Md.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Welfare rolls are shrinking more slowly in big
cities than elsewhere in the states and, as a result, welfare
recipients are increasingly concentrated in urban areas, state and
local officials and welfare policy experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest American cities are becoming home to a larger and
larger share of the nation's welfare recipients,'' said Bruce Katz,
director of the Center on Urban and Metropolitan Policy at the
Brookings Institution here.
</P>
<P>
   Urban counties containing the 30 largest American cities have 20
percent of the nation's population, but 39 percent of the welfare
recipients _ up from 33 percent in 1994, Katz said. He recently
completed a two-year study of welfare rolls in U.S. cities,
methodically tabulating caseload data for each city after finding
that the federal government no longer collected such information.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1998, the number of families on welfare declined 35
percent in the big cities (those with populations of more than
470,000), compared with a decline of 44 percent for the nation as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state and local officials offer many explanations for
the disparities.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Cooper, a deputy mayor of Philadelphia, said:
``Philadelphia, the city proper, has had a weak economy with a slow
recovery from the last recession. The proportion of welfare
recipients who have been on the rolls for two years or more is
higher here than in the rest of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had 39 percent of the families receiving welfare in
Pennsylvania in 1994, but the proportion reached 47 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy has created millions of jobs across the
country. But Ms. Cooper said that job growth in Philadelphia had
been stunted because of ``an extraordinarily high business-tax
burden,'' which includes a 4.7 percent tax on wages. A recent
report from Mayor Edward Rendell, a Democrat, said that
Philadelphia's ``oppressive tax structure'' had driven hundreds of
businesses from the city and caused the loss of tens of thousands
of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Cooper said, auto insurance premiums are
extremely high for many inner-city neighborhoods of Philadelphia,
so it is difficult for poor people to afford cars to get to jobs in
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services, said: ``Three-fourths of the people on welfare
live in inner cities. But two-thirds to three-fourths of all new
jobs are being created outside urban areas.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City has aggressively reduced its welfare rolls,
converting welfare offices to job centers and emphasizing ``work
first.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1998, the number of families on welfare in New York
City declined 28 percent, to 225,651, while the total number of
families on welfare in New York state declined 30 percent, to
323,723. The city now has 70 percent of the state's welfare cases,
up from 68 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Los Angeles County now has 37 percent of the families
on welfare in California, up from 34 percent in 1994, while Chicago
(Cook County) has 74 percent of the Illinois caseload, up from 66
percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Katz said, people who remain on welfare are those
with the most problems. They are more likely to have mental
illnesses, learning disabilities or histories of alcohol and drug
abuse. They tend to have fewer job skills, less formal education
and less work experience. Many of the women suffer abuse from
husbands or companions.
</P>
<P>
   Katz found that Baltimore's share of the Maryland caseload rose
to 56 percent in 1998, from 48 percent in 1994, while Detroit's
share of the Michigan total rose to 48 percent, from 42 percent.
Shelby County, Tenn., which includes Memphis, has 35 percent of the
state's welfare families, up from 28 percent in 1994. Cleveland has
24 percent of Ohio's cases, up from 19 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, states now have more money to spend on each welfare
recipient because they receive a fixed amount of federal welfare
money each year, a ``block grant,'' even if the number of welfare
recipients declines. But Ms. Cooper noted that the money goes to
the state, and she said there was no guarantee that the governor
and the state legislature would provide money to cities in
proportion to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bias in Harrisburg against appropriating resources
to the city of Philadelphia,'' Ms. Cooper said. ``That's a historic
bias. It's like a mantra: no state money in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements over welfare policy have caused ``considerable
antagonism between the city and the state,'' which cooperate on
many other issues, Ms. Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Walker, director of operations at the Illinois Department
of Human Services, said Chicago and Cook County had initially
lagged behind other parts of the state in responding to the
landmark welfare law approved by Congress in 1996. But that has
changed, Ms. Walker said, and the city accounts for much of the
recent decline in the state's welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Month after month in the last year,'' Ms. Walker said, ``we've
seen a rise in the number of welfare recipients who are working in
poverty-stricken communities of Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   A few cities, defying the national trend, have reduced their
welfare rolls faster than the states in which they are located.
These cities include San Jose, Calif., in Santa Clara County.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Szalay, executive director of the California State
Association of Counties, said, ``Santa Clara came out of the
recession early and did a tremendous amount of work to anticipate
welfare reform,'' using its own money to provide job training,
child care and transportation for welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The growing concentration of recipients in big cities coincides
with changes in the racial and ethnic profile of families on
welfare. Whites are leaving the welfare rolls much faster than
black and Hispanic families, and the minority share of the caseload
has, as a result, risen to the highest level on record. Black and
Hispanic welfare recipients together outnumber whites by about two
to one.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials carefully monitor the number of welfare
recipients in each state. But Kharfen, from the Department of
Health and Human Services, said the federal government stopped
collecting welfare data on counties and metropolitan areas about
five years ago, when officials placed a higher priority on carrying
out changes in welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said his research on the cities should serve as ``a
cautionary note for states that are boasting a bit too loudly about
the dramatic declines in welfare caseloads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
