<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     06-05 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE KNICKS' EVOLVING SEASONS THROUGH THE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every generation gets the Knicks team it deserves,
actually the Knicks team we fantasize about. Already, I am becoming
defensively nostalgic for this team. Who knows how the world will
turn this week? We already know fate is an Achilles' tendon, a
questionable call, a finger roll away. You go to sleep with Jeff
Van Gundy biting your leg and you wake up to find Phil Jackson
meditating at the foot of your bed. Now and Zen. We might deserve
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   This all presupposes that you really know and care about the
similarities and differences between Red and Gumby, between the
Captain and Patrick, between Clyde and Spree, between, most
important, George Lois and Spike Lee. On the other hand, you might
well be a pure hoops junkie, a lover of mechanics, in which case
you can just post up and out.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can try to take this as far as it goes to ``Black Planet:
Facing Race During an NBA Season,'' a risky and brilliant book that
Crown will publish in the fall. It compares favorably to Frederick
Exley's classic ``A Fan's Notes.'' It is an emotional journey into
Jock Culture's heart of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Our protagonist-guide in ``Black Planet'' is novelist David
Shields, who writes: ``It would be impossible to overstate the
degree to which sports-talk radio is shadowed by the homosexual
panic implicit in the fact that it consists almost entirely of a
bunch of out-of-shape white men sitting around talking about black
men's buff bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields was on sabbatical from teaching English at the
University of Washington when he began covering the Seattle
SuperSonics for a local weekly and for an insider's book about the
1994-95 season. He caught a sense of the routine contempt athletes
have for sportswriters, but he didn't last long enough to be used
by them for negotiations and revenge. Management suddenly withdrew
credentials and access, which turned out to be to Shields' and the
reader's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of another piece of reportage, made bitter or
ingratiating by how the reporter was treated, we get serious
reflection; Shields wrote from a spectator's remove, buying good
season tickets and monitoring the Internet and talk radio. Exley's
object of obsession was Frank Gifford; Shields' is Seattle's point
guard, Gary Payton, whose ``outlaw'' pose he found ``erotic.''
</P>
<P>
   How else to think of Latrell Sprewell, who makes some people
nervous, who liberates others? Is Spree the free radical who will
destroy the body, or is he the ruthlessly self-focused artist who
will finally get that chapel ceiling painted? Remember that Walt
Frazier, currently such a consciously benign role model, was
watched warily 30 years ago lest his clothes, his now-quaint
``rocking steady'' cool (a jazz root of hip-hop) corrupt the
suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the '60s there was talk of the game's becoming too
black. Bill Bradley was promoted as a Knick who would bring to the
Garden white, upper-middle-class, well-educated consumers like
himself, the kind of crossover customers who would decades later go
to opera to hear the three tenors. No one seemed whiter than
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Shields writes: ``The tension between players and coaches in the
NBA seems a reflection, in part, of the fact that a middle-aged
white man is acting as a faux father figure for young black men,
the overwhelming majority of whom grew up without fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Red Holzman and Jeff Van Gundy, comforting
figures for their times. A been-there-done-that former player,
Uncle Red masked his authoritarianism with chuckly aphorisms
(``Never go to a bald barber'') and never blatantly tried to
upstage his players. Of course, he didn't have to then; the white
press naturally assumed that Coach was the central intelligence,
players merely the arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Another former player, workaholic and teacher, Pat Riley, had to
make more of an issue of his control, flaunting his amateur
head-shrinking and his inspirational babble. Ultimately, it didn't
help John Starks, who probably could have used real therapy, or the
group dynamic; was the mugger image Riley's genius or his loss of
control? Or was it what we wanted then, the swagger of rap coming
to the mainstream? Now, of course, it is considered poetry, on a
par with the Cavaliers (not Cleveland), and slams are as
institutionalized as dunk contests.
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes are in a stage of arrested adolescence, glancing
over their shoulders at Dad while pretending to rebel against him.
The best seem to make peace with that conflict, even if it involves
choking Dad without actually killing him. Who would ever choke Van
Gundy, who looks and acts like those killer nerds, brilliant,
consumed, loyal, who built the silicon empires. Given the chance,
Van Gundy will make everyone richer or die trying.
</P>
<P>
   Holzman and Van Gundy both had to build around stationary
pillars, strong and moral centers, Willis Reed and Patrick Ewing,
both of whom played with pain. The Captain, grievously injured,
medicated, limped out to beat Wilt Chamberlain and the Lakers in
1970. Poor Ewing, tagged ``warrior'' by a generation that took its
warlike victories in boardrooms and on playing fields, never got
the support he needed to win. Eventually, even his body let him
down. But he can't lose. If the Knicks are beaten without him, it
will be seen as proof of his importance. If they win, it will be
proof of his inspirational leadership from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   No one understood any of this better than the superstar fan of
each era. The Holzman-Bradley-Frazier-Reed cheerleader was an
advertising executive, George Lois, ahead of his time in sensing
the edgy eroticism of the game and its potential to transcend the
hardwood. He was replaced by Spike Lee, who may be remembered for
his provocative films, but seems to be making his living selling
the shoes his heroes wear. (It's interesting that New York's
superfans are image-makers and Los Angeles' superfans are images.)
</P>
<P>
   The superfan of the future may be the intellectual from a small
market who played high school basketball and, approaching middle
age with a wife and child, still finds something in the game that
engages him in ways that nothing else can. This is Shields in
Seattle, willing to write himself naked about the hungers and
envies that move across the grandstand like the wave. In one of his
dreams, he knocks down jumpers off Payton passes, but worries about
passing the real test _ the repartee between plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
