<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-05 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JACKSON PUTTING SHOULDER TO VAN GUNDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That was quite an off-Broadway performance the other
day by Jeff Van Gundy up at the Knicks' training base in Purchase.
The embattled coach made a colorful and calculated plea to the
officials to come to their senses and save the Knicks from being
rear-ended out of the playoffs by a sturdy compact named Mark
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the same Mark Jackson who was driven right out of New York
by a certain coaching legend for allegedly being too slow, unable
to guard a waste basket and for desecrating the sport with a push
shot he developed by watching early home movies discovered in the
basement of Dr. Naismith's long-deceased third cousin.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, Jackson has dramatically been elevated, at least against
the Knicks, from cagey point guard to controversial post god.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to end up doubling Mark, he's going to crush
you,'' Van Gundy raved before the Knicks and Pacers squared off
Saturday night in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference final at Madison
Square Garden. ``He's as good a passer out of the post as anyone _
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Before we get carried away, let's remember that out West in the
Portland-San Antonio series, the post confrontation is Arvydas
Sabonis, who passes like Bill Walton, against Tim Duncan, who plays
like Bill Walton. Here in the East, the strategic fascination has
been centered around the 6-foot-3-inch, 185-pound Jackson backing
up rather inelegantly, like a bumper car with a reverse gear,
against Charlie Ward and Chris Childs.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. Sell that one to Madison Avenue. Mark Jackson's
posterior against Chris Childs' chest. Fantastic!
</P>
<P>
   If there is one ratings-driving luxury the National Basketball
Association has been able to count on for years, it has been
prime-time matchups for climactic late-night programming. Magic
versus Dr. J. Bird against Magic. Kareem on Moses. Hakeem and Shaq.
Jordan against the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if it isn't bad enough that Jordan has left and pro ball
has devolved into a stationary game of dribble, dribble, foul,
clank, here is Larry Bird, of all people, trying to have Jackson
back the Pacers into the finals, with all the fluidity of a piano
being shoehorned through a doorway.
</P>
<P>
   In the mind's eye, Oscar Robertson and the Knicks' own Walt
Frazier are always playing with their backs to the basket, but
about to pirouette, float in the lane, or fade gracefully for a
textbook jumper. And there was always ballet in the feet of the
great post giants, Kareem positioning for his sky hook, Olajuwon
drawing the defender off his feet, again and again, like a
frustrated marionette.
</P>
<P>
   That was dance. This is drudgery, none of it the fault of
Jackson, who is only best using his modest offensive gifts. Van
Gundy is right _ Jackson is and always has been a great passer. If
the Knicks are foolish enough to double-team, Bird would be crazy
not to run this set every time down. With a lineup of outside
shooters who have difficulty creating their own shots, that is
allowing the Pacers to create a good shot without so much as
breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy agrees, but complains that Jackson is too often
allowed to turn his left shoulder and lower it into the chest of
the defender, to support the drive of his legs and rear. If the
defender gives ground, he'll wind up under the basket with Jackson
in position to shoot a jump hook that is short on jump and long on
hook. If Ward and Childs hold their ground but get called for the
block _ as was the case in Game 2 _ they'll foul out by the end of
a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go to basketball camp when you're young and practice
that move,'' Van Gundy said. ``You learn the back-in in the NBA.
It's called displacement, but an offensive player doesn't have the
right to drive his shoulder through you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wars could begin and end with all the time between these games,
but one argument Van Gundy is not going to settle is what actually
constitutes a playoff foul. The mood of the officials. The
alignment of the stars. From one game to the next, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Quit posturing. Jackson is not the first point guard to cause
problems on the post. When Tim Hardaway was healthy, he, too, could
score from there against Childs and Ward. If the Pacers want to
stand around and watch their season hinge on Jackson's hang time,
let them.
</P>
<P>
   Mix up the defensive matchups. Put a bigger man on Jackson from
time to time. The Bulls sent long-limbed Scottie Pippen after
Jackson in last year's conference final and the jump hook went the
way of the hula hoop. The Pacers went back to setting screens for
Reggie Miller, and playing off Rik Smits. On Broadway, we prefer
dance. Used to be that displacement came for those who couldn't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
