<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES VS. STARS: SUPER BOWL, OF SORTS, FOR STANLEY FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Stanley Cup finals were a presidential campaign, the
National Hockey League's ticket would be balanced. The Dallas
Stars, who qualified by beating Colorado on Friday night, are an
older team from a Southern state that borders Mexico. They were the
top-seeded team in the Western Conference, they play in an older
arena due to be replaced and their coach never played professional
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Their opponents will be the Buffalo Sabres, who eliminated
Toronto on Monday and have rested since then. The Sabres are a
younger team from a northern state bordering Canada. They were a
seventh-seeded team from the Eastern Conference and they play in a
new arena. Their coach played for 12 seasons in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Stars may be weary from a seven-game third round
and the Sabres are rested after a five-game series, the Stars
should be favored when the four-of-seven-game championship round
begins in Dallas on Tuesday night. During the regular season,
Dallas finished 23 points ahead of Buffalo. In the last four
seasons, the finals have ended in sweeps, the most recent three won
by the Western qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   Many hockey observers thought that the Dallas-Colorado series
was the real championship round, with Dallas clinching it at home
Friday night with a 4-1 victory behind two goals from Mike Keane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's anticipating a letdown,'' Mike Modano, the
Dallas alternate captain, said, even before the final game. ``And
I'm sure Buffalo will use that as a great motivator. They're going
to read a lot of statements from players who don't think the Sabres
have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Should this series go the distance, it will end on June 22. The
latest finish in history was the Devils' clinching on June 24,
1995, ending a season delayed by a 15-week lockout. The weather
around this season's late finish could be a factor, especially in
Dallas, where ice conditions are often poor even in the coldest
months and where June temperatures sometimes go above 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   That could favor the Stars, who are more accustomed to it. They
reached the third round last season before losing to Detroit as the
Red Wings were on their way to their second consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Buffalo reached the third round last season
before losing to Washington. Keane said the Stars might not get too
many more chances, at least not with this group. The Sabres'
average age is 26 years; the Stars' average is 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an older club,'' Keane said. ``So this is an important
time for the Dallas Stars. We know that we have a very mature club,
so this year we want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said he did not think the age of the
Dallas team, combined with the long series, would make any
difference. ``When you get into the finals, I don't think anybody
is tired,'' Ruff said. ``They are going to have three days to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Peca, the captain of the Stars and their first-line center,
said the Stars ``have got a lot of guys contributing offensively
and scoring goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they are playing now, they are a team that is
extremely tough,'' Peca said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has won the cup. The Stars, who started in
Minnesota with the 1967 expansion, have reached the finals twice,
losing to the Islanders in 1981 and to Pittsburgh in 1991, both
times while the team was still based in Minneapolis. The Sabres, an
expansion team of 1970, reached the finals once, losing in 1975 to
Philadelphia. The Sabres and the Stars have met twice before in the
post-season, each winning one series, but they have not played in
post-season since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   A Buffalo-Dallas matchup sounds more like the Super Bowl than
the Stanley Cup finals. But instead of comparing quarterbacks, it
is hockey style to compare goalies, and these two teams offer an
interesting match.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Dominik Hasek used to be the backup to Dallas' Ed
Belfour when both played for Chicago in the early 1990s. Since
going their separate ways, Hasek has evolved into the best goalie
in the business, winning the Hart trophy the last two seasons as
most valuable player in the NHL as well as the Vezina trophy as
best goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has had less success in Dallas and is generally regarded
in the second echelon of NHL goalies _ good but not great. After
Friday night's victory, during which he stopped 18 of 19 Colorado
shots, Belfour discussed Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got along fine,'' Belfour recalled. ``We worked hard
together. He was a good partner for me and we learned a lot from
each other. I respect him and he respects me, and I look forward to
competing against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff is in his second season behind the Sabres' bench, and his
team is also less experienced. While Dallas players such as Keane,
Guy Carbonneau and Brian Skrudland have played for cup winners, the
Sabres have no players with championship experience in the NHL,
although Hasek won a gold medal with the Czech Republic in the
Winter Olympic Games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
