<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TELLS JETS: DON'T LOOK AT THE POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Parcells gathers his players each year before training camp
and delivers a little speech about football as a metaphor for life.
As the New York Jets got ready for their series of minicamps, which
ended Saturday, he told them that they were vulnerable after their
surprisingly successful season _ that unless they watched it, they
could soon resemble ``chickens falling off a cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Jets are going to be reminded by outsiders that
they are one of pro football's best teams, that they came
incredibly close to reaching the Super Bowl last season, that one
of their nemeses _ John Elway _ is gone from Denver, and that
another potential obstacle _ Marshall Faulk _ has been traded by
Indianapolis and no longer plays in their division.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has told the Jets to ignore all this, to pay no
attention to friends who tell them how good they will be, or to the
Las Vegas oddsmakers who have already established the Jets as a 9-2
shot to go to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But deep down, Parcells is only human. So, after Faulk was
traded to the St. Louis Rams, Parcells admitted, ``I went upstairs
and joined the conga line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna's dancing in celebration because Faulk is no longer in
the East Division to torment his team may have been a chimera. But
as the minicamp opened at Hofstra University on Friday, Parcells
was earnest in his warnings. It's true the Jets went 12-4 in 1998,
scored an impressive victory over Jacksonville in the second round
of the playoffs, and had a halftime lead over the Broncos in the
American Football Conference title game. Yet Parcells knows that of
the last 10 AFC teams that lost the conference championship game,
none won the Super Bowl the next season. And only one even got to
the Super Bowl a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The players have heeded him. They already are speaking
conservatively, as if last season's dramatic turnaround was
something in the distant past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it,'' linebacker Bryan Cox said, ``is that
everything is absolutely new. New rookies, new players coming in,
the makeup, the chemistry, will be different. You just can't insert
somebody into a role and expect it to be better right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But the Jets certainly appear to be better than they
were last season except at guard, where no one has played in a
National Football League game. (That could change if Matt O'Dwyer
accepts the Jets' offer to return from free agency.)
</P>
<P>
   They appear to have upgraded themselves with Steve Atwater at
free safety (where three players tried and failed last season), Tom
Tupa booming punts, Roman Phifer on the outside of a four-man
linebacker corps, and Eric Green at tight end _ not to mention the
important factor of Vinny Testaverde's starting the season at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, nobody expected it,'' Cox said, referring to the
Jets' success. ``The pressure was different. Tampa Bay, the Giants,
San Francisco, people expected all those teams to win the division.
They didn't. Instead of being the hunter, we're the hunted.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has had every one of his players in the New York area
for most of the off season. He knows they have heard glowing
predictions from friends and fans and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that last year the Jets started 0-2 and turned
it around. He is concerned about another slow start with a more
difficult schedule and has been contemplating how to avoid that. He
wants his team in place and ready immediately. He will alter his
exhibition-game strategy to avoid experimenting so much and to get
his players prepared for a tougher schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we faced eight playoff teams and won seven games,''
he said. ``This year we face 10 playoff teams.''
</P>
<P>
   He has already explained the schedule to the players: they face
the Patriots in Week 1, have a Sunday night game at Buffalo in Week
2, and that by the end of Week 5 will have faced four playoff
teams, including Denver in a Monday night game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elway's absence doesn't affect us,'' linebacker Mo Lewis
claimed. ``We're all 0-0 now.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is aware of Parcells' ruses to avoid overconfidence.
``He's planted things in our mind about what we have to do,''
Testaverde said. ``So if you're thinking of taking a day off and
not working, you realize how difficult it is to play hard and win,
and you don't sit around on the couch.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis, even breaking in free-agent veterans like Phifer,
from the Rams, and Atwater, from the Broncos, is difficult. Players
like Pepper Johnson, Kyle Brady, Glenn Foley, Jerome Henderson and
Brian Hansen are gone. Whatever their shortcomings, they were part
of a team that went 12-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Colts,'' Lewis said. ``They don't have Faulk but
they figure a new running back will do well there, too. Other teams
will improve. We've changed. It's never going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult transition. It has taken the Jets decades to
feel this good about themselves. And now they cannot revel in their
success. Parcells seems to remember only that they lost their last
game. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
