<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SCRIPT FOR THE SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that almost all the discussion about the
upcoming U.S. Senate race in New York concerns personalities. The
cast of characters is, after all, larger than life. First lady
Hillary Clinton has all but officially announced her candidacy, as
has New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. If Giuliani has to fight
for the Republican nomination against Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island, chances are that the mayor's combative persona will be the
focus of that primary as well.
</P>
<P>
   But New York is a state with more than its quota of economic and
social problems. It deserves a campaign that includes a full
discussion of the issues that will affect it in the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Education is a critical concern, and even at this early date,
Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton have been sparring gingerly about school
vouchers, which the mayor supports and the first lady opposes. But
New York deserves a broader debate about how to improve the quality
of its educational system. What is the proper role for the federal
government in supporting local public schools? Should there be
national standards to measure teacher qualifications and student
success? What part could a U.S. senator play in debates about
social promotion, remedial education and the proper role of
teachers' and principals' unions?
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for the Senate always promise to bring home more
bacon, but Mrs. Clinton will have to explain why it would be in the
state's interest to have two Democratic senators when the
Republicans appear to have a hold on majority control. Her opponent
should be challenged to describe what he would do when his
Sunbelt-dominated party pushed legislation that threatened the
Northeast on matters like acid rain and transportation spending.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare reform bill, which Lazio supported and Giuliani
opposed in part, is now the law of the land with wide backing even
among the Democrats. But New York's role as a haven for immigrants
and the presence here of so many second- and third-generation
welfare recipients will make it hard for the state to proceed to
the next step, when time limits kick in and families start being
ejected from the system. The candidates should tell us what changes
they would endorse to help states with large populations of recent
immigrants and the very poor.
</P>
<P>
   Past experience suggests that when it comes to foreign policy,
the Senate campaign will focus on the Mideast, with each candidate
trying to grab the mantle of best friend to Israel. We would like
to see a broader discussion that focused on the proper
international role for the United States. Under what circumstances
should Americans intervene in other countries' affairs? How much
should we rely on the United Nations and NATO to represent our
interests? How important are human-rights issues when it comes to
relations with trading partners like China or Indonesia?
</P>
<P>
   On campaign finance reform, Mrs. Clinton would have a great deal
of explaining to do about the abuses of existing laws that went on
during her husband's administration, some of which involved her
close associates, including her senior political adviser, Harold
Ickes, and members of her White House staff. Giuliani ought to
discuss how far he would be willing to buck his party, which has
been blocking serious reform in Congress. Lazio, who has voted to
strengthen the campaign finance laws, would have to tell voters why
he declined to join his party's reform wing to force those bills to
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has already said that she would not try again to
create the sort of sweeping solution to the nation's health care
problems that she advocated in her early days as first lady. But
about 43 million Americans remain uninsured, including 3.1 million
New Yorkers, and many of those who do have coverage express
dissatisfaction with the restrictions of managed-care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, during the exciting but not always enlightening
Senate race between Charles Schumer and Alfonse D'Amato, the
candidates were asked how health care costs could be kept down if
insurance companies were forced by Congress to cover more and more
procedures. The candidates, who had been vying to appear toughest
on health maintenance organizations, both avoided the query and
went back to arguing about who was more of a liar.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a year and a half before the Senate election, the
candidates should have plenty of time to answer serious questions.
</P>
<P>
   Personalities are not irrelevant to this race. Mrs. Clinton and
Lazio would have every right to question whether Giuliani has the
temperament to be an effective senator. Giuliani, who has already
been harping on the carpetbag issue, is not out of line in
wondering whether New York should be represented by someone who has
actually lived here. Voters would naturally want to know how Mrs.
Clinton plans to balance her role as Senate candidate with her
duties as first lady, and we have confidence her opponent will
bring the matter up on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a shame if this contest, which may be the focus
of almost as much attention as the presidential race, should
degenerate quickly into a sound-bite battle. Besides being national
personalities, Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani are intelligent and
thoughtful political veterans with very different takes on the
proper role of government. Lazio, who seems intent on depriving the
national media of their dream race, is a serious legislator who has
surprised people in the past with his ability to topple a
high-profile politician.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too early to ask that the candidates, as they
announce, commit themselves to a series of issue-based debates
throughout the campaign, each focusing on a single topic, like
education or foreign policy. The campaign will inevitably make
compelling theater, but the candidates will need to give serious
topics their due.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
