<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-05 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR KNICKS' WILLIAMS, REMINISCING IS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You might think that after 18 seasons in the National
Basketball Association, Herb Williams would have become a
sentimentalist. Sentimental about the Knicks' unlikely playoff run.
Sentimental about the chance to turn in one last exhilarating
playoff performance. Looking forward to doing in his old Indiana
Pacers teammates.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' career hasn't been based on sentiment but rather cold,
hard analysis. The impact of Patrick Ewing's season-ending injury
after two games of the Knicks-Pacers series reverberates all the
way to the end of the Knicks' bench, where Williams, the
41-year-old center, has sat and watched like a sage.
</P>
<P>
   He mostly has served as a cheerleader, but with yet another
dramatic twist added to the team's tale, the 6-foot-11-inch
Williams, relegated to chants of ``We want Herb,'' when games are
out of reach, may be pressed into duty for the remainder of the
series. When, where, how remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never know when I'm going to play,'' he said. ``I always
want to play. That's no secret.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams was asked how he could get his body to play
``young,'' he said: ``You don't have to be young; you have to be in
shape, ready to play hard.'' Asked if he thought he could ``mix it
up'' with Rik Smits, the Pacers' 7-2 center, Williams was
incredulous: ``Do I think I can do what? Don't ask me questions
like that. Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, what about the Pacers' physical style? ``Physical?''
Williams said. ``They're not physical. Rik? Physical? He's not
physical. Rik's a scorer. He shoots the ball well. He's good on the
pick-and-roll.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy didn't discount using Williams in
the remainder of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have in Herb is a very intelligent player who won't
make mistakes, which is very critical,'' Van Gundy said. ``If
you're going to bring in a guy for just a few minutes what you
don't want is a mistake player, and Herb is the exact opposite of a
mistake player. He's going to do the right thing on the court to
help us be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans only know Herb Williams as the team elder whose
appearance in a game has become the ceremonial confirmation of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Williams was a star in the league. In Patrick Ewing's
first season, 1985, Williams enjoyed his finest year as a pro with
the Pacers. He scorched the Knicks for a career-high 40 points that
season, was the Pacers' leading scorer and had a career high with
184 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' minutes and role have evolved since he arrived in New
York in 1992 after 11 seasons in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't want to take a stroll down memory lane. He is
focusing on the Pacers, the Knicks' sudden change in fortunes. The
here and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what I did in the past; all that matters is
that I'm confident in myself and what I can do,'' Williams said.
``If they have seen me play or if they remember me, it would have
been all right. But I don't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, called ``a reserve for a reserve'' by the assistant
coach Don Chaney, has been upgraded from a reserve who was not on
call to a reserve who is on call because of the injury to Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he came to the Knicks expecting to play serious
minutes. Instead he went from the 27 minutes a game he played with
the Dallas Mavericks to 10.4 minutes a game with the Knicks and
that is what his role has been for most of the last six seasons. A
large part of Williams' longevity has been his ability to adapt and
accept a role _ no matter how far out on the periphery _ and think
``team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to change your mind-set; you've got to adjust,'' he
said. ``I'm always ready to play. I don't come to the game ready to
sit on the bench. When you play in New York, there are a lot of
different variables that can cause you to play or not to play. I
understand that and I've always been the guy who has been out. So,
its hard at times. Some guys can't take it, other guys don't want
to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the bottom line is that it's not Herb Williams. It's
team _ and it has always been that way, even though you may feel
you should play or you may feel you should be put in at certain
situations. The bottom line is that if the team wins, the team is
doing well and you've got to be happy for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone expressed surprise that Williams still carried a passion
for crucial minutes at this point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you something,'' he said with mild indignation, ``if
I didn't want to play, I wouldn't have on this uniform. I don't
need to be out here playing just to make money. That ain't what I'm
out here for. I'm out here to play and to win a championship.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what about the ``We want Herb'' chants? Wouldn't it be great
to prove, one last time, that he can still contribute?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I can play and that's all I worry about,''
he said. ``The chant, that's great, but you can't get caught up in
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the possibility of being pressed into service against his
old team and ousting them from the playoffs, Williams once again
deflects: No. No. No. No sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't matter who we are playing,'' Williams said. ``It's
not going to be extra good because it's Indiana and I used to play
for Indiana. This series is the same as playing against Atlanta,
the same as playing against Miami. I just want to win and go on to
the next series.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
