</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSUING JOB OF INCUMBENT COACH IS NOT COVERED IN RULE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago in the wake of Dave Checketts
disclosing that he had met with Phil Jackson, the name of Glenn
``Doc'' Rivers surfaced in connection with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the former player and current television
analyst was interested in the team's head coaching or the general
manager job, but Rivers had reportedly made contact with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, worried that he was about to be disparaged in the
coaching fraternity for maneuvering behind the scenes for a job
currently held by Jeff Van Gundy, called the Knicks coach to assure
him he had not personally campaigned for the position.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers was so concerned and upset over the report that he
telephoned his Atlanta-based agent, Lonnie Cooper, to find out if
his representative had spoken to Checketts, the president of
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became moot this weekend after Rivers came off the
league's most-coveted list and was signed for $8 million over four
years by the Orlando Magic. The team is expected to announce at a
news conference Monday that Rivers, 37, will become the fourth head
coach in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   But the uncomfortable situation faced by Rivers two weekends ago
underscored a major problem for prospective coaches trying to
secure multimillion dollar deals: do you follow the profession's
unwritten rule and wait for the current coach to finally be
relieved of his duties before applying, or risk losing out to a
candidate whose agent worked the phones months ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's proper to talk about a job or speculate or
meet with somebody about a job if the job is filled, simple as
that,'' said Dick Harter, the Indiana Pacers assistant coach who
once worked with Van Gundy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's an unwritten rule in the coaching
fraternity because the coaching fraternity doesn't have a lot of
rules,'' Harter said. ``But among the good people, though, that's
the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the financial rewards increase, so, too, does the dealing
behind the scenes. It often leads to insecurity and mistrust at the
highest levels. Case in point: When a rumor got back to Nets coach
Don Casey three months ago that Van Gundy was being considered as a
candidate to coach the Nets, he grew agitated that such false
information could get around.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Casey earning the respect of his players and Van
Gundy's team floundering across the Hudson River at the time, but
Van Gundy's agent, Rob Ades, was also Casey's personal lawyer and
friend for the last 30 years. The notion that Ades would go behind
Casey's back to campaign for Van Gundy at the Meadowlands was
ludicrous, Casey thought.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. The rumor turned out to be bogus. And yet, this is
the kind of unstable environment created by the rush for a
lucrative job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think agents are going to make contact beforehand; it's part
of the business,'' Rivers said. ``I think it's more unethical when
the guy himself does it. If Phil Jackson is picking up the phone
and calling Dave Checketts when Jeff Van Gundy has a job, I think a
lot of coaches would have a problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it's Phil Jackson's agent, his agent is just doing his
job. I don't think Jeff Van Gundy would be upset about that
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning Jackson and Checketts, the Knicks made first contact.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana assistant Rick Carlisle has been up for several jobs
over the past year, and will likely entertain more offers in the
off season. He, too, is bothered by the approach taken by some
agents and their clients. But like the trend of teen-age phenoms
leaving school before their time, he believes the ongoing lobbying
for coaching jobs has become a seedy but accepted part of the
profession. ``The situation is one where you would hope to be
treated the way you would want to be treated,'' Carlisle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a job, of course I would feel horrible if they were
talking about somebody else taking my place before I'd actually
been relieved of that position. On the other hand, it's certainly
got to be tempting if you're another person interested in a job,
and they're willing to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs Hop on Merry-Go-Round?
</P>
<P>
   At some point over the last few months, the Knicks, the Lakers,
the Nuggets, the Magic and the Nets have sprouted up as possible
franchises for Phil Jackson's return to the National Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the job that may be the best fit of all for the former coach
of the six-time champion Chicago Bulls has not been mentioned _ for
obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs, under Gregg Popovich, are motoring toward
the finals and looking like a juggernaut for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich, the team's general manager, took over the team on an
interim basis from Bob Hill two years ago with the intention of
eventually hiring someone else.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the team was 6-8 in March, he casually mentioned
to a prominent coaching candidate to stay by the phone in case
something happened.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was not that candidate, but the Spurs appear to have all
the prerequisites to lure him away from Bill Bradley's Presidential
campaign: a maturity level among the veterans. A one-newspaper town
that does not cover the team like the White House. And, yes, Tim
Duncan, perhaps the best player in the game for the next 10
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   More signs are pointing toward Jackson waiting a year to rejoin
the coaching ranks, especially after his agent, Todd Musburger,
spurned a lucrative package from the Nets in the last week. And
from all accounts, the Spurs' owner, Peter Holt, is very pleased
with Popovich and has no inclination to hire Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Jackson were to enter the picture, there are some
drawbacks. Holt has intimated that the team will move if city does
not vote in favor of building a new arena late this summer; the
team lost a vote on the arena last year.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is that if the team advances to the finals, the vote
will pass.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Under Inquiry
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter is one of the league's new meal tickets, a
skywalking guard with more athleticism than even Michael Jordan
possessed his first season in the National Basketball Association.
But the rookie of the year for the Toronto Raptors may be in the
market for new representation soon.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's current agent, William (Tank) Blank, is under
investigation by the National Football League players association
for allegedly doling out cash payments to prospective NFL recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Black represents about 40 NFL players, but Carter is his only
NBA client.
</P>
<P>
   If Black were disciplined by the players association, there is a
chance he would also be disciplined by the NBA's players
association. The union's general policy is that any NBA agent who
is charged or disciplined by another union is required to provide
an explanation of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Carter may still retain Black in the wake of the allegations,
but the players association has shown recently it does not tolerate
unbecoming behavior from its agents.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the decertification of Steve Woods was upheld by the
arbitrator George Nicolau. Woods had his right to represent NBA
players revoked when the union deemed his comments and actions
during the lockout as harmful to the players' cause. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
