<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL: A PSYCHOLOGICAL GAME BETWEEN THE COACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beyond their profession, Larry Bird and Jeff Van
Gundy do not have much in common. The former is among the best
players in history, a 6-foot-9-inch Hall of Famer who enjoys bass
fishing, beer and mowing his lawn; Van Gundy is a 5-9 intellect who
happens to be a coaching lifer, his Division III point-guard body
constantly grappling with an Ivy League mind.
</P>
<P>
   Their sideline demeanors don't mesh, either. If Bird were told
his pant cuffs were on fire during a game, he would gradually shift
his eyes downward at the flames before ever so slowly looking up
again to declare: ``Yep, yer right. They are.'' Van Gundy fidgets
like a ferret, sipping his Diet Coke, moving to and fro like an
expectant father.
</P>
<P>
   Big Larry and Little Jeffy, two birds of a different feather.
</P>
<P>
   Yet throw this odd couple in the crucible of a hotly contested
playoff series _ in which an official's call could mean the
difference between nirvana and next season for the Knicks or the
Pacers _ and they become spiritual brothers in the art of off-day
politicking on behalf of their unjustly persecuted team.
</P>
<P>
   After his team lost Game 1, Bird wanted the referees to respect
Mark Jackson's low-post game. After the Knicks lost Game 2, Van
Gundy wanted Jackson penalized for bulldozing his itty-bitty point
guards.
</P>
<P>
   After only two games, the Knicks coach has already labeled
Reggie Miller and Rik Smits ``flop artists,'' players who act as if
they have been assaulted after incidental contact.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Pacers forward Antonio Davis' labeling of Kurt
Thomas as ``dirty,'' Van Gundy said Indiana was a much more
physical team than the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   To which Bird facetiously replied: ``We're not bullies. We're
not that tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear exactly when these two became some of the most
influential lobbyists of the 20th century. But now that the whiners
within have emerged and the chess match is on, Bird and Van Gundy
join those political animals of post-seasons past _ Pat Riley, Phil
Jackson and Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   On an off day, even an old-school purist like Red Auerbach was
not immune to running for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to do it to too _ all that psychological stuff between
the games,'' said the patriarch of the Boston Celtics by telephone
from his home in the Washington area. ``But these guys nowadays
take it a little too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, you got fined for saying something dumb, and it was
a lot of money. It meant something to lose that money. Now? So they
fined the coach $5,000 _ what does that mean? The team might be
paying that for him, and what's $5,000 to these guys with huge
deals?''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bird nor Van Gundy is a proud lobbyist. But since Riley
and Jackson raised the stakes during the Knicks-Bulls rivalry of
the early 1990s, it has become a necessary evil to jockey for
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy, an assistant under Riley, soaked in the knowledge _
just as Bird did in Boston when he played for a great playoff
politician, K.C. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's first real indoctrination came in his first season as the
Pacers coach last June. He complained about Scottie Pippen's
defense on Jackson in the conference finals, wondering aloud if a
foul would ever be called after the Bulls went up 2-0 in the
series. It worked. Jackson began getting those calls.
Coincidentally or not, the Pacers extended the Bulls to seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy complained about the officiating earlier this week to
Rod Thorn, the league's senior vice president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, whining wins,'' Van Gundy said. ``And that's
sad, and that's not what the game of basketball game is about.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls of Jackson mastered the subtleties of working the
referees through the news media between games, Jerry Sloan's Utah
Jazz were not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Jazz learned from the Bulls is how to get the world
to see the game through their eyes,'' said Bill Walton, the Hall of
Fame center and television analyst. ``You've got to convince the
referees what you're doing is right. That whole psychological
relationship with the referees is critical to your overall
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton added: ``What real champions don't do is argue on the
court at the moment of the call. They convince the referees over
time, between the games and through the media. You never saw
Michael Jordan, John Stockton, Larry or Magic going crazy during
the game. During the course of a series, they would establish
themselves as credible advocates for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem with this whole process is, every time a team
loses it becomes the referees' fault. And some of these coaches
almost set the stage for fights. They plant the idea in their
players' heads that they've been victimized and persecuted, and
that's when they lose their cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to benefit from four days worth of lobbying, Bird and Van
Gundy led their teams into Game 3 at Madison Square Garden last
night. Whiners, crusaders or merely people doing their jobs, they
both honored a longstanding tradition last week _ a tradition
handed down by some of the great complainers of our time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The psychology is all about the next game, the next call,''
Auerbach said. ``Or, how far you can go without a technical to
influence the next call. That hasn't changed from when I used to
say something to the officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, the squeaky coach gets the grease. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
