<HEADLINE>
L. JOSEPH BUTTERFIELD, 72, PIONEER IN NEONATOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Ill., Ind. N.M.)  (rk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. L. Joseph Butterfield, whose innovative care of newborns
earned him a reputation as a pioneer of modern neonatology, died
June 2 at his home in Denver. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, according to the Children's
Hospital of Denver, where he spent more than 40 years in
neonatology, the branch of medicine dealing with infants up to 2
months old.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield established one of the country's first regional
centers for perinatal care, a field involving the period closely
surrounding the moment of birth. He also gave Children's Hospital
an innovative hospice unit where families could be close to their
dying infants.
</P>
<P>
   He vigorously propagated the work of Dr. Virginia Apgar, a
pediatrician and anesthesiologist at Columbia Presbyterian Medical
Center who died in 1974, and helped win general acceptance of what
is now known throughout the world as the Apgar score, which lets
pediatricians assess the health of a child within five minutes of
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by Dr. Apgar in 1953, the simple, inexpensive
procedure appraises five vital functions to alert doctors to the
need for intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   To assist health workers, Butterfield devised a mnemonic for the
procedure: A _ appearance (skin color); P _ pulse; G _ grimace
(reflexes); A _ activity, and R _ respiration.
</P>
<P>
   After Dr. Apgar's death, Butterfield led a 10-year campaign that
persuaded the Postal Service to issue a commemorative stamp in her
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield was born in Terre Haute, Ind., and grew up in Pana,
Ill. He received bachelor's and master's degrees in biology at the
University of New Mexico and moved to the University of Colorado
Medical School to receive his medical degree in 1955. The next
year, he began his affiliation with Children's Hospital in Denver
as a pediatric resident.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, the hospital asked Butterfield to set up its Children's
Newborn Center and be its medical director. The center served a
vast area and set a national pattern for regional perinatal care.
</P>
<P>
   His later influence in newborn and family matters went beyond
the nursery, verging into advocacy on broader children's issues. He
spent much time on a program in which he taught the intricacies of
the legislative process to people hoping to use it on behalf of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield is survived by his wife, Perry; a son and daughter,
Bruce Butterfield and Tate Ulrich, both of Monument, Colo.; three
brothers, Bernie, George and Dr. Donald Butterfield, all of
Albuquerque, N.M., and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The hospice program Butterfield started at Children's Hospital
in 1979 provided a private family space next to the neonatal
intensive-care ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensive-care unit can be a bizarre and impersonal place,
with all of the monitors beeping and constant clatter,''
Butterfield said at the time. ``That's why it is important for a
family to have a quiet place, to be alone with the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   For him it was a deeply felt matter, the remembrance of a
child's death. ``When my own 23-year-old daughter died,'' he said,
``we were there at the end to hold her, to say goodbye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELANY-SISTERS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELANY-SISTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.C.)  
 SELLING REMINDERS OF 2 SISTERS' SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. _ The memento seekers who lined up at the
two-story brick home at the end of a cul-de-sac Saturday were a
mixed crowd of women and men, black and white.
</P>
<P>
   But they were all hoping to obtain a piece of history at the
estate sale of the Delany sisters, the daughters of a freed slave
who became trailblazing professionals and lived past the age of
100.
</P>
<P>
   Bessie and Sadie Delany, who grew up in Raleigh, N.C., and went
on to become a dentist and a teacher, respectively, were famous for
their book ``Having Our Say,'' which became a Broadway play and a
television movie.
</P>
<P>
   And those who came Saturday for a teacup, a cookie cutter, a
mirror, a crumbling almanac, some of which were sold for as little
as $2, also wanted a bit of the sisters' spirit, their religious
beliefs and their commitment to family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible history,'' said Donna Dunkelman, whose son
read the sisters' book in the eighth grade. Ms. Dunkelman said she
was particularly awed by the fact that their father, a freed slave,
went on to become the country's first black Episcopalian minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just to be here with all this history, knowing about
their past and feeling that I'm a part of it,'' that she came, she
said as she waited patiently outside to enter.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, many of the women browsing in the old-fashioned kitchen
and in the bedrooms upstairs said the Delanys had been role models.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Lloyd, a lawyer, mused on the secrets of the sisters'
lives that allowed Bessie to live to 104 and Sadie, who died less
than five months ago, to 109. She examined a bottle of mineral oil
and reflected that the Delanys also ate garlic every day, did yoga
and remained unmarried, which she thought might have added to their
longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Hudson, a retired IBM employee back for the second day of
the sale, said as she clutched a blue flowered plate and a handful
of books, ``I'm hoping I can capture their spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   After a sleepless night, she had returned for the plate after
realizing that it was the one pictured on the cover of the Delanys'
book.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement, Cynthia Evans showed off her purchases _
old-fashioned cookie cutters and jars, a box of thread, and an old
edition of the Gospel of St. John.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by their lives and wanted to get my little
piece of history,'' she said. The jars brought back memories of her
childhood summers in Bridgeville, Del., where she helped her
grandmother preserve strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, the estate sale has attracted 1,500 people, said
Barbara Hawkins, who is running it for the Delanys' heirs. She said
that a North Carolina museum had called and, sight unseen,
purchased Sadie's Victorian bed, a fur coat, and Bessie's dental
chest, for $1,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Their papers, including their mother's diary from 1850, will go
to St. Augustine's School in Raleigh, N.C., where their father
worked as a vice-principal.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Arrindell, an actuarial consultant from Brooklyn browsing
in the library, said she had come because her daughter, Lisa
Arrindell Aaronson, had played Sadie in the television movie. She
explained that her daughter had recently baked her a pound cake
using Sadie's recipe from the book, so she wanted to buy a Delany
family plate to hold future pound cakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
