<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-05 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR OPENERS, YANKS AND METS OFFER A SERIES FOR THE
FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although the Yankees and the Mets keep trying to
deflate the tension of their subway series, they all acknowledge,
``It's great for the fans.'' And for Friday night's opener, 56,175
of those fans showed up, the fourth-largest non-opening-day
regular-season crowd at Yankee Stadium since the House that George
Rebuilt reopened in 1976. But one of those fans turned the Yankees'
4-3 victory. Maybe a Yankee fan with a method to his madness?
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine wouldn't bite, saying, ``Maybe it was a Mets
fan.'' But whatever that fan's allegiance, the Yankees prospered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad the fans decided to participate,'' Valentine, the
Mets manager, would say later. ``They're not participants.''
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the Mets' sixth and the Yankees leading, 3-2.
Robin Ventura walked and hurried to third on Brian McRae's single.
Rey Ordonez slashed a line drive down the right field line but a
fan reached out and touched the ball. Ground-rule double. Ventura
scored, but McRae, instead of possibly scoring, had to stop at
third.
</P>
<P>
   And the question will never be answered: if the fan hadn't
touched the ball, would McRae have scored the Mets' fourth run?
</P>
<P>
   Had a Yankee fan been smart enough to touch the ball on purpose
in order to prevent McRae from scoring the go-ahead run?
</P>
<P>
   Yankee catcher Jorge Posada wouldn't rule that out. He talked
about how he had seen home fans deliberately stay away from balls
hit by Yankees, but touch a ball hit by an opponent in order to
create a ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 playoffs, remember, umpire Rich Garcia awarded Derek
Jeter a home run when a then 12-year-old Yankee fan, Jeffrey Maier,
leaned over the right-field wall and caught the ball above Oriole
right-fielder Tony Tarasco's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won that game and the American League Championship
Series. And now a fan, knowingly or not, helped them win the subway
series opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether Brian could have scored, that's the umpires' judgment
call, we'll never know,'' Valentine said. ``If the ball had gone
into the corner and rattled around, Brian might have been able to
score; at least there would have been a play at the plate. But
because the fan touched the ball so quickly, the play was called
quickly. So we'll never know what might have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae was running toward third when he heard ``one of the
umpires yell'' for him to stop at third as Ordonez glided to
second.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno walked, loading the bases, but Jason Grimsley,
replacing Yankee starter David Cone, induced Rickey Henderson to
bounce a grounder to second baseman Chuck Knoblauch for the third
out. The Mets never scored again as their losing streak reached
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   McRae, the Mets' center fielder who was put on waivers recently,
had three of the Mets' seven hits, including a second-inning homer
off David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't look at Coney,'' he said, alluding to his circling
the bases, ``because I was going to laugh. Me and him are good
friends. We hang out in the city. And he'll get back at me. I got
three hits, but they won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the three seasons of inter-league competition, the Yankees
now have a 5-2 record against the Mets in their subway series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series takes on a life of its own,'' Joe Torre, the
Yankee manager said. ``The media builds it up and the fans love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans were as much of a show as the game. The assembly of
predominantly Yankee fans enjoyed welcoming Rickey Henderson to the
Stadium where he once was the Yankee left fielder. When he made a
snatch-catch of Scott Brosius' fly ball in the third inning, the
fans in the lower left-field stands buzzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were yelling for me to make a snatch-catch even before I
made it,'' Henderson said. ``I recognized a few fans who were out
there when I played here. And all that yelling at me, it don't
bother me. It makes you play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson had a single and two stolen bases, but the Mets
couldn't quite play well enough to win the subway series opener
after having been swept by the Arizona Diamondbacks and the
Cincinnati Reds at Shea Stadium in their six previous games. And
they had two more games at Yankee Stadium this weekend, then three
more against the Yankees at Shea on July 9-10-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fans and media blow this way out of proportion,'' said
Rick Reed, the Met starter who allowed only five hits before being
relieved in the seventh. ``This is just another series for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not. And it shouldn't be. Until the Yankees and the
Mets meet in the World Series, if ever, the subway series will have
to do. And it does very nicely, thank you. No matter which team
wins. All those fans at Yankee Stadium this weekend are the proof
of that.
</P>
<P>
   Even if one of those fans was a participant. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
