<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTES--2TAKES-NYT     06-05 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTES--2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE ZONE CHANGE HURTS MADDUX AND GLAVINE 
MARLIN ANSWERS DOUBTS 
NOMO A HAPPY BREWER 
THE NO-HOME-RUN RACE 
`CIVILIZED' AT SHEA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In spring training, before pitchers and hitters knew how umpires
would adjust to the strike zone edict from the commissioner's
office, a couple of pretty good pitchers were expressing their
views on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   What's that, Greg Maddux asked, they're going to stop calling
strikes on pitches beyond the outside corner of the plate? ``I
didn't know they called pitches off the plate intentionally,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His pal at the next locker, Tom Glavine, was more forthcoming.
Asked if the change would affect him, he said, ``Of course it
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine added: ``I'm not going to lie. We get a little off the
plate. But people want you to believe we're getting six or eight
inches off the plate. We don't get that. There aren't many umpires
out there who will give you two inches, four inches, six inches if
you keep going. They might give you two, but they're going to draw
a line.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the edict to reduce the widened strike zone,
umpires for the most part have taken away the pitch, and the
artistic ability that helped Maddux and Glavine win six Cy Young
awards between them.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the new strike zone or not, the Atlanta Braves'
devastating duo are suffering this season as they haven't since
their earliest years in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, a 20-game winner last season for the fourth time in his
career, has a 3-7 record and 5.00 ERA. Maddux pitched against the
Red Sox Saturday with a 4-3 record and a 4.54 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Other numbers make their performances even worse. Opposing
batters were hitting .329 against Maddux, .291 against Glavine.
That's like a career .202 hitter suddenly winning a batting title
with a .348 average.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has allowed 113 base runners in 711/3 innings, Glavine
121 in 771/3, giving each a ratio of 14 base runners per nine
innings. The last time Maddux reached double figures in base runner
ratio was in 1991, when he permitted 10.4. In three of the
intervening seven seasons, his ratio was under 9, reaching a
personal low of 7.5 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 of the last 11 seasons, Maddux has allowed fewer hits than
innings pitched. This season opposing batters have 100 hits in
711/3 innings, peppering Maddux for 10 or more hits in five
successive starts at one stretch. Last season teams amassed 10 or
more hits against Maddux a total of four times, only once in his
first 27 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who walks many more batters than Maddux, has
traditionally put more runners on base, but not as many as he is
putting on this season. In the previous two years, his ratios were
10.5 and 10.9.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, their manager, played down the problems they have
experienced. But he acknowledged they are not pitching to the same
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strike zone is tightened up a lot,'' Cox said. ``We don't
want strikes off the plate; we want strikes on the plate. The
problem is the strike zone has become so small with a lot of guys.
The outside, if you want to shrink it, shrink it. But that crease
below the kneecaps and the letters are supposed to be a strike. But
they aren't, so nothing's a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling, Philadelphia's strikeout pitcher, has said that
some umpires have gone so far to show they are not calling pitches
off the plate strikes by not calling pitches on the corners of the
plate strikes either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I see,'' Cox said. ``They're not giving the
corners. Then they're blowing pitches right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves' hitting coach, Don Baylor has watched Maddux and
Glavine from a different dugout this season. For the last six
seasons he watched them as the Colorado Rockies' manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making them throw the ball over the plate a little bit
more,'' Baylor said. ``I see a lot of that. I see a lot of
inconsistency with the umpires. With Glavine early, even in spring
training, he threw pitches and got nothing but ball, ball. Here's a
Cy Young guy who threw those same pitches last year and got
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   His hitters in Colorado, Baylor said, chased pitches that Maddux
and Glavine threw ``because they knew they were going to be around
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it seems they're on the plate more,'' he said. ``I see
guys sitting there waiting for their pitch, even young guys.
They're taking ball one, ball two, then they get their pitch and
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor mentioned a game a few weeks ago in which the Chicago
Cubs battered Maddux for 14 hits. ``Sometimes you didn't have 14
swings against him,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps next winter the stars of one of the best television
commercials ever made can make a commercial about their
determination to improve their pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Answers Doubts
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins were not certain this past spring that
Preston Wilson would win a job. Before they decided whether to put
him on the team, they had to determine if he would get enough
playing time. They didn't want him spending too much time on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   But Cliff Floyd began the season on the disabled list with a
knee injury, opening an outfield spot for the rookie the Marlins
acquired from the Mets in the Mike Piazza deal last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what direction we would have gone in,'' general
manager Dave Dombrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the best choices are the ones made for you. Wilson,
son of Mets coach Mookie Wilson, hit .177 through April 27, but
since then he had batted .337 (30 for 89) entering Saturday night's
game, hit nine home runs and driven in 19 runs in 29 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known that he has tremendous power,'' Dombrowski said.
``The thing he needs to do is make better contact. He doesn't have
to take a big swing. The ball jumps off his bat. Lately he's
shortened his swing some. He's a young player and I can't tell you
he will do that on a consistent basis. But he's swinging at more
strikes and getting more hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's rapid development prompted the Marlins to send Todd
Dunwoody, their starting center fielder, to the minor leagues two
weeks ago to work on his hitting (.208). Wilson took over in
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have to improve out there, but he has played
solidly,'' Dombrowski said. ``He can run and throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The general manager said he wouldn't burden the 24-year-old
right-handed hitter with specific expectations, but the Marlins
certainly like his power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the capability of hitting 30 home runs at the big
league level,'' Dombrowski said. ``I'm not saying he'll do it this
year. But he's always a threat to hit the ball out of the
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nomo a Happy Brewer
</P>
<P>
   Released by the Mets and the Chicago Cubs this year, Hideo Nomo
has found success in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's throwing strikes; that's the big thing,'' Steve Phillips,
the Mets' general manager, said. ``He didn't do it with us and he
didn't do it with the Cubs in Triple A.''
</P>
<P>
   From his entry into the major leagues in 1995 to his twin
releases this year, the Japanese right-hander suffered a
precipitous plunge in status. Then he was the NL rookie of the
year, the league leader in strikeouts and shutouts and the major
league leader in opponents' batting average. Now he was a discarded
pitcher, seemingly on the way to a premature, forced retirement.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets released him during spring training, Nomo gained
an audition with the Cubs by way of their Triple A team. But he was
wild, and the Cubs asked for one more start before making a
decision. Don Nomura, Nomo's agent, declined, and the Cubs released
him.
</P>
<P>
   With pitching in a fragile state, the Brewers were willing to
give Nomo a third chance, and this one worked. In his first five
starts with the Brewers, Nomo compiled a 2-1 record and a 2.41 ERA
walking only nine and striking out 30 in 33 2/3 innings. His loss
was a 3-2 decision to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he thought Nomo has found a comfortable place to
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   `It's slightly different pitching there and pitching here,'' he
said. ``The expectations were such that I think he put a little
pressure on himself. Now he's on minimum salary and it's a
can't-lose situation for Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   The No-Home-Run Race
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa's home runs command all of the attention in Chicago
Cubs games, but last Wednesday Lance Johnson hit a home run that
was noteworthy for its timing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, noted for his triples, has not hit many home runs in
his career _ 34 in more than 5,000 times at bat _ and he does not
usually hit them this early. Last year, for example, he hit two all
season, the first in the Cubs' 157th game (Sosa already had slugged
63), the second in their 158th.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Johnson hit one home run, his first in 641 major league
at-bats. He hit none in 1991 (588 at-bats) and 1993 (540) and three
in 1992, giving him four home runs in his first 2,599 at-bats. He
hit his first this season in his 182nd at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson already on the home run chart, it is left to others
to run the no-home-run race. Entering Saturday's games, Luis
Castillo of Florida was leading with 193 times at bat without a
home run. Tony Womack of Arizona was right behind at 191 and Mike
Caruso of the Chicago White Sox was next at 187.
</P>
<P>
   `Civilized' at Shea
</P>
<P>
   After Randy Johnson pitched at Shea Stadium for the first time
last Sunday, he had an observation. ``The biggest thing I noticed
was the fans were a lot different than in Yankee Stadium,'' he
said. ``I mean that in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   How were they different? ``I just think a little more, you know
`go get em, Randy,' more positive, considering I'm a visiting
player.'' Did he mean more civilized? ``Yeah,'' he said, laughing,
``that's a good word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
