<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRAIN-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT AUTHORITY WAGED AN UPHILL BATTLE TO BUILD TRAIN TO KENNEDY
AIRPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In its all-out campaign to win approval for a rail
line linking Kennedy International Airport to local subways and
trains, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey recently
treated some City Council members to a bus ride through Queens. It
even provided some entertainment along the way: a brief clip from
an old ``Seinfeld'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   But the clip was hardly chosen at random. It showed one of the
characters, Elaine, explaining her elaborate plans to reach Kennedy
on time, only to be foiled by the perpetually clogged expressway
leading to the airport, the roadway whose very name is a punch
line: the dreaded Van Wyck.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if to demonstrate that life is too short to waste
time imitating art, the bus load of Council members, who were
heading to the rail line's proposed transfer point in Jamaica, got
stuck in traffic on the Van Wyck.
</P>
<P>
   The bus trip was just one aspect of the Port Authority's intense
and ultimately successful mission to win a $1.5 billion project to
connect the airport to the city's mass transit system _ a plan that
its representatives agree is both imperfect and a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Community boards in Queens questioned the disruption that
building an elevated rail line down the middle of the Van Wyck
would cause. Some transportation experts deplored the failure to
link the system to La Guardia Airport in northern Queens and
doubted its overall practicality. The staff of the City Council
issued a report that described the project's purported economic
benefits as illusory.
</P>
<P>
   The authority also had to overcome the problem of its own
reputation. One of its lobbyists described that reputation as ``the
evil empire.'' One of its executives went further: ``We are the big
fat bloated bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   To overcome those perceptions, the authority hired a SWAT team
of lobbyists, made expensive promises to various communities,
showered southeastern Queens with marketing studies and fact
sheets, and _ in the last days _ tinkered with the design to
appease Peter F. Vallone, speaker of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   It also had on its side a simplistic but nevertheless persuasive
argument: Something is better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the pieces fell into place. Very reluctantly, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani cut a deal that propelled the project forward. The
Planning Commission described the project, called Airtrain, as a
disaster-in-waiting, but then approved it. And despite the
devastating Council report, two Council committees gave
near-unanimous approval last week, clearing the way for the full
Council to grant final approval this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they were all spurred by the realization that New
York City lags far behind other cities in providing quick,
convenient access to its airports. Travelers can reach Kennedy by
public transit, but only circuitously. The trip involves taking the
A train to the Howard Beach-Kennedy stop in Queens, about an hour
from midtown Manhattan, and then a free bus to the terminals, which
takes another 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Sabini, the chairman of one of the Council committees
that endorsed the Airtrain plan, reflected the lawmakers' general
sentiment this way: ``It's not the best project I've ever seen. But
on the whole, weighing pluses and minuses, we thought this was the
best thing _ and we voted for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things: you hold your nose and vote for
it,'' said one of the Port Authority's lobbyists, Martin
McLaughlin. ``But sometimes a flawed project is better than nothing
at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
