   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-LEAD-$ADV06 _ TORREON, Mexico _ Facing what could be one
of its worst environmental disasters, Mexico is trying to clean up
waste from a metals refinery in Torreon that is blamed for
poisoning more than 1,000 children. The children _ and some people
who are now adults _ are suffering from elevated levels of lead in
their blood, which can cause permanent developmental damage. The
refinery has agreed to set up a $6.4 million health fund and sweep
affected areas in this northern Mexican city with special vacuums.
This brewing crisis didn't come out of nowhere: residents in one
poor neighborhood that sits next to the refinery and a giant slag
heap began to fight the company back in 1984. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   With information for a locator map. MOVEDKOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV06
_ TIRANA, Albania _ Beneath the calm surface, Albania is on the
brink of anarchy largely because of the influx of refugees has far
exceeded this very weak government's ability to cope. The effects
of the refugee influx has been delayed because so many are staying
in private homes, an arrangement that already is showing signs of
strain with host families beginning to evict refugees. In some
ways, order is being preserved only because of the international
presence here. Will focus on Albania and do what is possible with
Macedonia. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service). With
information for a locator map. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/REFUGEES-BOX-$ADV06 _ Refugee data in Albania and Macedonia.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-CAMP-$ADV06 _ KUKES, Albania _ A day _ and night _ in
the life of a refugee camp from the vantage point of a refugee.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SARAJEVO-OVERVIEW _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The city of Dayton is sending
a group of university professors, musicians, city staffers, chamber
of commerce types and the mayor into a country a U.S. State
Department travel advisory recommends Americans avoid because of
``risks from occasional localized political violence, landmines,
unexploded ordnance and carjacking.'' Why go? Because while NATO
bombs fall as near as 60 miles away in neighboring Serbia, Sarajevo
and the rest of troubled Bosnia-Herzegovina are struggling to enact
a peace plan that has the name ``Dayton'' emblazoned on it. Who is
going, why and what do the Sarajevans think about the trip.
(Bebbington, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EXPERTS _ WASHINGTON _ Who is an expert and how can a judge or a
jury know? Controversies have swirled around several
multimillion-dollar jury verdicts and the quality of the science
presented to jurors. How is a judge to determine, in light of U.S.
Supreme Court instructions that they act as ``gatekeepers'' over
the admissability of scientific evidence, what is good science and
what is good argument? (Nesmith, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/EXPERTS-CASES _ WASHINGTON _ Are losers in some big verdicts
financing the growing clamor to eliminate ``junk science'' from the
court room? MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-WARS _ WASHINGTON _ The rhetoric and budgetary salvos
have quieted since President Clinton appointed two Southerners,
Bill Ivey and Bill Ferris, to head the National Endowment for the
Arts and the National Endowment for the Humanities. In interviews,
the two talk about how they changed their agencies' cultural focus.
(Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The most important witness left to be
heard in the Microsoft antitrust trial may be the one appearing
this week. He is former IBM official Garry Norris, who charges that
Microsoft manipulated its prices for Windows to hinder IBM's
development of OS/2, a rival operating system. (Glass, Cox News
Service)
</P>
