   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-CRUSADE _ INDIANAPOLIS _ A feature on ``being saved'' at
a Billy Graham crusade. We follow the activities of Scott Davis,
who works to match the newly saved with compatible congregations -
and they are not all Baptist. (Jesse, Dayton Daily News) WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GA-EDUCATION-GAGRULE _ ATLANTA _ The state Department of
Education might be hard at work, but a new unwritten policy makes
it impossible for employees there to say anything to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution about education _ or about anything. State
Supertinendent Linda Schrenko, stung by a Constitution editorial
that called one of her latest ideas on school safety ``goofy,'' has
cut off all contact between her department and the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, forbidding department workers even from
attending events sponsored by the newspaper. The only contact can
be responses to Open Records requests by the newspaper, said Ed
Floyd, Schrenko's former Baptist pastor who is now her
administrative assistant. (Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WINDMILLS _ WINFIELD, Ala. _ Dusk was still several hours away
as Ken O'Brock tightened the final screws on the windmill he had
constructed on a sweltering spring day in a rolling pasture about
75 miles northwest of Birmingham. ``I'm doing twice as many jobs
this year,'' said the owner and installer of O'Brock Windmills of
North Benton, Ohio. ``In one week, I put up four windmills. One
near Athens, Ga. One outside of Bainbridge, Ga. And two in
Florida.'' Why this surprising surge in a centuries-old technology?
Credit a more modern technological glitch _ the Y2K bug. (Dart, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DDAY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Virgil Akers of Franklin Township was part
of the United States invasion fleet on Normandy Beach on June 6,
1944. We'll discuss the experience with Akers on the anniversary of
the event. (Smith, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
