<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ONCE THE BOMBS STOP, REBUILDING KOSOVO WILL BE SLOW, DIFFICULT
AND COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON When U.S. Marines first set foot as peacekeepers
inside Kosovo, perhaps as early as this week, they'll begin what
promises to be a long-term mission to try to nurse the ravaged
province back to health.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring security and rebuilding Kosovo, however, are only the
most urgent steps in an emerging plan to knit the war-torn Balkans
back together and somehow shepherd the bloodstained region into the
fold of modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That goal, which only in recent weeks has become central to the
ambitions of the United States and its European allies, will likely
cost American taxpayers tens of billions of dollars and could take
a generation to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Even that prognosis assumes success in a region that has a way
of dooming the best of intentions to failure.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that as soon as NATO bombs stop falling on
Serbia, NATO peacekeepers will march in. When their job will be
finished, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking decades,'' said Kurt Bassuener, associate
director of the Balkan Action Council, a research and policy group
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent billions on this war, and we're going to have to
spend billions to prevent another one,'' said Bassuener. ``It's
going to take leadership, it's going to take money, it's going to
take attention and it's going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   After 74 days of NATO air strikes, Serbia, and Kosovo in
particular, was still being pounded with bombs early Sunday. NATO
and Serb military commanders were scheduled to meet Sunday for a
second day at a cafe along the Macedonian border to try to agree on
a plan for pulling all Serb troops, police and paramilitary forces
out of Kosovo over the next seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the withdrawal begins in earnest, U.S. and NATO
officials insist, will the air strikes end.
</P>
<P>
   Once that happens, some 2,000 Marines as well as French, British
and other lead elements of a NATO peacekeeping force that will
eventually be 48,000 strong will start moving into Kosovo. Next,
convoys would begin hauling food and medical supplies into the
province to an estimated half a million ethnic Albanians who have
fled their homes and are living off the land inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 800,000 or so living in refugee camps or scattered
throughout private homes in neighboring Albania and Macedonia will
likely have to wait weeks, if not months, to return to their homes,
as NATO troops and aid workers rebuild shattered roads, bridges,
water supplies and shelter to accommodate the returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A certain amount of security has to be established before it's
safe for them to go back,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said
Saturday. ``I'm not positive that everybody will be able to get
back before winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Daunting as it is, the task of securing Kosovo and enabling
refugees to return is only the first step in an overarching scheme
unfolding in Washington and European capitals to try to resuscitate
a region wheezing from nearly a decade of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an enormous opportunity to be seized here, a chance
to shift our focus from defeating something evil to building
something good,'' President Clinton said Friday. He was laying out
the fresh challenge to American policymakers and the public at
large to invest billions of dollars to help the Balkans mature into
a democratic and economically viable part of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a goal that has been worth fighting for over the last
weeks,'' said Clinton, ``a goal we must work for with steadfast
determination in the months and in the years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The wording was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton once promised, after all, that American troops would be
required in Bosnia for a single year. That was nearly four years
ago. There are still 6,200 U.S. troops in Bosnia, part of a larger
NATO peacekeeping force there of some 31,000. And they appear
certain to remain for a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made clear this time that stitching Kosovo back
together will be neither quick nor easy.
</P>
<P>
   No one yet knows how much it will cost to repair the destruction
NATO bombs have rained down upon Serbia's bridges, factories,
railroads, power plants and refineries, not to mention its military
barracks, ammo dumps, tanks and warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has destroyed nearly 1,000 major targets or pieces of
military equipment in the field, and Belgrade has estimated the
damage at up to $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and European aid will begin pouring into Kosovo as soon as
NATO peacekeepers secure the province. The issue of massive
assistance will be near the heart of the agenda when Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright meets with her counterparts from the
so-called Group of Eight _ Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, Russia and the United States _ in Europe sometime this week,
and when Clinton joins other G-8 leaders in Cologne later this
month for their annual summit.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the rest of Serbia, however, is more problematic.
Anything other than humanitarian aid is likely to be withheld so
long as Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Indicted for war crimes by a United Nations tribunal, Milosevic
is blamed by the West for Kosovo's humanitarian nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   With Serbia in ruins, the outlook for broader Balkan recovery is
grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prospects are bad,'' said Daniel Serwer, a former U.S. envoy
to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could rebuild every house in Kosovo and still not have an
economy,'' said Serwer. ``Kosovo's economy is dependent on Serbia,
as are the economies of several of Serbia's neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is rimmed by Balkan states struggling along the road to
political and economic renewal. Democratic and free market reforms
have swept through Bulgaria, Romania, Albania, Macedonia and even
Montenegro. All are tied economically to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got ideal conditions in the surrounding states and a
disaster, a black hole, in the center of the Balkans,'' said
Serwer, a senior fellow at the U.S. Institute for Peace, a
government think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Brittle as his future may be, Milosevic has proven to be a
political survivor. Every day he remains on his last leg in power,
said Serwer, postpones Balkan renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region as a whole can't recover fully without a change,
not only in leadership, but in the kind of regime that Serbia
has,'' said Serwer. ``The last thing they want to do is be left in
a cage with a wounded bear.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
