u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THEIR STARTERS FALTER, WILL THE METS IMITATE STEINBRENNER?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter is considered the leader of the Mets'
pitching staff. He has a 2-5 record and a 6.39 earned run average.
Is that any way to lead a pitching staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put that on myself,'' the left-hander said
Saturday, when he was asked about himself as the leader. ``I can't
worry about everybody else. I've got to worry about getting hitters
out. My focus is on their lineup tomorrow night and what I have to
do to get them out, not to think about the big picture. That, for
me, is total distraction. It doesn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone here help the Mets' starting pitchers? With a 5.58
earned run average, 14th worst among 16 National League starting
corps, they are, to a large extent, responsible for the team's
plight a third of the way into the season. Leiter himself has the
fifth-worst era among pitchers who have made 10 or more starts.
</P>
<P>
   That's why rumblings have begun to surface about the status of
Bob Apodaca, the pitching coach. A report in Saturday's Newsday
said the club had begun to contemplate Apodaca's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps sheer coincidence that the Mets are at Yankee
Stadium this weekend for a three-game interleague series with the
Yankees. Under the ownership of George Steinbrenner, the Yankees,
if they didn't invent it, mastered the art of firing the pitching
coach when the team wasn't playing well. Or the hitting coach, or
the bullpen coach, or any combination of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Further coincidence had Clyde King in the stands Saturday. He
was seated behind the Mets' dugout because he was the guest of a
friend who had seats in that location, but King is employed by the
Yankees. He also has vast firsthand knowledge of pitching coach
changes from his active days with the club.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner would fire a coach for one of two reasons: as the
scapegoat for the team's poor play or to get at the manager, whom
he really wanted to fire but didn't feel he could at the time.
</P>
<P>
   If Apodaca goes, he could fit either one of those categories,
scapegoat or conduit, with the former being more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, declined to talk
about Apodaca. ``I'm not going to comment on the status of any of
the coaches,'' he said. ``Clearly we have not pitched well. We have
to evaluate things on a daily basis as to how we're performing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, though, Phillips, when asked, did comment on
the manager's status. ``He's fine,'' Phillips said. ``I think he's
doing a good job. I expect him to be able to lead us out of this
slump we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, who despite comments from Mets' officials to
the contrary, could himself be in jeopardy if the Mets don't get
serious about contending for a playoff spot. When they began play
Saturday, three first-place teams and six other teams had better
records.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who becomes offended at the suggestion that he does
anything wrong, staunchly defended Apodaca. ``Bob Apodaca is a very
good pitching coach,'' he said. ``His track record is as good as
anybody's in the game. He works as hard as and is as knowledgeable
as any coach I've been associated with.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine added that he remains committed to all of his coaches
``until they prove they're not doing the job they were hired to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Apodaca, who came to the Mets from their Norfolk minor league
team with Valentine in 1996, said passionately that he continues to
do his job the same way he always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only known one way to do it,'' he said, ``and that's be
the first person at the ball park everyday, to prepare myself for
the team we're playing, to prepare my pitchers for the team we're
playing, work with them constantly as far as getting better,
including myself. If I'm responsible because I'm not doing more
than that, I don't know what more I can do. I approach the game the
same way I've always approached it and that's give my employer
every ounce of my energy.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue beyond the way Apodaca does his job has been raised,
and that is the coach's relationship with Leiter and reliever
Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not unaware of that issue,'' Phillips said. ``Not this
year, but I was aware of the question last year, the relationship
of those guys.'' One team member said the relationship between
Apodaca and Leiter has improved ``a little bit'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   One pitching coach has paid the price for an underachieving
pitching staff. The Rupert Murdoch Dodgers, who signed Kevin Brown
to a $105 million contract last winter, fired Charlie Hough 11 days
ago. If the Mets make a similar move, they would not be plowing any
new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we've struggled and we have to be open to
considerations as to how we're going to turn it around,'' Phillips
said. He added, ``We are all accountable, including me, for the
team's performance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
