<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES OWN SERIES AS METS LOSE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees and Mets are as different right now as
the Bronx and Queens. Having come to grips with the reality they
are not going to win 125 games in 1999, the Yankee are formidable
once more. The Mets, on the other hand, are headed for upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   The loser of the Subway Series was seemingly destined for
in-house turmoil, and with their 6-3 defeat at Yankee Stadium on
Saturday. the Mets are assured of that distinction. Having won the
first two games of this three-game series, the Yankees will send
Roger Clemens to the mound Sunday, bearing his personal 20-game
winning streak. The Mets have lost eight consecutive games and the
pitching coach, Bob Apodaca, is reportedly in jeopardy of losing
his job.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, 32-21 and 11 games over .500 for the first time
this year, were led by Derek Jeter _ who else _ who had a sacrifice
fly and doubled to start another rally. Jeter has reached base in
all 53 of the Yankees' games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' desperation to win this game _ to win any game _
became apparent in the third inning, when, with the starting
pitcher Masato Yoshii (5-5) struggling, the left-hander Allen
Watson got up to throw in the Mets' bullpen and the right-hander
Pat Mahomes joined him. Warming up two relievers in the third
inning is something only seen in the World Series or the playoffs _
or in the Subway Series, when an entire city is watching and your
team is in danger of drowning in the National League East standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets grabbed victory by the throat in the early innings,
before losing their grip. With runners at second and third and
nobody out in the second inning, Brian McRae pulled a grounder to
the right side to drive in the game's first run and send Robin
Ventura to third base. Rey Ordonez then smashed the ball on one
bounce, a grounder destined for center field _ before Orlando
Hernandez jabbed it with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez reached with his right hand to retrieve the ball from
his glove, and realized immediately that it was stuck in the
webbing. Hernandez began running toward first base, like a
quarterback on a rollout, and, with an overhand motion, he flipped
his glove and the ball to first baseman Tino Martinez, who caught
the whole package for the second out of the inning. The 55,935
fans, witnessing a play few had ever seen before, roared in
delight, saluting Hernandez's calm and quick thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Soon their responses turned ugly, however. The next hitter,
Roger Cedeno, pushed a bunt in front of home plate. Hernandez (6-5)
rushed in to barehand the ball, and he had little chance of
throwing out Cedeno. But Yankees catcher Jorge Posada directed
Hernandez to throw to first, with a wave of his arm. Posada had not
bothered to notice that Ventura was coming down the line from third
base; nor had Posada returned to his position, to cover home plate.
Cedeno was safe at first base, and when Martinez tried to throw the
ball back to Posada in an attempt to nab Ventura, Posada was
completely unprepared, and Ventura ducked home with the Mets'
second run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla's sacrifice fly in the third inning gave the Mets
a 3-0 edge. Yoshii, who pitched a strong game against the Yankees
last year, had shut them out in the first two innings, and there
was a sense that the Mets might hang on for a day and quash their
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Yankees did not score in the first or second
inning, they looked comfortable at the plate against Yoshii; they
looked aggressive and confident, as if it was only a matter of time
before they were going to pound him. Yoshii threw 68 pitches on
this day, and the Yankees' batters swung and missed exactly once
(Bernie Williams leading off the second inning).
</P>
<P>
   Tony Tarasco, who is being given a chance to claim the
left-field job as his own, lined a double into the right-field
corner leading off the third. Scott Brosius fouled off three
consecutive pitches against Yoshii, his timing improving with each
offering, before ripping a run-scoring single to right field.
Following Brosius, Chuck Knoblauch fouled off six straight pitches,
and on the 10th pitch of the at-bat, Yoshii threw a pitch down and
in, Knoblauch's favorite area of the strike zone; the Yankees'
second baseman bashed a double to left field, Brosius stopping at
third.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's fly ball allowed Brosius to score and Knoblauch to
take third, and Brosius scored on a ground ball, tying the score at
3-3. The Mets require miracles to establish three-run leads these
days, and within the span of six hitters, their advantage was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The third inning ended with Mahomes and Watson both warmed up
and ready to go in the Mets' bullpen, but Yoshii came out to pitch
the fourth _ and allowed an upper-deck home run on the first pitch
he threw, to Tino Martinez. Chili Davis lofted a fly ball high and
to left field, where Rickey Henderson stared deeply into the sun.
He learned nothing about his inner soul and lost sight of the ball,
as well, and Davis ended up with a double. The Mets' dugout was
seized in mournful inertia.
</P>
<P>
   Three batters later, Brosius hammered a line drive to
right-center, beyond right fielder Cedeno, and Davis trotted home
with the Yankees' fifth run. With their eighth straight loss, the
Mets (27-28) fell under .500 for the first time since losing their
season opener. They will send Al Leiter (2-5) against Clemens on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
