<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-PANTINI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACERS EXPRESS SHOCK AT ITALIAN'S SUSPENSION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Sweden, France, Poland, Belgium)   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAMBERY, France _ Far from the Giro d'Italia, 116 bicycle
riders were starting their own race Saturday morning when the news
about Marco Pantani's disqualification there for failing a drug
test swept through their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a joke,'' said Glenn Magnusson, a Swede with
the U.S. Postal Service team in the one-day Classique des Alpes.
``A very bad joke too. Then people understood that it was true.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani was over the authorized limit of the hematocrit (red
blood-cell ratio) in his body and faces an automatic two-week
suspension. There was doubt as to whether he would ever race again.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Italian, who is the Tour de France champion, was
the only rider of the 10 competitors to be tested by the sport's
world governing body, UCI, whose level was above the legally
permitted 50 percent, registering 52 percent. Anything above 50
percent suggests that the rider had taken erythropoietin, or EPO,
which boosts the red blood cells that carry oxygen around the body.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani was devastated. ``I have already undergone two tests as
race leader,'' he told Agence France-Presse in Madonna di
Campiglio, Italy, ``and I think there is something strange going on
here. I feel all sorts of things but words would be too much. I had
the pink jersey, my hematocrit level was at 46 percent, and I wake
up to this surprise. I think there's certainly something not quite
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who has twice fought back from serious injury, then
addressed the future. ``I've returned from two big accidents, but
this time, morale-wise, we've touched the bottom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Chambery, Pantani's fellow riders were left shaking their
heads. ``Unbelievable,'' Magnusson said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the one word riders used to sum up their reaction after
the Italian failed a drug test and was not allowed to start the
next to last stage of the Giro he was leading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' said Geert van Bondt, a Belgian with the TVM
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' said Darxiusz Baranowski, a Pole with Banesto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still stunned by the news,'' said Cedric Vasseur, a
Frenchman for the Credit Agricole team who finished 14th here
today. ``This is bad for the whole family of racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, the American leader of the Postal Service team
who dropped out late in the race, said: ``I'm surprised. I like
Pantani. He's an honest guy, an intelligent guy, and that's why I'm
surprised and disappointed. Like all of this, it's bad for the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Thevenet, who won the Tour de France in 1975 and 1977
and now is a television commentator, saw some benefits in the
announcement in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible for the sport but in a strange way it may be
good for the sport,'' Thevenet said. ``This tells all the riders
that no matter how much of a star you are, no matter what race you
are leading, you can be caught and punished if you're using
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one of the riders who quit Saturday's race, Pascal
Derame, a Frenchman with the Postal Service team, said he had been
stunned by the news at first, but then pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be candid, as a Frenchman,'' he said, ``I'm glad this
happened because it shows that it's not just France that's cracking
down on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The French battle, led by the courts and the police, began last
July in Tour de France and resulted in the expulsion of the Festina
team, then top-ranked in the sport. Its nine riders were accused of
the systematic use of illegal performance enhancing drugs, a charge
that six of them later admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of what became known as the Festina Affair,
French authorities have questioned dozens of riders, team officials
and doctors plus French officials in organizations that govern
bicycle racing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some foreign teams have avoided French races since
the season began in February. The Classique des Alpes Saturday, for
example, had a field reduced by about two dozen riders from last
year's edition and the weeklong Dauphine race, a major tune-up for
the Tour de France begins Monday with only 96 riders, about 40
fewer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Absent Sunday from the Classique des Alpes of last year's
winner, Laurent Jalabert, a Frenchman with the ONCE team based on
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wears the blue, white and red jersey of the French
national champion, Jalabert has not ridden a race on native soil
this season. He also refuses to take the quarterly medical
examinations now required of riders with a French license, and so
is ineligible to defend his title later this month and cannot
represent his country in the world championships in October.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
