<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-05 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRIPLE CROWN IS BRIGHTER EVERY PASSING YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ This was back before Charismatic was a Triple
Crown contender, back when he was merely a colt who had almost been
claimed for $62,500.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas called co-owner Bob Lewis and tried to
explain why the colt was worth the oats and the hay and the
supplements they poured into him every day.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas told the owner that he wasn't sure Charismatic was ready
to win the Kentucky Derby or the Preakness. ``But then Wayne said,
`I'm really confident he's a Belmont type of horse,' ' Lewis
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Lewis hung up the phone, he told his wife, Beverly,
``This is one salesman who knows how to pump up another salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who had made his fortune peddling beer to the waiting
world, could relate to Lukas' gift of gab.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's Belmont turned out dismally Saturday as the colt
finished third behind Lemon Drop Kid, and was hobbling after the
finish line. With the colt's health a concern, it was almost
overlooked that racing would not have its first Triple Crown since
Affirmed won in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years proves it is not easy to win those three races
in one frantic springtime. It is one thing to win the Derby at a
mile and 1/4, another to win the Preakness at a mile and 3/16, and
a third to win at a mile and 1/2, to be a Belmont type of horse.
</P>
<P>
   It is a totally different thing to win all three races in one
year, which going into Saturday had happened only 11 times in more
than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert came close the last two years with Silver Charm and
Real Quiet, discovering in June that he did not have a Belmont type
of horse.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas and Baffert really are rivals. Don't believe all the
poppycock about being respectful colleagues. Last year, Lukas found
himself in the same box with Baffert at the Belmont as Real Quiet
tried to hang on for the first Triple Crown in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got it!'' Lukas shouted as Victory Gallop and Real Quiet
pounded across the finish line. ``I thought he did,'' Lukas
recalled this week.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the ``Inquiry'' sign went up, Baffert did not dare
hope because he knew that Victory Gallop had lived up to his name.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Baffert was throwing off verbiage about the Belmont's
being merely the end to a grueling ordeal. That was not true,
either. Winning the Triple Crown was huge, a windfall waiting to
drop on somebody. ``The Triple Crown pulls the average guy in off
the street,'' Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how in 1973 Secretariat ``was on the cover of
Newsweek, Time and Sports Illustrated,'' but he conceded that if
Charismatic won, he would make Sports Illustrated, at best. There
will only be one Secretariat, ever. Still, the long wait had made
the Triple Crown valuable, like a trust fund that has been sitting
there collecting interest.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing has almost none of the cachet it did 40 to 50 years
ago, before television brought Michael Jordan and Wayne Gretzky and
Ken Griffey Jr. into everybody's living rooms in the glorious
springtime.
</P>
<P>
   Racing has slipped backward into a slower way to gamble than
scratching a card at the local stationery store, except for a few
minutes every spring, particularly if there is the potential for a
Triple Crown. ``There are no soft spots these days,'' Lukas said
recently. ``In the '50s and '60s, the horses could prepare all
spring. There was no Breeders Cup in the fall, not as many December
and January races. The style is different now. They run at you
every step of the way. We have to train harder.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the theory that because of the emphasis on speed,
horses are bred too fine, and find it hard to stay healthy for the
longest race, to become a Belmont type of horse. Lukas tried to
portray his colt as an underdog, mostly because Charismatic was
almost lost in a claiming race last February. ``This is the player
who didn't get a full scholarship and had a tough sophomore and
junior year but now he's an all-American,'' said Lukas, who coached
basketball in high school and college.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas added: ``America loves the underdog, the low draft choice
who makes the pros. America wants Rudy to play for Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   That was fine, but Charismatic was now a 2-1 favorite, being
challenged by the trainer who did not win the Triple Crown the last
two years. Lukas said the concept of a bitter rivalry was ``way
overdone,'' and tried to shrug off the insertion of
Silverbulletday. The filly had been held out of the Derby and the
Preakness because Baffert depicted her as not strong enough for the
male field. Now she was here, only the 21st filly to run in the
Belmont, with only two _ Ruthless in 1867 and Tanya in 1905 _
winning it.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert tried to play down the weight of the Triple Crown,
claiming the Derby was the true rush _ ``you forget how you got to
the winner's circle'' _ but he said that by the Belmont, ``you're
just glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you win the Belmont, of course. And the winner of a
Triple Crown just might never be able to recall how he got to the
winner's circle, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
