<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-ART-NYT &LR;      06-05 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMON DROP KID THWARTS INJURED CHARISMATIC IN BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Charismatic, standing on the threshold of
sweeping the Triple Crown, missed his date with history Saturday
when he ran third in the Belmont Stakes behind the long shot Lemon
Drop Kid. And worse, as Charismatic chased the winner across the
finish line, he sustained a cracked bone in his left front ankle
that brought a stunning end to an otherwise memorable day at
Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, ninth in the Kentucky Derby while Charismatic
was winning it at odds of 31-1, skipped the Preakness but came
roaring back in the Belmont Stakes, ridden by Jose Santos. In a
furious rush through the homestretch, he won his first race since
February, scoring by a head over an even longer shot, Vision and
Verse, and ended the dramatic saga of Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke down right after we crossed the wire,'' said Chris
Antley, who rode Charismatic in all three of the Triple Crown
races. ``He gave us a lot. He gave America a lot. But I think he'll
be OK The game goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's defeat was dramatic enough. It marked the third
straight year that a horse had stood on the edge of completing his
sweep of the Triple Crown, only to miss narrowly in the Belmont.
But this time, said Bob Lewis, who owns Charismatic, ``We're
devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley dismounted just after the finish line and Charismatic was
attended to on the track for five minutes before being taken away
in a horse ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Bramlage, a veterinarian from Lexington, Ky., reported
immediately after the race: ``The veterinarians on the track say he
may have cracked a bone in his ankle. They put a splint on it, and
he seems to be handling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday was in the hunt until the quarter pole, but
faded to seventh in her bid to become the first filly to win the
Belmont since 1905.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, who is trained by Scotty Schulhofer, ran the
mile and 1/2 in 2:27 4/5 and paid $61.50 for a $2 bet to win, the
third-highest payoff in Belmont history.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic took his shot at racing history on a resplendently
clear and sunny afternoon with a huge crowd jamming Belmont Park
with great expectations. The Yankees were playing the Mets in
Yankee Stadium and the Knicks were playing the Indiana Pacers in
Madison Square Garden on a day to remember in New York sports. But
at Belmont, the Triple Crown was on the line, one more time.
</P>
<P>
   This was the culmination of the saga that Charismatic had spun
beginning in February, when he ran in a claiming race for $62,500
at Santa Anita and was ignored. Since then, he raced from rags to
riches: fourth in the Santa Anita Derby on April 3, first in the
Lexington Stakes on April 18 with a record-setting performance,
first in the Kentucky Derby on May 1, first in the Preakness Stakes
on May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might overlook this horse, but at your own peril,'' said
his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, who confessed that he, too, had been
fooled by the colt. ``He has improved every time, and he is
legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas had won 12 Triple Crown races going into his day of days,
including six in a row at one point, but he had never swept the
series with one horse.
</P>
<P>
   And he acknowledged that the odds against Charismatic were long:
Only 11 horses had swept the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the
Belmont, three stakes within five weeks at three tracks with three
different surfaces and dimensions, and at three different
distances.
</P>
<P>
   The last to succeed was Affirmed in 1978; since then, no horse
had managed to sweep the series. Six horses had won the Derby and
Preakness but failed in the Belmont since then, two in the last two
years, both trained by Bob Baffert. In 1997, Baffert lost the
Triple Crown when Silver Charm was beaten in the final yards by
Touch Gold, and last year he lost again when Real Quiet was edged
out by a nose by Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way in this year's classics, some prized thoroughbreds
fell by the wayside in the rush to glory: notably Exploit, Vicar,
Cat Thief, General Challenge and Prime Timber. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
