<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBSTER-DEATH-MYSTERY     06-05 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBSTER-DEATH-MYSTERY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALLY, A FATHER-SON SUICIDE, BUT MOBSTER'S DEATH STIRS
DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN FEUER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SADDLE BROOK, N.J. _ There was no note, no sign of illness or
depression, and no apparent motive for suicide. But there was a
folding chair kicked over on the floor, a half-empty bottle of
Johnnie Walker Red nearby and two bodies _ one of them a convicted
gangster _ hanging from a ceiling beam.
</P>
<P>
   It is the type of mystery that mob buffs live for, an aging
wiseguy found dead with his dead son dangling at his side, a
curious brew of suicide and organized crime that many law
enforcement officials are saying just does not feel right.
</P>
<P>
   The story began May 21 when a Saddle Brook police dispatcher
received a frantic phone call from a young woman saying that her
father, Giovanni Ligammari, 60, and her brother, Pietro, 37, had
hanged themselves, face-to-face, in separate nooses, with nylon
packing cord from the basement rafters of the elder man's
two-family home in this affluent Bergen County suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Ligammari was a known figure in organized crime, having
been found guilty of racketeering and conspiracy charges in 1987 in
the so-called Pizza Connection case, in which 31 men were charged
with running a heroin ring from several New York pizza shops. But
his death was ruled a suicide, and the case was officially closed
after a brief investigation, during which his widow and daughter
were never interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the news of the deaths, cynical shop talk
started as veteran organized-crime investigators from as far away
as Rome began clucking their tongues at whether the salty old
Sicilian and his son had really killed themselves. Was it suicide
or something darker? For the moment, not many people are sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smells,'' said one veteran FBI agent who worked on the case
and agreed to speak only if his name was withheld. ``It just
doesn't jibe at all, you know? And I'm not normally a doubting
Thomas. But on this one I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Run down a list of possible motives for suicide and those who
knew the Ligammaris will say that none of them applied.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ligammari lived a quiet pensioner's life in Saddle
Brook, collecting Social Security and drawing income from renting
out the second floor of his well-appointed home, said Frank
Lucianna, his longtime friend and lawyer. He was not poor, not
depressed and, according to the Saddle Brook Police Department, no
longer involved in crime.
</P>
<P>
   In his 40s and 50s, Ligammari was associated with the Bonanno
crime family, the federal authorities said, but was a minor player
in the Pizza Connection case, one of several investors who put up
money for the heroin ring.
</P>
<P>
   He had suffered greatly, both physically and emotionally, during
the eight years he spent in federal prison and got out in 1995, a
troubled man, Lucianna said. But, he added, Ligammari seemed to
have left the painful memories of prison life behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was that hardy, old, tough-guy type from the mountains of
Sicily,'' Lucianna said. ``They both were, and it disturbs the hell
out of me. If you told me John Gotti had committed suicide, I'd be
just as surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Pietro Ligammari lived in Massapequa, N.Y., where, by all
accounts, he led an uneventful life, Lucianna said. Ligammari was
married and had two children. He was never implicated in the Pizza
Connection case or any other crime.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man was under investigation by the federal authorities,
said the U.S. attorney's office in New Jersey. And it was the
Manhattan office of the FBI, which helped prosecute the Pizza
Connection case, that initially looked into their deaths, rather
than the Newark office, only 20 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has left conspiracy theorists studying their
videotapes of ``Goodfellas'' and spinning sinister could-have-beens
late into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call the afternoon the bodies were discovered from one
of our old sources who said they'd actually been killed,'' said one
former prosecutor who worked on the Pizza Connection case. ``But
then I called an FBI guy I know, and he told me that the initial
report was a double suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way,'' he said, ``it's weird. Voluntary suicide or not.
Father and son? Very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in suicide agree. While they say that lovers will
sometimes kill themselves together and parents have been known to
kill their children and then themselves, double suicides involving
fathers and sons are exceedingly rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no other dual pact like this with a father and son,
none,'' said Dr. Andrew Slaby, a professor of clinical psychology
at New York University and a former president of the American
Association of Suicidology. ``It's a truly remarkable case,'' he
said, adding, ``if it's actually a suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Picture the scene, Slaby said: Father and son standing on the
same small chair, facing death, staring into each other's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To choose that mode of exodus,'' he said, ``would mean that
both of them would've had to create the noose and make the decision
to go at the exact same time. It's such a native thing in human
beings to preserve their children's lives that you would have to
posit that both were terribly, psychotically depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan office of the FBI closed its investigation once
the Bergen County Medical Examiner ruled the deaths a double
suicide, said spokesman Joseph Valiquette. And the Saddle Brook
police have never veered from their initial theory that the
Ligammaris killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a double hanging does seem a little far-fetched for a
typical gangland killing. Most mob hits are brazen, gory, public
affairs _ blood operas intended to make the point that next time it
could be you.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, over the last several years, a handful of fringe
characters from the Pizza Connection case have wound up dead.
Whether this is coincidence or a cold dish of revenge, law
enforcement officials who worked on the case have said they are
intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   The first to die was Edward Lino, 48, a reputed captain of the
Gambino crime family, who was pursued but never charged, said
federal prosecutors. He was found shot to death in Brooklyn in
1990, slumped over in the driver's seat of his black Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, police in Montreal discovered the body of
Joseph LoPresti, 44, a Canadian who was investigated as a financier
in the case but was also never charged. LoPresti was shot in the
head execution-style and his body was found wrapped in plastic
beside trash-strewn railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In March, police in New York City found the body of Gerlando
Sciascia, yet a third man who was looked at in connection with the
case but never formally accused. Sciascia's body was discovered
lying on a sidewalk in the Bronx, fully clothed, with four bullets
pumped into the left side of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Giovanni Ligammari's name has been added to the list of
dead Pizza Connection alums. The veteran FBI agent who worked on
the case said Ligammari may have tried to re-enter the narcotics
trade and run afoul of its new leadership, although the agent
conceded there was no evidence to support this theory.
</P>
<P>
   Another agent from the case, who also spoke on the condition
that his name not be used, said the taint of death surrounding the
case should be chalked up to no more than the occupational hazards
of a career in organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the former prosecutor said the arrests in 1984 put on hold a
vicious internecine war, which could have heated up again now that
time had passed and defendants were slowly starting to get out of
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a group that had a lot of conflicts,'' he said. ``A
lot of people were very upset by this trial because they felt that
there were too many people compromised and too many trusted people
who gave out information.''
</P>
<P>
   While none of the dead men, including Ligammari, provided
information to the government, the agent said, the fact that some
of them were not indicted or went to prison only for short terms
could have been enough to anger the wrong people. ``There's clearly
something going on here that we don't understand,'' he added. ``But
whether it's something old or something new is definitely hard to
say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
