<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      06-05 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF UPSETS PEEVISH HINGIS TO WIN FRENCH OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On the verge of being undermined in a bizarre and
bad-spirited French Open final by Steffi Graf, a war horse she had
dismissed as being past her prime a year ago, top-seeded Martina
Hingis delivered an underhand serve on Graf's first match point
Saturday. The underhanded move won Hingis a temporary reprieve. But
it was only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, desperate to stay alive at the only Grand Slam
tournament she has never won and frazzled after blowing two chances
to serve for the title in the second set, tried the same tactic on
Graf's second match point. The move provoked a crescendo of hissing
from the crowd as she flubbed the serve and ran like a chastened
child to the chair umpire. When she complained that the crowd's
noise had made it impossible for her to deliver her trick serve,
Graf, hitherto immune to Hingis' histrionics, joined the
contretemps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we just play tennis, OK,'' snapped Graf. So they did, and
Graf, appearing in her ninth _ and last _ French Open final just
nine days before her 30th birthday, shocked Hingis with a 4-6, 7-5,
6-2 comeback victory. She thus captured her 22d slam singles
championship, an achievement that left her just two titles short of
Margaret Smith Court's record 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely the last time I play here,'' said Graf, who
also decided after 16 French Opens that this match was a worthy
retirement announcement, at least from the clay of Roland Garros.
``The memory should be the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   With Graf glaring at her from across the net, Hingis served a
conventional second service, a puff ball of a serve. Graf muscled
back a return that forced Hingis' parting error, a backhand that
looped beyond bounds 2 hours 25 minutes after the final, delayed an
hour by stormy weather, finally began.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels amazing; I feel French,'' said Graf about the warm
embrace she received from the same gallery that made Hingis feel
like an alien. ``This is by far the biggest, the most unexpected
win I've ever had. It was one of the craziest matches ever; it had
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It had a little too much crowd involvement for Hingis. ``A
miracle would have to happen for me to win that match,'' she said.
She had been unequal, she said, to the task of fighting Graf and
the fans. ``I let it get to me.'' In fact, Hingis was one reprimand
from a default after she received a racquet abuse warning and a
point penalty in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, instead of claiming the only missing link to her
slam resume, Hingis had to settle for being second best at the
French for the second time. Too, her record against Graf, the only
player to provoke humility in her, dropped to 0-4 in slams and 2-7
over all.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the top-ranked Swiss player vowed to return and
prove that Roland Garros, an event she won in the juniors as a
12-year-old, belongs in her slam collection. ``I don't give up
until I have this one also,'' said Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   But she did give up Saturday, once she trailed by 3-0 in the
third set. ``At this stage I had nothing to play,'' Hingis said,
``she was too strong.''
</P>
<P>
   As Graf raised her arms in celebration, Hingis gathered her
gear, left the court in tears, and had to be dragged back by her
mother and coach, Melanie Molitor, to the awards presentation.
Hingis later said she wouldn't have come back if her mother hadn't
been there to make her observe loser's protocol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in anything else like that ever before,'' Graf
said about the odd twists and turns of this final, which featured
various bursts of petulance and insubordination and ended with both
combatants in tears.
</P>
<P>
   All smiles when the match began, Hingis allowed her mental
circuitry to go haywire in the middle set. Rattled that she not
only lost the second set but had to listen to derisive hoots from
14,000 Graf-loving center court fans, she suffered a meltdown
against the impassive Graf. Up 3-2 in the second set, she proceeded
to lose six straight games before holding for 1-3 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The querulous tone of the match was reflected early on. Hingis,
after taking a 2-0 second-set lead, tried to make the officials pay
for their mistake when they called a forehand drive long in the
next game. Hingis stared in disbelief when her down-the-line
forehand was ruled out, stamped her feet when the chair umpire,
Anne Lasserre, checked the mark and agreed with the call, and
crossed over to Graf's side of the court, a territorial taboo, to
reinforce her cause. Hingis not only lost the point, she was
penalized a point for venturing into her opponent's domain.
</P>
<P>
   Already running a distant second in the crowd's sympathies,
Hingis' behavior was met with a cascade of boos, jeers and
whistles. The partisanship unsettled her as the set wore on and
Graf coolly fought her way back into the match.
</P>
<P>
   Graf held for 4-3 and almost gained a break point for 5-3 on a
wildly improvisational point where both players scrambled between
the net and the baseline. But Graf, after sending a forehand lob to
the baseline, turned what should have been a point-ending overhead
tap into a netted overhead heartbreaker. Hingis won the game, and
then broke Graf with another of her patented down-the-line backhand
arrows to go up 5-4. Now, she had the chance to serve for her first
French Open title _ and sixth Grand Slam title over all.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf wasn't in the mood to give away a championship, not at
this sunset stage of her career, and she broke the teen-ager to
level at 5-5. The German held for 6-5, and with a faint smile on
her face as she watched a Hingis forehand veer wide of the
sideline, she broke Hingis again to claim the second set, 7-5, and
even the match.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the villain proved so stressful to Hingis that she
requested a third-set bathroom break at 0-1 in order to change her
clothes, her hair and her attitude. But Graf's momentum remained
unchanged, and a 22d Grand Slam crown all but hovered above her
head as Hingis faded and faltered.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena Williams, seeded ninth, reached their first
Grand Slam doubles final as a team Saturday with a 6-4, 6-1
demolition of 12th-seeded Lindsay Davenport and Mary Pierce,
becoming the third set of sisters to contest a women's doubles
final at a slam. They meet second-seeded Martina Hingis and Anna
Kournikova in the final on Sunday. ... Peter Graf, who had taken a
distant position in his daughter's life even before he spent 15
months in jail on tax evasion charges, was in attendance at a
tournament for the first time in five years but did not sit in the
friends' box with Graf's mother, Heidi, and her coach, Heinz
Gunthardt.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
