<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HIGHRISE-RENTS-REA     06-05 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HIGHRISE-RENTS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: AS NEW YORK BUILDINGS RISE, SO DO THEIR RENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN S. OSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Money was not the main problem for Andre Abucham, a
23-year-old from Brazil, when he went apartment shopping in
Manhattan a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is working in a training program at Salomon Smith
Barney for under $30,000 a year, Abucham was able to rent a
one-bedroom midtown apartment at the Sheffield on 57th Street off
Eighth Avenue for $3,000 a month. His father, who owns a civil
engineering company in Sao Paulo, is helping with the rent.
</P>
<P>
   If builders had to rely on parental largesse to help tenants
rent in any of the new luxury buildings rising in midtown Manhattan
these days, the renting process would be slow indeed. But they do
benefit from the prevalence of two-income households when they seek
rents that stretch the levels previously obtained in the locations
of some of the new projects.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation that it can attract higher-income professionals
has entered into the calculations of Rose Associates in launching a
residential project called the Madison Belvedere, a building that
is a departure for its immediate neighborhood in size as well as
market ambition. It is a 48-story tower in the middle of the block
between 29th and 28th Streets, east of Fifth Avenue. The entrance
will be on 29th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a transitional neighborhood between the Flatiron
District and midtown,'' said Rose Associates president Adam Rose.
He said he refers to it facetiously as NoFlaWeMu (north of the
Flatiron District and west of Murray Hill). ``We believe it will
eventually fill in with other new buildings,'' he said. Commercial
brokers would call the area the Midtown South office district, and
in fact office growth has helped give zip to the residential
market.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Associates has already found that it is getting rents
averaging $47 a square foot per year (about $2,450 to $2,750 a
month for a one-bedroom apartment) upon vacancy for the handful of
rental apartments it still owns a few blocks away at Madison Green,
the condominium it built in 1983 in what was then the untested
market at 23rd Street off Madison Square Park, now called the
Flatiron District.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the company will go on the market at $47 to $48 a
square foot at the Madison Belvedere in July. Bringing in a
``high-end'' apartment with expensive finishes, Rose will offer
one-bedroom apartments in a rental range of $2,400 to $3,200 a
month. The one-bedrooms _ in six varieties, with and without
balconies _ account for 54 percent of the apartments. The 79
two-bedroom apartments will rent from $3,800 to $5,500 a month, and
the 99 studios from $1,850 to $2,350.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Associates is by no means alone in the '90s in finding a
slightly offbeat location for a new residential building and then
attempting to demonstrate that it can command rents that are higher
than the norm in the area.
</P>
<P>
   With the healthy economic climate that has prevailed over the
last few years accompanied by a strong stock market, the developers
have been successful so far. Yet there are voices of caution as the
inventory of new buildings reaches the market in a steady flow, and
price resistance is reported by management groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Zucker Organization has made a specialty of choosing
locations where major builders have not ventured. Two recent
examples are Soho Court, at Elizabeth and Houston Street, which
came on the market three years ago, and CD 280, on East Second
Street between Avenues C and D.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company has gone into construction in another unusual
location, Broadway between Worth Street and Catherine Lane, two
blocks north of Chambers Street. It will be a 16-story building
with 147 apartments plus stores, and a parking garage for 114 cars,
for which a special permit was obtained. The main entrance will be
on Worth Street. Renting will start in February or March, with
occupancy in 10 or 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The percentage of people who can afford to pay $45 a square
foot is very small,'' said Donald Zucker, principal in the company.
``Once you're down to $40, apartments are like hen's teeth.'' At
$45 a square foot a year, a typical one-bedroom, with 700 square
feet of space, would rent for $2,650 a month. At $40 a square foot,
it would rent for $2,300 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of new buildings coming on the market,''
Zucker said. ``We may get back to the point where we're selling
condominiums again.'' Selling rather than renting is a last resort
for an investment building company, whose business is to hold
property longterm and build up equity for future projects. But in
an overbuilt market, it is the path many builders take.
</P>
<P>
   The Brodsky Organization concentrated on the Lincoln Center area
when it began building a large inventory of rental apartments. Now
it runs a total of 2,200 rentals in four properties in the area.
Its latest midtown project is One Columbus Place, with 729
apartments in two towers that share a large lobby, between 58th and
59th Streets at Ninth Avenue. It opened in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Rotkoff, director of leasing for the Brodsky Organization,
said she handled about 400 re-rentals a year in Brodsky buildings.
Typical rents for a vacancy at present are about $1,800 for a
studio apartment, $2,450 for a one-bedroom and $3,900 for a
two-bedroom. It works out to about $41 a square foot a year. At One
Columbus Place rents are somewhat higher, but ``it's hard to get
$45 a foot,'' Ms. Rotkoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In another location, the Resnick Organization said that it
completed the rent-up of the 440 market-rate apartments in the
Gershwin, at Eighth Avenue and 50th Street, only this month. The
process took 11 months and the average rent is $45 a square foot
per year, said Scott Resnick, executive managing director. ``We
have a substantial percentage of singles with incomes over
$100,000,'' Resnick said.
</P>
<P>
   And Glenwood Management, builder of the recently completed
Paramount Tower at 240 E. 39th St., says that its 464 apartments
were ``99 percent rented'' as of May, seven months after the rental
program began. Apartments tend to be larger on average than in most
new luxury buildings, so that rents, which the company says have
averaged $46 a square foot per year, tend to be higher on a dollar
basis per apartment than in most other new buildings in east or
west midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Most rents ranged from $2,800 to $5,000 a month, said Gary
Jacob, executive vice president of Glenwood Management, and most
tenants have incomes between $150,000 and $250,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Figures worked up by the Real Estate Board of New York in May
show that there are 4,000 new market-rate apartments under
construction in Manhattan for completion this year, the highest
figure since 1989, when there were 4,248 completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got 4,000 luxury rental apartments coming on the
market, you of course have got to be a little bit concerned whether
you're going to find all the tenants you need to rent them out,''
said Steven Spinola, president of the Real Estate Board.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, the tenant of a one-bedroom apartment renting at
$45 a square foot a year ($2,625 a month for 700 square feet)
probably should have an income of at least $150,000 a year, Spinola
said. This is a recommended rent-to-income ratio of about 21
percent, far lower than the standard 30 percent used elsewhere in
the country but an acknowledgment that Manhattan living, housing
costs aside, is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stretch,'' conceded Margaret Kuczynski, who moved in
January with her husband, Edward, and two children _ Justin, 17,
and Alena, 11 _ into a $2,850-a-month apartment at Le Rivage, Rose
Associates' reconstruction of a former office building at 21 West
St. in lower Manhattan. ``But we've been so transient until now
that I hope I die here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kuczynski and her husband, a medical researcher in
obstetrics and gynecology at New York University, had been living
part-time in a Manhattan rental for four years before they moved to
West Street. It took them two and a half years to sell a house they
owned in Coconut Grove, Fla., where they lived when Dr. Kuczynski
was working in Florida in the early '90s. The family has joined a
home-school group to educate their children at home in cooperation
with educators and other parents.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 West St. apartments are generally larger than Rose's
midtown apartments, and they also have unusually high ceilings.
Prices are considerably lower on a square-foot basis than they are
in midtown, reflecting both competition from other buildings and
the deep tax abatement that the city put in effect to stimulate
residential conversions of obsolete office buildings in the
financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Apartments at Le Rivage went on the market last year at about
$35 a square foot a year ($2,550 for a 900-square-foot one-bedroom
and $3,650 for a 1,150-square-foot two-bedroom), and rose to $37 a
square foot toward the end of the nine-month renting period ($2,700
for the one-bedroom and $3,850 for the two-bedroom), Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   The financial standards that new renters must meet reflect the
developers' sensitivity to the affordability issue. Besides needing
a good credit record, incoming tenants generally must show an
annual income of anywhere from 40 to 50 times the monthly rent,
with different managements holding to different standards. Rose
Associates is using the 48 multiple, said Jack Levy, senior
managing director for rentals and sales.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the renter of a $2,745-a-month 725-square-foot
one bedroom on the 30th floor of the Madison Belvedere, for
example, would have to show an annual income of $130,000. To rent a
1,250-square-foot two-bedroom apartment on the 42d floor for $5,075
a month would require an income of $243,000.
</P>
<P>
   Levy presides as rental director over an inventory of 3,000 Rose
Associates apartments, and witnesses a turnover of about 600
apartments a year. Almost all the new renters of two-bedroom
apartments have incomes over $180,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, almost all the new renters come in as free-market
rather than rent-stabilized tenants, usually because the building's
10-year Section 421a tax abatement has already expired. In pre-1985
Section 421a buildings, apartments are deregulated when the
regulated tenant moves out. In post-1985 Section 421a buildings,
apartments are deregulated after 10 years even with the regulated
tenant in place.
</P>
<P>
   In buildings that were converted to co-ops or condominiums, all
rental apartments are decontrolled after a vacancy, and in
pure-rental buildings they are decontrolled if the first rent after
vacancy exceeds $2,000. Two-thirds of the Rose Associates rental
inventory is now free market, and one-third remains
rent-stabilized, Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   On average, 20 percent of the free-market apartments become
vacant every year, and probably three-quarters of the re-rentals
each year are of apartments that were already deregulated before
the vacancy. ``People's lives change,'' Levy said. ``Some people
are sharing and they later want their own home. Other people decide
to buy an apartment, or a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the issue of affordability, the Madison Belvedere
represents architecturally a style of building that is gradually
being phased out in Manhattan _ the straight tower behind a
street-level plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The Madison Belvedere is on a 21,000-square-foot lot in a zone
that with no bonuses would have allowed only 220,000 square feet of
construction on the building lot itself. But the project got a
bonus for its 12,700-square-foot public plaza (though not the full
20 percent that zoning allows, since that large a plaza was
impractical) and also additional development rights from
neighboring properties _ the Carlton Hotel and two other buildings.
It also got a bonus of 9,300 square feet for including four
apartments for low-income tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting 48-story project has 348,000 gross square feet of
space and is built to a floor-area ratio, or FAR, of 11 on its
zoning lot, less than the 12 FAR allowable. The floor-area ratio of
the project to the property on which it stands, however, is 16.6.
</P>
<P>
   The architect is the firm of Schuman Lichtenstein Claman Efron,
with James Davison, a senior partner, as design architect. The
building's landscaped public plaza, facing 28th Street, has been
designed by Thomas Balsley of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the last of its genre,'' said Davison. The ``tower
in the park'' style, in conjunction with unrestricted transfers of
development rights from adjacent lots, sometimes lends itself well
to extremely tall buildings, sometimes resembling an intruder in
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The tallest of all has gone into construction on First Avenue
between 47th to 48th Streets north of the United Nations complex.
The Trump Organization is building a condominium there that is to
be 861 feet tall to the top of its squared-off superstructure. It
will have 72 floors, many of them with ceiling heights of 10 or 13
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Rose, chairman of the City Planning Commission (and Adam
Rose's cousin), alluded to this project in a speech last April in
which he condemned the ``trail of exceptions, caveats and
interpretive gymnastics'' that tower-in-the-park zoning had
spawned. He said that a new set of bulk regulations would soon be
proposed to respond to this problem, while still allowing zoning to
provide for growth and change.
</P>
<P>
   The Madison Belvedere will be 454 feet tall from street level to
the main roof (and 554 feet to the top of its decorative crown).
Among new buildings at or near completion, only Glenwood
Management's Paramount Tower is in its height class. It is 51
stories high _ 526 feet to the main roof and 567 feet to the top of
its superstructure. For zoning purposes, ``height of the building''
traditionally means the height to the main roof.
</P>
<P>
   For Rose Associates, the $150 million Madison Belvedere marks
another step in what might be called an overhaul of the residential
inventory. The company undertook a major co-op conversion program
in the early '90s, converting nine buildings and selling, in the
first two years, about 600 apartments for about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion effort required new investment in old buildings
and ultimately cost as much as it brought in during those years,
said Rose, who led the campaign with his cousin Amy Rose, a
managing director of the company. Rose Associates has kept the
management of all these buildings, even though they are now
controlled by the residents. It has continued to sell
renter-occupied apartments upon vacancy of a regulated tenant, but
still holds 900 apartments in these buildings. ``The cash flow from
our ongoing sales fuels our new development,'' said Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, 40, succeeded his uncle, Daniel Rose, now vice chairman of
the company, as president last December. His father, Frederick
Rose, continues as chairman, taking a hands-on role in new
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
