<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME COOKING HELPS KEEP KANSAS TOWN ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOLDIER, Kan. _ The sign set up in the middle of Main Street
here had a simple, chalked message:
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIAL MEALS
</P>
<P>
   8 - 4
</P>
<P>
   FREE WILL
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, on Memorial Day weekend, that sign, the 600
people it drew and the resultant profit accounted for about 6
percent of this town's annual budget -- $1,500 added to $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's comparable to Kansas City, Mo., with its $881 million
yearly budget, having citizens pass the hat for about $52 million
and hand it over with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   But then this was Soldier, population 200, and semifamous
hereabouts for the victuals it offers up on Memorial Day weekend at
its white-painted community center.
</P>
<P>
   The food? All you wanted. Chili dogs and sandwiches, salads and
fruits, cinnamon rolls and cookies, and lemonade, coffee and tea.
Plus tables covered with pies and cakes. Name a kind and it was
there.
</P>
<P>
   The cost? Those eating decided. That was what ``free will''
meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one man come in who'd brought a whole flock of people,
'' said Lena Baxter, who helps put on the get-together. ``He left
$150. Said it was a bargain at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one year we had a whole bunch of bikers. Nice folks.
Happy to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, from as far away as Nebraska; Wichita, Kan.; Kansas City,
Mo.; and Oklahoma, leave $5 or $10 and go away more than satisfied.
Little wonder. It's all home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Soldier's growing renown as a gastronomic destination started in
1981 when Karl Biester died. Biester had loved the little city park
next to the community hall. Members of a women's civic group called
the Soldieretta Unit decided to help his widow, Lucile Biester,
raise money for a modest shelter house with a table where people
could visit, maybe have a picnic, get out of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that started it,'' said Baxter. ``That first year we just
made a few hundred dollars. But that was enough. We got it built.''
</P>
<P>
   That shelter became a catalyst. Pretty soon another civic
organization, the So and So Club, was involved. Then the Lions
Club. People found out they could do something.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Lynn Reschick, a farmer who calls Soldier ``a Walton
kind of place,'' it was about time. That there was anybody left at
all in Soldier as the 20th century entered its last decades seemed
to defy common sense.
</P>
<P>
   In 1874, grasshoppers denuded the crops. In 1883, a tornado
ripped the town to shreds. In 1915, a disastrous flood on nearby
Soldier Creek ravaged the town. In 1934, a fire set by a faulty
kerosene stove consumed all but two or three businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it was some fire,'' said Henry Pugh, now 86. ``Burned down
almost the whole town. Both sides of Main Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the bank shutting its doors during the Depression,
young people leaving for big cities, the old Kansas Central
Railroad abandoning its tracks, and the closing of the schools with
consolidation in 1969, and what was left in Soldier was a
tavern/lunch counter, a feed store and a post office.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, said Reschick, the two churches -- Methodist and Christian
-- that have always been here.
</P>
<P>
   Right from the first, those planning the meals had noticed
something about Memorial Day or, as some still call it, Decoration
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Every year people came back to Soldier and the surrounding
communities -- Delia, Bucks Grove, Circleville, Whiting and
Netawaka -- to tend the graves in a half-dozen little cemeteries
where their loved ones are.
</P>
<P>
   Not just a few came -- hundreds showed up.
</P>
<P>
   They brought flowers. Decorating the graves would start Thursday
and proceed through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That custom is still alive in 1999. The Soldier cemetery last
weekend was carpeted with flowers from one end to another. It
looked like a kaleidoscope.
</P>
<P>
   And while some who came were young, the majority were middle-age
and older. Some used canes; a few needed walkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we had all these people coming home,'' said Baxter, whose
husband ran Soldier's long-departed gas station for years. ``They
needed something to eat. And what they really needed was a place
with facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the restaurant and tavern, but it's not open on
holidays. And Holton is 17 miles. People want to stay here, you
know, to visit, to see people they haven't talked to in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we thought, why not have food and raise some money?''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the 1934 fire played a part. When Soldier's City Hall
burned, there was a modicum of insurance money. With it and what
other money could be scraped up, residents built a large community
hall that could double as a place for City Council meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Architecturally, the building on the east side of Main was
undistinguished -- flat-fronted, plain, but it was amazingly deep.
There was lots of room inside, perfect for a sit-down dinner and a
hedge against bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   The flooring was hardwood, a seeming extravagance now but an
absolute necessity in the mid-1930s. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``People went to dances then,'' Pugh said. ``That was what we
did for entertainment. I remember the Saturday afternoon we
finished, and the floor on one side still lacked about a foot of
meeting the wall. Didn't matter; we had a big dance that night
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, with the passage of more than half a century,
the community hall showed some wear and tear. Its rehabilitation
became the focus of those putting on the Memorial Day meals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the hall has been rewired,
air-conditioned and painted; a new furnace was installed; and the
restrooms were redone. That may not sound like much for big-city
people, said Baxter, but without the meals it wouldn't have been
done at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is amazing,'' said Ida Nadeau, Soldier's
mayor. ``I'm a very organized person. Everything has to be
scheduled, planned for and figured out in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the meals, they're running around, asking who's going to
do this and who'll bring that, who'll be behind the counter and how
many pies do they need. It goes on like that right up to the edge,
and then you're sure it'll be a disaster. And then, somehow, it all
falls into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau said that besides the money raised for the town, always a
worry in rural Kansas, the Memorial Day activity kept the residents
on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just down from here we had a lot with a building on it that
was falling down, just a ruin,'' she said. ``That was two years
ago, and people who came for Memorial Day noticed. Didn't complain.
But there was talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we'd gotten the building torn down, but the lot
still looked raw. People noticed that, too. This year the lot is
all cleaned up and graded, and people have really said how nice the
town looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau says those who come back don't exert pressure. But, she
adds, there's a certain truth in the old saw about how people seem
to spiff things up when company is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if they're staying to eat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
