<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICTIM-RECOVERY-KAN &LR;      06-05 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIM-RECOVERY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE WINS OUT FOR TEEN HIT BY TRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Live or die _ it was the choice of a lifetime
for Joy Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The quandary came to the teen-ager late in the day or maybe the
night of April 13 _ she does not really remember, because of the
pain and shock and the bright lights she could not see and the
chatter she could not understand.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment in this honor student's young life, dying did not
seem to be a terrible thing.
</P>
<P>
   A train had struck a car carrying her and four friends home from
Belton High School. The crash punctured both her lungs and
fractured seven ribs. She was bleeding internally. Her left leg was
broken. Her eyes were black.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I had to do was let myself go...just take one step...it
was that close,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange now to think about it, but...I know it would have
been OK for me to die that day.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes, essentially, a fork in the road. Had it been her
choice alone, she might not have been around weeks later to sit in
her living room in her family's rural Cass County home and tell
this story.
</P>
<P>
   But in a blurry place just beneath where doctors worked to save
her life, Joy thought of the parents who gave her life and the
babies she might someday bear.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents tell a story about how love and prayer can pass
through hospital walls and find a way into a young girl's soul.
</P>
<P>
   When Joy finally awoke, her father was at her side. She did not
tell him about her journey or how far she had gone. His look told
her he probably already knew.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Joy used sign language _ which she had learned while
performing in a school production of ``The Miracle Worker'' _ to
ask about the four other teens in the car.
</P>
<P>
   They were OK, he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Joy then asked about her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's asleep on a couch in the waiting room,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   Joy signed: ``Is she comfortable?''
A nervous day
</P>
<P>
   When Joy Jackson tells how the train looked that day, she points
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just...right there,'' she said. ``Big and tall, like a
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, April 13 was a nervous day for Joy, a sophomore at
Belton High School. She _ a budding photographer _ had a job
interview at 3:30 p.m. at a portrait studio in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there after school would be tight. To give herself a few
extra minutes, Joy hitched a ride home with friends. There were
five teens in the car: Elizabeth Aldridge, 15; Catherine Smothers,
15; Melissa Schult, 16; and the driver, Michael Walker, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Most lived in a rural Cass County subdivision just off Holmes
Road.
</P>
<P>
   The youths were talking school gossip when the car slowed nearly
to a stop at the crossing on 183rd Street near Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   That's when somebody screamed. Joy Jackson, riding in the front
passenger seat, saw the train just before impact.
</P>
<P>
   The northbound freight picked up the car and swung it 360
degrees before slamming into it a second time.
</P>
<P>
   One girl was knocked to the trunk. The teens scrambled from the
car. Melissa and a neighbor who had run to the scene pulled Joy
from the burning vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The car soon exploded.
</P>
<P>
   After investigating the accident, authorities said the rail
crossing, marked only with crossbucks, was dangerous because of the
lay of the land and spring weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Cass County, Kansas City Southern Railway and the
Missouri Department of Transportation visited the site recently.
They will decide whether to close the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Mills, a Cass County commissioner, said Friday that the
county might consider installing stop signs at all rail crossings
that lack lights and arms.
</P>
<P>
   `She looked so bad'
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jackson, a computer-software contractor, was fidgety that
day at work. He knew his daughter had the job interview and was
nervous about her driving on the wet roads.
</P>
<P>
   He called home a little after 3 p.m., but Joy was not there.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, she still had not arrived.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:45 p.m. Joy's brother told him there had been an accident.
He knew no details but told his father to call another parent who
was at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   A Cass County deputy took the phone and told Jackson that Joy
had been critically injured and taken by helicopter to St. Joseph
Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jackson called his wife before he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy has been in an accident,'' he told her, his voice
breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Jackson, who worked in a doctor's office, fainted and
dropped to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When they saw Joy in the hospital's emergency room, her face was
bloody, cut and bruised. Air escaping from her punctured lungs had
swollen her body. A respirator kept her breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes were black _ and fluttering.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked so bad, I didn't know if she would make it,'' Brian
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the waiting room, Marie Jackson heard an erroneous
news report that one of the teens in the accident had died.
</P>
<P>
   She did an accounting of those in the car _ and decided the
fatality must be Joy.
</P>
<P>
   She ran down the hall and barged into the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come in here!'' someone yelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she alive _ I have to know!'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Jackson, yes, she's alive. We're working on her. You have
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   For eight hours the parents, along with friends and family,
prayed as doctors worked to stabilize Joy.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksons wanted good news. The doctors would say they were
doing what they could.
</P>
<P>
   Joy is the couple's middle child. Alan is 22, Jonathan is 14.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, in the quiet of night, Brian Jackson pondered life
without his daughter. What would her death do to his family? How
would it change his own life? He wasn't sure he could recover.
</P>
<P>
   He knew she was in great pain, and wondered whether she would
give up.
</P>
<P>
   He asked God to give her strength to fight and to let her know
that too many people would suffer if they lost her.
</P>
<P>
   It was after midnight when doctors finally reported she was
stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her later that God spared my life that night, too,''
Brian Jackson said.
No regrets
</P>
<P>
   Joy Jackson is convinced she is alive today because she made a
conscious decision to live.
</P>
<P>
   The three weeks or so in the hospital, including 10 days in
intensive care, were not fun. She faces still more surgery and
weeks of therapy on her injured leg.
</P>
<P>
   She never made it back to school this year, except for a brief
appearance on the last day. Friends do not call as often as she
would like, and she sometimes feels left out.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot run or play the sports she loves.
</P>
<P>
   A train whistle scares her.
</P>
<P>
   But she certainly has no regrets about her choice. In fact, she
has a higher value for life now, especially little things such as
taking a shower, walking or sleeping on her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``And just doing this,'' she said one day last week.
</P>
<P>
   She was sitting in a recliner and looking out the window toward
trees and lawn. A breeze rustled her hair.
</P>
<P>
   Maxie, the family dog, lay in her lap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEEPING-SABBATH-KAN &LR;      06-05 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEPING-SABBATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BUSINESSES KEEPING THE SABBATH HOLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A small but growing contingent of businesses
is deciding to keep the Sabbath holy.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby Lobby, a chain of arts and crafts stores, is risking an
estimated $100 million in sales this year by closing its stores on
Sundays to give employees a day off for family time and worship.
</P>
<P>
   Seven area Hobby Lobby stores started closing on Sunday on
Mother's Day, May 9. About 350 area employees are affected by the
change, which the company announced to shoppers through ads and
signs on its store doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give this day back to our employees and
customers,'' said Bill Hane, vice president for advertising at
Hobby Lobby headquarters in Oklahoma City. ``The company is based
on Christian principles and honoring the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobby Lobby is not alone. The national Chick-fil-A chain closes
all its stores Sundays, as does the Franklin Covey Co. chain. A
Godfather's Pizza in Liberty, Mo., also closes Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend closing to observe the Sabbath is not limited to stores
reflecting the Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   When Harvey Jacobson opened a kosher grocery nine years ago,
Jacobsons' Kosher Foods in Prairie Village, Kan., he decided to
keep the Jewish Sabbath holy by closing on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the grocery business Saturday was the big day; there was no
way you would close,'' Jacobson said. ``But in the Jewish religion
work is not permitted on Saturdays. After seven days a week, it's a
pleasure. It's my God-given day off.''
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the company has decided to swim against the
capitalistic stream and risk sacrificing profit in the name of
principle.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, such closings also help businesses attract
employees in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it a lot,'' said Angela Hill, who has worked at Hobby
Lobby for two-and-a-half years. ``I go to church and get to be with
my family. It's a day we're all home together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Farmer, a Hobby Lobby customer from Overland Park, Kan.,
likes the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to spend Sunday with our family, not shopping,''
Farmer said. ``And I kind of admire them for having some values.''
</P>
<P>
   Some retail experts say that closing on Sundays will cost sales
and customer good will.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Melaniphy, president of Melaniphy &AMP; Associates, a market
analyst and site selection company in Chicago, said: ``There might
be some public relations to be earned in Salt Lake City, but they
don't have much to gain in Chicago, Los Angeles or New York. Sunday
is a day when people have time to shop. The loss is greater than
the savings. Sales have gone up at Hobby Lobby's competitors since
the Sunday closings.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of competing companies, such as Michaels, which
has five area locations, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that Sunday has become a big shopping day _
malls are open fewer hours Sunday but draw more customers an hour
than on Saturday, the week's busiest day _ but Hobby Lobby and
others say they are winning over customers by embracing a
17th-century idea.
</P>
<P>
   Blue laws, so called because they were written on blue paper,
were the means by which the Puritan colonies restricted nearly all
Sunday retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those laws remained in effect until the late 1960s and
early 1970s, when state legislatures began phasing them out or
turning the decisions over to counties.
</P>
<P>
   Car dealerships in many markets still are closed Sundays.
Missouri's blue laws still prohibit the sale of motor vehicles on
Sundays. Although they are not required by law to do so, about 75
percent of Kansas dealerships in the area also are closed Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   It is also common for mom-and-pop operations to be closed
Sundays to give the owners a break. The Hawthorne Plaza shopping
center in Overland Park, where about half of 40 operations are
closed Sundays, is a good example. Most are locally owned and
operated.
</P>
<P>
   Most shopping centers require tenants to keep regular mall
hours, which include Sunday hours. Slim profit margins and
increased competition lead many stores to offer daily service.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-fil-A, the fast-food chain based in Atlanta, has refused
to open on Sunday, even though most of its stores are in malls.
Shopping centers such as Topeka's West Ridge Mall allow Chick-fil-A
to close Sundays because its sales for a six-day week often are
higher than sales at other food court operations open seven days a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a common practice when we opened in 1946 to close
Sundays, but what's unique is that we continued the practice,''
said Don Perry, spokesman for Chick-fil-A, which has more than 840
locations and reported sales of $799 million in 1998. The chain
does not have any Kansas City area locations.
</P>
<P>
   Truett Cathy, Chick-fil-A's founder, grew up in a poor,
hard-working family and always looked forward to rest and worship
on Sundays. He wanted the same benefit for his employees when he
opened his first Dwarf House restaurant near Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're introducing Christian principles into the workplace, and
we're blessed as a result,'' Perry said. ``We've had sales
increases for 31 years, and for the last five or six years we've
had double-digit sales increases.''
</P>
<P>
   As a privately held company, Hobby Lobby has more leeway to
decide its operating hours. The company has slowly introduced
Sunday closing so the financial effect would not be felt at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sales aren't our primary goal,'' Hane said. ``It's a
matter of principle, not profit. We're one of the fastest-growing
and most-profitable hobby stores, and we work very, very hard at
what we do. But we're here to honor God.''
</P>
<P>
   Customer calls have been 10-to-1 in favor of the change,
although some customers have complained about having their normal
shopping pattern interrupted, Hane said.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby Lobby said that Kansas City sales had increased since the
Sunday closings started and that the company expected to reach its
goal of $1 billion in sales in 2001. Part of the company's sales
help support several ministries, including Bible distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Another area business closed on Sundays is the Godfather's Pizza
in Liberty, thought to be the only restaurant in that chain to
close on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible makes it very clear that it's the Lord's day and he
will bless you for it,'' said David Crowdus, who owns the
restaurant with his wife, Kathy.
</P>
<P>
   While other Godfather's locations post their busiest days from
Friday through Sunday, the busiest days at the Liberty Godfather's
have shifted to Thursday through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday closing cost the restaurant a recent order of 200
pizzas for a graduation party. Sales, however, have increased more
than 300 percent since the couple bought what was a struggling
corporate-owned store in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Franklin Covey Co. closes its 125 retail stores on Sunday,
including two in the Kansas City area. It has built its business on
helping people set priorities with day planners and other
organizational tools.
</P>
<P>
   People juggle different roles _ spouse, parent, employee,
volunteer _ that they have to fit into seven days, said Debra Lund,
spokeswoman for Franklin Covey in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are searching to find some kind of balance between work
and home,'' Lund said. ``Sunday is a great day for retail, but we
wanted to give them one day when they didn't have to focus on
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The day off pays off tenfold, Lund said, because employees are
more refreshed and dedicated when they return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby Lobby's Hane agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's driving our performance is good customer service,'' he
said. ``Sunday is one of the worst days for customer service,
because no one is in a good mood about working on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the retail experts who frown upon Sunday closings say the
practice could help businesses attract and retain top employees in
a tight labor market. Unemployment in the Kansas City area recently
has been about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment rate is so low it's hard to get anyone in
your door to apply for a job,'' Crowdus said. ``Then to find good,
reliable workers is even harder. Closing Sundays is unusual,
especially for the restaurant business. So this is wonderful for
our kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
