<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-REDEVELOP-REA     06-05 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-REDEVELOP-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A $1.5-BILLION RENEWAL OF A CHICAGO NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ This city has bulldozed architectural masterpieces and
burnished them. Never before, however, has it set aside a 16-story
landmark for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened to the McGraw-Hill Building, an Art
Deco tower that used to stand at 520 North Michigan Ave., just
across the Chicago River from the Loop. Today, carved into some
4,000 carefully labeled pieces, it sits in a warehouse not far from
the Cook County jail.
</P>
<P>
   No previous experience with landmarks quite prepares a visitor
for the sight of an entire building on wood pallets, stretching
horizontally rather than vertically, farther than the eye can see,
over more than two acres of floor space _ a rippled, Cubist ocean
of limestone, cast stone and pink granite.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, 98 percent of these pieces will
be used to clad the principal facades of an entirely new structure
at No. 520, a 310-room Grand Bay Hotel that is to be completed late
next year. It will adjoin the entrance pavilion of a
260,000-square-foot Nordstrom department store that is now under
construction and is to open in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time something on this scale has been done in
Chicago,'' said Christopher Hill, commissioner of the Planning and
Development Department. ``We're very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The new hotel will have two more floors than the former
McGraw-Hill Building, but these will be set back far enough so as
not to be visible from across Michigan Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, to the man in the street, it will look exactly
like the old 520 Michigan Avenue _ except cleaner,'' said John
Buck, chairman and chief executive of John Buck Co., which is
developing the site in partnership with Morgan Stanley Real Estate
Funds.
</P>
<P>
   The dismantling and re-erection of a designated landmark is
itself an appropriately brazen Chicago tale, but it is only one
part of an astonishing transformation by Buck Co. of nine blocks
west of Michigan Avenue into an enormous mixed-use district called
North Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy on shopping, dining and entertainment, North Bridge will
strengthen a growing east-west commercial axis that runs from Navy
Pier to State Street and beyond, across the tony Michigan Avenue
retail precinct. ``By way of analogy, where Times Square meets
Fifth Avenue,'' Buck said.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the end of next year, North Bridge is to get
three new hotels with a total of 902 rooms, a five-level
DisneyQuest virtual theme park, an ESPN Zone sports theme
restaurant, a northern outpost of Joe's Stone Crab restaurant of
Miami Beach and three parking garages with 2,113 spaces.
</P>
<P>
   All told, almost $1.5 billion is going into North Bridge: $530
million for current construction projects and $300 million for
tenants' completion of their spaces, with $630 million already
invested in the stores, hotels, offices, theaters and apartment
tower developed or renovated by the Buck Company.
</P>
<P>
   Buck spent nearly a decade trying to convince Nordstrom that
North Bridge was not too far south of the fanciest stretch of
Michigan Avenue, known as the ``Magnificent Mile.'' He argued that
Ohio and Ontario Streets, which run through the district, are an
important corridor since they connect to the Kennedy Expressway
(I-90 and I-94).
</P>
<P>
   But the giant Seattle retailer had other requirements that were
seemingly impossible to meet simultaneously: very large floor areas
and a Michigan Avenue entrance. Buck owned a site large enough to
suit Nordstrom, but it was a block west of Michigan Avenue. And the
McGraw-Hill Building stood in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't modify the building to accommodate new uses,''
Buck said. ``We were stopped dead in our tracks until we could
solve the 520 Michigan problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Completed in 1929 to designs by Thielbar &AMP; Fugard, the
McGraw-Hill Building was one of a series of small limestone towers
_ each fairly modest on its own, but extraordinary as an ensemble _
that once characterized Michigan Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Resembling a truncated version of Eliel Saarinen's unbuilt but
influential design for the nearby Tribune Tower, the McGraw-Hill
Building claimed as its distinguishing feature two sets of panels
carved by the sculptors Gwen Lux, who also worked on Radio City
Music Hall, and her husband, Eugene Van Breeman Lux.
</P>
<P>
   Figures from the zodiac and Greek mythology adorn the panels,
including a gentle-looking Taurus, a stressed-out Atlas struggling
with the world on his shoulders and a haughty, high-cheekboned
Diana who could almost pass for Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the city's best collaborations of sculpture and
architecture,'' the Commission on Chicago Landmarks declared in
1995 when it recommended the McGraw-Hill Building to the City
Council for designation.
</P>
<P>
   Buck was compelled to make a deal with city officials. ``We
didn't fight the designation,'' he said, ``but they gave us the
right to dismantle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismantling began last November and was completed two months
ago. The extra cost for disassembling and re-erecting the facade is
about $9 million, said Greg Merdinger, a principal in the John Buck
Company.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the project is not likely to set a precedent.
``It's a nice solution and they've done a great job but I don't see
it as a model,'' said James Peters, deputy commissioner in the
landmarks division of the planning agency. ``I can't think of many
places, except Fifth and Madison Avenues, where the retail market
is so high that it would make this feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters stepped gingerly as he spoke, threading his way in the
warehouse among _ and occasionally across _ limestone panels up to
14 feet wide and 10 inches thick; some plain, some fluted; some
deeply carved, some lightly incised, all of them labeled with metal
tags. Taurus, for example, is piece No. G61-25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad walking on that stuff,'' Peters said, leaving
Helios behind.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the limestone panels came off the old structure with
relatively little serious damage. ``We're not in a situation where
we have to repair the carved areas, so we don't have someone
learning Gwen Lux's technique,'' said Michael Sullivan, the senior
vice president of Anthony Belluschi Architects, designers of the
new 520 Michigan Ave. building.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Nordstrom entrance on Michigan Avenue will take the form of
an 80-foot atrium sandwiched between 520 Michigan and an existing
Marriott Hotel. Shoppers will reach the department store itself
through a four-level retail arcade and a bridge over Rush Street.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the salvaging of the facade will
yield a credible simulacrum of the landmark or merely an awkward
hybrid. And there is no telling yet whether the effort will
ultimately be worth the considerable political and financial
capital that was required to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   Another landmark battle is brewing three blocks away, on a block
just outside the North Bridge project area, where two significant
remnants of Chicago's artistic and social history still stand: the
Medinah Temple and Tree Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Completed in 1913 for the Chicago chapter of the Shrine of North
America, a Masonic fraternal organization best known for its
children's hospitals and circuses (and for the fact that its
members wear red fezzes), the Medinah Temple is an auditorium
cloaked in Moorish fantasy, with delicate filigree and horseshoe
arches. Its corner towers once had onion domes and crescent
finials.
</P>
<P>
   Tree Studios is a two- and three-story artists' compound built
in stages between 1894 and 1913 on what was once the backyard of
Judge Lambert Tree, a civic leader and the great-grandfather of the
model Penelope Tree. Its facade bristles with fanciful sculptural
touches _ like a palette with paint brushes on one of the chimneys
_ attesting to its creative purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists who lived or worked there were J. Allen St.
John, illustrator of the ``Tarzan'' books; Andrew Rebori, a Chicago
architect; John Franklin Storrs, sculptor of the Ceres statue atop
the Chicago Board of Trade; Alson Skinner Clark, an Impressionist
painter, and actor Burgess Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a repository of so much passion, searching, hard work and
creativity,'' said Barbara Koenen, a project manager in the city's
Cultural Affairs Department, which is organizing a show, ``The Art
of Tree Studios,'' this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The State Street frontage of the Tree Studios is already a
landmark, but the designation does not include its annexes on Ohio
and Ontario Streets, nor the inner courtyard. The Medinah Temple is
not a landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Shriners own the entire block and have contracted to sell it
for at least $20 million to the developer Steven Fifield, chairman
of the Fifield Companies. Until recently, he planned to replace the
temple with an apartment tower, while maintaining at least the
State Street facade of Tree Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, a movement to designate the entire studio and the
temple _ which would apparently frustrate Fifield's plans _ is
quickly gaining ground. Even Mayor Richard M. Daley has stepped in
to say that the Medinah Temple is a ``very special building'' and
that ``sometimes you need an oasis in big cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The landmarks commission is to take up the Tree Studios question
this month, to be followed by a consideration of the Medinah
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Because the commission has not acted, neither Hill nor Jack
Guthman of Shefsky &AMP; Froelich, a lawyer representing Fifield and
the Shriners, would comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Barton Faist, an artist and gallery owner who has lived in
Tree Studios for 17 years, was under no such restraint in urging
preservation. ``If they don't care about Tree Studios,'' he said,
``they don't care about Chicago history _ or art, for that
matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
