<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-PROM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY CHURCH SPONSORS GAY PROM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It was planned with flashing strobe lights,
glittering tablecloths and even a theme: ``Studio 54 Forever.''
Just like any other prom.
</P>
<P>
   Except some women rented tuxes. One man went shopping for a
gown. Guys asked guys, and women invited women.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's prom at midtown's Metropolitan Community Church
was the first gay prom in the Kansas City area, organizers said.
From 50 to 100 youths were expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   It was organized by Passages, a social and support group for
gays, lesbians and other youths between the ages of 14 and 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted an event where the atmosphere is very affirming, not
that thin gruel of tolerance,'' said Bruce Hall, a Passages board
member who helped organize the event. A gay prom, he said, allows
youth to experience ``the same opportunities and the same
traditions'' as their peers without fear of insults or physical
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Gay youths need occasions to feel positive about themselves,
said Kansas City psychologist and Passages board member David
Donovan. They face crises from taunts in school to evictions from
their homes, he said. One study found gay youths were more than
five times more likely than peers to be targets of school violence
or harassment. Another survey found that gay and bisexual male
teens were seven times more likely to attempt suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Many Passages youths said they were afraid to bring a same-sex
date to their prom. Others were barred entry. Saturday night was
their time to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Gay proms are traditions in several cities, including Des
Moines, Iowa; Springfield, Mo.; and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Passages members say more youths are confronting their sexuality
in an era with gay politicians and out-of-the-closet sitcom
characters. Passages started in 1990 with about seven teens and has
since grown to 50 who attend Sunday meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Gay youths still face challenges in school, notably during prom
season. Many local school districts do not have policies
restricting prom dates or dress. Some public schools, such as those
in St. Joseph, Mo., do have such rules. That angers civil rights
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment rights of free expression allow all public
school students to attend their proms with a date they chose and a
manner of dress in keeping with their sexual orientation, said Dick
Kurtenbach, the executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union of Kansas and Western Missouri. Excuses that gay couples will
disrupt a prom, he noted, ``could have applied not so long ago for
an interracial couple who attended.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Gallatin, Mo., one student's planned prom dress became a
problem. Before his senior year, B.J. DeWeese told family and
friends that he was gay. In the Daviess County town, DeWeese became
a familiar sight wearing high-heeled shoes, ``skorts'' and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   As prom approached, DeWeese was summoned to school offices.
</P>
<P>
   There, school officials asked him if he was planning to wear a
dress to prom. He was. If he arrived like that, they told him, he
would be turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' said DeWeese, 19. ``All by myself, defending
myself. Not knowing any school policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mickes, Gallatin High School's attorney, said the school was
within its rights. He said the Supreme Court had allowed public
school officials to restrict students' dress and activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, students get confused about what their
constitutional rights are. Their constitutional rights are to go to
school. Not to be third trumpet in the band. Not to be starting
quarterback. Not to go to the prom,'' Mickes said. ``Those are
privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWeese skipped his prom, but went dress-shopping before
Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ACCORD-1STLD-W     06-05 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ACCORD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING WITH NATO COMMANDER STALLS AS SERBS STUDY CONDITIONS OF
DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS headline, lede; CHANGES throughout)  (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ After meeting for more than five hours with
NATO officials on the border of Kosovo, Yugoslav military officers
failed Saturday to agree to the terms of their withdrawal from the
southern Serbian province, saying they needed more time to check
with leaders in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Five senior Yugoslav military officers came here Saturday to
meet with NATO officials and to review and sign the terms for their
withdrawal from Kosovo after 10 weeks of bombardment by the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials had expected the meeting to seal Yugoslavia's
capitulation and to mark the end of a decade of wars that have
dismantled the country. They insisted that there would be no
negotiations over the details of the military agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO agreed to meet again on Sunday after most of the
Yugoslav delegation went back across the border into Kosovo late
Saturday afternoon to consult with their leadership and did not
return.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting two hours, the head of the NATO delegation, Lt.
Gen. Michael Jackson, left. Officials declined to say exactly which
issues most concerned the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegation has asked for more time to consult with higher
authorities in Belgrade,'' a NATO spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin
Clifford, said. ``We have in the interest of seeking a swift
resolution to this agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Russian delegation was invited to attend, but did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and the Parliament in
Belgrade had already accepted NATO's terms to end the airstrikes on
Thursday after meetings with a special Russian envoy and the
president of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Though alliance officials would not provide specifics of the
document presented, the military agreement would allow NATO troops
to enter Kosovo as early as this week, a humiliation for
Yugoslavia's military.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, alliance officials said the document spells out how
and when Serbian troops are to leave Kosovo, the routes NATO troops
are to use to enter the province, and the troops and equipment to
be used in maintaining peace there.
</P>
<P>
   They also said it requires the Yugoslav army to remove or
provide information on the land mines with which it has seeded the
province. And unlike the military annex to the peace accord that
ended the war in Bosnia in 1995, this document is a separate
military agreement that goes into effect as soon as it is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Before NATO troops enter Kosovo, however, Serbian forces must
demonstrate within 24 hours that they are indeed withdrawing. Only
then, said a alliance spokesman, Trey Cate, would the alliance call
a pause in the bombing, which has continued despite the impending
accord. The first of 16,000 NATO troops would enter Kosovo on the
heels of the withdrawing Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature abhors a vacuum,'' Cate said, ``so we'll be following
pretty closely behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO would reserve the right to resume bombing if the Serbian
forces fail in any way to abide by the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Two sedans carrying the Yugoslav officials arrived here two
hours late for their 9:00 a.m. appointment with the NATO
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The delay came when the Yugoslav delegation, waiting across the
border less than one-half mile away, raised questions with a NATO
official about several details of the meeting, including their
insistence that the modest roadside cafe NATO had leased for the
meeting was not in a sufficiently neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that this was an attempt to postpone Saturday's signing,
NATO officials immediately solved the problems ``at the highest
levels,'' Clifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the hundreds of reporters waiting outside, the Yugoslav
officials then entered the restaurant, near the site where railway
cars had only recently disgorged some 60,000 dispirited Albanians
who had been evicted from Kosovo by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, Jackson, commander of NATO forces here, presented
the military agreement to Gen. Obrad Stevanovic, assistant
secretary of the Interior, and Gen. Blagoje Kovacevic, representing
the Yugoslav general staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav delegation sat on one side of a U-shaped table
across from General Jackson, who is British, and two top NATO
officials, including one American officer.
</P>
<P>
   Four brigade commanders from Italy, France, Germany and Great
Britain sat behind the men and were joined by at least 20 other
NATO officials. The meeting was put together so hastily that the
place cards were blank for the Yugoslav delegation because Belgrade
was unable to confirm who would represent the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   As they read the document line by line on the green-covered
tables, representatives of the two sides regularly excused
themselves to walk out of the restaurant and use secure
walkie-talkies to call headquarters. First a Serbian general, then
Jackson himself, strode out of the hilltop cafe to speak in private
about matters of interpretation and translations.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the atmosphere in the somber dining room was ``very
professional,'' according to Clifford, the NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a military agreement, Milosevic is not required to
sign the document, allowing NATO to avoid further negotiations with
the Yugoslav leader, who was indicted for war crimes last month by
an international tribunal. Nor were any other members of
Milosevic's government who have been indicted sent here from
Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MORE)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO officials completed writing the military
agreement, which is a revision of the military annex to the accord
negotiated in February in France, according to a NATO spokesman.
NATO officials then sent the document to the Yugoslav government
and settled on Saturday's meeting. For extra insurance, NATO
commanders confirmed the appointment late Friday night with the
Yugoslavs after the North Atlantic Council had approved the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels Saturday, the NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said
Jackson had full authority to lay down detailed withdrawal terms to
the Yugoslav commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firstly, they have to commit themselves, and Yugoslavia, to a
phased and rapid withdrawal of the Yugoslav ground forces,'' Shea
said. ``This means that all personnel, all organizations with a
military capability, must start to withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``This would involve, of course, units from the
regular army, but also armed civilian groups, national guards,
border police, army reserves, military police, the intelligence
services, police of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, local special
riot and anti-terrorist police, and any other groups or individuals
that will be designated by General Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also means that as these military and police forces leave,
they will have to stick to a firm schedule, using designated
assembly areas and designated routes, and designated areas that
will have to be vacated,'' he added. ``The withdrawal of the
Yugoslav armed forces must be completed within seven days from the
entry into force of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav forces would also have to agree to withdraw all
their aircraft, air defense radars and communications systems,
surface-to-air missiles, and anti-aircraft artillery ``very
quickly,'' Shea said, so that allied planes could safely carry out
reconnaissance missions during the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers would also be expected to see to it that the
Kosovo Liberation Army is disbanded and disarmed, though Maj. Gen.
Walter Jertz, a spokesman for the allied military command said
Saturday that this was ``a difficult issue.''
</P>
<P>
   British forces will be the first to enter Kosovo, according to a
NATO spokesman, an acknowledgment of their leading role in the
peacekeeping force, which will be led by Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The British, French, German, Italian and American forces will
each establish a zone of command in Kosovo, NATO officials said.
Those sectors will divide the province like slices of a pie. All of
these forces will enter with armor, including tanks and armored
personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   One NATO official said the United States will use Apache
helicopters during the first phase of the entry. ``It will send a
strong message that we are serious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rough outline of the military agreement, NATO
forces will have the right to prevent any disruptions to the peace,
whether by Serbian forces or troops of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
They will also have to contend with the problems of booby traps
left by the Serbs, especially in the houses and shops of the
Kosovar Albanians who have fled over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The five sectors will also include soldiers from other NATO and
non-NATO countries to police the peace agreement for years to come,
according to NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops hope to establish a ``safe and secure environment''
in advance of any return of the more than 500,000 Kosovar refugees
waiting in camps here and in Albania. At the same time, they will
be searching for the tens of thousands of Kosovar Albanians who
have hidden in the hills and abandoned villages after being thrown
out of their own homes and are believed to be in desperate need of
food, water and medical attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
