<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4378 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISIKOFF-LEWINSKY-KAN &LR;      06-05 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISIKOFF-LEWINSKY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER DISCUSSES ETHICAL QUESTIONS SURROUNDING LEWINSKY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WINSTON ROSS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Michael Isikoff learned about Kenneth
Starr's secret investigation of Monica Lewinsky, Starr's staff
begged him to keep it quiet _ at least for a day. It's a request
many journalists who cover politics confront.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a request many journalists automatically would deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `No way,' '' said Isikoff, Newsweek's investigative
correspondent. ``That's a no-brainer. In a case like this, with a
highly politicized atmosphere, it was not even a question of
holding off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Isikoff thought about it and realized that if he tipped off
President Clinton, Vernon Jordan and Lewinsky to the hunt, he'd
spend the rest of the weekend writing about their reaction to his
phone calls. The idea is to stay out of the story, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Isikoff obliged, and Starr saw his window. He sped up the
investigation during the next 24 hours and confronted Lewinsky.
Isikoff was a part of the story, like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical decisions such as this were what made the Lewinsky story
difficult to report, Isikoff told 900 journalists Saturday at the
1999 Investigative Reporters and Editors Conference at the Kansas
City Marriott Downtown. The conference ends today.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on the most infamous presidential scandal since
Watergate, Isikoff said he realized it was futile to agonize over
every ethical decision.
</P>
<P>
   His challenges were those any reporter would experience wading
through the muck toward truth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of Monica and Clinton and Starr and the whole saga
was first and foremost a story,'' Isikoff said. ``There's a reason
we call what we write stories. They are events and things that
happen that we find interesting. We get in real trouble when we try
to extrapolate lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   But the questions that emerged also were interesting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   How much should reporters write about the private lives of
public officials? When and how can they let themselves become part
of the story? Should they protect sources who lie?
</P>
<P>
   These are questions Isikoff said he was left with as the
Lewinsky story fades from the public spotlight. And they are the
questions journalists should consider in everything they do, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Lewinsky debacle, many Americans said the
president's personal life was no one's business, Isikoff said.
Journalists never blanketed their front pages with tales of John F.
Kennedy's tawdry affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But those reports eventually leaked, and people began to realize
that Kennedy's private life did have an effect on the public,
Isikoff said. After that, it became more acceptable to look into
what presidents and other public figures do when they're not
working.
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff said he realized Clinton's personal life was also
relevant to how he ran the country. His actions with Lewinsky
reflect who he is, and people needed to know about them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the circumstances that govern,'' Isikoff said. ``What we
had was a continuing pattern of recklessness. ...It ultimately came
to a culture of concealment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0606-COX     06-05 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    YUGOSLAV GENERALS BALK AT SIGNING PEACE SETTLEMENT AS SERBS
SHELL ALBANIAN REFUGEE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 800 
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia The three-day-old Kosovo peace settlement hung
in the balance Saturday night after a delegation of senior Yugoslav
generals balked at signing a detailed military withdrawal plan
drawn up by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Serb forces shelled a northern Albanian border town
crowded with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were to resume Sunday morning at the border town of
Kumanovo, the site of a NATO air base in Macedonia. Tanjug, the
state-run Yugoslav news agency, quoted unnamed sources who said an
agreement might be signed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials tried to put a favorable spin on the Yugoslav
delegation's overnight delay in signing the so-called ``military
technical agreement'' that the allies regard as one of the most
crucial steps before peace can begin to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   British Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, a NATO spokesman, said
Saturday's talks had been ``constructive'' and ``positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each point of the military technical agreement has been
discussed word by word, line by line and sentence by sentence,'' he
told reporters. ``What we now have is a full understanding on both
sides as to (its) content . . .and what it actually requires the
Yugoslav delegation and the Yugoslav armed forces to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the Serb shelling of the
Albanian border town of Kruma would complicate Sunday's resumed
talks. Officials of the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe reported that eight shells had exploded in Kruma, located
about nine miles from Kukes and about five miles west of the
Yugoslav border. The number of casualties was not immediately
known.
</P>
<P>
   OSCE spokesman Andrea Agneli said relief workers and townspeople
in Kruma had fled into cellars. Agneli said that three Serb shells
hit the nearby village of Nikoliq, injuring three young women.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have often shelled Albanian border areas, where rebels
from the Kosovo Liberation Army are trying to move arms and
fighters to continue their battle for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO air strikes entered their 75th day early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied pilots continued to hammer at Serb positions
near Kosovo's border with Albania, where fighting between Serb
forces and units of the Kosovo Liberation Army continued to rage.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon insisted the strikes would
continue until Serb forces begin pulling out in earnest from
Kosovo. ``That hasn't yet started,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the bombing could end shortly after a pullout begins,
but added: ``Nothing like that is going to happen as long as the
Serbs refuse to move.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what caused the delay in signing
the military technical agreement.
</P>
<P>
   By one account, the Yugoslav delegates said they needed
clearance from their superiors before they could accept NATO's
proposed date for starting to deploy American, British, French,
German, Canadian and other nations' peacekeepers inside war-torn
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   British Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, heading the NATO delegation, has
insisted that the NATO peacekeepers must begin crossing the Kosovo
border very soon, perhaps within the next 48 hours. ``There has to
be the avoidance of a vacuum,'' as one officer close to Jackson put
it.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a quick agreement in the military-to-military
talks, NATO has begun rushing peacekeepers into Macedonia. They
already were on alert to move into Kosovo in the next few days.
Among the contingents arriving at Macedonia's main airport Saturday
was a planeload of German tank troops aboard a transport plane.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's military talks took place at a roadside cafe called
``Europa 93'' several hundred yards inside Macedonia, along the
main highway where tens of thousands of Kosovar refugees trudged
toward exile in refugee camps earlier this year. On a hillside
above the cafe are six fresh graves of refugees who died in a
cramped, makeshift refugee camp that at one point
</P>
<P>
   this spring swelled to 60,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   On a mountaintop overlooking the cafe, Serbian snipers have
sometimes been spotted peering down on refugee columns. But there
were no snipers in evidence during the military-to-military talks.
</P>
<P>
   After realizing that the Yugoslav delegation would not sign the
document Saturday evening, a NATO staff member could be seen
walking off to his car carrying two armloads of rolled-up oversized
military maps. Another staff aide carried a thick sheaf of plastic
overlays for the maps, which were apparently meant to inform the
Yugoslavs of the precise details of
</P>
<P>
   which routes Yugoslav troops were to use in exiting Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place around a large square table in the first
floor of the cafe. On one side sat Jackson and his interpreter.
Opposite sat the two top Yugoslav delegates, Col. Gen. Blagoje
Kovacevic, the assistant chief of the Yugoslav Army general staff,
and Col. Gen. Obrad Stevanovic, the deputy minister of interior.
</P>
<P>
   On a third side sat ``observers,'' including U.S. Air Force Lt.
Gen. ``Doc'' Fogelsong from NATO headquarters and two Finnish
military representatives of Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who
negotiated Thursday's apparent peace breakthrough. The fourth side
was occupied by note-takers.
</P>
<P>
   Another 25 lower-ranking aides, mostly on the NATO side, sat
around the outside of the room listening.
</P>
<P>
   For unexplained reasons, there was no Russian delegate at
Saturday's session, despite the critical role played by Russian
</P>
<P>
   envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin in convincing Yugoslav leader Slobodan
Milosevic to give in and allow foreign peacekeepers into Kosovo in
exchange for a halt in NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The session was called for 9:30 a.m. but didn't start until noon
because the two sides had trouble agreeing on the exact place and
configuration of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After five hours and ten minutes of discussions, the six
Yugoslav generals insisted that they needed further instructions
from Belgrade. Stern-faced and ignoring shouted press questions,
they sped away into Kosovo in a procession of six Mercedes sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Still expecting the session to conclude by sundown Saturday,
NATO spokesman Clifford emerged from the cafe at 5:15 p.m. to say,
``All that is required now is for one or two small points of detail
that the Yugoslav delegation wish to consult back to
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade. They have gone off to go and do that. We expect them
back here within one hour.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour expired. Then Jackson, the British general leading the
NATO delegation, got a phone call, apparently from a low-ranking
Yugoslav official at the Yugoslav border crossing several hundred
yards north the roadside meeting place.
</P>
<P>
   Four NATO officials, led by Fogelsong in his combat flight suit,
sauntered past a cluster of about 150 journalists. As they ambled
up the road toward the Yugoslav border post, Fogelsong joked that
he was on his way ``to find out what's happening in the Cleveland
Indians game.''
</P>
<P>
   When the four returned, they gave no hint that anything about
the talks was amiss. Fogelsong again bantered to the journalists
about baseball, then returned inside the cafe apparently carrying
the message that the Yugoslavs weren't willing to continue the
meeting into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 8 p.m., NATO spokesman Clifford once again stood
before a microphone in the cafe parking lot to announce that the
talks had been adjourned until 8:30 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
