for women in Harlem, sees a conflict of interest in the modern AIDS
research clinic run by Cornell Medical College in Port-au-Prince,
Haiti. Ms. Cyr says there is a ``clear conflict of interest''
between the desire to collect information from research subjects
and the obligation to effectively warn patients at risk. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- HAITI-CORNELL-AIDS-1, 6-5 --
Dr. Jean William Pape, a native of Haiti and a Cornell Medical
College professor who has studied AIDS in Haiti for two decades.
Pape says that AIDS research subjects are treated the same as any
AIDS patients at the modern research clinic run by Cornell in
Port-au-Prince, Haiti. ``You have to take into account people who
mean well for their country and not impose on them things that you
feel are good for Western ideas,'' says Pape. (Angel Franco/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- -- June 5, 1999 -- ADOPT-A-PAINTING-2, 6-5 --
``A Storm in the Rocky Mountains'' by Albert Bierstadt, from the
Brooklyn Museum of Art's permanent collection, where having your
name on a label next to a painting now costs just $500 a year.
Under a program that began with a mailing to 15,000 people, the
museum is urging its members and visitors to ``be a modern-day
Medici'' and ``adopt a masterpiece'' from its permanent collection.
Critics say the program lacks dignity and cheapens the museum
atmosphere. (Brooklyn Museum of Art/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- -- June 5, 1999 -- ADOPT-A-PAINTING-1, 6-5 --
The name of Sue Stoffel, 41, will appear on a label next to ``A
Storm in the Rocky Mountains'' by Albert Bierstadt, because she
gave $500 to the Brooklyn Museum of Art. Under a program that began
with a mailing to 15,000 people, the museum is urging its members
and visitors to ``be a modern-day Medici'' and ``adopt a
masterpiece'' from its permanent collection. A contributor can even
adopt a work in memory of someone. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LITTLETON, Colo. -- June 5, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-FAITH,
6-5 -- Two Columbine High students, Charise Walters, 16, left, and
Gwen Bartlett, 17, receiving communion at the St. Frances Cabrini
Catholic Church in Littleton. Many Columbine students are finding
solace in prayer groups and their churches, spurning counselors
brought in by their school after the shootings. Experts say
adolescence is a prime time for seeking spiritual meaning along
with personal identity. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
