<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 06/05/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- MEDSCHOOL-OLDEST, 6-5 -- Dr.
Robert Lopatin with his stepmother, Ruth, right, and other
relatives after commencement ceremonies at the Albert Einstein
College of Medicine in the Bronx last week. At 55, Dr. Lopatin, who
operated a clothing manufacturing firm for many years before
returning to school, fulfilled a longtime dream of becoming a
doctor. He is the oldest graduate in the medical college's history.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 5, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-4, 6-5 --
Jockey Chris Antley with Charismatic right after crossing the
finish line, holding his lame leg off the ground. Charismatic was
gallant in defeat, pressing the early pace and staying on gamely
for third place despite sustaining a cracked bone in his left front
ankle. Longshot Lemon Drop Kid rallied to pass Charismatic, then
held off fast-closing Vision and Verse to win the Belmont Stakes
Saturday and deny Charismatic's Triple Crown bid. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 5, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-3, 6-5 --
Lemon Drop Kid, left, rallying down the center of the track on
Saturday to win the Belmont Stakes by a head over an even longer
shot, Vision and Verse. Charismatic, the favorite, who finished
third, chased the winner across the finish line, but sustained a
cracked bone in his left front ankle that brought a stunning end to
an otherwise memorable day at Belmont Park. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 5, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-2, 6-5 --
Jose Santos riding on Lemon Drop Kid, celebrates after winning the
Belmont Stakes on Saturday by a head over an even longer shot,
Vision and Verse. Charismatic, standing on the threshold of
sweeping the Triple Crown, missed his date with history by running
third in the race. Charismatic, the favorite, chased the winner
across the finish line, but sustained a cracked bone in his left
front ankle that brought a stunning end to the race. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 5, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-1, 6-5 --
Lemon Drop Kid, foreground, a longshot ridden by Jose Santos,
crossing the finish line and winning the Belmont Stakes on Saturday
by a head over an even longer shot, Vision and Verse. Charismatic,
the favorite, who finished third, chased the winner across the
finish line, but sustained a cracked bone in his left front ankle
that brought a stunning end to an otherwise memorable day at
Belmont Park. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- NY-INNOCENT-INMATE, 6-5 --
Accused of a serious sex crime and unable to raise $5,000 for bail,
Jose Padro, 28, spent more than a year and a half on Rikers Island,
in what is euphemistically known as pretrial detention. Adamant in
proclaiming his innocence, he turned down two offers for a plea
agreement. In the end, after being acquitted in late January, Padro
served more time in jail before acquittal than he probably would
have under either of the plea offers. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- MUNICIPALITIES-ACCOUNTING,
6-5 -- Tom Allen, the former auditor of Utah, is now chairman of
the Governmental Accounting Standards Board, a group that sets the
accounting standards for how the nation's 84,000 state and local
governments keep their books. The board is expected to approve a
plan this week that would require them to operate more like
businesses, providing taxpayers with a more complete picture of
what their dollars buy. (David Gatley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- June 5, 1999 -- BLACKLEY-PROSECUTION, 6-5
-- Ronald H. Blackley, who worked for a congressman named Mike Espy
in 1993, may soon go to prison for 27 months. Espy was accused but
ultimately cleared of taking favors from companies that did
business with the Agriculture Department. Blackley, 48, has not
been as fortunate. He has been a target of special prosecutors, his
lawyer says, under a statute that has spawned boundless
multimillion-dollar investigations that have gone on for years.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- HAITI-CORNELL-AIDS-2, 6-5 --
Marie Saint Cyr, a native of Haiti who now directs an AIDS program
for women in Harlem, sees a conflict of interest in the modern AIDS
research clinic run by Cornell Medical College in Port-au-Prince,
Haiti. Ms. Cyr says there is a ``clear conflict of interest''
between the desire to collect information from research subjects
and the obligation to effectively warn patients at risk. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 5, 1999 -- HAITI-CORNELL-AIDS-1, 6-5 --
Dr. Jean William Pape, a native of Haiti and a Cornell Medical
College professor who has studied AIDS in Haiti for two decades.
Pape says that AIDS research subjects are treated the same as any
AIDS patients at the modern research clinic run by Cornell in
Port-au-Prince, Haiti. ``You have to take into account people who
mean well for their country and not impose on them things that you
feel are good for Western ideas,'' says Pape. (Angel Franco/New
York Times Photo)
