<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--KAN &LR;      06-05 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL WORLD WAR II MEMORIAL WOULD GIVE VETERAN A SENSE OF
CLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a faraway shore 55 years ago today, Donald McKee
came face to face with death. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was a 20-year-old medic attached to the 29th Infantry that
was being chewed to pieces on the beaches of Normandy. It was a
scene of unimaginable chaos and carnage: burning tanks, beached
boats and bodies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When McKee waded ashore at twilight on June 6, 1944, the air was
thick with smoke and the cries of the wounded. The injured were
stacked on litters; the dead still lay in the wet sand where they
had fallen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day to remember,'' said McKee, 75, a retired chemical
engineer from Silver Spring, Md. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now he hopes that a patch of greenery along the capital's Mall
near the Lincoln Memorial will soon provide the type of remembrance
already enjoyed by veterans of Korea and Vietnam, but that has long
eluded the soldiers of World War II. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some states have World War II memorials. McKee helped erect a
tribute in Maryland. Missouri and Kansas have memorials to veterans
of all U.S. wars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drive to build a national World War II memorial passed
another hurdle last week when its preliminary design got a
thumbs-up from one of several federal agencies that determine where
memorials go in the capital and how they look. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million project still needs final design approvals and
the blessing of the interior secretary. It also could use an
additional $50 million in private donations since the budget is
only halfway there. The pace of contributions has picked up ever
since Tom Hanks, who starred in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' an
Oscar-winning film about D-Day, became the fund-raising campaign's
national spokesman this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April, for instance, the campaign received about 3,600
pledges. In May, after Hanks' television ads started running, the
number shot up to 35,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he gets on TV and makes a pitch, we end up with a
flurry of phone calls,'' said Mike Conley, spokesman for the
American Battle Monuments Commission, an independent federal agency
that is building the memorial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barring unforeseen roadblocks in an undertaking that has been
anything but trouble-free, construction could begin next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But with only 6.3 million World War II veterans left, and with
more than 1,000 dying every day, supporters are getting anxious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking,'' Herman Harrington, a veteran and an
American Legion official, said at a public hearing last week. ``I'd
like to see as many of my old comrades as possible join me when we
have the groundbreaking ceremony.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is to be built on a 7.4-acre section of the Mall
that has been the source of much of the controversy. It is planned
for the foot of the Reflecting Pool, thereby intruding on the vista
between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial, two of
the capital's most prominent symbols. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the site is perfectly appropriate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, it is the nave of our cathedral,'' said Charles
Atherton, secretary of the Commission of Fine Arts, an independent
federal design review agency. ``If you compare it to Westminster
Abbey, with all its great national heroes, our Mall is something
akin to that. ``It's a very, very special place. A lot of people
were concerned about putting the memorial in the middle of it, that
it's not the right thing to do. We're just as convinced it's the
only thing to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The design also has fevered some of the opposition. It involves
rebuilding the pool, adding fountains and surrounding it with a
large plaza. Two granite memorial arches would stand at the north
and south entrances, along with curvilinear ramps to provide
access. Fifty-six stone pillars representing all the states and
territories _ symbolizing the unity of the nation during the war _
would embrace the plaza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There also would be ceremonial steps that would double as an
amphitheater for ceremonies, flags, sculpted American eagles,
laurel wreaths and inscriptions. A key element would be a ``sacred
precinct'' with cascading waterfalls and a cenotaph commemorating
the sacrifice, a light of freedom arising out of a crater and a
Wall of Freedom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest design is the result of several revisions after the
fine arts commission and another design review agency, the National
Capital Planning Commission, had rejected earlier versions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to finally come up with a visual statement that
is powerful and commensurate with the significance of World War
II,'' said architect Friederich St. Florian, former dean of the
Rhode Island School of Design. ``What we are trying to do is that
somebody who would come to visit the memorial, say 100 years from
now, will really understand that this was the generation of
Americans that lived in the mid-20th century that upheld the ideals
and principles of the nation like it never has happened before.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents see little that they like. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conglomeration of parts; some are triumphant; some are
funerary,'' said Judy Scott Feldman, an art and architectural
history professor at American University. ``It's confusing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feldman, who serves on the Committee of 100, the oldest citizens
historic preservation group in Washington, told last week's public
hearing that through the use of eagles, wreaths, fire and large
stone arches, the design unwittingly employed architectural devices
popular in the Nazi regime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the right symbols for the World War II
memorial,'' she said. ``This is not how we want to commemorate that
era.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the memorial as it is now envisioned seems on a glidepath
toward final approval.
</P>
<P>
   That is welcome news to former Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, a wounded
World War II veteran who is co-chairman of the fund-raising
campaign. To the Kansan, the memorial stands for ``peace, strength
and victory, but freedom more than anything. That's what I hope it
would say.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For McKee, whose two Purple Hearts offer testimony to his own
sacrifice half a century ago, it means: ``After 50-some odd years,
we've got closure, which we've never had before. It was probably
the most catastrophic event that took place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognition is long overdue.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
