<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KKK-RECRUIT-KAN &LR;      06-05 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KKK-RECRUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLAN USES SOFTER RHETORIC IN EFFORT TO EXPAND MEMBERSHIP IN
MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBERLY, Mo. _ Ina Boon stood at the church lectern and, like a
sage schoolmarm, shared some lessons from her years in civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People lamented that many African-Americans today thought
the struggles for civil rights were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had already climbed the rough side of the
mountain,'' the St. Louis woman said Saturday. ``We thought we had
it made.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the Klan decided to revisit us and let us know we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people gathered at the Second Baptist Church to
protest plans for a Ku Klux Klan unit near Moberly, 35 miles north
of Columbia. Fliers distributed by the Klan have energized
opponents statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers are part of an effort by some Klan groups to move
into the political mainstream. Facing competition for members, the
groups disavow the Klan's history of lynchings and cross burnings.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers certainly don't read like the type of material
normally associated with the Klan. They are free of racial slurs.
Instead, they list the group's positions on immigration, foreign
aid, gun control and education.
</P>
<P>
   They end with a plea to reclaim America's ``white Christian
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts say the softer rhetoric hides deep-rooted bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, many Moberly residents want no part of the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want one message from my lips to be heard,'' said state
Rep. Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat who is House speaker. ``Hate has
no place here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Klan has thrived in Missouri since the 1860s. In 1871, the
governor was forced to use the militia to quell Klan terror in
southeast Missouri. By the 1920s, Klan newspapers were common, and
some political candidates acknowledged membership.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the 1920s, the Klan had more than 1.5 million
members nationwide. The Southern Poverty Law Center estimates that
various Klan groups now have only 5,000 members in about 160
chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Two organizations that monitor hate groups report Missouri
chapters in St. Louis, Humansville, Leslie, Mountain Grove, Nixa
and Overland. The groups list no Klan chapters in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Robb, the group's national director, said the group was
expanding in mid-Missouri at the request of two members. He refused
to reveal the membership in Moberly or statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Robb is well known to those who monitor hate groups. He split
with national leaders and formed a smaller group, the Knights of
the Ku Klux Klan. He says his group is the largest, a statement
disputed by monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Robb is rarely seen in the Klan's traditional white hood. He is
more likely to appear in a business suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made a real effort to portray himself as part of the
kinder, gentler Klan,'' said Mark Potok, a spokesman for the
Southern Poverty Law Center who monitors hate groups nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, the Klan adopted a stretch of highway near St.
Louis, joining other groups that pledge to pick up litter. The
state Department of Transportation is trying to deny the
application in court.
</P>
<P>
   A former Robb associate also tried to underwrite ``All Things
Considered,'' a National Public Radio program, on KWMU-FM in St.
Louis. The station blocked its attempt in court. A Klan leader
testified that the group wanted to reach a highly educated
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Robb's writings on Moberly show a willingness to soften the
Klan's rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no time nor interest in hating black people or anyone
else of color,'' he wrote. ``Our interest is with our people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a flier, however, he wrote: ``By the time (our children)
reach adulthood, they are an obedient slave to the ideas of
race-mixing, globalism, homosexuality, abortion and dozens of
Marxist-based, liberal schemes meant to artificially lift
non-whites to a higher level of western civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said: ``We're in a race war. It's not one
that occurs on streets with people shooting at each other. It's
occurring in the courts, in business. It's a very one-sided war
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who monitor hate groups say Robb's soft words mask the
deep hatred of minorities that other Klan groups express more
overtly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may portray a more benign image, but the rhetorical games
they play are merely a face for the same old style of bigotry,''
said Devin Burghart of the Center for New Community, which monitors
hate groups in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ratliff, state director of the NAACP, puts it more bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leopards never change their spots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in mid-Missouri and the Department of Justice, which
monitors hate crimes statewide, report no recent violence connected
to the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Robb said his group wanted to acquire influence in Missouri
through political office. He said he would encourage ``sleeper''
candidates, who run for office without disclosing Klan membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are common, ordinary folks,'' Robb said. ``They
are not terrorists. If people are concerned about somebody driving
down the street and attacking them, they shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where the danger lies, Burghart said. He worries that
residents might become inflamed by Klan rhetoric and turn to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Burghart said, the Klan's presence could push
Moberly residents of all races to come together.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the NAACP chapter in Moberly was in danger of folding.
But the recent controversy drew one of the best turnouts in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good community,'' said Arthur Gross, a longtime
black resident. ``It's like you're taking backward steps. It's hard
to believe that it's 1999 and you still have hate groups around. We
won't stand for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
