<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INJURED DESERVE TO BE THE ENVIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the radio the other day I heard a man say how, now that the
Kosovo nightmare is near an end, there would have to be a Marshall
Plan for the Balkans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of damage has been done, he rightly noted. And it
will need to be repaired if the people in that fractious corner of
the world are to begin to learn to live together, if not in
harmony, then at least without savaging one another. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But now let's speak of conditions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly help -- generous help -- is owed to those countries in
the region that have borne the principal burden of the humanitarian
emergency, Albania and Macedonia chief among them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the reconstruction effort, of course, must be in
Kosovo, where the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and his
political and military cohorts unleashed a frenzy of terror and
destruction that has claimed thousands of lives and sent a tragic
multitude of refugees fleeing the region. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many, perhaps most, have nothing to go back to. Homes and
villages have been blasted or burned. Murder has taken their loved
ones. Torture and rape have scarred the survivors. Their most
intimate possessions have been ripped from them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There even are reports of Serbs turning on their longtime
Albanian neighbors, joining in the pillage. As nearly as can be
said of any population today, they have lost everything --
property, trust, their hope of a reasonable future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, insofar as it is possible, let us set out to restore the
Kosovar Albanians' prospect for safe and decent lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, put in place international peacekeepers to guarantee
their protection. Evict, forcibly if necessary, those who usurped
their lands and goods. Then set to work to reconstruct their
shattered world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Build each family a house, finer than it had before, and furnish
it sufficiently. Build schools. Build hospitals. Provide them the
means and machinery _ tractors, harvesters, seed, fertilizer and so
forth _ to restore their economy. Give whatever resources and
technical aid are necessary to ensure that that happens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a word, make those who have suffered in this affair the envy
of those who injured them. The task is large and will cost
something, but it is not unimaginable. For the numbers are not so
great. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The job could be done several times over for less than this
little war has cost, and far less than we have spent in other parts
of the world trying to impose civility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what of the Serbs? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After all, it will be argued, not all of them were guilty. Not
all of them supported Milosevic -- not at the outset, anyway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombs and missiles have destroyed buildings and bridges,
and shattered the infrastructure across much of Serbia. Who will
remedy all this harm? Why should a whole people be made to pay for
the crimes of a few? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer, not wholly satisfactory but perhaps the best
available, is that people have always paid a price for allowing
themselves to be ruled by wicked and unprincipled men. And the man
who authored this ordeal still rules in Belgrade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So not one cent, I would hope _ not of my tax money anyway _ to
make the Yugoslav Serbs whole! Not until the other and more urgent
work is finished. And not until Milosevic, his cronies and all who
took part in this barbarity have been brought to trial and made to
pay for their crimes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then will be soon enough to consider what might be done to help
Serbia repair the ruin it called down upon itself. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
