<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL SAY FED WILL RAISE INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street's rising anxiety over the prospect of higher
interest rates may be roiling both the stock and bond markets for
no rational reason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The concern began to mount last month when the Federal Reserve's
monetary policy panel adjourned by announcing it was leaving
interest rates alone but signaling a bias toward a boost rather
than a cut. The caveat meant continuing signs of inflation would be
met with an increase in the short-term rates controlled by the
central bank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets have been in a tizzy ever since. Stock
prices have been choppy, and many bond yields are at their highest
levels in more than a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the May reading of the index of the National Association of
Purchasing Management showed a substantial gain Tuesday, this
measure of manufacturing health was at its highest level in 19
months. What really disturbed the financial markets, though, was
the index component that tracks prices paid, which also surged to
its highest point since October 1997. The markets read this
development as ammunition for Fed inflation hawks advocating a rate
increase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the Fed's announcement, however, is being overdone,
says Merrill Lynch analyst Jack W. Lavery. He noted in a recent
commentary that although the Fed had indicated a bias toward
tightening monetary policy 15 times since 1996, it subsequently had
raised rates only once after signaling such bias. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tame hourly earnings figures, a minute growth in the
employment cost index and continued vigor in productivity portend a
neutral Fed conclusion,'' Lavery advised. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the inflationary threat itself, Brian Wesbury says anyone
worried about it should check out what the price of gold has been
doing lately. Wesbury, chief economist for GKS&AMP;T Economics in
Chicago, says gold's price decline over the last month is more than
ample confirmation that deflation remains a greater danger than
inflation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At midweek, gold was trading just under $265 an ounce, which
represented a drop of about $25 since early May and put its price
at a 20-year low. Because gold is traditionally a barometer of
inflation anxiety, its continuing swoon reflects lack of real-world
concern about inflation, Wesbury told clients in a recent
advisory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is so despite explanations by some analysts focusing on the
effects of planned gold sales by the Bank of England and others.
Gold's slump has nothing to do with any announced sales, Wesbury
contends, because its price decline represents a problem of too
little demand instead of an anticipated supply glut. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wesbury concurs with Lavery's view that conventional wisdom has
gone too far in anticipating a rate increase by the Fed. In fact,
he says, a strong dollar, weak commodity prices and a relatively
high federal funds rate indicate monetary policy is too tight
instead of too loose. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The continued strong growth of the gross domestic product aside,
Wesbury says if Fed policy were too loose, other indicators
wouldn't be as weak as they are. He says weakness in retail sales
and durable-goods orders, for instance, are significant signs of
slowing growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes Wesbury the boldest of contrarians. He's
brave enough to predict that the Fed's next move will be a rate cut
instead of the boost that conventional wisdom is expecting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
