<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TALKS-BOS &LR;      06-05 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON DETAILS OF PULLOUT BEGIN AS BOMBING CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Underlining the haze between war and peace in
Yugoslavia, NATO had its peacekeeping chief for Kosovo detail peace
terms to Yugoslav military leaders throughout the day Saturday,
then rained bombs and missiles on Yugoslav military targets at
nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are expected to resume Sunday in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five hours, British Lieutenant General Michael
Jackson, who commands some 16,000 NATO forces in Macedonia,
delivered the terms for an orderly and verifiable pullout of 40,000
Serbian forces from the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   The plan requires Yugoslavia's military to begin its pullout
within 24 hours of an agreement and complete it in seven days. Once
NATO has evidence Serb forces are withdrawing, it will suspend its
10-week-old bombing campaign of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Without final approval of the conditions Saturday by the
Yugoslav military, NATO launched new attacks on Yugoslav positions
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in Kosovo and other parts of Serbia. Yugoslav
forces shelled the Albanian border town of Kruma, a base for the
rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. There were no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman in Brussels privately questioned why Belgrade,
which has lost many troops during the 74-day air campaign, would
prolong the suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Such questions arose when the Serbian delegation arrived three
hours late for the meeting. Late in the afternoon, the Serbian
officials asked for an additional hour to confer with Yugoslav
leaders in Belgrade, according to Lieutenant Colonel Robin
Clifford, a NATO spokesman. After more than two hours of delay, the
talks were suspended for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford, a British officer, said it was ``a very constructive
day of very positive talks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each point of the military-technical agreement has been
discussed word-by-word, line-by-line, sentence-by-sentence,''
Clifford said. ``What we now have is a full understanding . . . on
what it actually requires the Yugoslav delegation and the Yugoslav
armed forces to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman David Leavey did not signal a
breakdown in the talks. ``There's obviously a number of very
important, very detailed elements of compliance that need to be
gone over between the two militaries,'' he said, `` and that's what
we're in the process of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesmen said the Yugoslav delegation of senior army and
police officers pored over maps of Kosovo as Jackson gave
instructions on how they should extricate their forces from the
province. One aim was to coordinate timetables and routes so that
NATO pilots would not fire on the withdrawing Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was held at a roadside cafe called Europa, near the
border checkpoint at Blace where more than a quarter of the 800,000
ethnic Albanians forced from Kosovo have crossed into Macedonia.
Participants were served a lunch of cheese and spinach pastries,
and they took one 10-minute break to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs that a cease-fire might be imminent, there was no
pause in NATO's air campaign. NATO flew more than 500 sorties and
struck at least 130 targets in Kosovo and Yugoslavia, alliance
officials in Brussels said.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive day, there were no bombing raids in
the Yugoslav capital. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon would not
confirm NATO intentionally was sparing Belgrade during the Blace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said a halt in NATO's bombing depended
on the Serbian military agreeing to Jackson's instructions and
beginning the withdrawal. ``NATO will not stop the bombing campaign
until we see concrete evidence of them withdrawing,'' Shea said.
``It is all up to the Serbs. They know what they have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Pentagon had no evidence a pullout was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said Saturday that while the White House
was hopeful about ending the war, ``caution is the watchword.''
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``has broken his promises in
the past,'' Gore said on CNN. ``We want to see the facts on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic still has made no public comment to explain why he
sued for peace and accepted nearly the same terms offered before
the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Shea stressed that the Blace meeting was ``not a negotiating
session, not a place for haggling or equivocation . . . not a place
to discuss the size or the positioning of the conference table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place for decision and action,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shea, Jackson demanded that Yugoslav military
leaders agree to the following measures in order for the bombing to
stop:
</P>
<P>
   --The phased and rapid withdrawal of all Serb ground forces,
including the regular army, armed civilian groups, national guards,
border, military, and antiterrorist police, and intelligence
services.
</P>
<P>
   --The dismantling of Serbian air forces and air defense systems
inside Kosovo, including the swift removal of all aircraft, radars,
surface-to-air missiles and antiaircraft artillery.
</P>
<P>
   --The disclosure of information on the location and types of
land mines in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a multinational peacekeeping force of 50,000 is
building, Bacon said, and five NATO countries, the United States,
Britian, France, Germany, and Italy, are preparing to police
specific sectors of Kosovo. They will face the challenges of
demining, setting up an infrastructure for their own troops, and
then helping get the ethnic Albanians to their homes by rebuilding
roads and bridges, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk of the boots on the ground will be Marine boots,'' he
said, noting that the first wave of US Marines will begin arriving
in Greece Sunday and head toward Macedonia Monday. The British are
sending 12,000 soldiers, the United States 7,000, the French 6,500.
Others will come from Italy, Germany, and a number of non-NATO
countries.
</P>
<P>
   No Russian military officials took part at the Blace meeting,
though they were invited. Russian troops are expected to be
included among the Kosovo peacekeepers, but NATO and Russian
officials have not yet agreed on the size of the force or who will
command it. ``NATO has made it clear we want a unified command
structure,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Moscow, Victor Chermomyrdin, the Russian envoy who helped
broker the peace deal, said Saturday no Russian peacekeepers would
be under NATO command. ``If NATO countries participate there . . .
they will be led by NATO itself,'' Chernomyrdin told Russian
television. ``As regards Russian participation, we will never be
under NATO. Never. This is ruled out.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, a spokesman for the Kosovo Liberation Army told CNN
the rebels view Russia as a Serb ally, and they would not agree to
keep the peace if Russians were commanding their own forces in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to cooperate with NATO,'' said Pleurat Sejdiu, a
political representative for the KLA. ``We very much welcome the
single command. We will not accept a separate command of Russian
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Sejdiu said the KLA, which has been fighting for Kosovo's
independence, also was anxious about the political consequences of
the peace deal. ``There will be a political struggle now that the
military struggle has ended,'' Sejdiu predicted. ``Nobody can think
the Albanian struggle for independence stops here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Serb forces leave Kosovo, NATO is counting on the KLA
rebels to disband, put down their weapons, and turn into a civilian
police force. Under the terms of the agreement in Rambouillet,
France, which KLA representatives signed earlier this year but the
Serbs did not, the rebels were to demilitarize, give up most of
their arms and stop wearing their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Shea urged the KLA to renounce violence and abide
strictly by the alliance's orders for ending the war or face NATO's
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Walter Jertz, a NATO military spokesman, confirmed
ongoing fighting between Serbian forces and the KLA along the
Albanian border. Jertz called the disarming of the KLA ``a separate
issue, and it's a difficult issue,'' in reaching a peaceful
settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon noted that once ethnic Albanian refugees begin returning
to Kosovo, it may not be ``happy place'' for the Serbian minority
that lives there. ``I don't think Serbs will want to stay there,''
Bacon said. ``I think they'll want to return to Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to this report were Susan Milligan of the Globe
staff in Tirana, Albania, and correspondent Kurt Pitzer, in Blace,
Macedonia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
