<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT RANGERS PITCHING HELPS TEXAS SIZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The center of the baseball universe this weekend is not Yankee
Stadium and it certainly isn't Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix, the Texas Rangers and
Arizona Diamondbacks are hotter than the weather outside in the
most exciting battle of division leaders on the interleague
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have added impressive pitching to their usually
fierce offense, came into Friday night with a nine-game winning
streak, their longest in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson took a no-hitter into
the seventh inning and won 11-3, the Rangers are threatening to run
away with the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for the Angels, who are sniping at manager Terry
Collins from last place in the division. But it's also trouble for
the Dodgers, who play host to the Rangers in a three-game series
beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally doing what people said we could do in spring
training,'' said third baseman Todd Zeile, the former Dodger.
``Early on we were hanging on with offense. We'd lose the
low-scoring games or outslug the other team to win. These nine
games, we've shown that our starting pitching is good and our
bullpen is outstanding. As a result, if we're within striking
distance after five innings, we feel we're within striking distance
of a win.''
</P>
<P>
   During the winning streak, the Rangers beat Minnesota 3-2 on
Sunday and Kansas City 3-1 on Tuesday. Those marked the first two
times the Rangers won a game scoring less than four runs. They were
0-11 when scoring less than four runs last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very important,'' said outfielder Roberto Kelly,
another former Dodger. ``Eventually we're going to run into a team
with good pitching and they won't let us score seven or eight runs.
We've got to find little ways to score.''
</P>
<P>
   One often overlooked sign of a winner is beating the teams you
are expected to beat. The Rangers are 7-1 against Minnesota. The
Dodgers are 0-3 against Pittsburgh and the Angels are just 2-4
against Detroit and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice for the Rangers to have MVP Jose Gonzalez, who had 10
homers in May; Rafael Palmeiro, who returned to the club this year
and is among the league leaders in average (.360) and homers (15);
and Ivan Rodriguez, who ended a 20-game hitting streak Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improvement, however, has been the starting
pitching, which had a very credible 4.04 ERA during the streak. As
a result, the Rangers are starting to feel much better about their
rotation. Going into the winning streak, Rangers starting pitchers
had a 7.00 combined ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are plenty good enough,'' manager Johnny Oates
said. ``Our guys are as good as anybody's guys, it's a matter of
going out and doing what they are capable of doing. They may not
have a 3.90 ERA at the end, but it's going to be good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning streak gives the Rangers a little room in the West
and general manager Doug Melvin doesn't feel the pressure of giving
up premium prospects in a trade for a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, they were in a late-season struggle with the Angels
for the AL West title. At the trade deadline, they sent top
prospect Fernando Tatis to St. Louis for pitcher Todd Stottlemyre
and shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Texas made the playoffs but was swept by the New York Yankees in
the first round. Stottlemyre then left through free agency and
signed with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   When the team got off to a slow start this year, there were
feelers made to acquire pitching. But the price always was the
same: outfielder Ruben Mateo, the new kid on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez, David Cone, they're not available,'' Melvin
said. ``I haven't asked lately, but those kind of pitchers aren't
available, even if you said Ruben Mateo. You have a short list of
No.1 starters; then I'm not sure there's a huge difference between
what you call No. 2, 3 and 4 starters in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be something better, but the cost might not make
sense. You keep digging holes if you give up young players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
