<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE HURT: NO MARTINEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mariners play in San Diego this weekend, then onto Colorado
beginning Monday, meaning a six-game stretch without DH and cleanup
hitter Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Although this past week the Mariners reached 100 homers faster
than any team in major-league history, Martinez's loss will hurt
the lineup. He no longer plays in the field and will be limited to
pinch-hitting duties for a week.
</P>
<P>
   And Seattle pitchers are bad enough pitchers, let alone hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague play hurts us more than some teams, because we
have an every-day DH and he's a huge part of our offense,''
Mariners manager Lou Piniella said. ``We lose our cleanup hitter
and get a pitcher hitting for six games? That's not a good trade
for us.'' &QL; 
DL FOR ARROYO
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rolando Arroyo was the Tampa Bay Devil Rays first
All-Star. Now the club has done him a favor by putting him on the
disabled list. The reason is mild tendinitis in his pitching
shoulder, but he is not bad enough physically to lose 5 mph off his
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say he has lost his competitive edge. In 302/3 innings
at Tropicana Field this season, Arrojo is 0-5 with 52 hits _ almost
two per inning _ and 30 earned runs, an 8.80 ERA. His problems at
home go back to last season, going 1-9 there since July 2. &QL; 
SIGNABILITY
</P>
<P>
   Using compensation picks for Albert Belle and Robin Ventura, the
White Sox were able to claim five of the top 23 pitchers in the
draft, according to ratings by Baseball America, and six of the top
33 overall.
</P>
<P>
   They are saying it was a better draft than 1997 when they
selected Crescenta Valley and UCLA left-hander Jim Parque, now in
the big leagues. The only question is whether they can afford to
sign their top picks. It took six months for the Sox to sign last
year's top choice, right-hander Kip Wells, who eventually received
a $1.495 million bonus. They failed to sign Detroit Tigers
right-hander Jeff Weaver after drafting him in '97 but have since
slashed the major-league payroll. &QL; 
RAPPING HIS MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   The song players choose for their walk to the plate has caused
some problems at Yankee Stadium. New outfielder Tony Tarasco's
selection was a rap song from the soundtrack of ``Belly'' by Hype
Williams that contained several obscene references _ and were
clearly audible to fans Tuesday in his at-bat. When Tarasco batted
in later innings, the music had been changed to a Backman Turner
Overdrive song. The club later said the PA attendant was on his
first day on the job and would be disciplined. &QL; 
HIGH AND TIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Jaret Wright's surprise when the Indians right-hander
entered AL president Gene Budig's office Tuesday to discuss
recently hitting Boston's Darren Lewis and Detroit's Tony Clark
with pitches near or on the head. At the meeting was Hall of Famer
Bob Gibson, who intimidated batters throughout his career with St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, a consultant to Budig, was reportedly there to talk to
Jaret about pitching inside _ a how-to lesson, so to speak. The
meeting took place before Wright's next start, against the Red Sox.
He didn't pitch inside and was shelled for eight runs on nine hits
in 32/3 innings. &QL; 
TOUGH SPOT
</P>
<P>
   The ``personal situation'' that forced Red Sox right-hander Mark
Portugal to leave the club last week was an offshoot of a messy
divorce. According to a report in the Providence Journal, the
source of Portugal's problems center on visitation rights for his
children, who live in Barrington, R.I. Part of the reason Portugal,
36, signed with the Sox was to be closer to his kids. Portugal
cleaned out his locker after Monday's 8-7 victory over Detroit and
talked to teammates about retirement but announced Friday he will
stay with the team. Now in his 15th season, Portugal signed a
one-year, $3-million deal with Boston in December. &QL; 
FINALLY
</P>
<P>
   Toronto manager Jim Fregosi, commenting on NL umpiring crew
chief, Frank Pulli, using a TV replay Monday to overturn,
correctly, a homer for the Marlins' Cliff Floyd:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything because Frank lives right down
the street from me (in Tarpon Springs, Fla.) and I don't want him
burning anything in my lawn. I will say that Frank's wife isn't
going to be happy with the fine he's going to get. She's tougher
than him.... Has better vision, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
