<HEADLINE>
TAKING AIM AT VALENTINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Angels' Terry Collins is lucky. He is just disliked by a few
players on his team. Mets manager Bobby Valentine appears to be
hated by just about everyone in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So says his center fielder, Brian McRae, who places part of the
blame for the Mets' eight-game losing streak on the way opposing
teams get charged up for the Mets, based on their personal dislike
for Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   McRae is incensed with the way Valentine is rotating five
outfielders: himself, Bobby Bonilla, Rickey Henderson, Roger Cedeno
and Benny Agbayani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys, when they come to the ballpark expecting to play
and don't, their whole day is ruined,'' McRae said. ``And when they
don't expect to play, and do play, they start panicking. It's
easier when you know what's going on on a day-to-day basis. This
game is hard enough to play without having other things on your
mind to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of grit that the Mets took into this weekend's
series with the crosstown Yankees. Saturday was considered the
biggest day in New York sports history with the Yankees/Mets game,
the Belmont Stakes with Triple Crown implications and an NBA
Eastern Conference final game between the Knicks and Indiana
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's the price we pay for playing in New York,''
closer John Franco said. ``Going up against (David) Cone and El
Duque (Orlando Hernandez) and Roger Clemens... that's like facing
John Smoltz and Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux on the last weekend of
the season last year.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Mets lost all of those games. &QL; 
D'BACKS STINGING
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Matt Williams and Jay Bell were the first teammates to
hit at least 15 homers in the first 50 games of a National League
season since Hank Aaron and Rico Carty did it in 1975. Bell also
was the first in the NL to reach 50 runs, on pace to score 153
runs. That would rank 10th in major-league history. Babe Ruth has
the record with 177 in 1921. Lou Gehrig scored 167 in 1936, the
last time anyone has scored as many as 152. Ted Williams had 150 in
1949. &QL; 
RED LETTER DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati went into interleague play on a 5-1 roll as part of a
12-game road trip. The rest of the trip includes games against
beatable Kansas City and Minnesota. The Reds took two of three from
Florida and swept New York for the first time at Shea Stadium since
July 7-9, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the (opponents') records, you say, `We can
handle this club,''' manager !boldJack McKeon said. ``But still,
road wins are road wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds won 10 of their last 12 away from home heading into the
weekend and are right behind the Cubs in the early wild-card race.
Overall, they had won 13 of their last 17 games and were five games
over .500 for the first time since the end of 1995, when they won
the NL Central. &QL; 
IS A PATTERN FORMING?
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh time in eight years, Colorado selected a pitcher
in the first round of the draft _ Jason Jennings from Baylor. The
exception was Todd Helton in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The others haven't exactly been success stories: '92: John
Burke, now retired after being a bust; '93: Jamey Wright, now in
the minors; '94: Doug Million, who died from an asthma attack after
underachieving in the minors; '96: Jake Westbrook (traded to
Montreal in the Mike Lansing deal); '97: Mike Mangum (traded along
with Westbrook) and '98: Matt Roney, who underwent surgery to
repair a torn labrum one day before this year's draft. &QL; 
BIG BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had five fans arrested last weekend for throwing Oh
Henry! bars onto the field during a game against St. Louis.
Throwing the candy had become a tradition in Montreal after Henry
Rodriguez hit home runs. The five fans are to appear in court later
this month on charges of disorderly conduct, and the Cubs could use
video from new surveillance cameras as evidence. The cameras were
installed because fans in the bleachers at Wrigley Field had become
more rowdy than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will pay their fines for them because it's a rule they
probably didn't know,'' Rodriguez said. ``You have to let the fans
know what the rules are and they'll follow the rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
