<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-AIRWAR-BOS     06-05 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-AIRWAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID AIR POWER ALONE FORCE MILOSEVIC TO YIELD?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a strange development, but President Clinton might end up
best-remembered as the first leader in history to win a war with
air power alone.
</P>
<P>
   Most military analysts have long held such an achievement to be
impossible. Bombing can wear out and soften up the enemy, the
argument goes, but ultimately, only troops on the ground can push
an army out of occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after suffering 72 days of NATO bombing, Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic surrendered as close to unconditionally as
anyone might have imagined. And he did so without a single NATO
soldier firing a shot from the ground or any troops amassing on his
borders.
</P>
<P>
   A debate will probably rage for months or years over just which
pressures led Milosevic to cave. The outcome of this debate could
have dramatic consequences, well into the next century, for the
contours of global diplomacy, the perception of American power, and
the structure of the American military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that strategic bombing _ punishment of the
Serbian population _ did the deal here,'' said Robert Pape,
professor at Dartmouth College, whose book, ``Bombing to Win,''
demonstrated that air power by itself has never won a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it did work, you're going to see a lot more use of air
power, because it's really easy to punish populations, and you
don't lose any American lives,'' Pape continued. ``You could get
rid of the Army, a lot of the Navy, and just use cruise missiles to
blow up power plants. This will be the US Air Force's world.''
</P>
<P>
   Pape and other analysts, for now, are holding back from such a
judgment. For one thing, it is not entirely clear that air power
did win all by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, US and NATO officials say, the Kosovo
Liberation Army grew a lot stronger _ so much so that its raids on
Serbian military positions forced Serb troops to come out of hiding
and fight. As they did so, US A-10 attack planes suddenly appeared
overhead and pummeled Serbian tanks, armored personnel vehicles,
and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   If this one-two punch was what tipped the balance of power, it
nonetheless puts a new twist to the traditional concept of
``combined-arms'' warfare. The idea used to be that air power would
assist the troops on the ground. Now, it seems, ground troops serve
as little more than feints to bring the enemy out in the open, and
force him to concentrate into target-packets for the airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, military specialist at the Federation of American
Scientists, thinks both types of air warfare _ bombing the Serbian
troops in Kosovo and the various targets in Belgrade and other Serb
cities _ took their toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite possible that Milosevic would have been content
letting his 19-year-old draftees get slaughtered in the field, if
everything was fine at home,'' Pike said. ``He might have been
content if he was doing well militarily in Kosovo, despite all the
destruction in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he was getting degraded everywhere _ when everything
was going against him _ then that's when he had no choice but give
up,'' Pike continued.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Arkin, a former US Army intelligence officer and a
consultant to the United Nations, said, ``The main thing is that
Milosevic failed to achieve his objective _ which was to wait it
out till the NATO coalition collapsed. That didn't happen. The war
ended because Milosevic didn't outlast the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, Arkin said, all of NATO's fine-tuned strategies
concerning which targets to hit, and in what order to
``choreograph'' the destruction, had no effect whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter what we bombed,'' Arkin said. ``It just
mattered that we bombed. It was sheer repetition, sheer brute
force, and Milosevic finally concluded it wasn't going to stop.
Before people say we need more cruise missiles or more smart
weapons, they might want to consider _ this is not calculus, this
is mystery. It is utterly unclear what it was about the bombing
that forced Milosevic to capitulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few dispute that it was bombing _ and, from the point of
view of what NATO contributed to the fight, bombing alone _ that
won the war. And that is what could change not just the way people
think about warfare but also the way the world conducts it.
</P>
<P>
   John Keegan, the eminent military historian, admitted in
Thursday's London Daily Telegraph that he was ``wrong'' to think
bombing would not be enough to win. When he first began to realize
this, he wrote, ``I turned the thought around for a while and
looked at it from several directions, rather as a Creationist
Christian might have done on being shown his first dinosaur bones.
I didn't want to change my beliefs, but there was too much evidence
accumulating to stick to the article of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan sees the war as a victory not just for air power but for
the ``New World Order'' that President Bush declared after the Gulf
War. ``If Milosevic really is a beaten man, all other would-be
Milosevics around the world will have to reconsider their plans,''
Keegan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the planes that bombed Serbia into submission took off
from distant aircraft carriers, some from the continental United
States. ``What that means is that there are now no places on Earth
that cannot be subjected to the same relentless harrowing,'' he
continued. ``What that implies . . . is that no rational ruler will
choose to commit the crimes that have attracted such punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion here is that, just as British gunboats once
sailed by distant lands and imposed order by threatening to shell
the harbor, now American B-2 bombers will fly over distant lands
and impose order by threatening to drop smart bombs on their power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts shudder at this possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot A. Cohen, professor at the Johns Hopkins School for
Advanced International Studies and author of the US Air Force's
five-volume study of the air war against Iraq, said of Keegan's
view, ``That would be a very dangerous lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen continued, ``Yes, in a sense, air power won. We threw
everything we had at a country whose gross domestic product is
one-15th the size of the US military budget, and after 72 days and
a lot of mess-ups, we succeeded. Maybe that's our future. But to
draw sweeping generalizations for air power _ that's a big mistake.
In 20 years' time, if we're up against the Chinese, it's a
different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also cautioned, ``Other people react to these sorts of
things.'' If Western leaders suddenly conclude that knocking out a
country's power plants is an effective technique of foreign policy,
then various foes might figure out ways to destroy power plants
here.
</P>
<P>
   And what if Westerners never really discover what pushed
Milosevic over the edge?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's true that bombing did it all I want to know that it's
true, I want to know the world has changed,'' Pape said. ``Maybe it
is true, maybe it's a new world now. But if it's not and we think
it is, we're going to learn a lot of false lessons, we're going to
make a lot of bad mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
