<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-INJURY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC, INJURED AT BELMONT, IS THROUGH AS A RACE HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ It wasn't the type of picture Bob Lewis and D.
Wayne Lukas had wanted nine hours earlier, when they gathered their
friends for a group photograph in front of Barn 10 on the
backstretch of Belmont Park. At 8:45 a.m. the owner and trainer
were full of hope. Their horse, Charismatic, was one and a half
miles and 11 horses away from making history as the 12th Triple
Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to get one of these at 5:28 p.m.,'' Lukas
said determinedly, at the time believing they would reconvene for a
winner's-circle photo to top an anticipated Charismatic sweep on
Saturday of the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness Stakes and the
Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, what Lewis and Lukas witnessed was an unexpected,
horrible image. Shortly after Charismatic finished third to Lemon
Drop Kid and Vision and Verse, Charismatic's jockey, Chris Antley,
pulled up his horse just beyond the wire and then leapt from the
horse's back. He fell on his seat, scrambled to his feet and began
rubbing Charismatic's left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The horse that had run five races in the last 63 days at the
highest level of the sport was limping as he boarded an ambulance
and was fitted with a pressure cast. The verdict was as swift as
Antley's reaction to his horse's discomfort _ X-rays determined
Charismatic had a lateral condylar fracture of his left front leg.
It was a complete fracture with the bone broken to the outside, as
well as a vertical fracture in his lateral sesamoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is through as a race horse. We expect him to be fine as a
stallion,'' said Dr. Larry Bramlage of the American Association of
Equine Veterinarians as he announced Charismatic would require
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure speculation, but it probably happened before the
wire. It's the type of injury that happens and they continue on
before they pull up. They try to run through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley, who found the perfect engine to drive his comeback from
depression and weight gain in the onetime claiming horse, sensed
his horse was in trouble as Charismatic barreled down the
staggering Belmont stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse from the outside came to us,'' he said of Lemon Drop
Kid, ``and passed us. At that point I rode just enough to hang on
for third. I had stopped whipping. Heading for the finish he
suddenly dipped underneath me and I could tell he was in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In their box seats, Lewis and Lukas' disappointment at being
thwarted in the history books was suddenly washed over with
concern. Antley's face was ghostly, and tears streamed down his
face moments after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke down right after we crossed the wire,'' said Antley,
sobbing. ``He gave us a lot. He gave America a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, whose horse Silver Charm was beaten here two years ago by
Touch Gold and denied the Triple Crown, also was visibly shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our only concern right now is Charismatic,'' Lewis said. ``We
hope to God he is going to be fine. We accepted the accolades in
Louisville and Baltimore and today was just one of those things
that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a heart-wrenching end to a day that began with so much
promise when Charismatic welcomed the daylight to Long Island with
an easy stroll on the Belmont track at 5:17 a.m. With Lukas on a
pony next to him and the exercise rider Joanne McNamara on his
back, Charismatic seemed eager to take on his rivals and bring home
a bonus of $5 million for his owners.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, perhaps he was too eager. Lewis said Charismatic had
been a bit agitated in the morning. ``Wayne said he was ready to
run, that he was a little upset that he could only walk this
morning,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Charismatic didn't leave that eagerness to run in
the barn. Instead of tracking the front runners early in the race,
as he did brilliantly to win the first two legs of the Triple
Crown, Charismatic dueled the filly, Silverbulletday, for the first
one and a half miles of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe he ran away with her,'' said Silverbulletday's
rider, Jerry Bailey, of the early pressure from Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I could see his horse was kind of rank. I looked over and
he was trying to pull him back but he couldn't get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   The great-grandson of Secretariat had captured the public's
imagination because of his modest background and his fondness for
hard work and the feed tub. He escaped from the claiming ranks
where he could have been bought for $62,500 back in February when
Lukas decided to bear down on his training and racing schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week, we talked about how maintenance-free this horse was
and how durable he is,'' said Lukas, whose training accomplishments
include unprecedented earnings of $200 million and a record 19
Eclipse Award winners. ``It's racing, and these things happen and
we have to deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians here indicated Charismatic's injury was a freak
accident, but that probably won't discourage critics of the
trainer, who believe Lukas is too hard on his horses in his search
for victories _ he has 12 _ in the grueling Triple Crown races. His
integrity and horsemanship were savaged when Union City, a horse
some believed was not sound, fractured a leg during the 1993
Preakness Stakes and did not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Other breakdowns by Lukas stars have followed; the 1994
Preakness winner, Tabasco Cat, was retired with a leg injury at the
age of 4; the 1994 champion juvenile filly, Flanders, broke a bone
in the Breeders' Cup and was retired; the 1995 Preakness winner,
Timber Country, strained leg tendons and was retired on the eve of
the Belmont, and the 1995 Kentucky Derby winner, Thunder Gulch,
fractured a cannon bone in his foreleg five months after the Derby
at the Jockey Club Gold Cup and was also retired. In 1996, his
Derby winner, Grindstone, was injured and retired before the
Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was subdued and had adopted an all-business approach early
in the day of his run at history. He was downright somber by the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a victory photo, the Lewis-Lukas camps were looking
at X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   The fragile nature of horse racing had again taken much of the
air out of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
