<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-     06-05 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV LEADER RECEIVED CONTRADICTORY ADVICE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Did Leposava Ristic have to die?
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old grandmother was working the fields when NATO
bombs peppered the rural countryside of Donji Neradovac in southern
Serbia last Monday morning. She died where she fell, on the land
her family has farmed for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted
a deal that was not even as good for him as the one he could have
had 11 weeks ago, before NATO warplanes laid waste his country,
killing hundreds of innocents like Ristic, and before he was
indicted on war crimes charges for overseeing the expulsion of
800,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO and Yugoslav generals huddled  &UR; yesterday &LR;  on the
Macedonia-Serbia border, working out the logistics of a Yugoslav
withdrawal from Kosovo, it remained unclear why Milosevic suddenly
capitulated to NATO's demands. Milosevic has yet to make a
statement or address the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview  &UR; yesterday &LR; , a member of Milosevic's Cabinet
and one of his closest advisers described a fierce debate between
those who urged Milosevic to fight NATO to the end and those who
urged him to cut the country's losses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being someone Milosevic listens to, Bogoljub Karic is
one of the richest men in Yugoslavia. A millionaire businessman, he
said he accepted a Cabinet position to steer his country toward a
free-market economy and away from its isolationist policies. For
the last month, Milosevic listened as Karic and other influential
Serb businessmen argued that the battered Yugoslav economy could
take no more.
</P>
<P>
   Karic credits Milosevic with making ``a courageous decision'' to
end the war. He said the debate was ferocious when members of
Milosevic's inner circle reviewed their options May 27, the day the
international war crimes tribunal announced it had indicted
Milosevic and four of his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Karic said he had been arguing for acceptance of the principles
outlined by the Group of Eight nations, which would allow foreign
peacekeeping troops into Kosovo under the auspices of the United
Nations. He said Vojislav Seslj, the deputy prime minister and
leader of the ultranationalist Radical Party, argued for all-out
war, urging Milosevic to enlist the Christian Orthodox church
hierarchy to call ordinary citizens to arms.
</P>
<P>
   Karic said it was an emotional debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One archbishop from Kosovo called me a traitor,'' said Karic,
who is from Kosovo. ``I hugged him and kissed him and told him this
is the only way Kosovo will stay in Serbia. The Radicals said that
NATO will get tired, that there will be an uprising by the people
to go into Kosovo, but these were delusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Karic said that before Milosevic was indicted, the government
had been leaning toward pushing for a peace deal based on the
principles of the Group of Eight, which consists of the Group of
Seven industrialized nations plus Russia. He feared that Milosevic
would feel cornered by the indictment, which he called provocation
from some Western powers who wanted the war to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the indictments were announced, we expected a negative
reaction by our leadership,'' Karic said. ``It was a very rough
night. We were looking at total isolation and total war,
annihilation. But President Milosevic ignored it and extended his
hand in reconciliation. He surprised the whole world. We now have
to grasp the opportunity and bring about total stability in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, May 28, when Russian envoy Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin arrived here to meet with Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president had already decided to seek a deal based on the G-8
principles, Karic said. Chernomyrdin returned five days later, this
time with President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland, and by Thursday
 &UR; afternoon &LR;  Milosevic had formally agreed to the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Karic's version of events portray Milosevic in the kindest of
lights, as a leader who swallowed his pride to save his people from
more suffering. But Karic rejects suggestions that Milosevic should
resign for the good of his people, even though the United States
and European Union have said they will not pay for the
reconstruction of Yugoslavia as long as Milosevic is its leader.
</P>
<P>
   He called Milosevic a ``moderating influence'' on the likes of
Seslj, who has vowed to quit the governing coalition and bring down
the government rather than allow foreign troops into Kosovo. Karic
said the West should rebuild the shattered country ``without
preconditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the West may find it hard to believe Karic's version,
that Milosevic magnanimously accepted defeat to save his country
from further suffering. This, after all, is a leader who started
four wars in 10 years and lost them all, causing untold suffering
in Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia, and finally Kosovo, while the
standard of living for Yugoslavia's 10 million people sank as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The government here insists it has guaranteed that Kosovo will
remain part of Yugoslavia, and that by holding out for more than 70
days of bombing it made sure that the United Nations, not NATO,
would oversee the postwar administration of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But given the damage done to the country's infrastructure,
including 41 bridges that have been destroyed, it was an enormous
cost to pay for some political cover. None of the Western allies
wanted Kosovo to become independent or join a greater Albania in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   There are other explanations for why Milosevic suddenly
capitulated. One aide to a Yugoslav Cabinet minister said that the
entire country faced being without electricity within two weeks if
the war carried on.
</P>
<P>
   A politician says that Milosevic and his Cabinet finally
realized that the Russians, who had been sticking up for them and
chastising NATO for its bombing campaign, were getting nowhere with
NATO. Given its own financial mess, Russia needs the West more than
it needs Yugoslavia, this theory holds.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that Milosevic's health is deteriorating. Rumors that
he suffered a stroke have been stoked by his recent appearances on
television, in which the left side of his mouth appears droopy and
his left arm appears lifeless. Karic, however, said Milosevic's
health is good and had nothing to do with his decision to take the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But there were other cracks in the carefully cultivated image of
national unity. In Nis, headquarters of the Yugoslav Third Army,
which was hunkered down in Kosovo, conscripts were refusing to
report to their units. Last week, 24 reservists were arrested in
Krusevac for refusing to report for duty, just a week after there
were several days of protests against the war in that town. In
Cacak, a group of residents was arrested after organizing antiwar
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than follow Seslj into Kosovo to fight for the province
that contains religious and heritage sites important to them, more
Serbs were beginning to ask why they were enduring daily bombings,
blackouts, water outages, and lines for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown how many Yugoslav soldiers and police were killed
in Kosovo. The commander of the Third Army in Kosovo, General
Nebojsa Pavkovic, said about 1 percent, or 1,800, of his 180,000
men had been killed by the airstrikes. NATO estimates the figure at
three times that. There were near-riots in some towns in southern
Serbia when coffins of soldiers came home en masse three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why their president allowed their country to be
bombed when he could have got just as much by giving in sooner,
some Serbs tell a variation of the same joke: A group of cannibals
surrounded Milosevic, telling him they would eat him unless he gave
them $3 million, dug a mile-long trench, or drank a bucket of
manure. Milosevic began digging, but gave up just short of his
goal. He drank as much of the manure he could stomach, but didn't
finish it. Finally, he handed over the $3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
