A4421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-REBUILD-BO     06-05 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-REBUILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBUILDING KOSOVO A DAUNTING TASK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is called a DART squad, a small group of American
disaster-relief specialists now being assembled to go into Kosovo
as Serb forces retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The Disaster Assistance Response Team, under the auspices of the
Agency for International Development, will investigate one of the
biggest mysteries of the war: the fate of a half-million ethnic
Albanians who have been hiding in the hills and forests of the
devastated region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there may be hundreds of thousands of people with
inadequate or no access to food or medicine,'' Harriet Babbitt,
acting director of the agency, said in a telephone interview. ``For
all the problems of the refugees now in Albania and Macedonia, none
have been hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from ending with the conclusion of the military conflict in
the Balkans, humanitarian-assistance operations will need to expand
dramatically in the weeks ahead to cope with the internally
displaced people of Kosovo. At the same time, aid agencies will
continue to care for refugees in Albania and Macedonia who remain
fearful of returning, plus those who will begin trickling back into
Kosovo but have little or nothing to return to.
</P>
<P>
   So devastated is Kosovo, with 80 percent of the homes destroyed,
according to UN officials, that most relief officials doubt that
many of the refugees will be repatriated before winter. An
estimated 443,000 refugees are in Albania, 248,800 in Macedonia,
and 70,000 in Montenegro. Since early April, another 75,000 have
been sent to other countries, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the International Rescue Committee began
high-altitude air drops of high-energy rations for refugees
displaced within Kosovo. When Serb forces shut down their
antiaircraft batteries in Kosovo, as the NATO conditions demand,
these missions will expand and be flown at low altitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those refugees who have come out who were internally displaced
have been in worse condition than those who just left their
homes,'' said Babbitt. ``We are looking at a two-track operation as
the settlement goes forward. It is going to be a huge
undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   It is just one of the upcoming costs in a sea of costs,
estimated in the tens of billions of dollars, that will be part of
the disaster-relief, peacekeeping, and rebuilding effort for the
war-ravaged province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' said Anwyn Hurxthal, an official
with Oxfam America, a Boston-based humanitarian operation active in
the Balkans. ``Our concern is that as the media spotlight moves on
to other things, people will relax and think the problem is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Kosovo price tag, billions more will be needed to
reconstruct the rest of Yugoslavia and the economically battered
nations surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky is really the limit,'' said Chris Helman, a senior
analyst with the Center for Defense Information, a Washington think
tank. ``The US is looking to shift the burden to its European
allies, but whether they will sit still for it is highly
doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   At least verbally, European leaders are stepping up to the
plate. Romano Prodi, incoming president of the European Commission,
said last week the European Union would need to allocate $6 billion
a year for the next five years to Balkan rebuilding. Other European
officials spoke of the continent's moral obligation to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe will have to be generous in assistance to reconstruct
civil life and civil society in the Balkans,'' said Chris Patten, a
British official who is joining the European Commission and has
been mentioned as a possible successor to Javier Solana as civilian
chief of NATO. Patten met with Globe editors on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the European Union should also be ``much more
fervent and positive'' about enlarging its membership in order to
help elevate the economic status of the nations of southeastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With the fighting winding down, Helman and other analysts said
money originally appropriated for Operation Allied Force can be
redirected to the 50,000-member peacekeeping force that will soon
enter Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Kosiak of the Center for Strategic and Budgetary
Assessments, a Washington research group, estimated that the cost
of deploying the 7,000 US troops in the peacekeeping force will be
$2 billion to $3.5 billion a year. For the next year, that could
easily be covered by the unused portion of the $10.9 billion in
emergency Defense Department funding that Congress approved last
month, said Kosiak. Half of that money was for the war; the rest
was for military pay raises and construction projects. The 72-day
air war, said Kosiak, would have eaten up $1.7 billion to $2.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is there for peacekeeping,'' he said. ``Beyond that,
if you assist Yugoslavia, one could find billions of dollars' worth
of problems to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO said its missiles and bombs have destroyed 34 highway
bridges in Yugoslavia, 11 railroad bridges, and 57 percent of the
country's oil reserves. Factories are in ruins, power plants have
been crippled, and both military and civilian structures destroyed
in the air war. Yugoslav officials said the country needs $100
billion to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall insist on the international community, especially
NATO and the United States, paying for what they have destroyed,''
said Goran Trivan, a member of the ruling Socialist Party's
executive committee, last week.
</P>
<P>
   But US and European officials have made clear that as long as
Slobodan Milosevic remains in power, the West will not help rebuild
the nation. And even if Milosevic steps down or is overthrown,
reconstruction of the country is likely to have a lower priority
than aid to Kosovo and the nations surrounding Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the NATO summit in Washington in April, officials agreed to
create an assistance fund for southeastern Europe. In part, this
was to reward Bulgaria, Romania, Macedonia, Albania, Croatia,
Bosnia, and Hungary, which cooperated with NATO throughout the
conflict. In part, it was to cover the financial losses arising
from the cutoff of vital highway and waterway trade routes through
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard a lot of discussion of a Marshall Plan for
southeastern Europe,'' said Helman, of the Center for Defense
Information. ``They are thinking of tens of billions of dollars.
But it hasn't been very specific yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding is the crucial step in winning the peace, he added,
just as the rebuilding of Japan and Germany was successful in
creating good will after World War II. The record was not as good
after the Vietnam conflict, he said, which had a murkier outcome.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen which pattern Kosovo will fit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
