<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-NANOOSE-BOS &LR;      06-05 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-NANOOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COLUMBIA PREMIER STIRS UP HORNET'S NEST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Start with the bad boy premier of British Columbia, a
politician whose polls are in decline, whose administration is
dogged by mismanagement, and whose home life has lately been
disrupted by search warrant-wielding police investigating links
between government and gambling interests.
</P>
<P>
   Add an obscure military facility whose lease is about to expire.
</P>
<P>
   Heap on Pacific salmon, then stir in Western Canada's resentment
of federal politicians back east. Add environmental groups. Stir in
a dollop of natural Canadian antipathy toward the big American
neighbor. Then a pinch of well-heeled homeowners along Georgia
Strait, the spectacular waterway between Vancouver Island and the
mainland, fretting that big naval warships represent a hazard to
their sailing yachts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, season with scare talk about nuclear weapons. Careful
now! The merest insinuation is enough to make the stew a real
attention-grabber.
</P>
<P>
   That's the latest recipe from Glen Clark, British Columbia's
pugnaciously anti-American premier.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's political fortunes are drooping these days as British
Columbia's economy falters and critics accuse his administration of
incompetence and worse. In Canada, there's a time-honored tactic
for situations like his. Blame the Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   The premier is threatening to boot the US Navy from the Nanoose
Bay torpedo test range, where for decades American and Canadian
military researchers have fine-tuned weapons for undersea warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The test range is a Canadian military facility, but legal
ownership of the seabed belongs to British Columbia. Since the
facility was opened in 1965, Ottawa has leased the 75 square miles
of open water and a 300-acre islet.
</P>
<P>
   That lease expires on Sept. 4, and Clark insists he will give
the heave-ho to the Navy unless the United States makes some big
concessions to British Columbia on salmon catches and, in the
latest wrinkle, nuclear warheads that might or might not be carried
aboard US war vessels entering Georgia Strait.
</P>
<P>
   He has got their attention in Ottawa and Washington. Infuriated
by Clark's antics, and fearful of damage to the US-Canada military
alliance, Canada's federal government is making threats of its own,
to seize the seabed and lands of Nanoose Bay and make them federal
property.
</P>
<P>
   That has some British Columbians talking secession. Many in the
province are already deeply disaffected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by itself, the expropriation of provincial land by Ottawa
would be an extremely provocative act,'' said Jim Fulton, executive
director of the Vancouver-based David Suzuki Foundation, an
environmental group. ``But to do so solely to allow Americans to
keep testing their weapons in our waters is an incredible affront
to public sensitivity. There are real safety issues here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of it all is the US Navy, which uses the Nanoose
Bay range for sea trials of sub-killing weaponry, most notably the
deadly MK-48 torpedo, and has more than $100 million invested in
the site.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 31,000 torpedo runs conducted at Nanoose Bay over
the years have involved nonexplosive dummy warheads or electronic
simulations. The idea is to test not the bang but guidance systems
and other high-tech equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clark is tying the future of the base to the health of
British Columbia's salmon fishery, and to a ban on nuclear weapons.
The premier wants Americans to slash catches of Pacific salmon, a
hot-button issue with the province's fishermen, who have long
claimed that the US fishing fleets are devastating stocks of
Chinook salmon and other species.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter dispute appears close to resolution, with the US and
Canada last week announcing a new treaty to conserve the depleted
stocks and more equitably divide the catch between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But should salmon peace come, Clark has another card: Canadian
dislike of American military might, especially nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the premier proclaimed that unless the United States
publicly pledges never to send submarines or surface ships bearing
nuclear warheads to Nanoose Bay, there will be no renewal of the
test range's lease.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear-armed US warships or subs rarely enter Canadian waters,
and as a general rule, the Navy does not keep nuclear weapons
aboard surface vessels, attack submarines or naval aircraft,
according to a Navy spokesman. But it's unlikely Washington would
agree to Clark's condition, which goes against a basic US military
policy of refusing to confirm or deny the presence of nuclear
weapons aboard any vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's drumbeat on Nanoose Bay has become an embarrassment for
Canada's federal government. This is not the first time the cocky
premier has rocked the boat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Clark egged on British Columbian fishermen who for
three days blockaded an American ferry and more or less held its
passengers hostage in the port of Prince Rupert. Meant as a protest
against US salmon policies, the action was an extremely serious
violation of international law, one that had President Clinton
fuming and the US Senate demanding a military response.
</P>
<P>
   Canada these days is trying to combat its image in Washington as
an unreliable ally. The United States has made no secret of its
irritation with the neighbor's sharp cuts in defense spending, and
has repeatedly warned that Ottawa has to shoulder a more equitable
burden in NATO and other alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Ottawa last month announced it would
seize the Nanoose Bay seabed rather than continue discussing
Clark's ``red herring'' demands on the testing range.
</P>
<P>
   ``That base will remain open,'' said Canadian Defense Minister
Art Eggleton. ``It is vital. If we cannot get a resolution . . .
expropriation will be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   That's tougher talk than Ottawa usually employs in the sensitive
realm of federal-provincial relations. There is already much
antagonism toward Ottawa in British Columbia, which, like other
Western provinces, complains Canada is dominated by Ontario and
panders too much to separatist French Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, antagonism toward Ottawa's perceived coddling of
Quebec has ignited a real, if still tiny, Quebec-style secessionist
movement in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is no separatist. But he realizes no Western politician
ever lost votes kicking Ottawa and the United States. ``We have to
be tough with the Americans. . . . And we are going to keep out
nuclear warheads,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
