<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-LPGA-USOPEN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-LPGA-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST SLAM TITLE NOW IN REACH FOR INKSTER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RON SIRAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Juli Inkster looked amazingly fresh in the
suffocating heat as she climbed the slight hill to the seventh tee
at Old Waverly Golf Club, her eyes darting immediately to the green
where yet another pin was tucked in a remote corner. But try as
they might, tournament officials could put no pin out of Inkster's
reach in Saturday's third round. And try as they might, no one
might be able to keep her from finally winning the U.S. Women's
Open on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a masterly display of shot-making and composure on another
100-degree day here, Inkster started the front nine with
consecutive birdies, ended it with two more and punctuated the
round with a brilliant 8-iron from 138 yards to three feet on No.
16. A 67 on top of rounds of 65 and 69 put Inkster at 15-under-par
201 after 54 holes, four strokes ahead of Kelli Kuehne and Lori
Kane. Sherri Turner was another stroke back, and no one else was
within six strokes of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I keep playing the way I am playing. ... .'' Inkster said,
her voice trailing off as she contemplated becoming, along with Pat
Bradley, one of only two women to win the modern career grand slam.
``I think this is my tournament. All the pressure is on me. This
course lets you play aggressive, and I think that helps my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so, but the Old Waverly layout could make for a wild
Sunday shootout in what has been an uncharacteristic Open birdie
barrage, a result of bermuda grass rough that failed to grow to
full length because of an unusually cold spring and greens softened
by nearly three inches of rain in the two days before competition
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there is at least another 64 out there,'' Kane
said after she rallied from a shaky start, in which she made bogeys
on the second and third holes, to shoot a 71 to be at 205 along
with Kuehne. ``I like the position I'm in. I'll just try to make as
many birdies as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who lost the United States Open to Patty Sheehan in a
playoff in 1992, won the Nabisco Dinah Shore twice, the du Maurier
Classic and the McDonalds LPGA Championship once each _ all before
1990 and the birth of her first daughter. A victory here would
complete the career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to think about birdies when you don't have
to think about diapers,'' said Inkster, whose daughters Hayley and
Cori are now 9 and 5. ``I have confidence in my game and confidence
in my family. I need to shoot 2 or 3 under tomorrow. I can't see
throttling back.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was cooler than Inkster on a day when the temperature hit
102 degrees, and only Turner with a 68 made much of a move. The
defending champion, Se Ri Pak, slipped back with a 74 to be at 212,
and the U.S. Women's Amateur champion, Grace Park, continued her
impressive run with a 73 to be at 210.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anyone else mustering up the kind of magic and sense
of destiny Inkster has on her side, it is Kuehne, the 22-year-old
two-time U.S. Amateur champion whose foundering two-year
professional career burst to life in the last month. She missed
several short putts _ one from 30 inches on No. 15 _ and still shot
a 70 to earn a pairing with Inkster on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the expectations will be on her tomorrow,'' Kuehne said.
``I'm the underdog. No one thinks I'm going to win. There is no
pressure on me. But I will have to shoot 67 or 68 to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, her father, Ernie Kuehne, shuffled along
mopping the perspiration from his brow, gazed out at his diminutive
daughter and growled in a Texas drawl that sounded right at home as
it hung in the hot Mississippi air, ``Maybe the princess has grown
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but even the Kuehnes seemed to feel the sense of destiny
for Inkster that hangs heavy over this tournament. Later,
contemplating the four-stroke deficit his daughter faced, Ernie
Kuehne said, ``Face it, this is Inkster's Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is, or perhaps the shrewd father was cleverly laying
aside a mountain of pressure from his daughter's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tough day tomorrow,'' Inkster said. She knows.
She's been there before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
