u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-SAFARI-NYT &LR;      06-05 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SAFARI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY SLICKERS ON SAFARI: LIONS AND TIGERS, OH MY!  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably know little about tracking leopards, warding off
mosquitos, even handling a rifle (for protection only, of course),
much less an elephant's eating habits (300 pounds a day).
</P>
<P>
   But you can learn these things and also the fundamentals of what
it takes to be a safari guide in a four-day, three-night camp for
adults run by the prestigious Sabi Sabi game reserve in Skukuza,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   There are no more great hunters, at least not among the safaris
that now beckon tourists shooting cameras instead of guns. But the
thrill of the chase, as well as the intellectual breadth acquired
by learning to read nature and wildlife signs, are available to
campers, from Boomers to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat: You cannot write home for care packages. There is no
canteen, no once-a-week movies. Phone privileges? What phone?
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Ranger Training Experience, this program
accommodates from four to seven people at a time. Corporations such
as South African Airways regularly send small groups to the
15,000-acre Sabi Sabi, in the northeast part of the country
alongside Kruger National Park, to try to develop a spirit of
interdependence. ``Team-building,'' it is called.
</P>
<P>
   But you can do this if you are simply a camper longing to lose
yourself in a somewhat comfortable primeval experience, or learn
the tricks of the tracking trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have one hour of the Discovery Channel, you have to live
here six months,'' said Witas Mathe, a senior guide who also
conducts safaris at Sabi Sabi's three reserves.
</P>
<P>
   In the three nights, you still get a rich taste of an exotic
outdoor life. In your outsize tent built for two, you can look out
at night (if you dare) through the mesh ``window'' or simply cover
it up by lifting the Velcro screen. By the time your first night
falls, you will be attuned to the sounds and roars of the bushveld.
</P>
<P>
   Some things you do not have to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for an elephant to come into your tent,''
Mathe said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is comforting when your guide has a gun as he
arrives at your tent at 6:30 in the morning for your first day. If
you need a shower, there is an ingenious contraption: an overhead
pail with a spigot attached to the bottom that allows you to cover
yourself with water, like watering a plant. And, oh, yes, you draw
the water yourself in the bucket from a nearby well.
</P>
<P>
   As for a bathroom, well, you should have a sense of humor about
this: a raised platform, containing a toilet seat, overlooks the
African bush. It actually affords a pretty good view of the
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, when you are off with your guide, the first things
you'll be aware of are life's simple pleasures: the smell of the
grass, the tweet of the birds, those rustling sounds _ ominous?
benign? you will find out _ from the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you look after the environment,'' Mathe said, ``the
more it looks after you.''
</P>
<P>
   You will meet the ubiquitous guarri tree, a sort of life force
of the bush. This tree, you will learn, lives symbiotically with
man, animals and other trees.
</P>
<P>
   Break off a twig, and use it as a toothbrush. Its sap, say the
guides, kills bacteria that lurk in your mouth. Or you can brush
its leaves on your arms and legs and it wards off mosquitoes. Watch
for lions under the tree, though. They enjoy sleeping there since
it is a mosquito-free area. The large cape buffalo also come to the
guarri to rub against it and rid themselves of bugs.
</P>
<P>
   In your first moments in the bush, you follow in the footsteps
of the guides, soaking up their knowledge and natural instincts.
Guides at the various reserves are really remarkable people, part
zoology and botany professor, part fervent ecologist, part New York
City cab driver in their mad dashes through the bush to catch up to
the animals.
</P>
<P>
   By walking, you learn the difference between trees and the
different smells of plants. And you can tell when an elephant has
torn up the place recently when the scent of broken trees and
bushes wafts your way.
</P>
<P>
   When elephants strip the bark off a tree, and it dies, the
skeletal remains are a perfect home for vultures; they have
unobstructed views of the area. ``The tree,'' Mathe said, ``will
die. But the vultures will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Walks are followed by sit-down lectures, instruction in driving
the Land Rover (some shrubs bounce back when you drive over them,
others you learn to go around) and how to shoot a .458-caliber
rifle. In extreme cases, a warning shot will redirect the animal to
another path.
</P>
<P>
   The evenings, meanwhile, are filled with information about the
sky and the stars and animals' nocturnal habits.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, you are looking as well as listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stars,'' Mathe said, ``can also communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   You learn to use all your senses, which levels the playing field
somewhat. Now you can see the animals. They have probably seen you
all the while.
</P>
<P>
   By the third day you are tracking, looking for animal spoors,
leaving the protection of the vehicle to track on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The cost per person is about $600 for the three nights, meals
included. Further information can be obtained by calling (800)
524-7979. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
