<HEADLINE>
NBA PREPARES FOR WHEELING, DEALING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA draft is little more than three weeks away
and two things are already certain. This year's rookie class does
not have a clear-cut No.1 player and there will be an unprecedented
amount of wheeling and dealing by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The teams with the top seven picks in the draft are all willing
to trade away their choices, either to acquire some veterans or in
an attempt to move up.
</P>
<P>
   With so many possibilities for change, it might be foolish to
try to predict how the draft will pan out, but here's a first look
anyway at how the lottery picks might unfold.
</P>
<P>
   1. Chicago, Lamar Odom, SF, Rhode Island: The Bulls love the
idea of having an athletic scorer who could play at least three
positions. But they are worried about Odom's off-court problems and
don't want a bad citizen. Those fears will disappear when it comes
time to make their selection.
</P>
<P>
   2. Vancouver, Steve Francis, PG, Maryland: This is where the
action starts. The Grizzlies are advertising this pick for sale and
want a power forward. Duke's Elton Brand is too short (6-7, 6-6?).
Francis would be a great combo guard pairing with Mike Bibby, but
somebody else will move up here and snag him.
</P>
<P>
   3. Charlotte, Baron Davis, PG, UCLA: The Hornets are also
fielding offers. But they need a flashy point guard and Davis would
blend in perfectly with Eddie Jones, Elden Campbell and Anthony
Mason. It is hoped he won't be influenced by Campbell's and Mason's
sullen personalities.
</P>
<P>
   4. Clippers, Corey Maggette, G/F, Duke: They are praying that
Francis or Davis is still available. If not, it's dilemma time. Do
they reach for a point guard and take Andre Miller or Jason Terry?
Do they trade the pick?
</P>
<P>
   If they keep it, the roster is so depleted that the
best-available player route is the way to go. Maggette could be the
Vince Carter of the draft and the Clippers need some excitement as
they move into the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   5. Toronto, Elton Brand, PF, Duke: The Raptors are trying
everything they can to move into the top three. Don't bet against
them succeeding. In the meantime, someone else will be happy to
take Brand.
</P>
<P>
   6. Minnesota, Richard Hamilton, SG, Connecticut: Kevin McHale
wants to move up, too, and will grab a point guard so he can sign
and trade Terrell Brandon. But should the Wolves fail to move up,
they'll re-sign Brandon and then add Hamilton as a scoring threat
to ease the burden on Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   7. Washington, Wally Szczerbiak, PF, Miami, Ohio: The Wizards
want a scorer and will break the Cavaliers' hearts by drafting
Szczerbiak, who is likely to move up with a few good workouts in
the next two weeks. If the Grizzlies had guts, they would take him
at No.2.
</P>
<P>
   8. Cleveland, Jumaine Jones, F, Georgia: The Cavs are worried
about the injury to Zydrunas Ilgauskas, and with Szczerbiak off the
board, they need someone to rebound and score. Jones is capable of
playing inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   9. Phoenix, Jonathan Bender, PF, Picayune, Miss., H.S.: The Suns
don't need a guard or scorer, they need a fleet player with height.
Time to roll the dice on the 6-10 Bender, this year's prep darling.
</P>
<P>
   10. Golden State, Jason Terry, PG, Arizona: The Warriors need a
point guard and shooting guard. Terry is both and is an above
average defender. No chance he'll ever choke P.J. Carlesimo,
either.
</P>
<P>
   11. Cleveland, Ron Artest, SF, St. John's: The Cavs are looking
to trade this pick and the talent is getting slim. The only player
left capable of helping their anemic offense is Artest.
</P>
<P>
   12. Toronto, Andre Miller, PG, Utah: If the Raptors couldn't get
their point at No.5, they cross their fingers that the underrated
Miller drops down this low.
</P>
<P>
   13. Seattle, William Avery, PG, Duke: The Sonics need someone to
back up (replace?) Gary Payton and here's the fifth point guard to
go in the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Dead air: No one's ever really accused NBC's Ahmad Rashad of
being anything more than a shill for Michael Jordan, but somebody's
head should roll for his embarrassing interview with the Spurs'
Sean Elliott after Elliott hit a miraculous 3-pointer to win Game 2
of the San Antonio-Portland playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad droned on with several questions for Elliott but never
found the opportunity to ask Elliott about the 3-pointer, which was
the biggest shot of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody plugged into Rashad's earpiece should have demanded the
question be asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Czar dethroned: Mike Fratello thought he was a hot commodity
entering this week, while coaching the Cavs and hearing rumors he
was a candidate for the Nets job.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cleveland owner Gordon Gund popped into a staff meeting and
asked for a word with Fratello. Minutes later, he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs wanted to make a clean sweep in management after
kicking GM Wayne Embry further upstairs and replacing him with John
Paxson. Fratello's slowdown style also didn't endear him to Gund,
who was nervous about attendance slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Philly Pike? The Sixers are considering using their $2 million
salary exemption for Clippers free agent Eric Piatkowski, in an
attempt to improve their outside shooting.
</P>
<P>
   What did you expect? New York coach Jeff Van Gundy's tenuous job
security has not drawn sympathy from Indiana coach Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have known better than to go into New York and
coach,'' Bird said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
