<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VISIT TO WALLY'S WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those of you posing as hardcore basketball fans, but still
unfamiliar with the name Wally Szczerbiak, should please leave this
column immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, beat it. You're an imposter, and should find yourself
a nice page covered with soccer or horse racing. We'll wait while
you thumb your way out of here.
</P>
<P>
   The pretenders are gone. Back to Szczerbiak. OK, while you're
familiar with Wally - a lottery-listed forward from Miami of Ohio -
unloading his name in conversation could be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   It's three syllables, folks. The first one is ``Zir,'' which is
how you - as a teenager - addressed your old man: ``No, Zir, I have
not been drinking.'' The second syllable is ``B,'' which was your
algebra grade after unleashing those art-class skills on the letter
D. The final syllable is ``ack,'' the same sound that flew through
your lips during your sister's first attempt at meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   Right, Szczer-bi-ak. He's the rascal who dropped 43 points on
the Washington Huskies in the sunrise of March Madness (his
teammates combined for another 16, but Miami still won).
</P>
<P>
   Wally, known as ``World'' to his relentlessly clever college
pals who discovered National Lampoon's ``Vacation'' at Blockbuster,
worked out for the Clippers on Friday at USC's Lyon Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was 90 minutes of running, jumping, running, shooting,
cutting and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a typical day,'' said Szczerbiak, a self-made player who
finds this pre-draft selling process enjoyable. ``When I first got
to Miami, I never dreamed I'd be in this position, so I'm having
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the second stop on his ``World'' tour - the first
interview was in Toronto - with an all-comers audition scheduled
for Thursday in Chicago and trips lined up for Charlotte,
Washington and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The point-guard prowling Clippers, who have the fourth pick in
this month's draft, could use it to secure the dead-eye small
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak does have the endorsement of Clippers' power forward
Maurice Taylor, although each thumbs up from Mo wears a caveat. Mo
also talks up UCLA's Baron Davis, and Rhode Island's Lamar Odom,
among others. We are led to believe that Taylor thinks his team has
FOUR lottery picks instead of just the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Mo was winding down from his regularly scheduled workout
when Wally showed up to impress the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can shoot the blood out of the ball,'' Taylor said of
Szczerbiak. We believe shooting the blood out of the ball is a fine
thing, and that it suggests the Portland Trail Blazers were
shooting turnips in Friday's loss to the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the skinny on Wally:
</P>
<P>
   He isn't. Skinny, that is. He's a self-described
``late-bloomer'' who was thrilled to be offered a scholarship by
Miami, then began a weight-room siege in his desire to become a
pro. It worked. After averaging 24 points per game as a junior, he
was selected to play for the U.S. team at the 1998 Goodwill Games.
Wally subsequently stole the show, and inspired several NBA talent
hounds to believe they'd just discovered the next great sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   We're not sure if Wally has enough quickness to be great, but
his jumper is as deadly as dime-store cologne. Combine that with
240 pounds of weight-room victory and the combination may be even
more incongruous than a vanity plate on a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak frequently has been compared to Tom Gugliotta of the
Phoenix Suns, but Googs goes 6-foot-10, while Wally might be 6-7
after a collision with Don King's barber. While he can do business
inside, his game is more comparable to that of former NBA star Kiki
Vandeweghe.
</P>
<P>
   He probably won't average at least 20 points per game for seven
seasons in a row, like Kiki, but the Cleveland Cavaliers are said
to be willing to package their two lottery picks (8 and 12) to move
up and draft him.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, Chicago Bulldog Jerry Krause is another
vigorous Szczerbiak fan, and may be more than willing to offer up
that first overall pick to slide down a bit and select Wally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care where I end up,'' Szczerbiak said. ``I
just want to play for a franchise that wants to win and has great
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to hear my name called on draft night.''
</P>
<P>
   And if NBA commissioner David Stern remains a bigger hoops fan
than those other clowns, he may do justice when pronouncing the
kid's name.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Corey stories
</P>
<P>
   According to sources beyond our control, it took more than a
newspaper column to inspire Duke freshman Corey Maggette's leap to
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a replay on that one: While the Blue Devils were in
the Windy City (Maggette's hometown) to compete in the Great Eight,
the lively swingman came upon a newspaper list of the nation's
hottest draft prospects and saw his name at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before making his decision to leave Duke, word reached
Maggette that Krause was threatening to draft him - regardless of
where the Bulls landed on lottery day.
</P>
<P>
   June 30 should be a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead No Magic healing
</P>
<P>
   With Doc Rivers expected to be hired as head coach and Julius
``Dr. J'' Erving looming as executive VP, you'd think the Orlando
Magic will be able to manage a very important Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway Deal.
</P>
<P>
   One popular swap would be conducted with two-guard starved
Phoenix; the Suns shipping Gugliotta (a fine player who doesn't
have the wheels to help maximize the push tactics of Jason Kidd) to
Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Their salaries ($8 million and change) are salary-cap friendly,
but Penny does have the option of holding his breath for the
league's prevailing maximum deal.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead The rap on Rip
</P>
<P>
   Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton, a dandy shooting guard who led UConn
to the national championship, is making it difficult for teams with
early draft calls to fall in love with him.
</P>
<P>
   See, Rip hasn't hired an agent or anyone else who can expedite
those pesky individual workouts. He still could go in the top five,
but not getting up-close-and-personal could drop Hamilton a notch
or two.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, his replacement at UConn is expected to be 6-10 Ajou
Ajou Deng, a redshirt freshman defined by Huskies coach Jim Calhoun
as a ``6-foot-10 version of Reggie Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun should know; he coached the Lewis, the late Celtics
star, at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   We still think Portland's Greg Anthony should have made the
league's ``All-Defensive'' squad. It's obvious that by walking on
the court, he instantly becomes a threat to the offense of both
teams. ... Former Lakewood High and USC star Duane Cooper had a
fine season in Greece, and could be taking his point-guard skills
to an NBA camp near you. ... If the Knicks slip past the Pacers and
into the NBA Finals, Coach Jeff Van Gundy figures to join Gregg
Popovich of the Spurs as championship-round coaches who didn't play
in the NBA. The last time two pedigree-lacking coaches hooked up
was 1981, when Bill Fitch's Boston Celtics defeated the Houston
Rockets, coached by Del Harris. ... According to a rumor we might
have made up, Phil Jackson won't coach the Knicks unless the
venue's name is changed to Madison Triangle Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
