<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD OUSTS USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD _ It wasn't like the USC baseball team came into this
thing with an aura of invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Trojans were the defending national champions and the
preseason No.1 team in the country. But there was the awful start,
and the injuries and the suspect pitching depth.
</P>
<P>
   But even USC figured it was at least evenly matched with
Stanford when the two teams began their NCAA super regional series.
The answer was no. The Cardinal's pitching turned out to be better.
But not by much.
</P>
<P>
   USC's season ended Saturday with a 5-3 loss to the host Cardinal
in front of 3,742 sun-soaked fans at Sunken Diamond. Stanford
(48-13) advanced to the College World Series, which begins Friday
in Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (36-26) were left guessing by Cardinal sophomore
pitcher Justin Wayne, who struck out 12 and allowed just five hits
in eight innings. Wayne and sophomore Jason Young, Friday night's
Stanford starter who pitched a complete game 1-0 victory, combined
for 22 strikeouts in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we ran into outstanding pitching,'' USC head coach
Mike Gillespie said. ``It's a real credit to their pitching for us
to be held down like this. We can swing it. We can be an offensive
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, ironically, began the season with a brand-new set of
starters. Head coach Mark Marquess said he figured then that
pitching was the Cardinal's weakness. Now it is the strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go to Omaha with two hot pitchers,'' Marquess
said, ``and we've got that.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's pitching was almost as good, and good enough to win
against most every team the Trojans played this season. Senior
right-hander Justin Lehr gave up six hits and five runs in six
innings Saturday, and Stanford advanced to the CWS with just eight
hits in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching was just as good, if not better,'' said USC
catcher Eric Munson.
</P>
<P>
   But even Munson, a first-round pick by Detroit in last week's
draft, grudgingly admitted Young and Wayne were tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shut us down,'' said Munson, who hit his 15th homer in
the sixth that made it 5-2. ``Good pitching will shut you down, and
they did that over the last two days. Our bats got cold at the
wrong time.... (Young and Wayne) didn't throw too many hittable
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   USC and Stanford weren't strangers; they split six games this
season. Munson said, ``It's not like we didn't know what were
facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they know what was coming, they couldn't solve Wayne,
who struck out 14 in a win over the Trojans in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wayne) was just throwing his fastball by guys,'' Stanford
catcher Damien Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, just as it did Friday night, made the most of its
rallies, leaving only three runners on base. The Cardinal hit
back-to-back doubles when it scored three runs in the third and
back-to-back triples in the seventh when it scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   USC broke a 12-inning scoreless streak against Stanford in the
fourth when Seth Davidson tripled with one out and scored on
Dominic Correa's bloop single. But the Trojans didn't get very many
solid hits against Wayne, just as they hadn't against Young the
night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, for those two guys to be throwing like they are,''
Alvarado said, ``is super.''
</P>
<P>
   Super pitching for a super regional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
