u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MARKET-WATCH-ART-2T     06-05 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MARKET-WATCH-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL OFF THE DEATH WATCH FOR BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing)  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic comparing and contrasting several brokerage
services is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is the full-service stockbroker going the way of the
dodo bird?
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch's announcement on Tuesday that it would capitulate
to the on-line trading frenzy by offering do-it-yourself investors
$29.95 Internet trades later this year looked to some people like
the beginning of the end of the tradition that Merrill represents.
</P>
<P>
   Any corporate announcement that reverses decades of business
practice and entrenched philosophy, as this one did, is
breathtaking. Sure enough, investors knocked down brokerage stocks
on the news. Fears that Merrill's embrace of on-line trading and
its deep-discounted commissions would hammer profits drove the
American Stock Exchange's Securities Broker/Dealer index down 5.4
percent the day the news broke. The index ended the week down 8.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are right to be concerned about profitability at
brokerage firms. The $29.95 trades to be offered by Merrill Lynch
are well below the firm's current commission schedule and no doubt
the first salvo in what may devolve into a nasty price war.
</P>
<P>
   Net profit margins at brokerage firms _ currently around 6
percent, according to the Value Line Investment Survey _ will be
much lower in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But any celebration ofthose celebrating the death of the
full-service broker isare premature. Although the number of
old-fashioned brokers will surely dwindle, and those left will have
thinner wallets, many will survive, even thrive. The practice of
buying and selling stocks with the help of a human being is not
going to be supplanted by the click of a mouse just yet.
</P>
<P>
   This is certain, however: Brokers who do not provide value to
their customers are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lay-up business _ sell 1,000 shares of a $50 stock for a
$500 commission _ is going away,'' said Shad Rowe, who runs
Greenbrier Partners, a money-management firm in Dallas. ``People
don't have to pay for no-brainer trades anymore. But brokers who
can truly represent their customers? Their value goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line investing has a lot going for it. The beauty of the
Internet, of course, is that it often eliminates the middleman and
thereby cuts costs for consumers. It also allows Americans to
pursue one of their quintessential delights: the do-it-yourself
gig.
</P>
<P>
   Buying and selling stocks on line has the added appeal of
providing investors with the sense that they are in the midst of a
high-stakes game.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these people may not want a broker to interject herself
between them and the action because that dilutes the rush. After
all, people who frequent the craps tables in Las Vegas don't
usually ask others to throw the dice for them.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that the world of investors is in the process of
dividing into those who want help and those who don't. Still, the
trial and error that usually surrounds any do-it-yourself effort
will prove much more painful in investing than it would in, say,
plumbing or wallpapering.
</P>
<P>
   It's much harder to fix an investment that went awry than to
have a professional come in and correct a mangled drain pipe or
rehang some paper.
</P>
<P>
   An argument can also be made that now, more than ever, investors
need help sorting through the cacophony emitted by CNBC, Internet
investing chat rooms and the growing number of publications devoted
to financial issues.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, with American families more time-starved than ever
before, it seems strange that the interest in do-it-yourself
investing should surge just now.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the investor enthusiasm for on-line trading is a result
of the lengthy bull market. When stocks are going up, it's easy to
have success in the market as a do-it-yourselfer. On-line trading
aficionados have not yet had to endure a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the market starts requiring that people spend a lot
more time watching over their investments rather than just looking
at the paper and seeing that their Internet stock went up, people
will have to work on figuring out why a stock's not working,'' said
Seth Novatt, managing director at CIBC Oppenheimer in New York.
``There are many people who won't want to spend the time doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that investing on one's own is alluring, of
course, is that many investors have been burned by full-service
brokers. But all brokers are not the smirking pickpockets that
on-line brokers' advertisements portray. Many are honest and
hard-working, and bring years of experience and professionalism to
bear on their clients' behalf. (Full disclosure: From 1981 to 1984,
this columnist was a stockbroker at Dean Witter Reynolds in New
York.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is, people want advice from
experienced people who have been in the business,'' said David
Eidelman, a money manager at Eidelman, Finger &AMP; Harris in St.
Louis. ``A broker may call me up and say, `Did you notice this
stock has been slipping?' or point out something I didn't think of.
The extra commission I pay that broker is more than made up by the
service he provides.''
</P>
<P>
   Money managers say that a full-service broker must perform many
duties if he wants to earn higher commission rates. Here is a list
of what the pros say investors have a right to expect:
</P>
<P>
   _ Honesty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perspective. An alert broker cannot help but learn from the
market, a school of hard knocks to be sure. Sharing these lessons
with clients can help them from having to learn the hard way on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discipline. A good broker helps assess the risk in an
investment, playing the devil's advocate on a stock that may look
attractive or a bond with an alluringly high yield.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expert editing. A professional broker will help delete stocks
that look shaky or inappropriate from a portfolio and will keep a
client diversified.
</P>
<P>
   _ Error protection. A computer will not keep clients from making
dumb mistakes _ buying a stock that was supposed to be sold, for
example. A trustworthy broker will, and will also keep customers
from making trades with costly tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   _ Superior execution of trades. A good broker will work a
customer's NASDAQ or option trade, for example, squeezing between
bid and asked prices or watching for other ways to save an investor
one-eighth or one-quarter of a point.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grading of a firm's research analysts. An honest broker will
give her customers the benefit of her experience, separating the
amateurs from the pros.
</P>
<P>
   _ Independent research. A hard-working broker will check out
rumors or tips, using bona fide sources of information that are
relatively independent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good investment ideas that are off the beaten track.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the broker provides all of these services but
consistently loses money for his clients, he should be fired.
Making money is the goal, after all.
</P>
<P>
   A result of Merrill's on-line initiative will certainly be an
increased focus among the customers of full-service firms on the
costs levied and the benefits provided by their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good thing. If brokers don't perform, they will be
bounced, either by their clients or by their firms. No matter how
painful it is in the near term, survival of the fittest is long
overdue on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokers are going to have to adjust their philosophy as well
as their commissions,'' said Rod Fadem, a broker at Oppenheimer &AMP;
Co., in Clayton, Mo., who has been in the business since 1960.
``The philosophy must be `everything for the customer first.'
Investors need to have someone on their side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
