r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX     06-05 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH CAUSES SEEM CLEAR, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The deadly crash of American Airlines Flight
1420 in Little Rock will go down in aviation history as one of the
easiest accidents to figure out, federal investigators said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the mysterious, essentially unsolved crashes of Trans
World Airlines Flight 800 off the coast of Long Island, N.Y., and
USAir Flight 427 near Pittsburgh, the Little Rock crash has
relatively obvious answers. Investigators have suspected since
shortly after arriving in Little Rock that the crash was a clear
case of poor judgment combined with bad weather and a chain of
unfortunate contributing factors.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonnell-Douglas MD-82 jetliner touched down in a severe
thunderstorm at Little Rock National Airport, ran off the end of
the runway, hit a steel structure supporting runway lights and
broke in two.
</P>
<P>
   As the left wing ruptured, fuel spilled from the wing-mounted
tanks, ignited, and sent a fireball through the plane. That blaze
contributed significantly to some of the nine deaths and 82
injuries among the 139 passengers and six crew members on board.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, salvage crews continued to dismantle the charred
plane, loading its two engines onto a flatbed trailer and preparing
the wings and fuselage for removal. The wreckage will be taken to a
hangar at the Little Rock airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parts of the plane now that are obviously being
covered by wreckage that we'd like to be able to get to when we
lift the wreckage _ things we haven't yet seen,''said Matthew
Furman, a spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, a memorial service was held for James Harrison,
21, a student at Ouachita Baptist University who was returning from
a choir trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a service where we healed some of our hurt,'' said
crash survivor and fellow student Misha Perkins. Tears and laughter
punctuated the private service attended by about 200 in the small
town of Royal, southwest of Little Rock, Perkins said. ``I know
James is not worse off; we may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorial services for the eight other victims are scheduled this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will be at least a year before the National
Transportation Safety Board rules on the cause of the crash,
investigators believe that high winds from the thunderstorm at the
northwest corner of the airport played the largest role in the
accident _ by essentially pushing the speeding jet off the runway
as the captain tried desperately to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot error, aviation safety experts say, will eventually be
written as the primary factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did a guy with 9,000 flying hours, who was one of the
airline's chief pilots, make the decision to land when he had been
warned of rapidly deteriorating weather, the presence of
potentially deadly wind shear at the airport, and wind gusts of
more than 50 mph?'' asked David Stempler, a Washington aviation
attorney and executive director of the Air Travelers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the bigger question is, if a pilot with this much training
and experience would make this kind of mistake, what can we expect
of pilots with less experience with airlines that don't have
training programs as good as those of American Airlines?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will never be able to ask the pilot why he decided
to land. Capt. Richard Buschmann, 48, a 20-year veteran flier for
American, died instantly as his side of the cockpit slammed into
the steel light stanchion.
</P>
<P>
   His co-pilot, Michael Origel, who joined the airline in February
and is still on probation, hasn't been able to shed any light on
the captain's decision, either, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in the hospital Friday, where he is recovering from
a severely broken leg and other injuries, Origel told investigators
that he and the captain never discussed diverting to one of the two
alternate airports in the aircraft's flight plan: either returning
to the point of departure, Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, or continuing
for another 45 minutes to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps this was a case of a senior officer showing a green
co-pilot how it is done, and the co-pilot being afraid to speak up
because he is on probation for his first year and that senior
officer is one of the people with influence over his career,''
Stempler said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that factor is one they are focusing on in
their review of cockpit resource management and human factors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the indication of pilot misjudgment and weather factors,
investigators and aviation safety advocates will want other
questions answered if the industry is to learn from this accident.
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Would a high-tech Terminal Doppler Weather Radar system have
given the pilots better information about the location of the
thunderstorm so that they might have decided not to chance the
landing?
</P>
<P>
   Because of its light commercial traffic and relatively small
size, Little Rock National Airport doesn't have this high-tech
radar that was developed by the Federal Aviation as a direct result
of the deadly 1985 Delta Air Lines Flight 191 crash at D/FW
Airport, which was blamed on a severe thunderstorm. D/FW got the
radar in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame the FAA for that,'' said Michael Boyd, an aviation
consultant with The Boyd Group in Golden, Colo. ``The reality is
that if there was equipment that could have given the captain
information that would have prevented this crash, then the FAA is
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Could a soft concrete substance like that used off the ends of
the runways at New York's Kennedy Airport have prevented the crash
of Flight 1420 by safely bringing the plane to a stop as it left
the runway, in much the same way that a mountain highway's
runaway-truck lane stops a truck with its soft gravel?
</P>
<P>
   Would breakaway runway-light supports, like the breakaway light
and sign poles being installed on many highways, have kept the
plane from breaking up as it came to a stop?
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that, although the breakup caused the deaths
and injuries, it also probably saved dozens of lives. As fire
consumed part of the wrecked plane, survivors poured out of the
cracks in the fuselage because most of the emergency exits were
jammed. The high survivor count _ 136 people lived through the
ordeal _ was attributed to their ability to exit the aircraft
quickly through those breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Was there miscommunication between the pilot and co-pilot as to
who would arm the wing-mounted ground spoilers that are triggered
by the airplane's nose wheel making contact with the runway after
touchdown?
</P>
<P>
   The spoilers, which help push the plane down onto the runway by
decreasing lift, and help slow it down by inducing wind resistance,
did not deploy as Flight 1420 landed, NTSB investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Origel told interviewers that he thought the captain had pulled
the lever in the cockpit to arm the spoilers during the approach to
landing, but American Airlines officials said that arming the
spoilers is the duty of the nonflying pilot _ in this case, Origel.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the failure to use the spoilers would not in
itself normally have prevented an MD-82 from stopping safely on a
7,200-foot runway such as the one at Little Rock, said George W.
Black Jr., the NTSB member coordinating the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on a jetliner once whose spoilers didn't deploy on
landing, and I'm still here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the aircraft was having a hard time stopping because of
the high winds from the storm and water on the runway from the
heavy rain, the spoilers might have helped soften the final impact,
investigators said. As it was, the plane left the runway at about
100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   So even though investigators do not face the kinds of deep and
mysterious questions that continue to baffle investigators of the
TWA and USAir flights, there is still a lot of work to do on the
Little Rock crash, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an easy one to investigate, though,'' he said. ``It's
not in the swamp (like the Valujet crash), it's not in the Atlantic
Ocean (like the TWA crash), and it's not in Guam where nobody
speaks English (like the crash of a Korean Air Boeing 747 in
1997).''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the crash of TWA 800, whose cause is suspected to be
an explosion of unknown origin that blew up the center fuel tank,
and the crash of USAir 427, whose cause is suspected to be some
kind of rudder malfunction that investigators and other experts
cannot agree about, Flight 1420's demise seems to be a rather
clear-cut and easily discernible case of pilots continuing a flight
into weather that was not safe for even an airplane as large as the
111,000-pound MD-82, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   (This report contains material from The Associated Press. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
