<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK'S OUTBURST SPURS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The spike mark on the left thigh of Tim Belcher
was not the work of a crazy man, the Dodgers say.
</P>
<P>
   What they said under their collective breath after a
fifth-inning fight between Belcher and Chan Ho Park led to a
bench-clearing brawl Saturday afternoon was that they are praying
it is the turning point in their disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   Although Park was ejected and faces a certain suspension for the
scissors kick he threw Belcher after the two met on Park's
sacrifice bunt, the Dodgers fed off the frenzy for a 7-4 victory
over the Angels in front of 44,779 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the way the club responded to the brawl with a
five-run sixth inning that was capped by Devon White's grand slam.
Or the way the bullpen limited the Angels to two hits in four
innings after Park was tossed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the way the usually docile Dodgers came together in the
post-game clubhouse. Kevin Brown yelled across the room as Park
emotionally tried to explain his case: ``Just tell them what
happened and leave it at that. There is no need to say anything
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Eric Young said Park did what he had to after Belcher
insulted him by saying ``Shut up and get the (expletive) back to
the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was protecting a teammate with $105 million words, the way
the team hoped he would when they signed him last year. Young
simply was saying the Dodgers will not be pushed around, which has
happened plenty this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no telling where something like this can lead a
team,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels obviously saw the incident differently. They thought
there was no provocation. Belcher simply tagged, then briefly held
Park after fielding his sacrifice along the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   First Park threw a forearm that smacked Belcher in the left side
of the head. Then he left his feet and kicked Belcher with both
legs. Play was halted for several minutes as both benches emptied.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires agreed with the Angels, allowing Belcher to remain
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need to get into the altercation from my
standpoint,'' said Belcher, who issued a statement. ``I respect the
umpires for leaving me in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Angels catcher Matt Walbeck, who gave his team a 4-0 lead in
the fourth with a grand slam of his own, said that being on the
bottom of a huge pile for several minutes must have drained Belcher
(3-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only physically, but mentally, too,'' Walbeck said. ``That
was crazy what Park did, he could have really hurt him with his
spikes. I think it was a lot for Tim to go through and then come
out for the next inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher clearly was not the same pitcher in the sixth. Jose
Vizcaino, who hit a game-winning homer Friday night, opened with a
single. Gary Sheffield, who later hit a two-run homer, reached on a
base hit to right.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was laboring when Raul Mondesi smacked an RBI double
into the left-field corner and Eric Karros walked to bring up
White.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the ball to sink to Devo, but it just stayed up,''
Walbeck said. ``It's the same pitch we called in the fourth and he
grounded to short to end the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Park had been replaced by left-hander Onan Masaoka (1-1), who
pitched the sixth inning to earn his first major-league victory.
Jeff Shaw pitched the ninth for his 14th save and second in two
days.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said it was unthinkable that one
pitcher could be ejected and the other allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   He also thought the ill feeling started in the fourth inning
when Park threw two pitches behind the head of Angels second
baseman Randy Velarde. In the fifth, Park threw behind Velarde
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he swings his body in his delivery, he doesn't always
have the best control,'' Johnson said. ``Those pitches were not
intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for any Angels players to believe that. On July 2,
1997, at Anaheim Stadium, both benches cleared but no punches were
thrown when Park nearly hit then-Angel Tony Phillips with a pitch
up and in.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Johnson said Belcher probably gave Park a little
squeeze instead of throwing at him in retaliation for Velarde. Park
said he couldn't back down. ``When you do that, the other team
looks at you as soft and you can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft? Another word came to mind with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure stupidity on his part,'' closer Troy Percival
said. ``Belcher was just doing his job and (Park) acts like he's
never been on a field before. What he did was just plain stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
