<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY CREW GETS CRAFT READY FOR END OF MISSION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle &HT;    With threats of rain and high cross winds at their Florida
<TEXT>
landing site, the Discovery astronauts late Saturday forged ahead
with preparations to end their successful, 10-day mission to the
international space station.
<P>
   After a fiery re-entry through the Earth's atmosphere, Discovery
was scheduled to touch down at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in
Florida at 1:03 a.m., CDT, today, only the 11th night landing in 94
shuttle flights.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the astronauts were to begin their descent, flight
control teams were closely watching the skies around Kennedy for
rain showers and monitoring wind velocities, factors that could
force a wave-off. There was a second opportunity to land in Florida
at 2:38 a.m., CDT, before the four-man, three-woman shuttle crew
would have to wait until early Monday to try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an event I've been looking forward to for a long
time,'' said Discovery commander Kent Rominger, a veteran astronaut
who was anticipating his first opportunity to guide a shuttle onto
the runway as its skipper.
</P>
<P>
   His crew included pilot Rick Husband, flight engineer Ellen
Ochoa, mission specialists Tammy Jernigan and Dan Barry, Canadian
astronaut Julie Payette and Russian cosmonaut Valery Tokarev.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, the shuttle astronauts accomplished the last
of their mission objectives, the deployment of a glittering student
science satellite called Starshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out there,'' Payette informed mission control as the
beach-ball-size satellite sprang from Discovery's cargo bay at 2:31
a.m., CDT, in response to her remote commands from the shuttle.
``It was a fantastic sight.''
</P>
<P>
   The 86-pound aluminum sphere was covered with nearly 900 small
mirrors polished through the efforts of 25,000 schoolchildren from
18 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Starshine should remain in orbit at least through January,
flashing every few seconds as it crosses the sky at dawn and dusk.
The unpowered satellite was deployed at an altitude of 240 miles
and in an orbit that should make its transit visible to observers
on the ground between northern Canada and the tip of South America.
</P>
<P>
   Student observers plan to record its passage as part of an
educational project to teach them about the sun's influence on the
Earth's atmosphere. Atmospheric drag will gradually cause the
satellite's orbit to sink to about 60 miles. At that point, it will
plunge to earth, burning up harmlessly in the atmosphere, said Gil
Moore, a former Utah State University physics professor and
aerospace engineer who organized the project over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ground observers in Maryland sighted the satellite shortly after
it was deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could not have been a better deal,'' said Moore. ``We are
tickled. We invite everyone in the world to track this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   More information about the educational project, including times
to view the satellite as it crosses the sky, are available on the
Starshine homepage on the Internet at: www.azinet.com/starshine.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's flight was the first of five planned for NASA
shuttles this year. It was the second of 45 missions planned as
part of a multinational effort to assemble a new space station over
the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle astronauts delivered two tons of supplies for the
first resident crews that are expected to begin arriving in March.
They also repaired the station's satellite communications and
electrical power generation systems.
</P>
<P>
   The unstaffed outpost is orbiting the Earth at an altitude of
246 miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
