u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVOMAIN-HNS &LR;      06-05 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO BRASS SET TERMS OF PULLOUT PLAN; YUGOSLAV DELEGATION TAKE TIME
TO TALK WITH BELGRADE 
 

</HEADLINE>
 MAIN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
BRUSSELS, Belgium _ A NATO military chief Saturday laid out
detailed Kosovo withdrawal demands for Yugoslav commanders, but the
critical session was continued until today needed to consult with
officials in Belgrade.
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO officials said they saw nothing inherently worrisome in the
delay, although chances that the allied air campaign against
Yugoslavia might be called off today, as some had predicted,
appeared to be dimming.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-hour session in a Macedonian cafe 200 yards from
the Kosovo border, leaders of the Yugoslav delegation told Gen.
Michael Jackson, the Briton who heads NATO's rapid reaction force,
that they needed to talk about details of the pullout plan with
authorities in their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, NATO officials said the talks would resume Saturday
night, but after a recess of about three hours, the Yugoslavs'
request for an overnight delay was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have, in the interest of seeking a swift resolution to
this, agreed,'' said Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, an alliance
spokesman. He said that until then, it had been ``a constructive
day of very positive talks.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the withdrawal plan presented to
the Yugoslavs by Jackson spelled out details of the timetables,
routes and assembly points NATO wants all Yugoslav forces in Kosovo
to abide by as they depart. Shea said it was unclear if NATO
political leaders would decide to make public the complete plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford said that as a result of the session, ``each part of
the military-technical agreement has been discussed word by word,
line by line and sentence by sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we now have is a full understanding on both sides as to
the content of the military-technical agreement and what it
actually requires the Yugoslav delegation and the Yugoslav armed
forces to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting and then the delay came as questions intensified
about Russia's role in the international force that will police
Kosovo. A foreign-ministers' session scheduled for today in Germany
to finish drafting a U.N. Security Council resolution mandating the
multinational force was canceled because the Kremlin has yet to
agree on a chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   NATO had invited Russia to send representatives to the
withdrawal planning conference in Macedonia on Saturday, but no one
from the Moscow regime showed up.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's political arm, the North Atlantic Council, is standing by
at alliance headquarters in the Belgian capital to review the
Yugoslav responses and Jackson's view of the Serbs' intentions. If
satisfied that Milosevic's forces are prepared to carry out the
withdrawal plan the Yugoslav leader agreed to on Thursday, the
council can order a halt to NATO's air bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that from the time NATO puts the agreement into
effect, Yugoslav forces will have seven days to complete the
pullout. He said Yugoslav planes and air defense systems, including
radar, also must be removed from the province.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO expects the forces to withdraw well into Serbia
and not be repositioned in Montenegro, another anti-Milosevic
province of Yugoslavia. Still under discussion, the spokesman said,
is whether NATO troops moving into Kosovo can pick up Serb
officials who, like Milosevic, have been indicted as war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire will trigger the initial deployment of what
eventually will be approximately 50,000 international troops to
oversee the return of more than 800,000 ethnic Albanians who have
fled or been driven from Kosovo. The international force, which
could be in Kosovo for years, will be heavily reliant on soldiers
from NATO nations but also is to include Russians, who as fellow
Slavs have historic and emotional ties to Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said NATO members ``have to
recognize the realities that the Russians are not going to go back
to their Parliament and say we have put our troops under NATO
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what they will do _ and what they have done in Bosnia _ is
reach an agreement by which you do have a unified chain of command
of which Russia is a part and cannot operate independently and
separately,'' Cook said in a BBC interview.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is seeking to guard against a deployment of the KFOR (for
``Kosovo force``) that would leave Russian troops in control of
areas, including Orthodox Christian religious sites, of special
interest to Serb nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking about differentiated zones. That's very
clear,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, British military officials discussed
for ``outline'' purposes a map showing how the major elements of
the international force, including U.S. troops, would be stationed
geographically in Kosovo. The planned position of the Russian
forces was not shown.
</P>
<P>
   Shea refused to be drawn out on the point, contending: ``It's
our intention to have soldiers in every village and on every street
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Saturday, NATO airstrikes continued, focusing on Serb
armed forces in Kosovo. The alliance will ``remain fully vigilant''
and ready to resume the bombing if there is a breakdown in the
withdrawal plans, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to beef up again in case something happens,''
said NATO military spokesman Walter Jertz.
</P>
<P>
   NATO sought to keep the pressure on Milosevic even as Jackson
met with the Yugoslav officials because, Shea said, ``one thing
that we've learned is that we cannot take his (Milosevic's) word
for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize this is not a negotiating session,'' Shea
said as Jackson went over the detailed plan with the Yugoslav
representatives. ``Those troops have to pack their bags and leave
without delay, and certainly without a last fling of ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Shea also called on the Albanian Kosovar
rebels to stand down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the Kosovo Liberation Army to exercise restraint and
not to attempt to take advantage of the situation,'' Shea said. He
said NATO forces ``will not tolerate any hindrance to their
mission.'' He predicted the international force will be so strong
that ``people will be inclined to cooperate with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said Serb troops would have the right to defend
themselves if attacked by the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz said NATO will soon discuss the ``difficult issue'' of
disarming the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   While the KLA calls for independence from Serb-dominated
Yugoslavia, NATO nations have refused to endorse a breakaway. The
current peace plan dropped an earlier proposal for a Kosovo
independence referendum in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said, however, NATO has ``not backed off from the
fundamental goal of reaching autonomy'' for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let's allow the people to eat bread and live under one
roof first, then worry about the more political aspects later,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO-Yugoslav leadership meeting, in the Europe Cafe at
Blace, Macedonia, began about three hours late, apparently because
of Yugoslav concerns about lack of security at the site. The lead
Yugoslav officials were the army deputy chief of staff, Blagjoe
Kovacevic, and the Serb deputy interior minister, Obrad Stefanovic,
who is also a police general.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the recess, Clifford said: ``The delegation has
asked for more time to consult with their higher authorities in
Belgrade over the content of the military-technical agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
