</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-HOMES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOME CONSTRUCTION AT HIGHEST PACE IN 10 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With their three children in tow, Frank Santamaria
and his wife, Silvia, spent a recent Sunday afternoon browsing
through model homes, marveling at the spacious kitchens and big
yards. It's become a familiar ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Canyon Country, a community north of Los
Angeles, have been house-shopping for three months and were
revisiting a new Kaufman &AMP; Broad track north of the Foothill
Freeway in the Sylmar community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley
that they had checked out several times before.
</P>
<P>
   They know that the market is tight, which means sellers hold the
upper hand when it comes to negotiating price. But the Santamarias
are determined to make their next house a new one, even if it means
leaving the comfortable confines of the Santa Clarita Valley for
the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple case of math and money management as the family
tries to make its $230,000 go as far as it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get more house here than you can get there,'' said
Frank Santamaria, a salesman at a local Ford dealer. ``The area
makes a difference, but we want to get a nice house.''
</P>
<P>
   While the San Fernando Valley's resale housing market is in the
midst of a boom, the new home building market also is gathering
steam. Building pads are being graded and new homes are springing
up throughout the Valley at a pace not seen in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   This new product spans the entire price range, from homes
considered affordable _ the high $100,000 range _ to palatial
estates with seven-figure price tags. And while it can't be
classified as a boom, the gain is significant when compared to the
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   New home building in the Valley is now running 30 percent ahead
of what was taking place several years ago, said John Kennedy, the
Los Angeles City Planning Department tract supervisor for the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   New home construction is a cyclical business, and there have
been gains of this magnitude before. But the current one is the
biggest since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Since the economy remains strong, this resurgence has some legs
under it, but geography dictates that it cannot last forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big demand as long as the economy and interest
rates stay the way they are, so I can foresee this lasting for
months if not years. But at some point we are going to run out of
dirt, at least for large developments, anyway,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He notes there is a big demand for new homes that can put their
owners closer to jobs in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these are sold out as they are coming out of the
ground. There is a certain urgency at the time of final inspection
on these houses because people are waiting to get in,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the north and west ends of the Valley have been
hot spots for new construction. But in this latest burst, the
activity has moved east into Sylmar and Tujunga.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy estimated that about 770 homes are under construction at
various sites across the Valley, including smaller tracts of just a
handful of homes in existing neighborhoods on the Valley floor.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some big projects under way, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Hubbard Street winds its way into the low foothills of the
Angeles National Forest, the demarcation line between urban sprawl
and wilderness, Wilshire Builders of Santa Monica is hammering,
sawing and grading away on what will become a 467-home development,
Daybreak at Mountain Glen. Nature will be the neighbor next door.
</P>
<P>
   Prices start in the $190,000 range and top out at about $240,000
at what will eventually become a private, gated community with a
common pool and recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   The company broke ground last July on the first phase of 150
homes, and business has been brisk. So far, 29 homes have been sold
on a pre-build basis, or more than 20percent of the first phase
allocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well above our expectations,'' Howard Press, the
company's vice president, said of interest in the new development.
</P>
<P>
   The lots average about 4,000 square feet and, as in the case
with other new home developments, buyers will pay more for bigger
lots and better views. Down payment requirements can be tailored to
meet the needs of individual buyers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The project has been in the works for ``well over 10 years,''
and the economic factors have finally fallen into place for
development to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing today is a lot of appreciation for new
homes. We're seeing demand outstrip supply. And our prices are very
competitive for what's going on in the rest of the San Fernando
Valley,'' Press said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the traffic is from first-time buyers or families that
own a home and simply want to move into a new one, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
