r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     06-05 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE'S SLAM IS OVERLOOKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It hardly will be remembered that Devon White won
Saturday's game over the Angels with a grand slam. The 7-4 Dodgers
victory will permanently be stamped with the fight between pitchers
Chan Ho Park and Tim Belcher that led to a bench-clearing brawl.
</P>
<P>
   But White's sixth-inning shot, the seventh grand slam of his
career, could not have come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   At age 36, White is not having a very good year. The Dodgers
signed the center fielder to a three-year, $12.4 million contract,
but since the first week of the season, when he batted .500 (10 for
20), White had been hitting just .218 (31 for 142) entering the
Angels series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see Devo come through like that,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``He is a big part of this ball club
and we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   White, who played his first six seasons with the Angels, had two
hits in Friday's 5-4 Dodgers victory. He now is batting .259.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen in the course of a year,'' said White, who
batted .279 with a career high 22 homers last season. ``Good
players end up fighting through it. I don't think I have to prove
anything to anyone at this point in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice thought, but with pressure to win this season, the
Dodgers are keeping an eye on everyone. When White missed seven
games in mid-May with a strained right hamstring, some in the
organization were worried about his durability.
</P>
<P>
   But with Eric Young missing playing time and Mark Grudzielanek
and Todd Hollandsworth on the disabled list, injuries have been a
concern all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem this year has been everyone wants to go up
there and hit the grand slam every night,'' White said. ``The guys
have been feeling the pressure and they want to be the one to end
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Park slammed: Not only is Park expected to receive a three-game
suspension for his fifth-inning fight with Belcher, he now has tied
a major-league record by allowing four grand slams this season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck's fourth-inning slam tied Park with Detroit's Ray
Narleski (1959), Philadelphia's Tug McGraw (1979), and Seattle's
Mike Schooler (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Park previously gave up two grand slams to the Cardinals'
Fernando Tatis (April 23) in the same inning and one to Arizona's
Travis Lee on April 12. The major-league record for grand slams
allowed in a career is 10 by Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: White's grand slam was the first by a Dodger since
Raul Mondesi hit one May 31, 1998, vs. Cincinnati. White leads all
Dodgers in that department. Gary Sheffield is second with five....
Sheffield hit his 12th homer of the year in the seventh and
finished the game 2 for 4. In his last 25 games, Sheffield is
batting .354 (34 for 96).... Catcher Angel Pena had two more hits
and is 4 for 8 in the series, raising his average from .133 to .261
(6 for 23). He also threw out Todd Greene attempting to steal to
end the sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
