<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     06-05 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT PACERS, 92-91  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Johnson was all alone on the left wing with the
ball in his hands, the clock ticking down and the anxiety of an
impossible situation cascading on his sculpted shoulders. And at
that instant, he remembered what it was like to be in this
position. To be the star, to be the go-to man, to be the one to
pull off miracles.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, the former All-Star from Charlotte had
willingly put his ego aside as he deferred to Patrick Ewing and
then to the newer, hipper Knicks who came along. But without the
injured Ewing Saturday night, and without a lift from either
Latrell Sprewell or Allan Houston, it was all on Johnson for Game 3
of the Eastern Conference finals at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   There had been 11.9 seconds left when the inbounds pass was
tipped by Indiana's Jalen Rose and ended up in Johnson's hands on a
broken play that was meant for Houston. Johnson stared into the
eyes of Antonio Davis, head-faked him, then slipped to his left on
the perimeter. As Davis grabbed the waist of Johnson's shorts,
Johnson let go of a high, spinning 3-pointer that was gulped down
by the net like a smooth drink with 5.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   And then the whistle. Davis was called for the foul, and an
elated Johnson had to gather himself from the emotion of his
game-tying shot and deliver a free throw. He nailed it for an
unthinkable 4-point play to win Game 3, 92-91, and reinforce the
fact that nothing is impossible for the Knicks. As the Garden crowd
showered Johnson with cheers, he made the ``Big L'' sign with his
elbow and danced in the right corner of the floor. Amid the mayhem,
the Knicks grabbed a 2-1 lead in the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit it, it doesn't sink in until the game ends,''
Johnson said. ``Then it's like, `Oh, my.' And there's Spike Lee
coming at you. And the Garden crowd. Wow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I thought it was good when I let it go. It felt
right, and then there was contact. I just wanted to get it off. But
as good as it feels, you can't go and celebrate too much. You can
have a great win, a great shot and still lose the series, 4-2. The
main thing was, we hung around and hung around.''
</P>
<P>
   They've done it the whole series. Twice now, the Knicks have had
the big-shot makers, not the Pacers. Twice now, they have turned
fourth-quarter deficits into game-winning situations down the
stretch. That's usually Reggie Miller's job in a series like this.
But after Johnson's play, Miller was traced around the court by
Houston, and Mark Jackson was forced to toss up a desperation jump
hook that bounced off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd seen a lot of things,'' said Miller, who was 4
for 9 shooting and scored 12 points in an arena where he has been
known to devastate the Knicks. ``We had a 3-point lead, and you
think the worst thing you can do is tie. I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's 4-point play made all the feelings of despair over
Ewing's season-ending injury disappear for a night. But he was not
alone in the way he delivered. Even though Sprewell and Houston
combined to shoot 12 of 36 from the field, there was Marcus Camby
to hover over the paint for dunks, keep balls alive with taps and
come up with key stops on defense. Camby ended the night with 21
points off the bench
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the biggest play of the game was with 1:44 to go,
and we are up, and Marcus came flying in for a rebound, and three
of our guys are standing there,'' Indiana Coach Larry Bird said.
``Nobody went after him. We made a lot of mistakes down the stretch
and it cost us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Marcus was the best player out there. He had a
phenomenal game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was right there with Camby. Time and time again, this
man built for the low post came up with uncanny 3-pointers, like
the one from 30 feet that tied the game at the end of the first
quarter, and the one that banked in to put the Knicks ahead, 75-71,
early in the fourth. Johnson had 26 points and hit 10 of 18 shots,
including 3 for 6 from 3-point range. The last was a sight even
Coach Jeff Van Gundy had never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the shot, and we had no timeouts,'' Van Gundy said.
``He had the shot. And with that emotion, the hard part is to make
the free throw. I've never seen a 4-point play that won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' defense put them in position for the wild comeback.
Rik Smits, preying on a Knicks team without Ewing to answer his
offense, gave the Pacers an 89-81 lead with 3 minutes 21 seconds
left. They scored just 2 more points from there as the Knicks
scraped away _ using a 3-pointer from Chris Childs, a layin by
Sprewell _ until it was 89-88 with 13.8 seconds left after Camby
hit two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' first points since the 3:21 mark came when Jackson
was fouled and put at the line with 11.9 seconds remaining. He
delivered both free throws and forced the Knicks to hit a 3-pointer
just to tie. They did better than that, as Johnson sent the crowd
into an unreal frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   All night, the low-post vacuum Ewing left was filled by Johnson,
who wheeled inside for layups around everyone from Derrick McKey to
Dale Davis. He was in such a groove that he even popped a
buzzer-beating  &QC; 30-foot jumper to tie the game at the end of the
fist quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a live body for putbacks, as well, but more than
anything, he gave them a plan with Sprewell and Houston off their
shooting game. Houston also had five first-half turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks stayed in the game and even nudged ahead, 34-27, with
4:30 left in the half on fast breaks and second-chance points from
an active Camby. But once Johnson sat down, there was chaos in the
half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers just hummed along, and made up a 7-point
second-quarter deficit by scoring on their last 10 possessions of
the half to take a 47-42 lead. The main element of their run was
Smits. After fumbling around a game Chris Dudley, he started to
spring outside and bury his high-arching jumper.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 feet 4 inches, no one could stop him as he scored 14 points
in a row in the final 4:35 of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Things were different in the third quarter. Van Gundy broke from
his habit of not tinkering with his starting lineup and started
Camby for the third. And it made all the difference. He was
everywhere, jumping into the action from the start by taking a
steal by Charlie Ward and then soaring from the free-throw line for
a jam.
</P>
<P>
   He followed that up with a flurry of points, rebounds and
defensive stops to help the Knicks regain the lead four minutes
into the quarter on his fast-break dunk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
