r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     06-05 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DECRY PARK'S ACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Chan Ho Park and Tim Belcher took the baseball
term ``pitchers' duel'' a little too literally Saturday afternoon
at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The fight between Park and Belcher -- precipitated by what Park
called an excessively hard tag by Belcher -- included an elbow by
Park, a curse word from Belcher, a forearm to the chin by Park and
then an attempt by Park to throw a martial arts kick.
</P>
<P>
   As a crowd of players piled on the dueling pitchers, Belcher
threw a few punches at Park's head, none landing with much force.
And that's too bad, the Angels said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was, `What is this?' '' Angels shortstop Gary
DiSarcina said. ``Is this the new Dodger Blue? It was karate chop
Blue. From the looks of it, (Park) must not be an intelligent
person when it comes to playing the game. Whether it's because of
where he's from, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw kicking in a fight was after my older
brother took a Barbie Doll away from my younger sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn was first on the scene and
initially tried to restrain Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when you get into a brawl you've got a reason,''
Vaughn said. ``The whole time, I was screaming `What is going on
out here?' I know some of their guys over there, and we were
laughing, we couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were some light-hearted comments about the incident,
the general feeling in the Angels clubhouse was one of disbelief
and disdain for Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure stupidity on (Park's) part,'' closer Troy Percival
said. ``Belcher was doing his job and (Park) acts like he's never
been out on the field before. Ask their (Dodgers) players. I'm sure
they don't condone what he did. It was just stupid. He shocked
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said catcher Matt Walbeck, whose
fourth-inning grand slam went to waste in the Angels' loss. ``All
of a sudden they started fighting. Fighting is one thing, but when
spikes start flying ... That was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher refused to talk to the media after the game but issued a
statement through an Angels spokesman:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to get into the altercation from my
standpoint. But I do respect the umpiring crew for leaving me in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was not injured in the fight except for being spiked on
his left thigh and a bruise on his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins said was as baffled as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one thing if Tim had knocked some guys down,'' he
said. ``Park already knocked Randy (Velarde) down a couple times,
but Tim didn't respond. He went out and pitched his game. That's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina will have X-rays on his left forearm Wednesday and if
they show the bone has healed as expected, he could be cleared to
begin a rehabilitation assignment by Thursday, probably at single-A
Lake Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina hasn't played all season after breaking a bone in the
forearm Feb. 21 when coach George Hendrick accidently hit him with
a fungo bat. DiSarcina continues to take batting practice and field
ground balls in pregame workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One good thing I've got going for me is I've got a lot of the
soreness out of the way because I've stayed with the club and I've
been taking ground balls every day,'' DiSarcina said. ``The only
thing I need to do right now is adjust to game speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Sheets, acquired just before the start of the season in a
trade from the Padres, has done adequately as DiSarcina's
replacement. Sheets is hitting .226 with three homers, 23 RBIs and
eight errors. But Collins says DiSarcina can't be replaced for what
he does for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from the guys we have in
there,'' Collins said. ``But Gary's one of those guys whose energy
spreads. The way he plays the game, the way he says something on
the bench. His presence in our lineup is important.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina likely would need at least two weeks on a rehab
assignment before he's ready to play with the big league club.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Omar Olivares' strained left hamstring was sore
Saturday, one day after he injured it while trying to beat out an
infield grounder in Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first did it I thought I'd be able to go back out
there,'' Olivares said. ``But there was a little knot. I didn't
want to risk it and maybe tear the muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainers won't know until sometime today or tomorrow how severe
the strain is, but Olivares is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure it won't be bad,'' he said. ``Maybe I'll miss
one start, if that.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares' next scheduled start would be Wednesday in San
Francisco. If he can't go, Collins said he'd likely choose a
replacement from his bullpen. The two likely candidates are Scott
Schoeneweis and Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   The A.L. West is a bad division? The numbers don't say so. Based
on the combined records of the teams in each division (going into
Sunday's games), the A.L. West is the best division in the American
League and second best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The A.L. West is 12 games over .500, the A.L. East is even and
the A.L. Central is 17 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   In the National League, the N.L. Central is 23 games over .500,
the N.L. West is one game over .500 and the N.L. East is 19 games
under .500.
</P>
<P>
   Any question that the American League is a hitters' league? The
Angels began the day ranked No. 2 in the league in ERA (4.32) and
No. 1 in fielding percentage (.985) yet were in last place.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the offense ranked No. 12 in runs per game (4.6) and
No. 11 in batting average (.263).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
