<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMID TRIES TO MOVE AROUND PIECES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ It was only a matter of time before Sigi Schmid
started tinkering with the Galaxy's future.
</P>
<P>
   This is a person who had 19 straight winning seasons and three
NCAA championships at UCLA before taking over for Octavio Zambrano
five games into the Galaxy season. He's gone 3-3 since to run
L.A.'s record to 5-6, but a league-low seven goals prompted some
personnel changes over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the signing of New Zealand midfielder Simon
Elliott, and recently, the trade of Welton to Miami in exchange for
New York/New Jersey midfielder Roy Myers; all part of a three-team
MLS swap that also included sending Eric Wynalda from San Jose to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Myers joined the team Friday and Schmid expects him to see
valuable minutes this afternoon when the Galaxy plays host to
Kansas City (1-9) at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up a quality player (Welton) to get a quality
player,'' said Schmid. ``In Roy, we get someone to play the right
side of our midfield. I think he will do well in there with Simon
and Mauricio (Cienfuegos).
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we needed more creative play out of our midfield and I
think Roy will make those final passes for us on a consistent
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   These moves create another decision for Schmid _ does he leave
Clint Mathis on the front line with Cobi Jones and Carlos
Hermosillo (who returns Monday)? Or does Mathis return to his old
role as an attacking midfielder?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if Clint is playing well, we'll find spots for him,''
said Schmid. ``He's been struggling a little lately but Clint's an
awfully talented player. Eventually, though, I think Clint's best
position is when he's not on the front line. I think he's a better
attacker coming from the midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, though, we'll just have to see how all the pieces fit
when we get everyone together and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is returning from a tough 2-1 shootout loss to
Columbus last week. The Crew scored in the 88th minute to tie the
match, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my most frustrating loss since I've been here,''
admitted Schmid. ``We had a lead, played reasonably well and missed
other chances we should have had. So, after all that, to squander a
lead in the late minutes was really tough. Late in the game Clint
was one-on-one and Cobi was one-on-one and we got nothing out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to start finishing those opportunities if
we want to put these teams away.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid is convinced his players will work through the struggles,
particularly his stagnant offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it something that's starting to eat at them? Yes,'' said
Schmid. ``But they want to crack this open as much as anybody. I
think the key to this team is that they haven't lost their
composure or their willingness to turn this around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
