<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDSCHOOL-OLDSTER-ART     06-05 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDSCHOOL-OLDSTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 55, A NEWLY MINTED PHYSICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His silver hair glinted in the sun, and a tear
glistened in his eye. At the commencement ceremonies for Albert
Einstein College of Medicine last week, Robert J. Lopatin looked
like any of the proud fathers watching their children start medical
careers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lopatin's hair was covered by a cap, and his body by a gown.
He was not there to cheer the medical school graduates. At the age
of 55, he was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatin is the oldest graduate in the school's history _ he is
older than the school, which was founded in 1955 _ and one of only
about a dozen medical school students in the country to have
graduated at 55 or older, according to the American Association of
Medical Colleges. At an age when some doctors are hitting the links
or contemplating who should take over their practices, Lopatin, who
spent almost three decades in the garment industry, is just getting
started in his profession.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he has more in common with his professors, quite a
few of whom are younger than he is, than with his fresh-faced
fellow students. But as unusual as Lopatin seems, he may also be
the face of the future in a society with ever-increasing longevity.
If women are becoming mothers in their 50s, why not mint doctors at
that age?
</P>
<P>
   As a student at Stuyvesant High School, Lopatin said, he thought
of ``nothing else'' but being a doctor. But at Columbia College,
where he was in the class of 1965, he packed away his dream,
instead joining his father in the garment business upon graduation.
Together, the two ran Evelyn Pearson Inc., a manufacturer of
women's clothing that eventually employed 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatin said he was happy in the industry. The garment business
got in his blood, so much so that he still reads Women's Wear Daily
religiously.
</P>
<P>
   But as garment production shifted to cheaper factories abroad,
Lopatin found himself more importer than manufacturer, a change
that did not suit him. So in 1990, he and his father sold the
business. Lopatin stayed on for a year as a consultant. Then he was
a free man.
</P>
<P>
   He took classes: Shakespeare, Latin, calculus. ``To me, taking
time off means look for the nearest registrar's office,'' he
explained somewhat sheepishly. He never married or had children, so
there were few constraints on his time. He signed up to be an
interpreter at the United Nations (he speaks six languages). He
went on an archaeological dig in Belgium (he had earned a master's
degree in art history while working at Evelyn Pearson).
</P>
<P>
   And then, in August 1992, a conversation with a medical student
reawakened his long-dormant yearning to be a doctor. He began
pestering New York University to let him enroll in premed classes _
classes that were starting the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm not going to take you _ you're not going to get
into medical school,''' recalled Graham Underwood, the school's
assistant dean for preprofessional advisement. Lopatin persisted;
the next day, he was in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not recommend it for the normal person,'' Dean
Underwood said. But by all accounts Lopatin is not a normal person.
The decades have done nothing to dim his curiosity, his drive, his
love of learning, his eagerness to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anything Bob does he excels at, except for sports,''
said Chuck Meyer, Lopatin's college roommate at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatin again defied expectations by being accepted at Einstein,
which is in the Bronx. (His interviewer there had also attended
Stuyvesant _ 10 years after Lopatin.)
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lazar, the assistant dean at Einstein, said the school
looks for students with different perspectives. And Lopatin's
determination impressed him, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's the type of guy who's going to retire in
nine years,'' Dean Lazar said.
</P>
<P>
   So Lopatin packed up one life _ putting paintings and books in
storage and subletting his apartment _ and began another. For the
four years of medical school, he has lived on campus, in a studio
apartment where artworks line the walls.
</P>
<P>
   With his gold rimmed glasses and loafers, he already looks very
much the doctor, when in fact he is just beginning his residency in
the Bronx, at Montefiore Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   There is a decent argument to be made that Lopatin's space would
have been better used by a younger student with prospects of a
longer career. But Dean Lazar said he suspects the quality of
Lopatin's career may outweigh its brevity.
</P>
<P>
   And Lopatin said he believes that his age enhances the quality
of his care. Patients, he said, trust him, and life has given him a
wisdom to help them through their pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a young doctor, but I'm an old person,'' he said. ``I've
lost that youthful feeling of immortality.''
</P>
<P>
   His own father died a protracted, painful death while he was in
medical school. When Lopatin was accepted at Einstein, his father
told him he would not live to see him finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put myself in his mind, how a person could live day by
day facing death,'' Lopatin said. ``It's central to my work right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   As the son tried on his cap and gown last week, he stared into
the mirror, and his father stared back. Fingering the fabric of his
gown, Lopatin called his medical career a miracle. Asked where he
sees himself in five years, he was briefly silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee,'' he finally said, marveling at the notion, ``I'll be a
doctor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
