r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-05 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK'S ACTIONS HARD TO DEFEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers pitcher Chan Ho Park delivered a forearm
shiver and scissor kick to Angels pitcher Tim Belcher before being
restrained by catcher Angel Pena, and suddenly ``assault and
battery'' took on a whole new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The prudence of Park's psychotic turn Saturday in the fifth
inning of the Dodgers' 7-4 win over Anaheim is open to
interpretation. If you're not in the Foxhole fighting in Rupert
Murdoch's battalion, what Park did seems indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   From far afield of the slings and arrows, Park's argument
sounded preposterous. So what if Belcher fielded Park's bunt and
applied a little extra mustard to his tag? And what if Belcher
answered Park's plaintive challenge _ ``Whassup?'' with this
poisoned dart: ``Shut up and get the (expletive) back to the
dugout''?
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't strike this civilian as just cause to turn around
and fire to maim with the forearm and the foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He challenged me. I was just protecting myself,'' said a
non-contrite Park.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, he retaliated so swiftly, so violently, Belcher was
fortunate to escape with only a bruised left forearm and a mottled
left thigh. Truth to tell, the fresh blemish on his record was
probably what hurt the proud, 13th-year veteran the most.
</P>
<P>
   Until Park attacked him and cleared both benches, Belcher was
the one on the offensive. He had shut out his former team through
the first four innings, limiting them to three harmless singles. He
took the mound in the fifth with a 4-0 cushion that catcher Matt
Walbeck had provided via a grand slam off Park in the top of the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher didn't look like the same pitcher after the players
repaired to their respective corners and Park was ejected and the
game resumed. His fourth pitch to the next batter, Eric Young,
skittered past Walbeck. Young flied out to end the inning, but the
chink in Belcher's armor had been exposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, the Dodgers burned Belcher for five runs, four on
one mighty swing by Devon White. At that point, Belcher was
relieved of the ball without having retired a batter in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   So the Dodgers lost Park and won the game. The sacrifice bunt
that set off the fireworks? To his teammates, that was nothing
compared to the sacrifice he made for machismo. Listening to them
talk, it seemed they thought he was more deserving of a slap on the
back than the slap on the wrist that probably will be forthcoming
from the National League office.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher ``was pretty much handing it to us,'' Young said.
``There has to be an order of respect out there and Chan Ho felt
like he was being disrespected. If he's fired up and wants to go
out there, I'm going to be right behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand: You won't find any Dodgers choosing Sister Sledge's
``We Are Family'' as their at-bat song. But even with as many
individual agendas as there are on the Dodgers, everyone apparently
can agree on this: The warriors' code of honor is to be strictly
enforced.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, they had Park's back in the clubhouse after the game.
That's no small thing. Just ask the Angels how hard it can be to
put up a united front. Until Randy Velarde lobbed his verbal
grenade in the Angels clubhouse, the Dodgers' room was the greater
minefield of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Not Saturday, anyway. Pitcher Kevin Brown was quick
to come to Park's defense when reporters crowded around the South
Korean and clamored for answers.
</P>
<P>
   In his second language, Park was asked the same question a dozen
different ways:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, Brown had heard enough. From his locker
across the room Brown's voice _ the steely staccato of a clubhouse
leader _ rang out:
</P>
<P>
   ``Just tell them what happened,'' he told Park. ``Tell them your
opinion and be done with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Park saw Brown less as the team's starting ace
than a reliever who had just gotten him off the hook. ``Thank you,
Kevin,'' Park said, with a nod in Brown's direction.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a $100-million man to see the Dodgers need to
hold Park's hand through the fire. When his confidence gets singed,
they all get burned. Last year he overcame an early crisis of
confidence to set career highs in wins, starts, strikeouts and
innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   This year Park has been able to control his fastball about as
well as his agent. Which is to say not very well at all. The
pitcher is in the final year of his contract and his agent made the
negotiations very public, which put less pressure on the Dodgers
front office than on Park himself.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how two years ago Raul Mondesi became the first Dodger
in franchise history to hit at least 30 home runs and steal 30
bases?
</P>
<P>
   Park is on pace for a double of his own. So far this season he
has surrendered four grand slams and incited two brawls. At this
rate, he'll easily establish a franchise-first in bases and benches
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get right,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. Those
words sounded less convincing than these: ``We need him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
