<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GRUMHAUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD GRUMHAUS, EX-CHIEF OF CHICAGO'S TRIBUNE CO., DIES AT 96 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla.)   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold F. Grumhaus, a former executive of the Tribune Co. who
began his career as a loyal lieutenant of the legendary publisher
Robert R. McCormick and later helped dismantle some of his
conservative mentor's political and managerial legacy at the
company and its flagship newspaper, died May 29 at his home in
Naples, Fla. He was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Grumhaus, who joined the Tribune Co. as head of the insurance
department in 1934, moved seven years later to a job in the
production end of the business. Among his duties were labor
relations, which became a crucial area when trouble developed with
the International Typographical Union in 1947 and 1948.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent account in The Chicago Tribune, the
resulting strike forced early deadlines on the newsroom,
contributing to one of the best-known bloopers in newspaper
history. Instead of waiting for most of the election returns, the
editors decided to declare Thomas E. Dewey the winner of the 1948
presidential race in time for the strike-imposed deadlines. At a
subsequent victory rally, the real winner, Harry S Truman,
gleefully brandished the ``Dewey Defeats Truman'' early edition
headline.
</P>
<P>
   When McCormick, who was universally known as ``the Colonel,''
died in 1955, according to Clayton Kirkpatrick, The Tribune's
former editor, ``he left his possessions, including The Tribune _
he was very careful about it _ so that the people he considered his
trusted lieutenants would be in charge.'' One of those lieutenants
was Grumhaus, then the production manager.
</P>
<P>
   Grumhaus occupied a variety of executive positions in four
decades with the company. He became business manager in 1960, when
executives of the Tribune Co.'s two largest newspapers _ The
Chicago Tribune and The Daily News in New York, whose first
publisher was Joseph Medill Patterson, McCormick's cousin _ had
major roles in the company. In a reorganization led by Grumhaus,
Kirkpatrick said, Chicago Tribune executives gradually assumed most
authority over corporate strategy. (Today, The Daily News is
independently owned.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Grumhaus became general manager of The Tribune, and two
years later he became president of the Tribune Co.. In 1969, he was
appointed publisher of The Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick, who became the paper's editor shortly thereafter,
said Grumhaus backed him in making disputed decisions to split with
the McCormick legacy, such as removing political cartoons from the
front page.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Grumhaus was named chairman and chief executive of the
company. He resigned as publisher in 1973 and as chairman and chief
executive a year later. Three years later, he resigned as a
director. He later moved to Florida with his wife, Helen, who died
in 1984. He married Margaret Austin Rodgers of Naples, Fla., in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his second wife, Grumhaus is survived by a son,
David of Lake Forest, Ill.; a sister, Evelyn Parker of Clearwater,
Fla.; eight grandchildren; and 12 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
