</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CONN-NOISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROWING CITY IS COUNTING ITS DECIBELS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Roberto Cabrera has a $3,000 stereo in his
1990 Toyota Corolla, including a separate 600-watt amplifier just
to make that big bass speaker boom.
</P>
<P>
   So Cabrera might want to start worrying about a new city policy
that rests on the following formula: SPL (EQ) 20 log P in db over
Po, where Po (EQ) 0.0002 microbars. On second thought, maybe
Cabrera doesn't have all that much to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford, a small city that has become a magnet for corporate
headquarters, is escalating the fight against big-city noise.
Starting this month, the police have taken over the Health
Department's job of applying anti-noise laws to everything from the
garbage trucks that announce their presence at 4 a.m. to the clubs
that spill music and shouting into the street, to the young men
with the slammin' jams in their cars, like the ones Cabrera
installs at Elm Street Car Stereo and Security.
</P>
<P>
   But noise in Stamford and in a lot of other places is expressed
in more ways than the city's formula for measuring sound pressure
level (SPL) in decibels (db). Noise is a social and cultural issue,
to hear Stamford officials explain it with some delicacy, because
certain types of people make a lot of noise and other types call up
the mayor to complain.
</P>
<P>
   For years, these two types lived happily distant from each
other, but in the last 20 years, Stamford has not only grown by
more than 10,000 people, it has also attracted many former
suburbanites who moved to luxury condominiums and high-rise
apartments downtown. Now the exuberant sounds that one kind of
person makes run smack into the fury of another kind of person who
expects a little peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stamford has had a resurgence of high-rise apartments, and
more and more people are deciding they want to live downtown,''
said Stephen DeVito, the deputy chief of police. ``So now you don't
have the blue-collar or working-class people downtown anymore; you
have very upscale rentals and condominiums attracting a different
kind of person that has a different kind of expectation for the
government and their police.''
</P>
<P>
   People like, say, Agnes Fairchild, who was born in Stamford but
spent most of her life in the suburbs until she moved into a
retirement complex on Grove Street nine years ago. Her apartment
includes a little balcony overlooking the streets below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that it's summer, the motorcycles are out, and when they
zoom up the gas, it's enough to split your eardrums,'' she said.
``Then the cars with the loud radios come along with their windows
down, and it sounds like drums in the street at 11 o'clock at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching a loud car or motorcycle under the law is going to be
tough, DeVito said. The rules say that before a $99 ticket can be
written, the police must have sound measurements with and without
the offending noise, so most noisemakers on wheels get off with
only a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do with a moving vehicle,'' DeVito said. He
added: ``We can still pull them over and _ I don't want to use the
word pressure, but I guess pressure is the right word _ we say,
`Look, you're too loud.' Most people are very cooperative, but God
only knows what they do when they get around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   But the police figure that other noisemakers will be easier to
act against, including the garbage trucks and another phenomenon of
Stamford's extraordinary growth: night life.
</P>
<P>
   Before Stamford had high rises, it had blue laws that separated
bars by at least a quarter mile, ensuring that bars and their noisy
patrons would be scattered.
</P>
<P>
   The blue laws are long gone, and with the increase in downtown
residents, Stamford has developed a jumping night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, when I started, there were three clubs
downtown,'' said Edward Barrero, the owner of Apple's Bar and Grill
on Atlantic Street. ``Now there are 17 bars and clubs right in this
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrero said he has been the subject of only one noise
complaint, for a radio blaring after hours. As for the police
cracking down, he said he was not too worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, Stamford has a little night life, which is
good for the city,'' he said. ``And with night life, you have to
expect a little noise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
