<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-05 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 13)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brain Storm
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Dooling. Picador USA, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of this clever, densely packed thriller is a St. Louis
lawyer who is assigned to defend a despicable criminal and becomes
involved with a brain researcher with an explanation for
everything. ``Here is a whodunit that achieves a comic fugue-state
mastery of the language of our sexually charged, violent,
technocratic society,'' Colin Harrison wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   To End a War
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Holbrooke. Modern Library, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   The American diplomat in charge of the 1995 Dayton peace
accords, which resulted in a halt in the fighting in Bosnia, tells
his story through anecdotes, withering strategic analysis and sharp
portraits of the wily Balkan leaders and timid NATO military
commanders involved in the talks. His ``engaging, witty and
dramatic account,'' which was selected by the editors of the Book
Review as one of the best books of 1998, is also ``an impassioned
plea for Washington to use the military might at its disposal to
intervene when societies break down,'' Chris Hedges wrote here last
year. In Blood and Vengeance: One Family's Story of the War in
Bosnia, by Chuck Sudetic (Penguin, $14.95), a Croatian-American
journalist who covered the war for The New York Times follows
several generations of a Muslim family near Srebrenica, where
Bosnian Serbs massacred several thousand Muslims in 1995. Last year
our reviewer, Tom Gjelten, called this ``a narrative so rich and
strong it not only describes the crime but dares to explain it and
does so with eloquence and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Jones's Diary
</P>
<P>
   By Helen Fielding. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This comic novel follows a 30-something Brit who vows to lose
weight, control her drinking and basically get a grip on herself as
she struggles with demeaning dates and disastrous dinner parties.
``The book is a compilation of memorably silly moments in the life
of a hapless Everywoman,'' Elizabeth Gleick said here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Hacienda: A Memoir
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa St. Aubin de Teran. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The British author was 17 years old when she married an unstable
Venezuelan aristocrat and moved to his Andean estate. Out of her
nightmarish marriage came a 1982 novel, ``Keepers of the House,''
and this lyrical nonfiction account, which is also an affectionate
portrait of a lost world and its people. The result is ``a
transfixing performance,'' Michael Upchurch wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Place
</P>
<P>
   By Grace Metalious. Northeastern University, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   It may not seem as naughty today, but this lurid novel about a
New Hampshire town, with its deflowerings, suicides and other dark
goings-on, ruffled a lot of feathers when it was first published in
1956. ``Sinclair Lewis would no doubt have hailed Metalious as a
sister-in-arms against the ... bourgeois pretensions of allegedly
respectable communities,'' Carlos Baker wrote here.
</P>
<P>
   Tecumseh: A Life
</P>
<P>
   By John Sugden. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   The great Indian leader was a proud, charismatic warrior who
envisioned a pan-Indian alliance and helped defeat an American
invasion of Canada during the War of 1812. Last year our reviewer,
Barry Gewen, called this ``a richly detailed, utterly scrupulous
account that is as poignant as it is informative _ for Tecumseh
seems to have been doomed from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ibis Tapestry
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Nicol. Vintage International, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This novel's narrator is a South African writer who receives a
dead man's laptop computer and gets pulled into an underground
world of gunrunning. ```The Ibis Tapestry' plays skillfully with
truth and fiction to portray the landscape of a nation undergoing
revolutionary change,'' Erik Burns wrote here last year. Home
Ground, by Lynn Freed (Story Line, $14), focuses on a theater
family whose internal dramas provide a metaphor for apartheid-era
politics. ``What is extraordinary about this book is its
perspective,'' Janette Turner Hospital wrote here in 1986.
``Freed's guileless child-narrator takes us inside the neurosis''
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Voyage of the Karluk:
</P>
<P>
   A Survivor's Memoir of Arctic Disaster
</P>
<P>
   By William Laird McKinlay. St. Martin's Griffin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author was a meteorologist with a 1913 expedition to chart
the Arctic region that resulted in disaster: the ship sank early
on, and the few survivors were stranded on a barren island for six
months. In 1977 our reviewer, Alix Nelson, called this a tale
``written with a grace, modesty and power that are the measure of
the man.'' Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea, by Gary Kinder
(Vintage, $14), chronicles the sinking of a gold-laden paddle
steamer in a hurricane off the Carolina coast in 1857 and the
effort in the 1980's to recover its treasure. ``The author writes
beautifully _ historical and technological reporting of a high
order, as suspenseful and deft about the doomed steamer as the
salvage vessels,'' John Maxtone-Graham wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   A World Away
</P>
<P>
   By Stewart O'Nan. Owl/Holt, $13.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island circa 1943, a troubled family plays out its
summer of discontent, complete with adultery and an unraveling
marriage. Last year our reviewer, Timothy Foote, admired the
novel's ``intricately overlapping streams of consciousness that
rove back and forth, creating past and present with fleeting hints
about the characters' lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
