<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990605.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4715 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-05 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WORDS DON'T FIT THE EMOTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ What can you say at a moment like this?
</P>
<P>
   That's always been horse racing's quandry, from Ruffian to Go
for Wand to Prairie Bayou, from one televised tragedy to the next.
</P>
<P>
   What can you say when a popular racehorse is hauled off the
track in a van and the public wants to know why?
</P>
<P>
   The sport still hasn't quite figured that one out, nearly a
quarter century after Ruffian's ghastly breakdown in the 1975
``Battle of the Sexes'' match race with Foolish Pleasure mortified
a nation.
</P>
<P>
   That was proven again late Saturday afternoon, even as
veterinarians worked over Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner
Charismatic in a Belmont Park barn, even as the colt's 17-race
career was declared as over as his Triple Crown bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day!'' enthused Laddie Dance, husband of
Belmont Stakes winner Lemon Drop Kid's owner Jeanne Vance, in the
winner's circle _ because nobody had told him about the serious
injury to Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   And so began the whole sad circus of people tripping over their
tongues.
</P>
<P>
   We heard a TV interviewer trying not to gather information but
to comfort jockey Chris Antley.
</P>
<P>
   We heard Antley's voice quaver as he prematurely eulogized
Charismatic: ``He's given America a lot...''
</P>
<P>
   We heard the president of Visa, which sponsors the $5 million
Triple Crown, claiming to feel no qualm about the corporation's
association with racing on such a bitter day: ``You hate to see
that,'' Carl Pascarella said of the breakdown. ``(But) it's
something you have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   We heard trainer D. Wayne Lukas using the same cold language to
describe his reaction: ``It's racing, these things happen, and we
have to deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, as reporters scrambled for details of the trauma to
the bones surrounding Charismatic's left front ankle, we heard
veterinarians offer conflicting reports of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   To Dr. Larry Bramlage, the Lexington, Ky., veterinarian who
served as spokesman for the American Association of Equine
Practitioners, it was a clean fracture of the shin bone and a crack
of the smaller sesamoid bones, the former requiring ``urgent'' not
``emergency'' surgery and the latter likely to heal itself.
</P>
<P>
   To Dr. Stephen Selway, of the Belmont Equine Surgical Clinic,
both sets of bones were ``shattered,'' a considerably more
frightening image.
</P>
<P>
   Both men indicated Charismatic's 17-race career was over.
</P>
<P>
   But to Dr. Jim Hunt, identified vaguely in a track hand-out as
``veterinarian,'' the healing of the sesamoids ``will determine
whether or not he comes back to race.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of voices, a lot of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the racing industry has been trying to correct this
problem, believing the best public-relations policy in these
situations is full and clear disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Bramlage serves in the job of ``on-call physician'' for the AAEP
_ a fancy way of saying he's in charge of telling the writers and
broadcasters what the heck happened.
</P>
<P>
   The role was created in the wake of the jarring incidents
involving Go for Wand (broke down in the 1990 Breeders' Cup
Distaff, and destroyed), Mr Brooks (fell in the 1992 Breeders' Cup
sprint, and destroyed), Union City (broke down in the 1993
Preakness, and destroyed), and Prairie Bayou (broke down in the
1993 Belmont, and destroyed).
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a sort of love of horse racing,'' Bramlage said.
``It's very important... to get you the information as quickly and
accurately as we can so the first news story has got the right
stuff in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is somewhere in here: Charismatic is seriously hurt
but lucky it wasn't worse. He's in discomfort but not agony. His
life is not in danger. He'll have surgery today and more will be
known then about the possibility of complications.
</P>
<P>
   And in here: A sport that believes it's on the way back up might
be facing another crisis of public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   What can you say then?
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved what he was doing out there (Saturday),'' Bramlage
said of Charismatic when the veterinarian was asked what he'd say
to people who think racing is cruel. ``He wanted to run on. I think
if you just look at those animals running and how they thrive on
that sort of athletic competition, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know further, come visit us in Lexington. They
race among themselves in a field. All the colts will be out and
they're seeing who's the fastest. Horses are physiologically and
psychologically !ital!running!off! animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Well said by a man who loves horses, loves racing and finds no
contradiction in those emotions.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that simple at a moment like this. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
