<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     06-05 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES QUIET AS HE MULLS IRVIN'S FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jerry Jones is gladly dodging minicams and headlines. ...
</P>
<P>
   When Jerry willingly eats dust while the Stars steal both the
media show and hearts. ...
</P>
<P>
   When this is happening, then obviously bad times, bad P.R. and
still-to-come hard decisions have descended upon the Valley Ranch
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a wide range of emotional moments for the Cowboys. It
has been a spring and early summer of reaching the lowest of lows
with the stupid death of Mark Tuinei, followed by the continuing
stupidity of Leon Lett, followed by the ongoing comedy of Nine-Toed
Deion.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, keep praying to the football gods that Deion
Baybee can make it back in time for another Pro Bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a fraudulent subject, however, this morning's sermon
will center on what has become the most intriguing football debate
of the Cowboys' off-season.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's feelings have been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Do you care? No. Do I care? No. Should Jerry care? Yes. And
here's why:
</P>
<P>
   The word got out last week from Irvin's agent _ and Steve
Endicott is a good one _ that Michael was pouting. Since then,
there has been double talk about whether Irvin wanted to be traded,
requested to be traded, would accept a trade, etc.
</P>
<P>
   None of that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin is 33 years old, is coming off an awful season, and will
count $3.2 million against somebody's 1999 salary cap. Nobody wants
Michael Irvin. Except maybe the Cowboys, and that's questionable.
Jones did attempt to trade Irvin before the April draft.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, this story has received about as much play as what
Jones will eventually do with Nine-Toed. Typical of the national
response was this opinion in a Denver newspaper last week:
</P>
<P>
   ``So, the cocaine Cowboy, Michael Irvin, wants to be traded
because he doesn't get the ball enough in Chan Gailey's offense.
Yadda ... yadda ... yadda. Be like the other Mike \RJordan\S, kids,
not this loser.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Irvin set himself up for that kind of rip job, and
unfortunately, his off-the field past has become his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But what's going on at the moment is not about any Gailey
offense. Instead, it centers squarely on what Jones views as
Michael being ``fair,'' and what Michael views as Jones being
``fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of them have a good argument.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the Irvin side:
</P>
<P>
   The dynasty days of the '90s made Jones what he has become _ the
most powerful owner in the NFL. That dynasty happened for a lot of
reasons, but there can be no argument the three central players in
the success were Irvin, Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   This trifecta became the backbone of a team NFL historians will
always rank among the league's greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Jones has repeatedly rewarded Aikman with financial
riches, even when his performance no longer deserved it. The same
goes for Emmitt. In fact, it goes double for Emmitt. Jones did not
forget what they meant to him personally when it came time to reach
into his hip pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Like Smith two years ago, Irvin appears to be fading as a
player, plus his contract has only a year remaining. But if Jones
did it then for Emmitt, why not ``reward'' Michael, the undisputed
emotional leader of the Cowboys' glory days? And while we're at it,
only Aikman and a few others ever equaled Irvin in hardball
intensity combined with adherence to the total team concept.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry, you owe him plenty.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the Jones view:
</P>
<P>
   With his off-the-field escapades and his high-profile
personality, Irvin eclipsed even Lawrence Taylor in causing
irreversible damage to an NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   If Irvin dare uttered ``do you know who I am?'' to Jones, Jerry
could give him about two hours worth of heated reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, it has been an ongoing process of Irvin creating
trouble, trouble, trouble for the Cowboys, and for Jones. And
remember, the last incident was only last summer, with the
neck-slashing in Wichita Falls. Even the reputation of new coach
Gailey was stained a bit in the coverup that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, going back to that Irving hotel room, Jones
has stood by Irvin. To a fault, Jerry protected him, coddled him,
covered for him, probably even lied for him _ anything it took,
Jerry was there for Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's best friend in the world has been Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Based on everything, should Irvin now be volunteering to play
for free? Not a bad idea, frankly.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, you owe him plenty.
</P>
<P>
   So see there _ what Jerry does with Michael, and what Michael
does with Jerry, is as intriguing a question as I've seen lately in
the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder there's the perception Jones has suddenly become
media-shy. Actually, he's just got some deep thinking to do.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
