<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT_NOTES-LAD     06-05 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT_NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACE FAVORABLE TO LEMON DROP KID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Lemon Drop Kid, the grandson of Seattle Slew, who
won the 131st Belmont Stakes, took advantage of the fast pace set
by the filly Silverbulletday and pressed by favored Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-1 winner mounted an eighth-to-first rally on the outside
to beat Vision and Verse by a head as Charismatic faded to third,
breaking down at the wire, and Silverbulletday was virtually eased
to seventh in the 12-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a killer pace, but you just hate to go eyeball to
eyeball early in the race,'' said Jerry Bailey, who let up on
Silverbulletday in the stretch. ``She was beat and I didn't want to
kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarter-mile fractions _ 23 3/5 seconds, 47 4/5, 1:12, 1:36
2/5 and 2:01 4/5 _ and the 2:27 4/5 final time for 1 { miles were
among the fastest in recent Belmonts. So it was puzzling that
jockey Chris Antley let Charismatic race so close to the pace,
having rallied from seventh in the Kentucky Derby and 10th in the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said it appeared Antley had trouble restraining
Charismatic. It's also possible Antley was afraid to let
Silverbulletday set an uncontested pace.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid trainer Scotty Schulhofer said he was surprised
Charismatic was near the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was happy when I saw (that),'' Schulhofer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont victory was the second for Schulhofer, whose
Colonial Affair won in 1993, and the first for jockey Jose Santos
and owners Jeanne Vance and her lyrically named husband Laddie
Dance. The owners, who live in Maryland and Florida, are racing
veterans who once owned a breeding share in Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that (Belmont in 1973) because I was crying so
hard,'' Dance said. ``I cried harder after this one.''
</P>
<P>
   His reaction was not to Charismatic's injury but to his horse's
unexpected victory. Lemon Drop Kid ran ninth in the Kentucky Derby
and third in the Peter Pan Stakes at Belmont in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``His Peter Pan set him up nicely for this,'' Santos said. ``You
always need a good trip and he got that today. The filly and the
others set a pretty quick (pace) for him to make a run at.''
</P>
<P>
   At the turnstiles: The Belmont Park crowd of 85,818 set a track
record, exceeding the 82,694 who watched Canonero II fail to
complete a Triple Crown in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The undercard: D. Wayne Lukas had two Belmont Park winners in
the bag before the big race, including Yes It's True, who captured
the Riva Ridge sprint for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The other major winner: Yagli in the Manhattan Handicap on turf,
giving Bailey one of his four winners.
</P>
<P>
   Over there: Oath won the English Derby at Epsom Downs on
Saturday as Beat All and transplanted California rider Gary Stevens
finished an unthreatening third in the $1.7 million race.
</P>
<P>
   Oath is trained by Henry Cecil, uncle of California trainer Ben
Cecil, and owned by The Thoroughbred Corp., which had Patience Game
in the Belmont.
</P>
</TEXT>
